[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

{ The Benoni is one of the sharpest openings against d4. By its nature the Benoni is quite uncompromising, and it gives good possibilities to play for a win. It is also a risky opening, because we allow White to build up a strong pawn centre. Time and again it has come back into fashion, and it has been played by many strong players: Bobby Fischer, Garry Kasparov, Vugar Gashimov, Fabiano Caruana, David Navara and so on. Nowadays Levon Pantsulaia and Aleksander Indjic use this opening regularly in their games. The Benoni has also been regularly used in decisive games. I have to mention the critical game that Fischer won against Spassky in their match in Reykjavik, 1972 (you can see this game in the model games chapter).The Benoni is an opening that has always fascinated me. I used to play it when I was a junior, and I had a good feeling for the types of positions it gives rise to. Later on I switched to more solid openings, but from time to time I’ve included the Benoni in my repertoire, especially against the g3 system. I’ve also played the white side against the Benoni many times, and it always resulted in spectacular games. Recently I’ve made the Benoni my pet opening in online chess with very good results. I'm looking forward to upcoming over the board tournaments to be able to put in practice the ideas from this course.In preparing the material for this course, I analyzed a lot of variations and I selected lines for Black that offer good play in practical games. It won't be easy for the opponent to play for a draw, as the positions that arise in the Benoni are very resourceful. This course is suitable for all levels, from amateurs to experts in the Benoni (Grandmasters included). I’m certain everyone will discover some new interesting things about their favourite opening! } 1. d4 { A popular and solid starting move. } 1... Nf6 { The knight prevents White from putting a pawn on e4. Starting from this position this course will provide a complete repertoire against White's replies. } 2. c4 ( { The move that’s played the most often. White pushes the pawn forward before developing the knight to c3. In the course I’ve also covered many other options like } 2. Nf3 { , } ) ( 2. Nc3 { , } ) ( 2. Bf4 { , } ) ( 2. Bg5 { and even the early all-in attempt } ) ( 2. g4 { . } ) 2... c5 ( { We fight for the centre, allowing White to push the pawn forward. Nowadays many players prefer to reach the Benoni via a different move order: by playing } 2... e6 { and only after } 3. Nf3 { or } ( 3. g3 { to go for } 3... c5 { Thus they avoid the lines with f2-f4, which are known to be dangerous for both Black and White! } ) ) 3. d5 ( { The most principled move, grabbing space. } 3. Nf3 e6 { is covered in the course as well. } ) 3... e6 { We immediately challenge White's central pawns. } 4. Nc3 { White prepares to play e4. } 4... exd5 { The move order I intended for this course is to take immediately on d5 so as not to allow White to play e4 and take back on d5 with the e-pawn, which would result in a symmetrical pawn structure. } 5. cxd5 d6 { A multi-purpose move. We prevent White from playing d5-d6, we open up our light-squared bishop and also the b8-knight may develop to d7 in the future. Our plan is to play ...g6, develop our dark-squared bishop to g7 and castle short.I’ll take this opportunity to point out some basic plans. In general in the Benoni it’s good for Black to trade his light-squared bishop for a knight or even a bishop. This is because Black lacks space. Put concretely, the best square for the b8-knight is on d7 from where it controls the e5-square. However, if the knight is on d7 this means the bishop on c8 is shut in – hence we would like to exchange that bishop first, if possible.Another important feature is the struggle over the e5-square. If White manages to play e4-e5 under good conditions, even if it implies a pawn sacrifice, Black can easily get into  trouble. Most often White's dark-squared bishop is best placed on f4. A typical and strong maneuver for White is to bring a knight to c4 via d2. From there the knight exerts pressure on both the d6- and e5-squares. That's why we cannot allow White to keep a knight on c4 for too long. We usually try to exchange it with ...Ne5 or ...Nb6, or even ...Ba6 in some lines (after we have played ...b6).In case you're not a Benoni player, I hope this course will convince you to include this opening in your repertoire. If you are a long-time Benoni player or if you have some experience with the opening, I hope this course will be a good source of interesting ideas that you can put into practice. I wish you many interesting and fighting games in the Benoni! } *

