 White's replies. } 2. c4 ( { The move that’s played the most often. White pushes the pawn forward before developing the knight to c3. In the course I’ve also covered many other options like } 2. Nf3 { , } ) ( 2. Nc3 { , } ) ( 2. Bf4 { , } ) ( 2. Bg5 { and even the early all-in attempt } ) ( 2. g4 { . } ) 2... c5 ( { We fight for the centre, allowing White to push the pawn forward. Nowadays many players prefer to reach the Benoni via a different move order: by playing } 2... e6 { and only after } 3. Nf3 { or } ( 3. g3 { to go for } 3... c5 { Thus they avoid the lines with f2-f4, which are known to be dangerous for both Black and White! } ) ) 3. d5 ( { The most principled move, grabbing space. } 3. Nf3 e6 { is covered in the course as well. } ) 3... e6 { We immediately challenge White's central pawns. } 4. Nc3 { White prepares to play e4. } 4... exd5 { The move order I intended for this course is to take immediately on d5 so as not to allow White to play e4 and take back on d5 with the e-pawn, which would result in a symmetrical pawn structure. } 5. cxd5 d6 { A multi-purpose move. We prevent White from playing d5-d6, we open up our light-squared bishop and also the b8-knight may develop to d7 in the future. Our plan is to play ...g6, develop our dark-squared bishop to g7 and castle short.I’ll take this opportunity to point out some basic plans. In general in the Benoni it’s good for Black to trade his light-squared bishop for a knight or even a bishop. This is because Black lacks space. Put concretely, the best square for the b8-knight is on d7 from where it controls the e5-square. However, if the knight is on d7 this means the bishop on c8 is shut in – hence we would like to exchange that bishop first, if possible.Another important feature is the struggle over the e5-square. If White manages to play e4-e5 under good conditions, even if it implies a pawn sacrifice, Black can easily get into  trouble. Most often White's dark-squared bishop is best placed on f4. A typical and strong maneuver for White is to bring a knight to c4 via d2. From there the knight exerts pressure on both the d6- and e5-squares. That's why we cannot allow White to keep a knight on c4 for too long. We usually try to exchange it with ...Ne5 or ...Nb6, or even ...Ba6 in some lines (after we have played ...b6).In case you're not a Benoni player, I hope this course will convince you to include this opening in your repertoire. If you are a long-time Benoni player or if you have some experience with the opening, I hope this course will be a good source of interesting ideas that you can put into practice. I wish you many interesting and fighting games in the Benoni! } *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Modern Benoni"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter: the Benoni"]
[Black "7. Nd2 System #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 ( { Black immediately fights for the centre, but allows White to push d5. If you don’t want to allow White the option of playing f2-f4 Benoni lines, } 2... e6 { is a move order you can try. After } 3. Nc3 { you can then go for the Nimzo-Indian instead, while after } ( 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 { you reach Benoni lines. Here } 4... d6 { is an important detail, taking away some of White’s dangerous options. After } 5. Nc3 exd5 6. cxd5 g6 { followed by 8. Qxe4+. } ) ) 3. d5 e6 { Black is challenging White's centre. } 4. Nc3 exd5 { We're exchanging on d5 straight away. Otherwise White can play e4 and then retake on d5 with the e-pawn, resulting in a symmetrical position where Black is slightly worse because of his lack of space. } 5. cxd5 d6 { We prevent White's d5-d6 and prepare to fianchetto our dark-squared bishop with ...g6. This is the starting position of the Benoni. } 6. Nf3 g6 7. Nd2 { Quite a strong plan.  White avoids the exchange of light-squared bishops with ...Bg4 and prepares e2-e4. The knight will defend the e4-pawn, and at the right moment wants to jump to the ideal square c4. } 7... Bg7 8. Nc4 { It makes sense to bring the knight here and put pressure on the d6-pawn. However, White has delayed his development, and now the e4-square is not so well defended. } 8... O-O 9. Bf4 Nbd7 ( { There is nothing wrong with defending the pawn with } 9... Ne8 { as seen for example in our model game Moiseenko - Lupulescu. However, I think that is not necessary. I prefer to sacrifice a pawn and fight for the initiative. } ) 10. Bxd6 { This is tempting because it takes a pawn and attacks the rook. However, our rook will be well placed on e8, and after a future ...Nb6 the d5-pawn will be exposed. } 10... Re8 11. e3 Nb6 { The point of our play. } 12. Bxc5 Nfxd5 { The more precise capture as it opens up the Bg7. } 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. Be2 { White should hurry to complete development. } 14... Be6 { Defending the knight so that we can move our queen or even go ...Rc8. } 15. O-O Qg5 { Black has good compensation for the pawn. The game ½-½ (23) Istratescu, A (2583)-Rogulj, B (2397) Aschach 2017 continued } 16. Rc1 Nc3 17. bxc3 Qxc5 { with a pleasant position for Black. } *

