1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 ( { Black immediately fights for the centre, but allows White to push d5. If you don’t want to allow White the option of playing f2-f4 Benoni lines, } 2... e6 { is a move order you can try. After } 3. Nc3 { you can then go for the Nimzo-Indian instead, while after } ( 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 { you reach Benoni lines. Here } 4... d6 { is an important detail, taking away some of White’s dangerous options. After } 5. Nc3 exd5 6. cxd5 g6 { followed by 8. Qxe4+. } ) ) 3. d5 e6 { Black is challenging White's centre. } 4. Nc3 exd5 { We're exchanging on d5 straight away. Otherwise White can play e4 and then retake on d5 with the e-pawn, resulting in a symmetrical position where Black is slightly worse because of his lack of space. } 5. cxd5 d6 { We prevent White's d5-d6 and prepare to fianchetto our dark-squared bishop with ...g6. This is the starting position of the Benoni. } 6. Nf3 g6 7. Nd2 { Quite a strong plan.  White avoids the exchange of light-squared bishops with ...Bg4 and prepares e2-e4. The knight will defend the e4-pawn, and at the right moment wants to jump to the ideal square c4. } 7... Bg7 8. Nc4 { It makes sense to bring the knight here and put pressure on the d6-pawn. However, White has delayed his development, and now the e4-square is not so well defended. } 8... O-O 9. Bf4 Nbd7 ( { There is nothing wrong with defending the pawn with } 9... Ne8 { as seen for example in our model game Moiseenko - Lupulescu. However, I think that is not necessary. I prefer to sacrifice a pawn and fight for the initiative. } ) 10. Bxd6 { This is tempting because it takes a pawn and attacks the rook. However, our rook will be well placed on e8, and after a future ...Nb6 the d5-pawn will be exposed. } 10... Re8 11. e3 Nb6 { The point of our play. } 12. Bxc5 Nfxd5 { The more precise capture as it opens up the Bg7. } 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. Be2 { White should hurry to complete development. } 14... Be6 { Defending the knight so that we can move our queen or even go ...Rc8. } 15. O-O Qg5 { Black has good compensation for the pawn. The game ½-½ (23) Istratescu, A (2583)-Rogulj, B (2397) Aschach 2017 continued } 16. Rc1 Nc3 17. bxc3 Qxc5 { with a pleasant position for Black. } *

