1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 ( { Black immediately fights for the centre, but allows White to push d5. If you don’t want to allow White the option of playing f2-f4 Benoni lines, } 2... e6 { is a move order you can try. After } 3. Nc3 { you can then go for the Nimzo-Indian instead, while after } ( 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 { you reach Benoni lines. Here } 4... d6 { is an important detail, taking away some of White’s dangerous options. After } 5. Nc3 exd5 6. cxd5 g6 { followed by 8. Qxe4+. } ) ) 3. d5 e6 { Black is challenging White's centre. } 4. Nc3 exd5 { We're exchanging on d5 straight away. Otherwise White can play e4 and then retake on d5 with the e-pawn, resulting in a symmetrical position where Black is slightly worse because of his lack of space. } 5. cxd5 d6 { We prevent White's d5-d6 and prepare to fianchetto our dark-squared bishop with ...g6. This is the starting position of the Benoni. } 6. Nf3 g6 7. Nd2 { Quite a strong plan.  White avoids the exchange of light-squared bishops with ...Bg4 and prepares e2-e4. The knight will defend the e4-pawn, and at the right moment wants to jump to the ideal square c4. } 7... Bg7 8. e4 O-O 9. Be2 Na6 { Here I recommend the setup with the knight on c7, rook on e8 and then ...b6 and ...Ba6. The knight on c7 will help prepare ...b5, but it's not so good against the advance e4-e5. However, White has lost some time with his knight maneuver so we can afford this. } ( { We can also start with } 9... Re8 { and I think it should lead to the same thing. } ) 10. O-O Nc7 ( 10... Re8 { is the same thing as ...Nc7 is played next. } ) 11. a4 { A useful and flexible move. White could make other moves, but sooner or later  a2-a4 is needed anyway. Moreover, it prevents the direct ideas to prepare ... b5 by means of ...a6 and ...Rb8 because White can answer this with Nc4. } 11... Re8 { After thoroughly analyzing the position I think this is best. Black activates the rook and puts pressure on the e4-pawn. In order to play Nc4 White will have to play f3, thus clarifying his structure. } 12. f3 { This is the main move and it makes sense to securely defend the e4-pawn. White prepares to continue Nc4 and Bf4. } 12... b6 13. Nc4 { Now there is not enough time for ...a6, ...Rb8 and ...b5. We need to cut across White’s plan with Nc4. Thus the point is to play ...Ba6 after Nc4 and exchange the bishop for the knight. If White delays Nc4, we can play the useful move ...Rb8. } 13... Ba6 { The only move. We need to keep an eye on the Nc4. } 14. Bg5 Qd7 { We avoid the pin and prepare to push ...b5 after ...Bxc4 and ...a6. There is no need for ...h6 yet, which would just weaken our king. } 15. Qd2 Bxc4 { This is forced as White was threatening b3. } 16. Bxc4 a6 { Preparing ...b5. } 17. Qd3 { White is not making it easy for us to play ...b5. } 17... Nh5 ( { A provocative move with the idea to prepare ...f5. } 17... h6 { is playable as well. } ) 18. g4 { Both a weakening and an ambitious move. } 18... h6 { With an unclear position. It's good to include this before retreating the knight, because now White doesn't have the option to retreat the bishop to f4. } *

