[White "Quickstarter: the Benoni"]
[Black "Fianchetto System #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 ( { Black immediately fights for the centre, but allows White to push d5. If you don’t want to allow White the option of playing f2-f4 Benoni lines, } 2... e6 { is a move order you can try. After } 3. Nc3 { you can then go for the Nimzo-Indian instead, while after } ( 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 { you reach Benoni lines. Here } 4... d6 { is an important detail, taking away some of White’s dangerous options. After } 5. Nc3 exd5 6. cxd5 g6 { followed by 8. Qxe4+. } ) ) 3. d5 e6 { Black is challenging White's centre. } 4. Nc3 exd5 { We're exchanging on d5 straight away. Otherwise White can play e4 and then retake on d5 with the e-pawn, resulting in a symmetrical position where Black is slightly worse because of his lack of space. } 5. cxd5 d6 { We prevent White's d5-d6 and prepare to fianchetto our dark-squared bishop with ...g6. This is the starting position of the Benoni. } 6. Nf3 g6 7. g3 { Thus black players that want to avoid the Catalan with 3. g3 often go for this specific line in the Benoni. } 7... Bg7 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O { White's plan is to bring the bishop to f4 before or after playing Nd2. h3 is a useful move as it takes away the g4 square for Black. White will play a4 as a response to ...a6. Usually White doesn't go for e2-e4 quickly. Instead he will prepare it with moves like Re1. } 9... Re8 { The rook is well placed here, and White already has to take into account the move ...Ne4. This is the starting position of the fianchetto variation. It is generally useful for Black to exchange a pair of knights, so for now ...Ne4 is an idea. Also, after White's Nd2-c4 we need to be ready to play ...Nd7-e5 or ...Nd7-b6 in order to challenge White's knight on c4. Black's b8-knight goes to d7, as it is too slow to play ...Na6-c7. } 10. Bf4 { A popular move. White finishes the development and keeps an eye on the d6-pawn. } 10... h6 { An interesting and double edged continuation. We want to expand on the kingside by dislodging the bishop from f4. It may be a risky plan since we weaken our kingside, but I think this is a good variation if you want to play for a win. } 11. Qc1 g5 { Continuing the plan we set in motion with 10... h6. } 12. Bd2 { This is White’s most common reply. } 12... Bf5 { We develop the bishop to this nice square. Our kingside doesn't feel all that weakened as we have 3 minor pieces defending the king. } 13. h4 g4 14. Ne1 { White can activate this knight with Nc2-e3. } 14... Kh7 ( { Here this move is preferable to } 14... h5 { , as the latter would weaken our position. } ) 15. Nc2 Bg6 ( { The most precise. The immediate } 15... Nbd7 { allows } 16. Bf4 { . } ) 16. Ne3 Nbd7 { Here White's most aggressive continuation is } 17. h5 { , when } 17... Nxh5 18. Nxg4 { exchanges our g-pawn for White's h-pawn. We're well equipped for a battle on the kingside, however, as the lines in the Fianchetto chapter will show. Meanwhile, if White does nothing we can slowly prepare the ...b5 advance. } *

