1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 ( { Black immediately fights for the centre, but allows White to push d5. If you don’t want to allow White the option of playing f2-f4 Benoni lines, } 2... e6 { is a move order you can try. After } 3. Nc3 { you can then go for the Nimzo-Indian instead, while after } ( 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 { you reach Benoni lines. Here } 4... d6 { is an important detail, taking away some of White’s dangerous options. After } 5. Nc3 exd5 6. cxd5 g6 { followed by 8. Qxe4+. } ) ) 3. d5 e6 { Black is challenging White's centre. } 4. Nc3 exd5 { We're exchanging on d5 straight away. Otherwise White can play e4 and then retake on d5 with the e-pawn, resulting in a symmetrical position where Black is slightly worse because of his lack of space. } 5. cxd5 d6 { We prevent White's d5-d6 and prepare to fianchetto our dark-squared bishop with ...g6. This is the starting position of the Benoni. } 6. Nf3 g6 7. g3 { Thus black players that want to avoid the Catalan with 3. g3 often go for this specific line in the Benoni. } 7... Bg7 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O { White's plan is to bring the bishop to f4 before or after playing Nd2. h3 is a useful move as it takes away the g4 square for Black. White will play a4 as a response to ...a6. Usually White doesn't go for e2-e4 quickly. Instead he will prepare it with moves like Re1. } 9... Re8 { The rook is well placed here, and White already has to take into account the move ...Ne4. This is the starting position of the fianchetto variation. It is generally useful for Black to exchange a pair of knights, so for now ...Ne4 is an idea. Also, after White's Nd2-c4 we need to be ready to play ...Nd7-e5 or ...Nd7-b6 in order to challenge White's knight on c4. Black's b8-knight goes to d7, as it is too slow to play ...Na6-c7. } 10. Nd2 { The old approach. White is redirecting the knight towards c4, and at the same time keeps the e4-square under control. This way he prevents our ...Ne4. } 10... Nbd7 ( { This is flexible. Other moves are possible here, for example } 10... a6 { or } ) ( 10... b6 { could transpose later on. } ) 11. a4 { A useful move for White, preventing ...b5 and gaining some space on the queenside. } 11... b6 { This is an interesting move order as we keep open the option to play ...Ba6. However, most likely we will return to the plan with ...a6. } 12. h3 { This is the main move. White prevents a potential ...Ng4. } 12... a6 { This position can be reached via various move orders. For example if Black starts with ...a6 and then plays ...b6. The point of the ...b6 move is that we prevent White from playing a5, clamping down on our queenside pawns. We intend to continue with ...Rb8 and ...b5. In case of Nc4 we have ...Ne5. Time is important in this position. If we manage to play ...b5 we get a very good position. That's why White will try to push his central pawns and get his knight to c4. } 13. Nc4 { The most common move. } 13... Ne5 14. Na3 { This is a typical maneuver to open up the c1-bishop, lure our knight to e5 and prepare f2-f4 with tempo. } 14... Nh5 { With the idea to continue ...f5. White can push f2-f4 or g3-g4 and win a piece for 2 pawns, but Black will get a nice attack, so we're happy to see that! } 15. g4 Nxg4 { A typical piece sacrifice. The white king will be in danger for a long time from now on. } 16. hxg4 Bxg4 { We’ve sacrificed a piece for 2 pawns, but we get a lot of compensation. White's king is weak, there is the direct threat of ...Bxc3 followed by ...Bxe2, while ...b5 is an idea as well. At the same time White is struggling to coordinate his pieces. } *

