[Black "6. Nf3, 7. Bf4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 ( { Black immediately fights for the centre, but allows White to push d5. If you don’t want to allow White the option of playing f2-f4 Benoni lines, } 2... e6 { is a move order you can try. After } 3. Nc3 { you can then go for the Nimzo-Indian instead, while after } ( 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 { you reach Benoni lines. Here } 4... d6 { is an important detail, taking away some of White’s dangerous options. After } 5. Nc3 exd5 6. cxd5 g6 { followed by 8. Qxe4+. } ) ) 3. d5 e6 { Black is challenging White's centre. } 4. Nc3 exd5 { We're exchanging on d5 straight away. Otherwise White can play e4 and then retake on d5 with the e-pawn, resulting in a symmetrical position where Black is slightly worse because of his lack of space. } 5. cxd5 d6 { We prevent White's d5-d6 and prepare to fianchetto our dark-squared bishop with ...g6. This is the starting position of the Benoni. } 6. Nf3 g6 7. Bf4 { This is a popular setup for White. He puts the bishop on a good diagonal and will try to develop his pieces quickly. The idea is to merely play e2-e3 at first, so that Black cannot target White’s e-pawn. } 7... a6 ( { Black prevents the early check with Qa4+. This is a more solid and less forcing line. The alternative } 7... Bg7 { , which is also covered in the course in a separate chapter, leads to very double-edged play because Black often sacrifices a pawn for quick development. } ) 8. a4 { Preventing ...b5. Later on White can play a5 in order to make use of the b6-square. } 8... Bg7 9. e3 { is inaccurate, but is a move that is easily made by a careless player. } 9... Bg4 { I cannot stress enough the importance of this move! When we’re given the opportunity, we should exchange this bishop. } *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Modern Benoni"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter: the Benoni"]
[Black "6. Nf3, 7. Bf4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 ( { Black immediately fights for the centre, but allows White to push d5. If you don’t want to allow White the option of playing f2-f4 Benoni lines, } 2... e6 { is a move order you can try. After } 3. Nc3 { you can then go for the Nimzo-Indian instead, while after } ( 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 { you reach Benoni lines. Here } 4... d6 { is an important detail, taking away some of White’s dangerous options. After } 5. Nc3 exd5 6. cxd5 g6 { followed by 8. Qxe4+. } ) ) 3. d5 e6 { Black is challenging White's centre. } 4. Nc3 exd5 { We're exchanging on d5 straight away. Otherwise White can play e4 and then retake on d5 with the e-pawn, resulting in a symmetrical position where Black is slightly worse because of his lack of space. } 5. cxd5 d6 { We prevent White's d5-d6 and prepare to fianchetto our dark-squared bishop with ...g6. This is the starting position of the Benoni. } 6. Nf3 g6 7. Bf4 { This is a popular setup for White. He puts the bishop on a good diagonal and will try to develop his pieces quickly. The idea is to merely play e2-e3 at first, so that Black cannot target White’s e-pawn. } 7... a6 ( { Black prevents the early check with Qa4+. This is a more solid and less forcing line. The alternative } 7... Bg7 { , which is also covered in the course in a separate chapter, leads to very double-edged play because Black often sacrifices a pawn for quick development. } ) 8. a4 { Preventing ...b5. Later on White can play a5 in order to make use of the b6-square. } 8... Bg7 9. h3 { Both preventing ...Bg4 and creating a refuge for the bishop on h2. } 9... O-O 10. e3 { This is the point of White’s setup. On e4 the pawn would have been a target. In this way, White can finish developing without problems and only then prepare the advance e3-e4. } 10... Ne8 { In this position Black has tried many plans. With 10... Ne8 we defend the d6-pawn and prepare ...Nd7. Also in some lines we'll try to save on having to make the move ...Qe7. } 11. Be2 b6 { Black prevents a5 and prepares ...Nd7 and ...Ne5. After the exchange of knights on e5 the c5-pawn will be defended, which favours us. } ( { The immediate } 11... Nd7 { is possible as well. } ) 12. O-O Nd7 13. e4 { White is finally ready for this advance. } 13... Ne5 { The idea that we’ve prepared with our previous moves. } 14. Qd2 { Slightly improving the position. } 14... Nxf3+ { The most clear cut move. Sooner or later the knight trade would happen. } 15. Bxf3 Be5 ( { I prefer this move, although both } 15... f5 { and } ) ( 15... Ra7 { are also possible. By exchanging bishops we release some of White's pressure. } ) *

