1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 ( { Black immediately fights for the centre, but allows White to push d5. If you don’t want to allow White the option of playing f2-f4 Benoni lines, } 2... e6 { is a move order you can try. After } 3. Nc3 { you can then go for the Nimzo-Indian instead, while after } ( 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 { you reach Benoni lines. Here } 4... d6 { is an important detail, taking away some of White’s dangerous options. After } 5. Nc3 exd5 6. cxd5 g6 { followed by 8. Qxe4+. } ) ) 3. d5 e6 { Black is challenging White's centre. } 4. Nc3 exd5 { We're exchanging on d5 straight away. Otherwise White can play e4 and then retake on d5 with the e-pawn, resulting in a symmetrical position where Black is slightly worse because of his lack of space. } 5. cxd5 d6 { We prevent White's d5-d6 and prepare to fianchetto our dark-squared bishop with ...g6. This is the starting position of the Benoni. } 6. e4 { A natural and ambitious move. } 6... g6 { We continue the plan to fianchetto our bishop. } 7. Nf3 a6 { I recommend this move as White cannot parry both ...b5 and ...Bg4. Thus we manage to solve some of Black’s strategical problems in this position. } 8. h3 { I think this is a strong move. White prevents ...Bg4 once and for all and is going to get a nice setup with Bd3 and Bf4, putting pressure on the d6-pawn. } 8... b5 { Otherwise White plays a4 and Bd3 and we have nothing to show at all. } 9. Bd3 Bg7 10. O-O O-O 11. Bf4 { White tries to make it difficult for us to play ...Nbd7. } 11... Qe7 ( { I've analyzed this position for a long time. Finally I came to like the idea to develop the knight to d7 quickly. } 11... Qb6 { with the same idea would be wrong because of } 12. a4 b4 13. a5 { with a big advantage for White. } ) 12. Qd2 { This is flexible since White doesn't show yet where he will develop the rooks. } 12... Nbd7 13. Rfe1 { A natural move. The other rook may come to d1 or c1. White has a nice setup, the only drawback is that he has allowed ...b5. } 13... Re8 { The rook is useful here to prevent e5. } 14. Rad1 { White follows a central strategy, which  works in most cases. } 14... Ne5 ( { A concrete move. I think if we mark time with } 14... Bb7 { White is comfortable after } 15. b3 { . } ) *

