1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 ( { Black immediately fights for the centre, but allows White to push d5. If you don’t want to allow White the option of playing f2-f4 Benoni lines, } 2... e6 { is a move order you can try. After } 3. Nc3 { you can then go for the Nimzo-Indian instead, while after } ( 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 { you reach Benoni lines. Here } 4... d6 { is an important detail, taking away some of White’s dangerous options. After } 5. Nc3 exd5 6. cxd5 g6 { followed by 8. Qxe4+. } ) ) 3. d5 e6 { Black is challenging White's centre. } 4. Nc3 exd5 { We're exchanging on d5 straight away. Otherwise White can play e4 and then retake on d5 with the e-pawn, resulting in a symmetrical position where Black is slightly worse because of his lack of space. } 5. cxd5 d6 { We prevent White's d5-d6 and prepare to fianchetto our dark-squared bishop with ...g6. This is the starting position of the Benoni. } 6. e4 { A natural and ambitious move. } 6... g6 { We continue the plan to fianchetto our bishop. } 7. Nf3 a6 { I recommend this move as White cannot parry both ...b5 and ...Bg4. Thus we manage to solve some of Black’s strategical problems in this position. } 8. a4 { Many players would go for this instantly, as they wouldn't like to allow ... b5. However, I think White has more interesting choices, but for that he must delve deep into the position. } 8... Bg4 { Black should go for this move if White’s move order allows it. } 9. Qb3 { This is a risky move as it allows White’s pawns to be doubled on the kingside. White realizes his move order allowed us to exchange our light-squared bishop, and goes for this last moment resource. } 9... Bxf3 10. Qxb7 Nbd7 ( { This is the point of our play. } 10... Bxg2 { takes back the pawn, but at the cost of helping White develop his pieces. } ) 11. gxf3 Bg7 12. Qc6 O-O { There is no time to defend the d6-pawn. } 13. Qxd6 Nh5 { With the idea ...Be5 in order to take control over the dark squares. } 14. f4 Re8 { Activating the rook. We also have the idea to take on c3 and then on e4. } ( { A logical move. White parries ...Be5, and if } 14... f5 { there is } 15. e5 { . } ) *

