1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 ( { Black immediately fights for the centre, but allows White to push d5. If you don’t want to allow White the option of playing f2-f4 Benoni lines, } 2... e6 { is a move order you can try. After } 3. Nc3 { you can then go for the Nimzo-Indian instead, while after } ( 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 { you reach Benoni lines. Here } 4... d6 { is an important detail, taking away some of White’s dangerous options. After } 5. Nc3 exd5 6. cxd5 g6 { followed by 8. Qxe4+. } ) ) 3. d5 e6 { Black is challenging White's centre. } 4. Nc3 exd5 { We're exchanging on d5 straight away. Otherwise White can play e4 and then retake on d5 with the e-pawn, resulting in a symmetrical position where Black is slightly worse because of his lack of space. } 5. cxd5 d6 { We prevent White's d5-d6 and prepare to fianchetto our dark-squared bishop with ...g6. This is the starting position of the Benoni. } 6. e4 { A natural and ambitious move. } 6... g6 { We continue the plan to fianchetto our bishop. } 7. Nf3 a6 { I recommend this move as White cannot parry both ...b5 and ...Bg4. Thus we manage to solve some of Black’s strategical problems in this position. } 8. a4 { Many players would go for this instantly, as they wouldn't like to allow ... b5. However, I think White has more interesting choices, but for that he must delve deep into the position. } 8... Bg4 { Black should go for this move if White’s move order allows it. } 9. Be2 Bxf3 { I prefer to exchange the bishop right away, so as to avoid Nd2-c4. } 10. Bxf3 Nbd7 { This move order is aimed against any e5 breaks. } 11. O-O Bg7 { By exchanging the light-squared bishop we’ve managed to develop our pieces, establish control over the e5-square and prevent the e5 push. On the other hand White has the pair of bishops and the e4-pawn is safely defended. White may consider Be2 in the future to prevent the ...b5 break. } 12. Bf4 Qe7 { The queen is slightly better placed here than on c7, as we may have ideas to play ...Ne8-c7 later on. } 13. Re1 O-O 14. a5 { This seems a bit rushed to me. } 14... Rab8 ( { Preparing ...b5. } 14... Rfb8 { instead will leave us too exposed to e4-e5. } ) 15. Na4 Ne5 { This is a good moment to activate the knight. The other one will come to d7. } *

