1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 ( { Black immediately fights for the centre, but allows White to push d5. If you don’t want to allow White the option of playing f2-f4 Benoni lines, } 2... e6 { is a move order you can try. After } 3. Nc3 { you can then go for the Nimzo-Indian instead, while after } ( 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 { you reach Benoni lines. Here } 4... d6 { is an important detail, taking away some of White’s dangerous options. After } 5. Nc3 exd5 6. cxd5 g6 { followed by 8. Qxe4+. } ) ) 3. d5 e6 { Black is challenging White's centre. } 4. Nc3 exd5 { We're exchanging on d5 straight away. Otherwise White can play e4 and then retake on d5 with the e-pawn, resulting in a symmetrical position where Black is slightly worse because of his lack of space. } 5. cxd5 d6 { We prevent White's d5-d6 and prepare to fianchetto our dark-squared bishop with ...g6. This is the starting position of the Benoni. } 6. e4 { A natural and ambitious move. } 6... g6 { We continue the plan to fianchetto our bishop. } 7. h3 { White takes away the option of ...Bg4. } 7... Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Bg5 { White wants to play 10. Bd3 and avoid the forced lines with ...b5. In case of ...h6 he intends to retreat the bishop to e3, and after Qd2 to gain a tempo by attacking the h6-pawn. } 9... Re8 10. Bd3 c4 { This is Black's preferred solution in this position. } 11. Bc2 b5 { We got our queenside play going and have established a nice square for the knight on c5. On the other hand, we gave up the d4-square that White can use for his knight, and also for now it's not easy to advance the queenside pawns further. } 12. a3 { The most common move. White prevents ...b4, which will be difficult to play later on. We'll have to complete our development and then prepare it with ...a5. Of course, White players don't want to calculate the consequences of the ...b4 push every move. } 12... Nbd7 { The knight is heading to c5. } 13. O-O Nc5 ( 13... Qb6 { is also possible and likely transposes later on. } ) 14. Re1 Qb6 { We defend the b5-pawn and prepare the advance ...a5. } *

