1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 ( { Black immediately fights for the centre, but allows White to push d5. If you don’t want to allow White the option of playing f2-f4 Benoni lines, } 2... e6 { is a move order you can try. After } 3. Nc3 { you can then go for the Nimzo-Indian instead, while after } ( 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 { you reach Benoni lines. Here } 4... d6 { is an important detail, taking away some of White’s dangerous options. After } 5. Nc3 exd5 6. cxd5 g6 { followed by 8. Qxe4+. } ) ) 3. d5 e6 { Black is challenging White's centre. } 4. Nc3 exd5 { We're exchanging on d5 straight away. Otherwise White can play e4 and then retake on d5 with the e-pawn, resulting in a symmetrical position where Black is slightly worse because of his lack of space. } 5. cxd5 d6 { We prevent White's d5-d6 and prepare to fianchetto our dark-squared bishop with ...g6. This is the starting position of the Benoni. } 6. e4 { A natural and ambitious move. } 6... g6 { We continue the plan to fianchetto our bishop. } 7. h3 { White takes away the option of ...Bg4. } 7... Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Bd3 { This is one of the best possible setups for White against the Benoni. White doesn't allow us to play ...Bg4 and exchange the bishop. Given time White can castle, play Re1, Bf4, a4 and achieve a very harmonious position. } 9... b5 { Objectively this is the best move. The temporary pawn sacrifice is justified because White has wasted time by playing h3. } 10. Bxb5 { This leads to forcing lines and the resulting positions are drawish. } 10... Nxe4 { The point of our previous move. } 11. Nxe4 Qa5+ { Regaining the piece. } 12. Nfd2 Qxb5 13. Nxd6 Qa6 { The best square for the queen. We attack the knight on d6 and after White plays a knight to c4, the queen won't be under attack. } 14. N2c4 Nd7 { We need to bring this knight into play now in order to challenge White’s knights in the centre. } 15. O-O { White is happy to get castled, of course. } 15... Ne5 { The point of our play. I prefer ...Ne5 to ...Nb6 because the knight is more active on e5. } 16. Nxc8 Raxc8 17. Nxe5 Bxe5 18. Re1 { Was played the most often. It makes sense to activate the rook. } 18... Rfe8 { A natural reply, defending the bishop and activating the rook. } 19. Bg5 Bd4 { This is Black's preferred solution. The central bishop is very strong and parries the direct threat of d6. } 20. Rb1 Qd6 { We keep the d5-pawn under control. } *

