1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 ( { Black immediately fights for the centre, but allows White to push d5. If you don’t want to allow White the option of playing f2-f4 Benoni lines, } 2... e6 { is a move order you can try. After } 3. Nc3 { you can then go for the Nimzo-Indian instead, while after } ( 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 { you reach Benoni lines. Here } 4... d6 { is an important detail, taking away some of White’s dangerous options. After } 5. Nc3 exd5 6. cxd5 g6 { followed by 8. Qxe4+. } ) ) 3. d5 e6 { Black is challenging White's centre. } 4. Nc3 exd5 { We're exchanging on d5 straight away. Otherwise White can play e4 and then retake on d5 with the e-pawn, resulting in a symmetrical position where Black is slightly worse because of his lack of space. } 5. cxd5 d6 { We prevent White's d5-d6 and prepare to fianchetto our dark-squared bishop with ...g6. This is the starting position of the Benoni. } 6. e4 { A natural and ambitious move. } 6... g6 { We continue the plan to fianchetto our bishop. } 7. Bd3 Bg7 8. Nge2 { First of all, the point of this white setup is that it doesn't allow us to exchange the c8-bishop for the knight. Also, a quick ...b5 is not possible anymore. White wants to bring the knight to g3 where it will defend the e4 pawn and then continue play h3 and f4, with control over the centre. } 8... O-O 9. O-O a6 ( { I see no difference between this and } 9... Nbd7 { . They probably just transpose. } ) 10. a4 Nbd7 11. Ng3 Rb8 { The first step in preparing ...b5. } 12. h3 Ne8 { We bring the knight to c7 in order to prepare ...b5. } 13. f4 { White is pushing in the centre. The typical break idea is e5 ...dxe5 and then f5, so as not to give Black the e5-square for a piece. } 13... Nc7 { We continue our plan. } 14. e5 b5 ( { We're starting our counterplay. It isn't so good to take } 14... dxe5 { because of } 15. f5 ) *

