1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 ( { Black immediately fights for the centre, but allows White to push d5. If you don’t want to allow White the option of playing f2-f4 Benoni lines, } 2... e6 { is a move order you can try. After } 3. Nc3 { you can then go for the Nimzo-Indian instead, while after } ( 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 { you reach Benoni lines. Here } 4... d6 { is an important detail, taking away some of White’s dangerous options. After } 5. Nc3 exd5 6. cxd5 g6 { followed by 8. Qxe4+. } ) ) 3. d5 e6 { Black is challenging White's centre. } 4. Nc3 exd5 { We're exchanging on d5 straight away. Otherwise White can play e4 and then retake on d5 with the e-pawn, resulting in a symmetrical position where Black is slightly worse because of his lack of space. } 5. cxd5 d6 { We prevent White's d5-d6 and prepare to fianchetto our dark-squared bishop with ...g6. This is the starting position of the Benoni. } 6. e4 { A natural and ambitious move. } 6... g6 { We continue the plan to fianchetto our bishop. } 7. Bg5 Bg7 8. Nf3 { White wants to get an improved version of the Nf3-d2 variation by developing the dark-squared bishop first. We have to use the fact that White saved on the move h3 and exchange our light-squared bishop. } 8... a6 { First we have to secure the a4-e8 diagonal, preparing both ...b5 and ... Bg4. } ( { A hasty } 8... O-O { would allow White to play } 9. Nd2 { and get a grip on the position. } ) 9. a4 Bg4 { Now we get to exchange our light-squared bishop. } 10. Be2 Bxf3 { It's better to exchange this bishop for the knight, before White has time to play Nd2. } 11. Bxf3 Nbd7 { I'd rather develop the knight first and castle afterwards. It's probably a matter of taste, but I want to avoid any e5 breaks just in case. } 12. O-O O-O { We get a typical Benoni position in which we’ve managed to exchange the light-squared bishop. Thus we get enough space for our pieces and establish good control over the e5-square. } 13. Qd2 c4 { We should take advantage of the opportunity to play this move. now our knight gets a nice square on c5. } *

