1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 ( { Black immediately fights for the centre, but allows White to push d5. If you don’t want to allow White the option of playing f2-f4 Benoni lines, } 2... e6 { is a move order you can try. After } 3. Nc3 { you can then go for the Nimzo-Indian instead, while after } ( 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 { you reach Benoni lines. Here } 4... d6 { is an important detail, taking away some of White’s dangerous options. After } 5. Nc3 exd5 6. cxd5 g6 { followed by 8. Qxe4+. } ) ) 3. d5 e6 { Black is challenging White's centre. } 4. Nc3 exd5 { We're exchanging on d5 straight away. Otherwise White can play e4 and then retake on d5 with the e-pawn, resulting in a symmetrical position where Black is slightly worse because of his lack of space. } 5. cxd5 d6 { We prevent White's d5-d6 and prepare to fianchetto our dark-squared bishop with ...g6. This is the starting position of the Benoni. } 6. e4 { A natural and ambitious move. } 6... g6 { We continue the plan to fianchetto our bishop. } 7. f4 { This is the most aggressive approach White can choose against the Benoni. } 7... Bg7 { We're one step away from castling, but not quite there! } 8. Nf3 { I think giving a check with the bishop on b5 is stronger. By transposition we’ve reached the Four Pawns Attack Variation from the King's Indian Defence. This line is the specialty of Georgian Grandmaster Jobava for White. } 8... O-O { We’ve managed to castle and now we are ready to attack the white centre. } 9. Bd3 { The bishop is more exposed here to b5 and c4 ideas. } 9... b5 { The best reply. The pawn push is justified here and gives Black good play. } *

