1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 ( { Black immediately fights for the centre, but allows White to push d5. If you don’t want to allow White the option of playing f2-f4 Benoni lines, } 2... e6 { is a move order you can try. After } 3. Nc3 { you can then go for the Nimzo-Indian instead, while after } ( 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 { you reach Benoni lines. Here } 4... d6 { is an important detail, taking away some of White’s dangerous options. After } 5. Nc3 exd5 6. cxd5 g6 { followed by 8. Qxe4+. } ) ) 3. d5 e6 { Black is challenging White's centre. } 4. Nc3 exd5 { We're exchanging on d5 straight away. Otherwise White can play e4 and then retake on d5 with the e-pawn, resulting in a symmetrical position where Black is slightly worse because of his lack of space. } 5. cxd5 d6 { We prevent White's d5-d6 and prepare to fianchetto our dark-squared bishop with ...g6. This is the starting position of the Benoni. } 6. e4 { A natural and ambitious move. } 6... g6 { We continue the plan to fianchetto our bishop. } 7. f4 { This is the most aggressive approach White can choose against the Benoni. } 7... Bg7 { We're one step away from castling, but not quite there! } 8. Nf3 { I think giving a check with the bishop on b5 is stronger. By transposition we’ve reached the Four Pawns Attack Variation from the King's Indian Defence. This line is the specialty of Georgian Grandmaster Jobava for White. } 8... O-O { We’ve managed to castle and now we are ready to attack the white centre. } 9. Be2 Nbd7 ( { I like this move. We simply continue developing and prevent White from playing e5. } 9... Re8 { is possible, but too forcing for my tastes. } ) ( 9... Bg4 { is also a typical idea and fully playable in this position. } ) 10. O-O Re8 { We target the e4-pawn. } 11. Nd2 c4 ( { Black must act energetically. This is a typical move that makes room for the knight to come to c5. } 11... Nb6 { is also an interesting option. } ) 12. Kh1 { This is the main move here and rightly so: it's good to avoid a check on the g1-a7 diagonal. } 12... b5 ( { I like this idea. White cannot keep his centre together. } 12... Nc5 { is actually played more often. } ) 13. Nxb5 { in all the games I have in the database White took the b5-pawn. } 13... Nxe4 { We’ve traded the b5-pawn for the e4-pawn, which should favour us. } 14. Nxe4 Rxe4 15. Bf3 { This is tempting, so as not to allow ...Rd4. } 15... Re7 { A safe square for the rook in case White plays Nxd6. } 16. Nxd6 Ba6 { Both defending the c4-pawn and threatening ...c3. } 17. Ne4 c3 { Black is winning the exchange. We've been following the game 1-0
