1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 ( { Black immediately fights for the centre, but allows White to push d5. If you don’t want to allow White the option of playing f2-f4 Benoni lines, } 2... e6 { is a move order you can try. After } 3. Nc3 { you can then go for the Nimzo-Indian instead, while after } ( 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 { you reach Benoni lines. Here } 4... d6 { is an important detail, taking away some of White’s dangerous options. After } 5. Nc3 exd5 6. cxd5 g6 { followed by 8. Qxe4+. } ) ) 3. d5 e6 { Black is challenging White's centre. } 4. Nc3 exd5 { We're exchanging on d5 straight away. Otherwise White can play e4 and then retake on d5 with the e-pawn, resulting in a symmetrical position where Black is slightly worse because of his lack of space. } 5. cxd5 d6 { We prevent White's d5-d6 and prepare to fianchetto our dark-squared bishop with ...g6. This is the starting position of the Benoni. } 6. e4 { A natural and ambitious move. } 6... g6 { We continue the plan to fianchetto our bishop. } 7. f4 { This is the most aggressive approach White can choose against the Benoni. } 7... Bg7 { We're one step away from castling, but not quite there! } 8. Bb5+ { An important check. White is hindering our normal development. } 8... Nfd7 ( { This is the only good reply. Both } 8... Bd7 9. e5 { and } ) ( 8... Nbd7 9. e5 { lead to forcing variations where White gets an advantage. However, our knight is slightly misplaced on d7, and in some lines we may have to bring it back to f6. } ) 9. Nf3 { White continues with normal development. He will go for a fast kingside attack. White's next moves are likely to be O-O, Bd3, f5 and Qe1-g3. } 9... a6 { Of course, we need to take the opportunity to expand on the queenside. } 10. Bd3 { The most natural square for the bishop. } 10... b5 { If allowed we should generally play this advance. } 11. O-O O-O 12. Kh1 { This is the most played move and it’s also quite flexible. It is useful for White to prevent a check on the g1-a7 diagonal. } 12... Re8 { I like the rook here, it puts some pressure on the e4-pawn. } 13. a3 { A prophylactic move against ...b4. } 13... Ra7 14. f5 { Preparing to play Bg5. } ( { A typical maneuver to bring the rook into play. It's also good that after the move sequence } 14. -- Nf6 15. e5 dxe5 16. fxe5 Nxd5 { White no longer has } 17. Be4 { pinning our knight. } ) 14... Ne5 { We need to exchange the f3-knight in order to gain access to the e5-square and reduce White's attacking potential. } 15. Bg5 Bf6 { A suitable reply, as it prevents White from playing f5-f6. } 16. Bxf6 Qxf6 17. Nxe5 Qxe5 { The dark squares around our king are weakened, so we need to bring the knight over to cover them up. } 18. Qd2 Nd7 { Our control over e5 will compensate for the slightly weakened king position. } *

