1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 ( { Black immediately fights for the centre, but allows White to push d5. If you don’t want to allow White the option of playing f2-f4 Benoni lines, } 2... e6 { is a move order you can try. After } 3. Nc3 { you can then go for the Nimzo-Indian instead, while after } ( 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 { you reach Benoni lines. Here } 4... d6 { is an important detail, taking away some of White’s dangerous options. After } 5. Nc3 exd5 6. cxd5 g6 { followed by 8. Qxe4+. } ) ) 3. d5 e6 { Black is challenging White's centre. } 4. Nc3 exd5 { We're exchanging on d5 straight away. Otherwise White can play e4 and then retake on d5 with the e-pawn, resulting in a symmetrical position where Black is slightly worse because of his lack of space. } 5. cxd5 d6 { We prevent White's d5-d6 and prepare to fianchetto our dark-squared bishop with ...g6. This is the starting position of the Benoni. } 6. e4 { A natural and ambitious move. } 6... g6 { We continue the plan to fianchetto our bishop. } 7. f4 { This is the most aggressive approach White can choose against the Benoni. } 7... Bg7 { We're one step away from castling, but not quite there! } 8. Bb5+ { An important check. White is hindering our normal development. } 8... Nfd7 ( { This is the only good reply. Both } 8... Bd7 9. e5 { and } ) ( 8... Nbd7 9. e5 { lead to forcing variations where White gets an advantage. However, our knight is slightly misplaced on d7, and in some lines we may have to bring it back to f6. } ) 9. Bd3 { White retreats the bishop to an active square and prevents our expansion with ...a6 and ...b5. } 9... O-O ( { I prefer this move to } 9... Qh4+ { here. } ) 10. Nf3 Nf6 11. O-O ( { Here this move is possible because after } 11. e5 { the d5-pawn is hanging: the bishop on d3 blocks the access of White's queen to the d5-square. Yes, Black has lost a tempo, but now we want to exchange the light-squared bishop with ...Bg4. } ) 11... Bg4 { We exchange the bishop according to our plan. } 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Qxf3 Nbd7 ( { Black has managed to complete his development. } 13... a6 { is also possible, but probably that just transposes back to our continuation. } ) 14. Be3 { The bishop prevents any checks on the g1-a7 diagonal and later on could go to f2 via h4. } 14... a6 { Now it's a good moment to include this move. } 15. a4 Qa5 { The idea is to play ...Qb4 threatening both ...c4 and the b2-pawn. Also it allows us to bring the a8-rook to e8 if necessary. } 16. Kh1 { Even though he has the bishop on e3, it's useful to remove the king from the g1-a7 diagonal. } 16... Qb4 { We're preparing to play ...c4 or ...b5. } *

