1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 { The Trompowsky Attack. White intends to exchange the bishop for the knight and then take advantage of the pawn structure, or just to develop normally and claim that the pin is annoying for Black. } 2... e6 { lines. The idea is not to allow White to double our pawns, and we are preparing ...h6. } 3. e4 { White grabs the centre, and is ready to part with his dark-squared bishop. } 3... h6 { We get the bishop. Exchanging pieces is good for us because we lack space a bit. } 4. Bxf6 Qxf6 5. c3 { This little move is the start of a long plan. White intends to go Bd3, Ne2 and then play f2-f4, and that's why he needs to defend the d4-pawn first. } 5... d5 { In the past I’ve analysed this position for over the board games, and I came to the conclusion that Black needs to fight for the centre straight away. } 6. Nd2 c5 { Again, breaking up the centre. } 7. Ngf3 cxd4 { It makes sense to clarify the position in the centre. } 8. Nxd4 Bc5 { The bishop is developed to a nice square. } 9. N2b3 Bb6 ( { It is possible to go for the e4-pawn with } 9... Bxd4 10. Nxd4 dxe4 { , but why not keep things simple? } ) *

