1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 { The Trompowsky Attack. White intends to exchange the bishop for the knight and then take advantage of the pawn structure, or just to develop normally and claim that the pin is annoying for Black. } 2... e6 { lines. The idea is not to allow White to double our pawns, and we are preparing ...h6. } 3. e4 { White grabs the centre, and is ready to part with his dark-squared bishop. } 3... h6 { We get the bishop. Exchanging pieces is good for us because we lack space a bit. } 4. Bxf6 Qxf6 5. Nc3 { Usually after this White has the plan to play O-O-O, Qd2 and then push on the kingside. } 5... d6 ( { This keeps the fight complicated. It is also a flexible move, as it can help us with the move orders. } 5... Bb4 { is a worthy alternative. } ) 6. Qd2 { White continues the plan with O-O-O. } 6... c6 { Preparing ...e5. } 7. f4 { An ambitious move. } 7... e5 { We need to establish a foothold in the centre as well. } 8. dxe5 dxe5 9. f5 { Blocking our light-squared bishop in. } 9... Bb4 ( { The idea is to just pin the knight, not to take it. } 9... Bc5 { is good as well. } ) 10. Nf3 Nd7 { Black has good play. } *

