1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 { This line has successfully been tried by the Georgian Grandmaster Baadur Jobava lately. I don't think it's really dangerous for Black, but we should be prepared to meet it. By playing an early Nc3 White skips the option to go for c2-c4, and instead is looking for play in the centre and on the kingside. } 2... d5 { The most principled reply. We need to stop e2-e4. } 3. Bf4 { The main move. White develops the pieces and can consider to create threats with Nb5. } 3... c5 4. e3 { Now White is ready to play Nb5. } ( { We fight for the centre, as } 4. Nb5 { is not yet possible due to } 4... Qa5+ { . } ) 4... cxd4 { In order to avoid dxc5. } 5. exd4 a6 { We need to parry Nb5 as well. } 6. Nf3 Nc6 { Our b8-knight belongs here. Afterwards we can develop the c8-bishop. } 7. Ne5 { This way White avoids ...Bg4. } 7... Bd7 { The idea of this move is to be able to take back on c6 with the bishop, and thus not spoil the pawn structure. } 8. Be2 { White usually plays this move. } 8... e6 9. O-O Qb6 { Attacking the d4-pawn and thus disrupting White's coordination. } 10. Nxc6 Bxc6 { Black is quite happy to get rid of the active white knight. } 11. Rb1 Be7 { Normal development. } 12. Re1 O-O { The position is about equal. } *

