[Black "2. Nc3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 { This line has successfully been tried by the Georgian Grandmaster Baadur Jobava lately. I don't think it's really dangerous for Black, but we should be prepared to meet it. By playing an early Nc3 White skips the option to go for c2-c4, and instead is looking for play in the centre and on the kingside. } 2... d5 { The most principled reply. We need to stop e2-e4. } 3. Bg5 { White is fighting for the centre by keeping the option to take the knight. } 3... c5 ( { We immediately challenge White's centre. Of course, there are other good moves as well, and here I'd mention } 3... h6 { first and then 4... c5. However, the extra h6 may not make a big difference. } ) 4. Bxf6 { This exchange is debatable as it reinforces our centre, and White will have to keep the position closed so as not to open up our pair of bishops. } 4... gxf6 5. e3 cxd4 ( { Let's go for this as it limits White's options. } 5... Nc6 { is possible, when Black has to consider an extra } 6. dxc5 { . } ) 6. exd4 Nc6 { The most natural reply. } 7. Qh5 { This is White's idea. } 7... e6 ( { Again a natural reply. I’ve tried to make the lines easy to remember. Taking the pawn } 7... Nxd4 { is dubious, but } ) ( 7... Be6 { is an interesting alternative. } ) 8. O-O-O Bd7 { The only square left for the bishop, and now we can play ...Rc8 or even try to go for ...O-O-O later on. } 9. Nge2 { This is a typical maneuver for White in this variation. } 9... f5 { I like this plan. We intend to bring the queen to f6 and then castle long since the f7-pawn is defended. } 10. h4 { White wants to bring the rook into play via h3. However this seems a bit artificial to me. } 10... Qf6 { Just following the plan. } 11. Kb1 O-O-O { Our king will be safe on the queenside. } *

