1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 { White delays c4 for now and first wants to fianchetto the bishop to g2 and castle. } 3... c5 { The typical break in the spirit of the Benoni. } 4. Bg2 cxd4 { If allowed we will take the pawn on d4. } 5. Nxd4 { Sooner or later White has to take the pawn back. } 5... d5 6. O-O e5 { We use this opportunity to drive the knight away, while getting new perspectives for our light-squared bishop. } 7. Nb3 { A natural retreat. } 7... Be6 { The bishop belongs here in order to defend the centre. } 8. Nc3 { White’s most common move. } 8... Be7 9. f4 { Usually White goes for this move. } 9... exf4 10. gxf4 g6 { We have to stop White's f5-push. } 11. Kh1 { The most flexible continuation. } 11... Nc6 { It makes sense to develop the knight first before castling. This way we get control over the d4-square. } 12. Be3 { With the idea of Nd4, and after the knights exchange to recapture with the bishop. } 12... O-O ( { Time to bring the king to safety! I was tempted to recommend the interesting } 12... Qc8 { , but I think it's not so natural, and the resulting moves are difficult to remember. } ) 13. Nd4 Qd7 { Connecting the rooks and preparing ...Bh3. } *

