[Black "Torre Attack #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bg5 { The Torre Attack. White is developing his pieces harmoniously: pawns to e3 and c3, knight to d2, bishop to d3, castling short and then pushing e3-e4. The setup is very solid, but because of the pin on the f6-knight we have to be careful about possible ideas of an early e3-e4 or even d4-d5 after ...c5. } 3... h6 ( { I prefer to include this move as soon as possible in order to see what White intends to do. The immediate } 3... c5 { gives White more options, including } 4. d5 ) 4. Bh4 c5 { We're fighting for the centre. } 5. e3 cxd4 { I see no reason why we shouldn't exchange these pawns. } 6. exd4 b6 { I propose an easy to play setup: ...Be7, ...Bb7, ...O-O and then ...Nh5 in order to exchange the dark-squared bishops. } 7. Bd3 Be7 { This is more flexible, as we keep ideas to play ...Ba6. } 8. O-O O-O 9. Nbd2 Bb7 { It is normal to develop the bishop here. We can play like this if we don't want to bother to learn when it's good to play ...Ba6 or not. } 10. Re1 d6 11. c3 Nh5 { This idea works now. } 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. a4 Qc7 { We're just in time to stop a5. } *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Modern Benoni"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter: White Avoids the Benoni"]
[Black "Torre Attack #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 { The London System, one of the most solid setups for White. This system has quickly gained in popularity in blitz and rapid games, as it is suited for those time controls. White develops his pieces harmoniously. } 3... c5 ( { There is not much difference between this and } 3... d5 { I’ve decided to start this way because it's a logical consequence of 2... e6. } ) 4. e3 d5 { We just put our pawns in the centre. } 5. Nbd2 Nc6 6. c3 cxd4 ( { We clear the tension in the centre and prepare our next move. The immediate } 6... Nh5 { is interesting as well. } ) 7. exd4 Nh5 { This is the point of our previous move. We want to drive away the bishop from its active position. By exchanging on d4 we gave White the option to go Be3. However, that is not a problem, and without the exchange White had Bg5!, which would have been stronger. } 8. Be3 Bd6 { We take control over the important b8-h2 diagonal, and now the fight for the e5-square begins. } 9. Ne5 { This is the most ambitious continuation for White. By relocating the knight he has ideas to go f4 or even g4. } 9... Nf6 ( { An important moment. In most games that reach this position Black plays } 9... g6 { , which was considered the most precise. However, the reason I rejected } ) ( 9... g6 { is the forced line } 10. g4 Ng7 { (the most ambitious) } 11. h4 Nxe5 12. dxe5 Bxe5 13. h5 O-O { and here either } 14. Qf3 { or } ( 14. f4 { when White has a dangerous initiative for the pawn. Benoni players like to have the initiative themselves, and this position is not in that spirit. } ) ) 10. f4 { Very logical. White supports the knight in the centre and hopes for a long term edge. } 10... Qb6 { This is a big improvement. It's actually a double attack: both ...Qxb2 and ...Bxe5 are in the air (it seems better to go ...Bxe5 than ...Nxe5). } 11. Qb3 { The only way to stop both threats. } 11... Ng8 { A nice rejoinder. We want to play ...Nge7/...Nh6 and ...f6 in order to kick the white knight away from the centre. } ( { Exchanging the queens with } 11... Qxb3 { would give White a more comfortable ending. } ) 12. Bd3 Nge7 ( { This is natural. Let's keep the same plan for all of White's possible replies! That being said, in a correspondence game Black went } 12... Nh6 { with similar ideas. } ) 13. O-O f6 14. Nxc6 bxc6 { The game may become sharp, but Black is doing fine for now. } *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Modern Benoni"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter: White Avoids the Benoni"]
[Black "Colle System"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 { The Colle System. White is building up the position slowly, and is going for a setup with Bd3, b3 and Bb2. This system is popular in blitz and rapid even among top players. Although it's not so ambitious, White develops all the pieces on good squares and gets a playable position. } 3... d5 ( { This seems more natural to me than } 3... c5 { , as much as I prefer to avoid symmetry. } ) 4. Bd3 c5 ( { We can fight for the centre straight away. A good alternative is } 4... Bd6 { , but this is too symmetrical! } ) 5. b3 { White prevents ...c4 and gets ready to fianchetto the bishop. } 5... b6 ( { We need to solve the problem of our light-squared bishop. } 5... Nc6 { followed by ...b6 and ...Bb7 leads to the same thing. } ) 6. Bb2 Bb7 7. O-O Nc6 { This is the setup I recommend against the Colle: ...Nc6, ...Be7 and ...O-O. Afterwards we can act according to what White does. } 8. Nbd2 Be7 9. Ne5 { Colle players are usually fond of this knight jump. } 9... O-O { We bring our king to safety. } 10. a3 { Preventing ...Nb4. } 10... Qc7 { A useful move. It connects the rooks, we can now meet Nxc6 with ...Qxc6, and also in case of c4 we are ready to play ...Rad8. } 11. f4 { White prepares a fast Rf3. } 11... a5 { We follow up with our plan. } 12. Qf3 ( { This is an instructive blunder. White should probably play } 12. c4 { instead, opening the centre. Then we can reply } 12... Rad8 { as d8 is a great location for the rook. } ) 12... c4 { It’s hard to believe, but all the tactics work for Black! After either } 13. bxc4 dxc4 14. Nexc4 b5 { White will lose material. } *

