1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. Nc3 ( { White avoids playing } 4. d5 { and fights for the centre by developing the knight. We’ve now entered the English Opening. } ) 4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 d5 ( { Following a central strategy. Black has other choices here like } 5... Bb4 { or } ) ( 5... Nc6 { . However, I think the given move is simple and sound. } ) 6. Bg5 { White puts some pressure on the centre. } 6... e5 { I like this active move, as we take control over the centre. } 7. Nf3 { A reasonable retreat. } 7... d4 { We continue the advance in the centre. } 8. Nd5 { White postpones taking on f6 and for the moment wants to take the e5-pawn. } 8... Be7 { I think this is the simplest. We solve the pin and indirectly defend the e5-pawn. } 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 { Of course, it wouldn't make any sense to spoil our structure. } 10. g3 { White tries to play on the light squares. } 10... Nc6 ( { Continuing our development. It is possible to go for the d5-knight with } 10... Be6 { , but I think } ) ( 10... Nc6 { is more simple. } ) 11. Bg2 O-O 12. O-O g6 { Giving White a choice: either to take the bishop or to let it go to g7 with a good control over the centre. Black is doing well. } *

