1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. Nc3 ( { White avoids playing } 4. d5 { and fights for the centre by developing the knight. We’ve now entered the English Opening. } ) 4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 d5 ( { Following a central strategy. Black has other choices here like } 5... Bb4 { or } ) ( 5... Nc6 { . However, I think the given move is simple and sound. } ) 6. cxd5 { The most played move. White clarifies the situation in the centre. } 6... Nxd5 { This is the right recapture. We shouldn’t allow White to give us an isolated pawn. } 7. Bd2 { Obviously White doesn't want to spoil the structure after ...Nxc3. } 7... Be7 ( { We just finish our development. Other moves like } 7... Bc5 { , } ) ( 7... Bb4 { or } ) ( 7... Nf6 { are good as well. } ) 8. e4 { Removing our knight from its central square. } 8... Nxc3 ( { Simple and good. Previously } 8... Nb4 { has been tried as well. } ) 9. Bxc3 O-O { White's Bc3 doesn't really attack our king because it lacks other pieces to support it. Moreover, after ...Bf6 and ...Qb6 with the threat of ...Rd8 we may force the exchange of the dark-squared bishops. } 10. Be2 { The bishop is less exposed here than on c4. } 10... Qb6 ( { This was preferred in all the games played so far. I see no difference between this and } 10... Bf6 { . } ) 11. O-O Rd8 ( { Pinning the knight. } 11... Bf6 { is also good. } ) *

