1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. e3 { White avoids the Benoni, and just wants to get a normal game by developing his pieces. } 4... d5 ( { We’ve reached a symmetrical position. I was considering also to first play } 4... cxd4 5. exd4 { and then } 5... d5 { , entering the Panov Attack. However, those positions seem a bit passive to me, and the text move is very natural, just fighting for the centre. } ) 5. Nc3 { White is not yet defining the pawn structure. } 5... a6 { This is a useful move. Our plan is to play ...dxc4 and ...b5. By playing 5... a6 we also avoid an unpleasant check on b5. } ( 5... dxc4 6. Bxc4 a6 { which should favour Black. } ) 6. cxd5 exd5 { We’ve managed to avoid the check on b5 at the expense of a tempo. } 7. Be2 cxd4 ( { By going for the exchange we get an improved version in case White replies exd4. That being said, in most of the games Black played } 7... Nc6 { first. } ) 8. Nxd4 { White decides to play against the isolated pawn. } 8... Nc6 ( { This looks good now. I prefer this to } 8... Bd6 { because then White could play } 9. b3 { and fianchetto the bishop to b2. } ) 9. O-O Bd6 { This is the best square for our bishop. } 10. b3 Qc7 { Before castling we can go for this in order to misplace the white pieces. } 11. Nf3 Be6 { Defending the d5-pawn. } 12. Bb2 O-O 13. Rc1 Rad8 { From my experience with these positions the black rooks are best placed on e8 and d8. } 14. h3 Rfe8 { With a long fight ahead. The isolated pawn is not bad here because there are many pieces on the board. } *

