1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. e3 { White avoids the Benoni, and just wants to get a normal game by developing his pieces. } 4... d5 ( { We’ve reached a symmetrical position. I was considering also to first play } 4... cxd4 5. exd4 { and then } 5... d5 { , entering the Panov Attack. However, those positions seem a bit passive to me, and the text move is very natural, just fighting for the centre. } ) 5. cxd5 exd5 { In exchange for the isolated pawn we get good control over the centre. } 6. Bb5+ { This is the most testing move. } 6... Nc6 { I've analysed this position a lot, and looked for the best alternatives for Black. Every reply has its pros and cons, but developing the knight to c6 looks like the most natural move to me. } 7. O-O { White’s best reply and also the most flexible. } 7... cxd4 ( { I prefer to clarify the pawn structure early on. } 7... Bd6 { is an alternative. } ) 8. exd4 { This is the best version of the symmetrical structure that White can get. He intends to continue Re1+ and Bg5 and play for a slight edge. Among the top players Artemiev likes this move. } 8... Be7 { The bishop is not so active here, but it parries both Re1+ and the pin after Bg5. } 9. Ne5 { This knight jump restricts Black's options. } 9... Bd7 ( { This is forced, as we need to address the pin. } 9... Qb6 { would fail to } 10. Qb3 ) 10. Nc3 O-O { The next step is to bring our rooks into play. } 11. Bg5 { This was played twice by Artemiev. } 11... h6 { I think it's useful to include this move. } 12. Bh4 Re8 { Slightly improving the position and preparing to take action in different ways. } *

