1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. e3 { White avoids the Benoni, and just wants to get a normal game by developing his pieces. } 4... d5 ( { We’ve reached a symmetrical position. I was considering also to first play } 4... cxd4 5. exd4 { and then } 5... d5 { , entering the Panov Attack. However, those positions seem a bit passive to me, and the text move is very natural, just fighting for the centre. } ) 5. cxd5 exd5 { In exchange for the isolated pawn we get good control over the centre. } 6. Bb5+ { This is the most testing move. } 6... Nc6 { I've analysed this position a lot, and looked for the best alternatives for Black. Every reply has its pros and cons, but developing the knight to c6 looks like the most natural move to me. } 7. O-O { White’s best reply and also the most flexible. } 7... cxd4 ( { I prefer to clarify the pawn structure early on. } 7... Bd6 { is an alternative. } ) 8. Nxd4 { is more ambitious, White insists on the isolated pawn structure. } 8... Bd7 ( { We address the pin. } 8... Qc7 { deserves attention as well. } ) 9. Nc3 { The knight is more active here and attacks the d5-pawn. } 9... Bd6 { A good square for our bishop. } 10. Nf3 { Now White is attacking the d5-pawn. } 10... Bg4 { A good moment to activate the bishop, at the same time defending the d5-pawn. } 11. h3 { This is a useful move. } 11... Bh5 { We keep the pressure on the f3-knight. } 12. Be2 { White has to take care of the pin sooner or later. } 12... O-O 13. b3 { White completes his development and later on hopes to take advantage of the isolated pawn. } 13... a6 { I have some experience with this position, and my conclusion is that this little move is useful. } 14. Bb2 Re8 { The rook belongs on the e-file. } *

