1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. g3 { White avoids the Benoni and goes for an English Opening setup. Next he will play Bg2, putting pressure on the long diagonal. } 4... cxd4 { We have to act fast before White has time to get his ideal setup. } 5. Nxd4 d5 6. Bg2 ( { I like this natural move. We simply fight for the centre. Now } 6. cxd5 { is not good because we can take back with the queen } 6... Qxd5 { . } ) 6... e5 { This is a good moment to push the pawns in the centre. This means that we gain space and we'll be able to put our pieces on good squares. } 7. Nb3 { Preparing to push f2-f4. } 7... d4 { We keep our centre intact. } 8. O-O Nc6 { Knights should be developed first! } 9. f4 { The point of White’s play. He undermines our centre. } 9... Be7 10. Bxc6+ ( { Apparently ignoring White's threat. The idea is that after } 10. fxe5 { we can jump } 10... Ng4 { . } ) ( { White gives his strong bishop in order to win a pawn. } 10. fxe5 Ng4 { would likely lead to the same thing. } ) 10... bxc6 11. fxe5 Ng4 { This is a good square for the knight. } 12. Qxd4 O-O { We have good compensation for the 2 pawns. The e5-pawn is weak and may fall soon. If White trades the queens our pair of bishops and good structure give us compensation, while with the queens on the board the white king is weak. } *

