1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f4 { is the Queen's Gambit Declined.I don't think many white players are well prepared in the f4 line since Black can avoid it in several ways. So, if we're up for a challenge and want to play for a win, we should allow White to choose whatever setup he wants in our favourite opening! } 7... Bg7 { We're one step from castling, but not quite there! } 8. Nf3 { I think giving a check with the bishop on b5 is stronger. Now by transposition we reach the Four Pawns Attack Variation from the King's Indian Defence. This line is a speciality of Georgian Grandmaster Jobava for White. } 8... O-O 9. Bd3 { The bishop is more exposed here to …b5 and …c4 ideas. } 9... b5 { The best reply. The pawn push is justified here and gives Black good play. } 10. O-O c4 { By pushing the pawns we gain space on the queenside and throw back White's pieces. } 11. Bc2 b4 { The pawn rolling continues! } 12. Ne2 Re8 { Everything comes with tempo. } 13. Ng3 Qb6+ 14. Kh1 Ng4 { White's position is already unpleasant. } *

