1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f4 { is the Queen's Gambit Declined.I don't think many white players are well prepared in the f4 line since Black can avoid it in several ways. So, if we're up for a challenge and want to play for a win, we should allow White to choose whatever setup he wants in our favourite opening! } 7... Bg7 { We're one step from castling, but not quite there! } 8. Nf3 { I think giving a check with the bishop on b5 is stronger. Now by transposition we reach the Four Pawns Attack Variation from the King's Indian Defence. This line is a speciality of Georgian Grandmaster Jobava for White. } 8... O-O 9. Bd3 { The bishop is more exposed here to …b5 and …c4 ideas. } 9... b5 { The best reply. The pawn push is justified here and gives Black good play. } 10. Nxb5 { This moves the knight away from the centre. } 10... Re8 { Black is on top. ...Nxe4 is a strong threat. } *

