1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f4 { is the Queen's Gambit Declined.I don't think many white players are well prepared in the f4 line since Black can avoid it in several ways. So, if we're up for a challenge and want to play for a win, we should allow White to choose whatever setup he wants in our favourite opening! } 7... Bg7 { We're one step from castling, but not quite there! } 8. Nf3 { I think giving a check with the bishop on b5 is stronger. Now by transposition we reach the Four Pawns Attack Variation from the King's Indian Defence. This line is a speciality of Georgian Grandmaster Jobava for White. } 8... O-O 9. Be2 Nbd7 ( { I like this move. We simply continue developing and prevent White from playing e5. } 9... Re8 { is possible, but too forcing for my tastes. } ) ( 9... Bg4 { is also a typical idea and fully playable in this position. } ) 10. e5 { This is too premature. } 10... dxe5 11. fxe5 Ng4 { It turns out that White cannot support his centre. } 12. e6 Nde5 { White will probably need to give up a pawn to complete his development. } *

