1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f4 { is the Queen's Gambit Declined.I don't think many white players are well prepared in the f4 line since Black can avoid it in several ways. So, if we're up for a challenge and want to play for a win, we should allow White to choose whatever setup he wants in our favourite opening! } 7... Bg7 { We're one step from castling, but not quite there! } 8. Nf3 { I think giving a check with the bishop on b5 is stronger. Now by transposition we reach the Four Pawns Attack Variation from the King's Indian Defence. This line is a speciality of Georgian Grandmaster Jobava for White. } 8... O-O 9. Be2 Nbd7 ( { I like this move. We simply continue developing and prevent White from playing e5. } 9... Re8 { is possible, but too forcing for my tastes. } ) ( 9... Bg4 { is also a typical idea and fully playable in this position. } ) 10. O-O Re8 11. Qc2 { This is logical as it develops a piece. Given time, White can improve his position and make use of his centre. } 11... a6 { Sooner or later we have to include this move. } 12. a4 Qc7 { Black’s idea is to play ...c4 followed by ...Nc5. } 13. Nd2 Rb8 { A useful move. Now after the pawn sacrifice ...c4, the move ...b5 will follow with increased effect. } 14. b3 { White intends to meet ...c4 with b4. } 14... Nxe4 { This is risky, but we can take the pawn. } 15. Ndxe4 Rxe4 16. Nxe4 Bxa1 17. f5 { As a result of a forced sequence of moves, White has brought his knight to a very active square and continues by opening up the position. } 17... b5 { It's good to start our own play on the queenside, while at the same time preparing ...Bb7. } 18. Bf4 Bd4+ 19. Kh1 Ne5 { We’ve managed to coordinate our pieces. } *

