[Black "8. Nf3 O-O 9. Be2 #14"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f4 { is the Queen's Gambit Declined.I don't think many white players are well prepared in the f4 line since Black can avoid it in several ways. So, if we're up for a challenge and want to play for a win, we should allow White to choose whatever setup he wants in our favourite opening! } 7... Bg7 { We're one step from castling, but not quite there! } 8. Nf3 { I think giving a check with the bishop on b5 is stronger. Now by transposition we reach the Four Pawns Attack Variation from the King's Indian Defence. This line is a speciality of Georgian Grandmaster Jobava for White. } 8... O-O 9. Be2 Nbd7 ( { I like this move. We simply continue developing and prevent White from playing e5. } 9... Re8 { is possible, but too forcing for my tastes. } ) ( 9... Bg4 { is also a typical idea and fully playable in this position. } ) 10. O-O Re8 11. Nd2 { This is the other way to defend the e4-pawn. } 11... c4 ( { Black must act energetically. This is a typical move that makes room for the knight to come to c5. } 11... Nb6 { is also an interesting option. } ) 12. Kh1 { This is the main move here and rightly so: it's good to avoid a check on the g1-a7 diagonal. } 12... b5 ( { I like this idea. White cannot keep his centre together. } 12... Nc5 { is actually played more often. } ) 13. e5 { White breaks in the centre before taking on b5. } 13... dxe5 14. Nxb5 exf4 { Clarifying the situation in the centre. } 15. Nxc4 Ba6 { The idea is to play ...Nb6 after White defends his knight on b5. } *

