1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f4 { is the Queen's Gambit Declined.I don't think many white players are well prepared in the f4 line since Black can avoid it in several ways. So, if we're up for a challenge and want to play for a win, we should allow White to choose whatever setup he wants in our favourite opening! } 7... Bg7 { We're one step from castling, but not quite there! } 8. e5 { This is called the Mikenas Attack, after the Lithuanian International Master Vladas Mikenas. It's an aggressive line, but Black has good resources. } 8... Nfd7 ( { I prefer this although } 8... dxe5 { is possible as well. } ) 9. Nb5 ( { This is actually the point of White's early e5. Black will be deprived of the right to castle. } 9. Ne4 dxe5 { leads to the same position after } 10. Nd6+ { . } ) 9... dxe5 10. Nd6+ Ke7 { It's better to get rid of the knight immediately. } 11. Nxc8+ Qxc8 12. Nf3 Rd8 ( { Black’s aim is to attack the d5-pawn quickly after ...Nb6. } 12... Re8 { is played more often and is also a good move. } ) 13. fxe5 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. Bc4 Bd4 ( { We don't allow White to castle. } 15... Qf5 { is also good, for example } 16. Qe2 Nd7 17. Bh6 Kd6 18. Rf1 Qh5 19. Qxh5 gxh5 20. Rxf7 Rg8 { with an equal endgame. } ) 16. Qf3 Re8 17. Bh6 { White doesn't allow our king to f8 and prepares O-O-O. } 17... Kd6+ { The king is safe in the centre as well! } 18. Be2 Qf5 ( { I prefer to exchange queens, even if it will cost us a pawn. In return we'll get a good endgame with active pieces. Our king will be a strong piece. Alternatively } 18... Nd7 { is also possible. } ) 19. Qxf5 gxf5 20. Rf1 Nd7 { There is no good way to defend the f5-pawn, so we continue developing. } 21. Rxf5 f6 { Defending the remaining f-pawn. } 22. Bf4+ Be5 { The ending is about equal. Black’s king on d6 is a strong piece. } *

