2. O-O Na6 13. e5 { and White has an initiative. } ) 10. Nf3 Na6 ( { It makes sense to develop the knight this way. We keep the option open to jump to either c7 or b4. } 10... Nf6 { would be too slow. } ) 11. O-O Nb4 { The knight has reached its desired square. It cannot be expelled from b4, and it controls important squares like d5, d3, c2. } ( { I'm not so fond of } 11... Nc7 { , as I think in that case White achieves a nice setup, while we are struggling to show any counterplay. } ) 12. Kh1 a6 { We ask White where he wants to retreat his bishop to. } ( { A useful move, preparing } 12... -- 13. f5 Ne5 14. Bg5 { when there is no ...Nxf3 with check. } ) 13. Bc4 { An active but exposed position for the bishop. } 13... Nb6 ( { We immediately attack the bishop, at the same time preparing ...Bg4. } 13... Re8 { is also possible. } ) 14. Be2 Bg4 { Of course we exchange this bishop. } 15. h3 Bxf3 16. Rxf3 Nd7 { We have good squares for our pieces, so the position is fully playable. On the next couple of moves we can activate the queen and the rooks. } *

