1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f4 { is the Queen's Gambit Declined.I don't think many white players are well prepared in the f4 line since Black can avoid it in several ways. So, if we're up for a challenge and want to play for a win, we should allow White to choose whatever setup he wants in our favourite opening! } 7... Bg7 { We're one step from castling, but not quite there! } 8. Bb5+ { An important check. White is hindering our normal development. This is called the Taimanov Variation or Taimanov Attack. It was analyzed by Mark Taimanov in 1956 and played in 1957 against Trifunovic (according to my database). The line became very popular in the early 1980s when Kasparov played it with White. } 8... Nfd7 ( { This is the only good reply. Both } 8... Bd7 9. e5 { and } ) ( 8... Nbd7 9. e5 { give White an advantage after some forcing lines. However, after 8... Nfd7 our knight is slightly misplaced on d7, and in some lines we may have to bring it back to f6. Another important point is that for the moment we cannot play ...Bg4.With the knight on d7 we do get some additional options: we can develop the other knight to a6 and from there to b4 or c7, or we can even play ...Nb6. } ) 9. a4 { According to my database this was first played by Lutikov in 1959. A few years later Zaitsev started to use it regularly, and in the early 80s Garry Kasparov got a few wins with this move. By playing 9. a4 White prevents us from expanding on the queenside with ...a6 and ...b5. He also remains flexible about the b5-bishop; when attacked it can go to either d3 or e2.However White gives us the b4-square which we can use for the knight. It is debatable whether the knight on b4 will be a strong piece or not, as it may lack targets to attack. Therefore Black will have to play dynamically, but that's what the Benoni is about! } 9... O-O ( { A natural move. The alternative would be } 9... Qh4+ { when I think White is better. For example } 10. g3 Qe7 11. Nf3 O-O 12. O-O Na6 13. e5 { and White has an initiative. } ) 10. Nf3 Na6 ( { It makes sense to develop the knight this way. We keep the option open to jump to either c7 or b4. } 10... Nf6 { would be too slow. } ) 11. O-O Nb4 { The knight has reached its desired square. It cannot be expelled from b4, and it controls important squares like d5, d3, c2. } ( { I'm not so fond of } 11... Nc7 { , as I think in that case White achieves a nice setup, while we are struggling to show any counterplay. } ) 12. Kh1 a6 { We ask White where he wants to retreat his bishop to. } ( { A useful move, preparing } 12... -- 13. f5 Ne5 14. Bg5 { when there is no ...Nxf3 with check. } ) 13. Bxd7 { This is a concrete continuation. White doesn't waste time returning his bishop and gets rid of the knight on d7 which was controlling the critical f6- and e5- squares. } 13... Bxd7 14. f5 gxf5 { Yes, this move is possible and good. Black takes a pawn. } 15. Bg5 { Developing with tempo. This is the point of White's play. } 15... f6 { This looks ugly but again, it's a typical move. We gain a tempo and consolidate our position. The bishop on g7 gets shut in, but it still defends the king, and all our other pieces are active. Finally, Black is still a pawn up. } 16. Bf4 Re8 ( { Activating the rook. This is more precise than } 16... Qe7 { when the queen comes under an X-ray after } 17. Re1 { with the idea exf5. } ) 17. Nd2 { White defends his pawn and is ready to take on d6. } 17... Nd3 { The knight takes up the opportunity to sneak into White's position. This is possible because White has exchanged his light-squared bishop. } 18. Bxd6 fxe4 { We're one move away from freeing our g7-bishop with ...f5. } 19. Ndxe4 c4 { This move consolidates the knight on d3 and prepares both ...f5 and ...Nxb2. } ( { In the game ½-½ (47) Wen, Y (2592)-Idani, P (2508) Yerevan 2014 Black preferred } 19... Nxb2 { but after } 20. Qb3 Nxa4 21. Nxa4 Bxa4 22. Rxa4 b5 23. Qg3 { White got a strong attack. The line I recommend is safer and less forcing. } ) 20. Bg3 { Making room for the knight on d6. } 20... f5 { Finally the g7-bishop is freed. } 21. Nd6 Nxb2 { We have to take this pawn in order to put pressure on the long diagonal. } 22. Qd2 Nd3 { With the dark-squared bishop active again and a nice knight on d3, Black is doing fine. There is no need to be concerned about the exchange sacrifice, Black's play in the Benoni is all about activity! } *

