2. O-O Na6 13. e5 { and White has an initiative. } ) 10. Nf3 Na6 ( { It makes sense to develop the knight this way. We keep the option open to jump to either c7 or b4. } 10... Nf6 { would be too slow. } ) 11. O-O Nb4 { The knight has reached its desired square. It cannot be expelled from b4, and it controls important squares like d5, d3, c2. } ( { I'm not so fond of } 11... Nc7 { , as I think in that case White achieves a nice setup, while we are struggling to show any counterplay. } ) 12. h3 { I like this move. The idea is to retreat the bishop to c4 and not allow ...Bg4 after ...Nb6. } 12... a6 { We drive the bishop back. } 13. Bc4 { This is the point. On e2 the bishop would be less active. } 13... Nb6 { This is my recommendation if we want to avoid forced lines. We attack the bishop again, but the b6-knight is exposed to a4-a5. } 14. Bb3 { White keeps the bishop more actively positioned, but also exposed to a potential ...c4. } 14... Re8 { Activating the rook. If White goes a5 we'll be able to break the position open on the queenside with ...b5/b6 later on. } 15. a5 { It is tempting to drive our knight back. } 15... Nd7 { Preparing ...b5. } 16. f5 { White starts his attack. } 16... b5 { It's time to start our own counterplay. } 17. axb6 { White can’t really allow us to push ...c4. } 17... Qxb6 { The right recapture, as the knight is well placed on d7. } 18. Kh1 { White parries the discovered check threat. } 18... Nd3 { A useful move in order to exchange some pieces. } 19. Na4 { This doesn't win a piece, as Black has } 19... Qb5 { This is the only way to defend the knight on d3, but it's quite enough. } *

