2. O-O Na6 13. e5 { and White has an initiative. } ) 10. Nf3 Na6 ( { It makes sense to develop the knight this way. We keep the option open to jump to either c7 or b4. } 10... Nf6 { would be too slow. } ) 11. O-O Nb4 { The knight has reached its desired square. It cannot be expelled from b4, and it controls important squares like d5, d3, c2. } ( { I'm not so fond of } 11... Nc7 { , as I think in that case White achieves a nice setup, while we are struggling to show any counterplay. } ) 12. h3 { I like this move. The idea is to retreat the bishop to c4 and not allow ...Bg4 after ...Nb6. } 12... a6 { We drive the bishop back. } 13. Bc4 { This is the point. On e2 the bishop would be less active. } 13... Nb6 { This is my recommendation if we want to avoid forced lines. We attack the bishop again, but the b6-knight is exposed to a4-a5. } 14. Bb3 { White keeps the bishop more actively positioned, but also exposed to a potential ...c4. } 14... Re8 { Activating the rook. If White goes a5 we'll be able to break the position open on the queenside with ...b5/b6 later on. } 15. f5 { The typical way to develop an initiative in these positions. } 15... c4 { Black makes use of the knight on b6 to get counterplay. } 16. Bc2 Nd7 { This is important. The knight did its job on b6 and now relocates to greener pastures. } 17. Bg5 { White develops the bishop with tempo. } 17... Bf6 { Other moves are also possible, but the bishop on g5 is annoying so we'd rather exchange it. } 18. fxg6 { Sooner or later White has to go for this in order to open the f-file. } 18... hxg6 ( { We take back like this in order to keep control over the e6-square. Taking the bishop with } 18... Bxg5 { would be very unfortunate because of } 19. gxf7+ { winning. } ) 19. Bxf6 { It is good to exchange the bishops. } 19... Qxf6 { We leave the knight on d7 so that it can occupy the e5- or c5-square. } 20. Qd2 { Connecting the rooks and threatening Ng5. } 20... Nxc2 { The knight on b4 has done its job. } 21. Qxc2 Nc5 { With a playable position, Black will continue with ...Bd7 and ...Qg7. } *

