2. O-O Na6 13. e5 { and White has an initiative. } ) 10. Nf3 Na6 ( { It makes sense to develop the knight this way. We keep the option open to jump to either c7 or b4. } 10... Nf6 { would be too slow. } ) 11. O-O Nb4 { The knight has reached its desired square. It cannot be expelled from b4, and it controls important squares like d5, d3, c2. } ( { I'm not so fond of } 11... Nc7 { , as I think in that case White achieves a nice setup, while we are struggling to show any counterplay. } ) 12. h3 { I like this move. The idea is to retreat the bishop to c4 and not allow ...Bg4 after ...Nb6. } 12... a6 { We drive the bishop back. } 13. Bc4 { This is the point. On e2 the bishop would be less active. } 13... Nb6 { This is my recommendation if we want to avoid forced lines. We attack the bishop again, but the b6-knight is exposed to a4-a5. } 14. Be2 { The bishop is safe here but less active. } 14... Re8 { The rook is better placed here, although we are not really threatening to take the e4-pawn yet. } 15. Re1 { A prophylactic move. After moving the e2-bishop away, the rook will be ready to support the e5 push. } 15... h6 16. Bf1 { A natural move, activating the rook on e1. } ( { It is useful for Black to control the g5-square. This can be seen in the event of White's pushing f4-f5 when he cannot follow up with Bg5. Moreover, Black can now consider } 16. -- f5 { , since after } 17. e5 dxe5 { the pawn on d5 is hanging. } ) 16... f5 { The right moment for counterplay in the centre. } 17. e5 { Otherwise we just take on e4. } 17... dxe5 { Of course we cannot allow e6. } 18. Nxe5 { So as not to lose a pawn, White counterattacks the g6-pawn. } 18... N6xd5 { it's an achievement that we have managed to get rid of the d5-pawn. However, White in turn gets the g6-pawn, which means our king’s position is weakened. } 19. Nxd5 { First White has to get rid of the knight on b4. } 19... Nxd5 20. Nxg6 ( { Another line is } 20. Bc4 Be6 21. Nxg6 Nxf4 { , which works out well for Black. } ) 20... Rxe1 { I think it's good to exchange a pair of rooks, although other moves are possible as well. } 21. Qxe1 Nb4 { With a fighting position. Black's active pieces compensate for the slightly weakened king’s position. } *

