1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f4 { is the Queen's Gambit Declined.I don't think many white players are well prepared in the f4 line since Black can avoid it in several ways. So, if we're up for a challenge and want to play for a win, we should allow White to choose whatever setup he wants in our favourite opening! } 7... Bg7 { We're one step from castling, but not quite there! } 8. Bb5+ { An important check. White is hindering our normal development. This is called the Taimanov Variation or Taimanov Attack. It was analyzed by Mark Taimanov in 1956 and played in 1957 against Trifunovic (according to my database). The line became very popular in the early 1980s when Kasparov played it with White. } 8... Nfd7 ( { This is the only good reply. Both } 8... Bd7 9. e5 { and } ) ( 8... Nbd7 9. e5 { give White an advantage after some forcing lines. However, after 8... Nfd7 our knight is slightly misplaced on d7, and in some lines we may have to bring it back to f6. Another important point is that for the moment we cannot play ...Bg4.With the knight on d7 we do get some additional options: we can develop the other knight to a6 and from there to b4 or c7, or we can even play ...Nb6. } ) 9. a4 { According to my database this was first played by Lutikov in 1959. A few years later Zaitsev started to use it regularly, and in the early 80s Garry Kasparov got a few wins with this move. By playing 9. a4 White prevents us from expanding on the queenside with ...a6 and ...b5. He also remains flexible about the b5-bishop; when attacked it can go to either d3 or e2.However White gives us the b4-square which we can use for the knight. It is debatable whether the knight on b4 will be a strong piece or not, as it may lack targets to attack. Therefore Black will have to play dynamically, but that's what the Benoni is about! } 9... O-O ( { A natural move. The alternative would be } 9... Qh4+ { when I think White is better. For example } 10. g3 Qe7 11. Nf3 O-O 12. O-O Na6 13. e5 { and White has an initiative. } ) 10. Nf3 Na6 ( { It makes sense to develop the knight this way. We keep the option open to jump to either c7 or b4. } 10... Nf6 { would be too slow. } ) 11. O-O Nb4 { The knight has reached its desired square. It cannot be expelled from b4, and it controls important squares like d5, d3, c2. } ( { I'm not so fond of } 11... Nc7 { , as I think in that case White achieves a nice setup, while we are struggling to show any counterplay. } ) 12. h3 { I like this move. The idea is to retreat the bishop to c4 and not allow ...Bg4 after ...Nb6. } 12... a6 { We drive the bishop back. } 13. Bc4 { This is the point. On e2 the bishop would be less active. } 13... f5 { This is an interesting and direct approach. We break White's centre at once. } 14. e5 { This is critical. It's the start of a long forcing line, where both sides must know what they are doing. } 14... dxe5 { We cannot leave White with that pawn chain! } 15. d6+ { This discovered check is White’s idea. Not only will the d6-pawn be a thorn in Black's position, but the c4-bishop gains new perspectives as well. } 15... Kh8 16. Ng5 { The knight joins the fight. It wants to jump to e6, because if it goes to f7 we can just take it. } 16... e4 { Now we have a  strong passed pawn in the centre. There was no time to try to save the exchange. } 17. Nf7+ Rxf7 { Yes, we gladly give up the exchange for this monster knight. } 18. Bxf7 Nf8 { What a turnaround! White's position is strategically lost despite being an exchange up. ...Nd3 is the main threat, after which the d6-pawn falls. ...Be6 in order to exchange the bishops and bring the f8-knight into play is another strong idea. } *

