2. O-O Na6 13. e5 { and White has an initiative. } ) 10. Nf3 Na6 ( { It makes sense to develop the knight this way. We keep the option open to jump to either c7 or b4. } 10... Nf6 { would be too slow. } ) 11. O-O Nb4 { The knight has reached its desired square. It cannot be expelled from b4, and it controls important squares like d5, d3, c2. } ( { I'm not so fond of } 11... Nc7 { , as I think in that case White achieves a nice setup, while we are struggling to show any counterplay. } ) 12. h3 { I like this move. The idea is to retreat the bishop to c4 and not allow ...Bg4 after ...Nb6. } 12... a6 { We drive the bishop back. } 13. Bc4 { This is the point. On e2 the bishop would be less active. } 13... f5 { This is an interesting and direct approach. We break White's centre at once. } 14. e5 { This is critical. It's the start of a long forcing line, where both sides must know what they are doing. } 14... dxe5 { We cannot leave White with that pawn chain! } 15. d6+ { This discovered check is White’s idea. Not only will the d6-pawn be a thorn in Black's position, but the c4-bishop gains new perspectives as well. } 15... Kh8 16. Ng5 { The knight joins the fight. It wants to jump to e6, because if it goes to f7 we can just take it. } 16... e4 { Now we have a  strong passed pawn in the centre. There was no time to try to save the exchange. } 17. Ne6 { Obviously only like this should White win the exchange. } 17... Qf6 { The most active square for the queen. } 18. Nxf8 { Again, it is wrong to go for the rook. The value of the pieces is relative, and here the g7-bishop is more important than the rook on f8. } 18... Qd4+ { This in-between move helps us get control over the position. } 19. Qxd4 { Forced, as otherwise the c4-bishop falls. } 19... Bxd4+ 20. Kh2 Nxf8 { Black's pieces dominate the board. Black has a strong passed pawn on e4 while White's pawn on d6 is likely to fall soon. } *

