2. O-O Na6 13. e5 { and White has an initiative. } ) 10. Nf3 Na6 ( { It makes sense to develop the knight this way. We keep the option open to jump to either c7 or b4. } 10... Nf6 { would be too slow. } ) 11. O-O Nb4 { The knight has reached its desired square. It cannot be expelled from b4, and it controls important squares like d5, d3, c2. } ( { I'm not so fond of } 11... Nc7 { , as I think in that case White achieves a nice setup, while we are struggling to show any counterplay. } ) 12. Be3 { This move makes sense. The point is to bring the bishop to f2 and then h4. } 12... a6 13. Bc4 { On this square the bishop will be exposed to ...Nb6. } 13... Re8 { First we activate the rook. } 14. Bf2 Nb6 { Next, we attack the bishop. } 15. Nd2 { White parries both threats at the same time. } 15... Bd7 ( { It's important to finish our development. A huge positional blunder would be } 15... Nxc4 { when after } 16. Nxc4 { Black would be strategically lost. For example, after } 16... b6 17. f5 Ra7 18. Bg3 { the pressure on d6 is annoying. } 18... Bf8 19. Rf2 { White keeps c2 under control and prepares Qf3. Black has no counterplay and is probably already lost. } ) 16. Be2 a5 { Black has secured his knight on b6 and is ready to break in the centre with ...f5. } *

