2. O-O Na6 13. e5 { and White has an initiative. } ) 10. Nf3 Na6 ( { It makes sense to develop the knight this way. We keep the option open to jump to either c7 or b4. } 10... Nf6 { would be too slow. } ) 11. O-O Nb4 { The knight has reached its desired square. It cannot be expelled from b4, and it controls important squares like d5, d3, c2. } ( { I'm not so fond of } 11... Nc7 { , as I think in that case White achieves a nice setup, while we are struggling to show any counterplay. } ) 12. Re1 { This is played the most often. White makes room for the bishop to come to f1. He will play h3 in order not to allow Black to exchange his light-squared bishop by playing ...Bg4. Afterwards White's plan is to play either Bd2 or Be3 with a nice grip on the position. } 12... a6 { This had to be played in any case. } 13. Bf1 { Of course the bishop returns home. } 13... Re8 { A useful move, aimed at parrying e5. } 14. Bd2 { Developing the bishop. This move is actually not so easy to meet. } 14... f5 ( { I think this has to be done, otherwise we get a passive position as shown in the line } 14... Nf6 15. Bc4 Bg4 16. Rc1 Nd7 17. h3 Bxf3 18. Qxf3 Rb8 { . White can slowly improve his position further, while we can only sit and wait. } ) 15. exf5 { Although this spoils our structure, it gives us control over the e4-square. } 15... Rxe1 { It's better to exchange the rooks directly. If we delay it White would bring the other rook to e1. } 16. Bxe1 gxf5 17. Bh4 Nf6 { We bring our pieces into play and get a good position. } 18. Qb3 Qf8 { We remove the queen from the pin and prepare to play ...Bd7 followed by ...Re8. Black is fine. If White tries } 19. Re1 { we can respond } ( { Or if } 19. Ng5 { directly there is } 19... h6 20. Ne6 Bxe6 21. dxe6 d5 { We need to shut out White’s queen. } 22. Bxf6 Qxf6 23. Nxd5 Qd4+ { In order to force the white knight back. } 24. Ne3 Qxb2 { and after we swap the queens we have ...Bd4. } ) 19... h6 { and prevent Ng5. } *

