 e5 { Black needs to develop the knight to c7 via a6. } ) ( 12... Re8 { is a useful move, but afterwards Black still needs to go ... Na6. That's why I prefer to play ...Na6 directly and try to bring the knight to c7 faster. } ) 13. f5 { This is the direct approach, although it has only been played in a correspondence game. } 13... Nf6 ( { The knight comes back to the defence. An alternative would be } 13... Ne5 { but then after the exchange on e5 I think White can develop his pieces and slowly push on the kingside. } ) 14. Bg5 { This is interesting, but I'd be reluctant as White to exchange the important dark-squared bishop. However afterwards White can push g4 and try to get a grip on the kingside. } 14... h6 { Let's get rid of that bishop! } 15. Bxf6 { If White retreats the bishop we occupy the e-file and get ready to play ...c4. For example: } ( 15. Bd2 Re8 16. fxg6 fxg6 17. Nh4 { In order to attack the weakened pawns. } 17... Bh3 18. Rf2 c4 19. Nxg6 Nc5 { with counterplay - one of the knights is coming to e4. } ) 15... Qxf6 16. fxg6 Bh3 ( { This intermediate move is important. Black completes his development with tempo and has a good position. Wrong would be } 16... fxg6 { because of } 17. e5 { with a strong initiative for White. } ) ( { After } 16... Bh3 { a possible continuation is: } 17. e5 { It's good for White to close the diagonal of our bishop and gain the e4-square for his knight. } 17... dxe5 18. gxf7+ Qxf7 19. Qb3 c4 { We need to get the a6-knight into play via c5. } 20. Bxc4 Nc5 21. Qb5 Qh5 22. Qxc5 Bxf1 23. Rxf1 Rxf3 24. d6+ Kh8 { With an unclear position. White has enough compensation for the exchange, but we can also create threats against the white king. } ) *

