 e5 { Black needs to develop the knight to c7 via a6. } ) ( 12... Re8 { is a useful move, but afterwards Black still needs to go ... Na6. That's why I prefer to play ...Na6 directly and try to bring the knight to c7 faster. } ) 13. f5 { This is the direct approach, although it has only been played in a correspondence game. } 13... Nf6 ( { The knight comes back to the defence. An alternative would be } 13... Ne5 { but then after the exchange on e5 I think White can develop his pieces and slowly push on the kingside. } ) 14. Bg5 { This is interesting, but I'd be reluctant as White to exchange the important dark-squared bishop. However afterwards White can push g4 and try to get a grip on the kingside. } 14... h6 { Let's get rid of that bishop! } 15. Bxf6 { If White retreats the bishop we occupy the e-file and get ready to play ...c4. For example: } ( 15. Bd2 Re8 16. fxg6 fxg6 17. Nh4 { In order to attack the weakened pawns. } 17... Bh3 18. Rf2 c4 19. Nxg6 Nc5 { with counterplay - one of the knights is coming to e4. } ) 15... Qxf6 16. g4 { White achieves his main idea. } 16... c4 { If allowed, White will play Qd2, Rf2 and Raf1 increasing his initiative. That's why with this pawn sacrifice we intend to activate our pieces as quickly as possible. Our plan is easy to guess: the knight goes to c5, bishop to d7, ...Rfe8, ...Rac8, always keeping in mind ideas like the ...b5 push. } 17. Bxc4 { What else? } 17... Nc5 { We bring the knight into play. } 18. Qd2 Bd7 { Next is our bishop. } 19. Rae1 { White needs to defend the e4-pawn, as already ...b5 was a threat. } 19... Rfe8 { Black gets enough activity to compensate for the pawn. Next there comes ...b5-b4 driving White's pieces backwards. } *

