1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f4 { is the Queen's Gambit Declined.I don't think many white players are well prepared in the f4 line since Black can avoid it in several ways. So, if we're up for a challenge and want to play for a win, we should allow White to choose whatever setup he wants in our favourite opening! } 7... Bg7 { We're one step from castling, but not quite there! } 8. Bb5+ { An important check. White is hindering our normal development. This is called the Taimanov Variation or Taimanov Attack. It was analyzed by Mark Taimanov in 1956 and played in 1957 against Trifunovic (according to my database). The line became very popular in the early 1980s when Kasparov played it with White. } 8... Nfd7 ( { This is the only good reply. Both } 8... Bd7 9. e5 { and } ) ( 8... Nbd7 9. e5 { give White an advantage after some forcing lines. However, after 8... Nfd7 our knight is slightly misplaced on d7, and in some lines we may have to bring it back to f6. Another important point is that for the moment we cannot play ...Bg4.With the knight on d7 we do get some additional options: we can develop the other knight to a6 and from there to b4 or c7, or we can even play ...Nb6. } ) 9. Be2 { it doesn't defend the e4-pawn. However, with our knight on d7 the e4-pawn is not really under attack, and there is a more subtle nuance: after } 9... Qh4+ ( { this is a tricky move. Apparently the bishop is less active than on d3, as from } 9... O-O 10. Nf3 { there is no } 10... Nf6 { as White can push } 11. e5 { since his d5-pawn is defended. } ) ( { This loses a tempo but slightly weakens White's kingside. After we move the knight from d7 we'll be able to exchange our light-squared bishop. } 9... O-O { is seen more often. } ) 10. g3 Qd8 { I prefer the queen here, as although it seems a bit more active on e7 she is often exposed after an eventual sequence of  e5, ...dxe5 d6. } 11. Nf3 O-O 12. O-O Na6 ( { Since } 12... Nf6 { doesn't work in view of } 13. e5 { Black needs to develop the knight to c7 via a6. } ) ( 12... Re8 { is a useful move, but afterwards Black still needs to go ... Na6. That's why I prefer to play ...Na6 directly and try to bring the knight to c7 faster. } ) 13. f5 { This is the direct approach, although it has only been played in a correspondence game. } 13... Nf6 ( { The knight comes back to the defence. An alternative would be } 13... Ne5 { but then after the exchange on e5 I think White can develop his pieces and slowly push on the kingside. } ) 14. fxg6 { White wants to make use of the open f-file. } 14... hxg6 { It turns out this is the better capture. Although taking with the f-pawn would open our rook, it would also weaken the e6-square, which might become unpleasant after Ng5 and Bf4. } 15. Bg5 Bh3 { It's good to make use of weakened White kingside and develop with tempo. } 16. Rf2 { The exchange sacrifice would lead nowhere. } 16... Qb6 { I analyzed this position for a long time and came to the conclusion that 16… Qb6 is the best move. White's initiative may be dangerous, but we have enough resources to defend. } 17. Nd2 Qxb2 { We attack the c3-knight, thus indirectly defending the f6-knight. A possible continuation is } 18. Rc1 Ng4 19. Nc4 Bd4 20. Nxb2 Nxf2 { with perpetual check. Quite a nice line! } *

