 e5 { Black needs to develop the knight to c7 via a6. } ) ( 12... Re8 { is a useful move, but afterwards Black still needs to go ... Na6. That's why I prefer to play ...Na6 directly and try to bring the knight to c7 faster. } ) 13. f5 { This is the direct approach, although it has only been played in a correspondence game. } 13... Nf6 ( { The knight comes back to the defence. An alternative would be } 13... Ne5 { but then after the exchange on e5 I think White can develop his pieces and slowly push on the kingside. } ) 14. fxg6 { White wants to make use of the open f-file. } 14... hxg6 { It turns out this is the better capture. Although taking with the f-pawn would open our rook, it would also weaken the e6-square, which might become unpleasant after Ng5 and Bf4. } 15. Bg5 Bh3 { It's good to make use of weakened White kingside and develop with tempo. } 16. Rf2 { The exchange sacrifice would lead nowhere. } 16... Qb6 { I analyzed this position for a long time and came to the conclusion that 16… Qb6 is the best move. White's initiative may be dangerous, but we have enough resources to defend. } 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. e5 { A typical break-through. White makes room for his knight to come to e4. } 18... dxe5 { The position is very concrete and we have to act quickly. ...Bf5 to prevent Ne4 and ...c4 to bring the knight to c5 are our main ideas. } 19. Ne4 c4 { We open a path for the knight to come to c5. } 20. Nxf6+ Qxf6 21. Qd2 Bd7 ( { Preventing Ng5. Also interesting is } 21... e4 { , for example } 22. Ng5 Qe5 23. Qf4 Qxf4 24. Rxf4 Bf5 25. Bxc4 Nc5 26. g4 f6 { with a balanced endgame. } ) 22. Bxc4 b5 { Removing the bishop from its active position. } 23. Bf1 e4 { We need to act quickly. } 24. Ng5 Qe5 { Precision is still required because the position is open, but overall Black is fine. } *

