1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f4 { is the Queen's Gambit Declined.I don't think many white players are well prepared in the f4 line since Black can avoid it in several ways. So, if we're up for a challenge and want to play for a win, we should allow White to choose whatever setup he wants in our favourite opening! } 7... Bg7 { We're one step from castling, but not quite there! } 8. Bb5+ { An important check. White is hindering our normal development. This is called the Taimanov Variation or Taimanov Attack. It was analyzed by Mark Taimanov in 1956 and played in 1957 against Trifunovic (according to my database). The line became very popular in the early 1980s when Kasparov played it with White. } 8... Nfd7 ( { This is the only good reply. Both } 8... Bd7 9. e5 { and } ) ( 8... Nbd7 9. e5 { give White an advantage after some forcing lines. However, after 8... Nfd7 our knight is slightly misplaced on d7, and in some lines we may have to bring it back to f6. Another important point is that for the moment we cannot play ...Bg4.With the knight on d7 we do get some additional options: we can develop the other knight to a6 and from there to b4 or c7, or we can even play ...Nb6. } ) 9. Bd3 { White retreats the bishop to an active square and prevents the expansion with ...a6 and ...b5. } 9... O-O ( { I prefer this to the other main move } 9... Qh4+ { . } ) 10. Nf3 Nf6 ( { I have deeply analyzed this position, and I also considered the interesting possibility } 10... Qa5 11. Bd2 Re8 { However, 10...Nf6 is more natural and gives us a typical Benoni position. } ) 11. h3 { This move is too slow here. } ( { This move is possible because after } 11. e5 { the d5-pawn is hanging, as the bishop on d3 prevents White's queen from controlling the d5-square. Yes, Black loses a tempo, but now we want to get rid of our light-squared bishop with ...Bg4. } ) 11... c4 { Black is just in time with his counterplay. These pawn sacrifices should always be considered, especially if the opponent hasn't castled yet. } 12. Bxc4 Re8 { This is the point. Black intends to regain his sacrificed pawn by taking on e4. } 13. e5 { It's better for White to give the pawn back like this. } 13... dxe5 14. fxe5 Nbd7 15. O-O ( { In case of } 15. e6 { it's interesting to continue with } 15... Qc7 16. Bb3 Qg3+ 17. Kf1 fxe6 18. Be3 exd5 19. Nxd5 Kh8 20. Bf4 Nxd5 21. Bxg3 Ne3+ 22. Kf2 Nxd1+ 23. Rhxd1 Nc5 { with an edge for Black. } ) 15... Qb6+ { This is the most precise. Before taking back the pawn Black wants see how White responds to this check. } 16. Kh1 Nh5 { This is very strong. We're threatening to win an exchange with ...Ng3+, and if White defends against the threat we simply take the e5-pawn, after which White's attacking chances are gone. } *

