s development. } 13... a6 { is also possible, but probably it will just transpose back to 13... Nbd7. } ) 14. Be3 { The bishop prevents any checks on the g1-a7 diagonal and later on could go to h4 via f2. } 14... a6 { Now its a good moment to include this move. } 15. a4 Qa5 { The idea is to play ...Qb4 threatening both ...c4 and the b2-pawn. Also it comes in handy to bring either rook to e8. } 16. Kh1 { Even though he has the bishop on e3, it's useful to remove the king from the g1-a7 diagonal. } 16... Qb4 ( { I prefer to play this move immediately. } 16... Rfe8 { was played in 1-0 (32) Shulman,Y (2563)-Mikkelsen,N (2421) Reykjavik 2013. } ) 17. Rfb1 c4 { It’s time to get the counterplay going! Black gives up the d4-square but in return he gets the important c5-square for the knight and also achieves control over the b3- and d3-squares. } 18. Bc2 Nc5 19. a5 Nfd7 { Everything is going according to plan. Black's queen cannot be trapped, and we intend to play ...b5/...b6 in order to break open the queenside. } *

