1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Nf3 a6 { I recommend this move as White cannot parry both ...b5 and ...Bg4. Thus we manage to solve some of Black’s strategical problems in the position. } 8. h3 { I think this is a strong move. White prevents ...Bg4 once and for all and is going to get a nice setup with Bd3 and Bf4, putting pressure on the d6-pawn. } 8... b5 { Otherwise we would allow White to play a4 and Bd3. } 9. Bd3 Bg7 10. O-O O-O 11. a3 { This is a prophylactic move. White prevents ...b4 just in case and after Bf4 and Rc1 he intends to play b4 himself. } 11... Nbd7 ( { We can go for the same setup with ...Qe7. White's move order gives us a wider choice. Some players have tried } 11... Re8 { followed by ...Ra7-e7, although I'm not convinced of that plan. } ) 12. Bg5 { This pin doesn't really annoy us. } 12... h6 ( { We can play this before White goes Qd2. Alternatively, we could of course just go for a normal position with } 12... Re8 { followed by ...Bb7, ...Qb6 and so on. } ) 13. Bf4 Qe7 { We defend d6 while keeping the queen close to the kingside. } 14. Re1 { White prepares e5 in case we expand too much on the kingside. } 14... c4 { Depending on where the bishop goes, we decide where to put the d7-knight. If the bishop goes to c2 the knight is better off on e5; if on the other hand goes to f1, then the knight has a good spot on c5. } 15. Bc2 Nh5 { It's good to include this first in order to get better control over the dark squares. } 16. Bh2 Ne5 { With active play on the kingside. } *

