1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Nf3 a6 { I recommend this move as White cannot parry both ...b5 and ...Bg4. Thus we manage to solve some of Black’s strategical problems in the position. } 8. h3 { I think this is a strong move. White prevents ...Bg4 once and for all and is going to get a nice setup with Bd3 and Bf4, putting pressure on the d6-pawn. } 8... b5 { Otherwise we would allow White to play a4 and Bd3. } 9. Bd3 Bg7 10. O-O O-O 11. a3 { This is a prophylactic move. White prevents ...b4 just in case and after Bf4 and Rc1 he intends to play b4 himself. } 11... Nbd7 ( { We can go for the same setup with ...Qe7. White's move order gives us a wider choice. Some players have tried } 11... Re8 { followed by ...Ra7-e7, although I'm not convinced of that plan. } ) 12. Bf4 Qe7 ( { The preferred setup. In this move order } 12... Qb6 { is possible as well, because White doesn't have a4 (he has already played a3). } ) 13. Re1 Re8 { ...Re8 is a useful move, and then we can decide whether to go ...Nh5 or ...Bb7. } 14. Qd2 Qf8 { This transposes to the 11. Bf4 Qe7 move order - see variation. } *

