1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Nf3 a6 { I recommend this move as White cannot parry both ...b5 and ...Bg4. Thus we manage to solve some of Black’s strategical problems in the position. } 8. h3 { I think this is a strong move. White prevents ...Bg4 once and for all and is going to get a nice setup with Bd3 and Bf4, putting pressure on the d6-pawn. } 8... b5 { Otherwise we would allow White to play a4 and Bd3. } 9. Bd3 Bg7 10. O-O O-O 11. Bf4 ( { White doesn't make it easy for us to play ...Nbd7. } 11. Re1 { may well transpose after } 11... Nbd7 12. Bf4 Qe7 ( 12... Qb6 { . } ) 13. Qd2 { , although in this line we have the extra option of } ) 11... Qe7 ( { I’ve analyzed this position for a long time. Finally I came to like the idea to develop the knight to d7 quickly. } 11... Qb6 { with the same idea would be wrong because of } 12. a4 b4 13. a5 { with a big advantage, } ) ( { while after } 11... Re8 12. Re1 Ra7 13. a3 Rae7 14. Rc1 Qb6 15. b4 Nbd7 16. Be3 { White keeps some pressure. } ) 12. Qd2 { This is more flexible since White doesn't show yet where he intends to put his rooks. } 12... Nbd7 13. Rfe1 { This is a natural move. The other rook may come to d1 or c1. White has a nice setup, the only drawback is that he has allowed Black to play ...b5. } 13... Re8 { The rook is positioned usefully here to prevent e5. } 14. b3 { Preventing ...c4 and preparing a4 after moving the rook away from a1. } 14... Nh5 { This forces White to make a decision. } 15. Bg5 { White gains a tempo in order to move the a1-rook away from the pin. } 15... Qf8 16. Rac1 Ne5 { The good thing is that we manage to exchange a knight without having to take back with the pawn on e5. After we exchange the e5-knight we retreat  the h5-knight to f6. } *

