[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Nf3 a6 { I recommend this move as White cannot parry both ...b5 and ...Bg4. Thus we manage to solve some of Black’s strategical problems in the position. } 8. Qe2 { This is an interesting idea of GM Vladimir Epishin. White goes for a quick e5, hoping to gain some advantage from this central break. } 8... Bg7 ( { We continue developing in a natural way. } 8... Qe7 { is also interesting, and after } 9. e5 dxe5 10. Nxe5 { Black can challenge White’s knight with } 10... Nbd7 { . } ) 9. e5 { The logical follow-up. Otherwise Black castles and the move 8. Qe2 is not justified. } 9... dxe5 10. Qxe5+ Kf8 { This is forced. The king is not in danger on f8, although it will take some time to bring the Rh8 into play. This will be achieved with ...Kg8, ...h6 and ...Kh7. White’s queen is exposed on e5, so he will lose some time moving the queen away from there. } ( { Before analyzing this line I played it in a couple of blitz games. There I continued } 10... Qe7 { and after } 11. Qxe7+ Kxe7 12. d6+ { my king got into trouble. } ) 11. Bd3 Kg8 ( { Now we are really threatening to play ...Nxd5. It isn't good immediately because after } 11... Nxd5 { White can answer } 12. Bh6 ) 12. O-O Nbd7 { With good play for Black. Our plan is easy: ...b5 and ...Bb7 or ... h6 and ...Kh7. } *

