1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Nf3 a6 { I recommend this move as White cannot parry both ...b5 and ...Bg4. Thus we manage to solve some of Black’s strategical problems in the position. } 8. Qe2 { This is an interesting idea of GM Vladimir Epishin. White goes for a quick e5, hoping to gain some advantage from this central break. } 8... Bg7 ( { We continue developing in a natural way. } 8... Qe7 { is also interesting, and after } 9. e5 dxe5 10. Nxe5 { Black can challenge White’s knight with } 10... Nbd7 { . } ) 9. e5 { The logical follow-up. Otherwise Black castles and the move 8. Qe2 is not justified. } 9... dxe5 10. Qxe5+ Kf8 { This is forced. The king is not in danger on f8, although it will take some time to bring the Rh8 into play. This will be achieved with ...Kg8, ...h6 and ...Kh7. White’s queen is exposed on e5, so he will lose some time moving the queen away from there. } ( { Before analyzing this line I played it in a couple of blitz games. There I continued } 10... Qe7 { and after } 11. Qxe7+ Kxe7 12. d6+ { my king got into trouble. } ) 11. d6 { White pushes his passed pawn as far forward as possible, at the same time attacking the c5-pawn. } 11... Nbd7 { Defending the pawn with tempo. } 12. Qe3 b5 { This is more energetic than bringing our king to safety with ...h6 and  ...Kg8. } 13. a4 b4 14. Ne4 Nxe4 { We have other options as well, which means our position is already promising. These exchanges lead to a nice ending for Black. } 15. Qxe4 Qe8 16. Qxe8+ Kxe8 { It’s not bad for us to have the king in the centre in an endgame. } 17. Be2 Nf8 { I like this rejoinder. It makes room for our king to come to d7. } 18. O-O Ne6 { With the idea of playing ... Kd7 and ...Bb7. The d6-pawn is safely blocked and little by little we'll be able to attack it. For now White cannot move the Bc1 because then we take on b2. } *

