[White "Ch 2: Benoni 6.e4, 7.Nf3: 8th Move Alternatives"]
[Black "8. Be2 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Nf3 a6 { I recommend this move as White cannot parry both ...b5 and ...Bg4. Thus we manage to solve some of Black’s strategical problems in the position. } 8. Be2 { This is a tricky move. White is going for quick development, and we need to be careful about the possibility of e4-e5. } 8... Bg7 ( { We need to continue developing, as otherwise White's e5-push will be strong. For example, } 8... Bg4 { is wrong because of } 9. e5 { White gets a strong initiative. } ) 9. a4 { White prevents ...b5 and prepares Nd2. } 9... Bg4 ( 9... O-O { is not bad, but after } 10. Nd2 { we would get into a different line than the one I covered against this setup, so this is not covered in this repertoire. } ) 10. Nd2 { Otherwise we can exchange the knight on f3. } 10... Bxe2 11. Qxe2 O-O 12. Nc4 { This is the point: White delays castling in order to attack the d6-pawn with Bf4. } 12... Nbd7 ( { We have to go for this pawn sacrifice. The backwards move } 12... Ne8 { is not recommended because after } 13. Bf4 Nd7 14. O-O { White gets a long-lasting hold on the position. } ) 13. Nxd6 { the real test of this variation. } 13... Ne5 { Now there follows a forced sequence. } 14. Nc4 Nxc4 15. Qxc4 Qa5 { We prepare ...b5. } 16. O-O b5 { We open up the position by means of a second pawn sacrifice. } 17. Qxc5 Rfc8 { We need to move this rook (and not the one on a8) in order to keep the a6-pawn defended. } 18. Qd4 { The queen may be exposed on this square. } 18... b4 19. Na2 Re8 { We'll take back a central pawn. } 20. Qxb4 Qxb4 21. Nxb4 Rxe4 { In this particular position it is important that  the a6-pawn is defended. } 22. Nc2 Nxd5 { Black’s active pieces fully compensate for the pawn minus. } *

