[White "Ch 2: Benoni 6.e4, 7.Nf3: 8th Move Alternatives"]
[Black "8. Bd3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Nf3 a6 { I recommend this move as White cannot parry both ...b5 and ...Bg4. Thus we manage to solve some of Black’s strategical problems in the position. } 8. Bd3 Bg4 { We exchange the light-squared bishop and achieve a good position. The b8-knight will have a good square on d7, and we can comfortably develop all our pieces. We'll also get good control over the e5-square, thus making White’s e5-push more difficult to achieve. } *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Modern Benoni"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch 2: Benoni 6.e4, 7.Nf3: 8th Move Alternatives"]
[Black "8. a4 Bg4 9. Qb3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Nf3 a6 { I recommend this move as White cannot parry both ...b5 and ...Bg4. Thus we manage to solve some of Black’s strategical problems in the position. } 8. a4 { Many players would go for this instantly, as they wouldn't like to allow ...b5. However, I think White has more interesting choices, but for that he must delve deep into the position. } 8... Bg4 { Black should go for this move if the move order allows it. } 9. Qb3 { This is a risky move as it allows us to double White’s pawns on the kingside. White realizes that his move order has allowed us to exchange the light-squared bishop, and goes for this last moment resource. } 9... Bxf3 10. gxf3 Nbd7 { We can ignore the threat to the b7-pawn in order to get quick development. } 11. Qxb7 Bg7 { Transposing back to 10. Qxb7. } *

