[Black "8. a4 Bg4 9. Qb3 (alternative 14... Qa5 #3)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Nf3 a6 { I recommend this move as White cannot parry both ...b5 and ...Bg4. Thus we manage to solve some of Black’s strategical problems in the position. } 8. a4 { Many players would go for this instantly, as they wouldn't like to allow ...b5. However, I think White has more interesting choices, but for that he must delve deep into the position. } 8... Bg4 { Black should go for this move if the move order allows it. } 9. Qb3 { This is a risky move as it allows us to double White’s pawns on the kingside. White realizes that his move order has allowed us to exchange the light-squared bishop, and goes for this last moment resource. } 9... Bxf3 10. Qxb7 Nbd7 ( { This is the point. Instead, } 10... Bxg2 { wins back the pawn, but helps White to develop his pieces. } ) 11. gxf3 Bg7 12. Qc6 O-O { There is no time for us to defend the d6-pawn. } 13. Qxd6 Nh5 { With the idea ...Be5 in order to take control over the dark squares. } 14. f4 Qa5 { This is a more materialistic choice. The idea is to play ...Rfd8 or ...Qb4 next. } ( { A logical move as it parries ...Be5, and if } 14... f5 { there is } 15. e5 { . } ) 15. Bd2 Qb4 { Black has plenty of threats: ...Qxb2, ...Bxc3 followed by ...Qxe4+, and also ...Rfd8. } 16. f3 { White defends e4 and is ready to play Nd1. } 16... Qxb2 17. Rb1 ( { After } 17. Rc1 Rfd8 { Finally it's time to defend the d7-knight. Black is fine in the resulting complications, but the position remains very sharp. } ) 17... Qa3 { White is not in time to take on d7 because the c3-knight is hanging. } *

