1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Nf3 a6 { I recommend this move as White cannot parry both ...b5 and ...Bg4. Thus we manage to solve some of Black’s strategical problems in the position. } 8. a4 { Many players would go for this instantly, as they wouldn't like to allow ...b5. However, I think White has more interesting choices, but for that he must delve deep into the position. } 8... Bg4 { Black should go for this move if the move order allows it. } 9. Be2 Bxf3 ( { I prefer to exchange the bishop right away, so as to avoid Nd2-c4. However, it is also possible to play } 9... Bg7 { as this would transpose to the variation 8. Be2 Bg7 9. a4! Bg4 which has been analyzed previously. } ) 10. Bxf3 Nbd7 { This move order is aimed against any e5 break. } ( { For } 10... Bg7 { , see the model game Fedoseev - Livaic. } ) 11. Bf4 Qe7 { We defend the d6-pawn and will continue with ...Bg7. } *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Modern Benoni"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
