1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Nf3 a6 { I recommend this move as White cannot parry both ...b5 and ...Bg4. Thus we manage to solve some of Black’s strategical problems in the position. } 8. a4 { Many players would go for this instantly, as they wouldn't like to allow ...b5. However, I think White has more interesting choices, but for that he must delve deep into the position. } 8... Bg4 { Black should go for this move if the move order allows it. } 9. Be2 Bxf3 ( { I prefer to exchange the bishop right away, so as to avoid Nd2-c4. However, it is also possible to play } 9... Bg7 { as this would transpose to the variation 8. Be2 Bg7 9. a4! Bg4 which has been analyzed previously. } ) 10. Bxf3 Nbd7 { This move order is aimed against any e5 break. } ( { For } 10... Bg7 { , see the model game Fedoseev - Livaic. } ) 11. O-O Bg7 { By exchanging our light-squared bishop we have managed to develop our pieces, establish control over the e5 square and prevent White from pushing e5. On the other hand, White now has the bishop pair and his  e4-pawn is safely defended. White may consider Be2 in the future to prevent us from playing the ...b5 break. } 12. Bf4 Qe7 { The queen is slightly better positioned here than on c7, as we may have ideas to play ...Ne8-c7 later on. } 13. Re1 O-O 14. Qd2 { The queen is well placed here. White intends Be2-f1 in order to prevent ...b5 or ...c4. For the moment he keeps the pawn on a4 so that we cannot push ...b5. } 14... Rab8 { With the idea to push ...b5. } 15. Be2 { White prevents ...b5 and ...c4 ideas. The bishop is more useful for White on the f1-a6 diagonal. } 15... Rfe8 ( { This seems right. Of course, the e4-pawn is untouchable: } 15... Nxe4 16. Nxe4 Qxe4 17. Bg4 { and White wins the knight on d7. } ) 16. Bf1 Ne5 { We're planning both ...c4 and ...Nh5. } 17. Bg5 Qc7 { Black avoids the pin and his idea is the same: to play for ...c4. } *

