1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Nf3 a6 { I recommend this move as White cannot parry both ...b5 and ...Bg4. Thus we manage to solve some of Black’s strategical problems in the position. } 8. a4 { Many players would go for this instantly, as they wouldn't like to allow ...b5. However, I think White has more interesting choices, but for that he must delve deep into the position. } 8... Bg4 { Black should go for this move if the move order allows it. } 9. Be2 Bxf3 ( { I prefer to exchange the bishop right away, so as to avoid Nd2-c4. However, it is also possible to play } 9... Bg7 { as this would transpose to the variation 8. Be2 Bg7 9. a4! Bg4 which has been analyzed previously. } ) 10. Bxf3 Nbd7 { This move order is aimed against any e5 break. } ( { For } 10... Bg7 { , see the model game Fedoseev - Livaic. } ) 11. O-O Bg7 { By exchanging our light-squared bishop we have managed to develop our pieces, establish control over the e5 square and prevent White from pushing e5. On the other hand, White now has the bishop pair and his  e4-pawn is safely defended. White may consider Be2 in the future to prevent us from playing the ...b5 break. } 12. Bf4 Qe7 { The queen is slightly better positioned here than on c7, as we may have ideas to play ...Ne8-c7 later on. } 13. Re1 O-O 14. Qd2 { The queen is well placed here. White intends Be2-f1 in order to prevent ...b5 or ...c4. For the moment he keeps the pawn on a4 so that we cannot push ...b5. } 14... Rab8 { With the idea to push ...b5. } 15. Be2 { White prevents ...b5 and ...c4 ideas. The bishop is more useful for White on the f1-a6 diagonal. } 15... Rfe8 ( { This seems right. Of course, the e4-pawn is untouchable: } 15... Nxe4 16. Nxe4 Qxe4 17. Bg4 { and White wins the knight on d7. } ) 16. Bf1 Ne5 { We're planning both ...c4 and ...Nh5. } 17. h3 { This is aimed  against ...Nh5, and in general it’s also useful for White to guard the g4-square. } 17... c4 { It's time to get the counterplay going. } 18. Bxe5 Qxe5 { We keep the long diagonal open. } 19. Bxc4 Rbc8 { Now the rook is more useful on c8. } 20. Bf1 Nd7 { With good compensation for the pawn due to the active pieces. We'll probably have to relocate the queen, so ...Qd4 if possible or ...Qe7-d8 could be next. } *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Modern Benoni"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch 3: Benoni with 6.Nf3 g6 7.Bf4 a6 8.e4"]
[Black "9. Qe2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 ( 6. e4 g6 7. Nf3 a6 8. Bf4 b5 { is another way to reach the starting position of this chapter. } ) 6... g6 7. Bf4 a6 8. e4 { White allows ...b5 but goes for quick play in the centre. With the bishop on f4, White usually chooses a set-up with h3 and e3 (after he has prevented ...b5 with a4 - as in the next chapter), but we need to be prepared for the rare 8. e4 too. } 8... b5 { Of course, we take the opportunity to expand on the queenside, also avoiding an unpleasant check with Qa4+. } 9. Qe2 { White is preparing the e5 break with all his forces. } 9... Be7 ( { By simply developing the bishop to e7 we prevent the e5 push. Next we can castle, play ...Re8 and ...Bf8. } 9... Ra7 { also deserves attention, but } ) ( 9... Bg7 { falls into White's hands after } 10. Bxd6 Qxd6 11. e5 Qe7 12. d6 { . } ) 10. e5 { Although it seems like the logical continuation, this pawn push backfires on White. } 10... dxe5 11. Bxe5 Nbd7 { We're just in time to develop the knight and prevent d6. } 12. Bf4 { This ambitious move fails. We now sacrifice the e7-bishop in order to finish our development and press forward the initiative. } 12... O-O 13. d6 Bxd6 14. Bxd6 Re8 { This is the point. For a mere piece, our king is safe and the rook is putting tremendous pressure on White’s position. } 15. Ne5 b4 { We drive the white knight out of play. } 16. Na4 Nxe5 17. Bxe5 Ng4 18. f4 Bf5 { It is impossible to see how White could possibly untangle his pieces in the near future. } *

