1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 ( 6. e4 g6 7. Nf3 a6 8. Bf4 b5 { is another way to reach the starting position of this chapter. } ) 6... g6 7. Bf4 a6 8. e4 { White allows ...b5 but goes for quick play in the centre. With the bishop on f4, White usually chooses a set-up with h3 and e3 (after he has prevented ...b5 with a4 - as in the next chapter), but we need to be prepared for the rare 8. e4 too. } 8... b5 { Of course, we take the opportunity to expand on the queenside, also avoiding an unpleasant check with Qa4+. } 9. Qe2 { White is preparing the e5 break with all his forces. } 9... Be7 ( { By simply developing the bishop to e7 we prevent the e5 push. Next we can castle, play ...Re8 and ...Bf8. } 9... Ra7 { also deserves attention, but } ) ( 9... Bg7 { falls into White's hands after } 10. Bxd6 Qxd6 11. e5 Qe7 12. d6 { . } ) 10. e5 { Although it seems like the logical continuation, this pawn push backfires on White. } 10... dxe5 11. Bxe5 Nbd7 { We're just in time to develop the knight and prevent d6. } 12. O-O-O { This is called for. } 12... Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Qd6 { It is important that we’ve managed to exchange his dark-squared bishop and block the d-pawn. } 14. Nc6 Bb7 { With a balanced position. Black's ideas are ...Bxc6 or even ... Nxd5. } *

