1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 ( 6. e4 g6 7. Nf3 a6 8. Bf4 b5 { is another way to reach the starting position of this chapter. } ) 6... g6 7. Bf4 a6 8. e4 { White allows ...b5 but goes for quick play in the centre. With the bishop on f4, White usually chooses a set-up with h3 and e3 (after he has prevented ...b5 with a4 - as in the next chapter), but we need to be prepared for the rare 8. e4 too. } 8... b5 { Of course, we take the opportunity to expand on the queenside, also avoiding an unpleasant check with Qa4+. } 9. Qe2 { White is preparing the e5 break with all his forces. } 9... Be7 ( { By simply developing the bishop to e7 we prevent the e5 push. Next we can castle, play ...Re8 and ...Bf8. } 9... Ra7 { also deserves attention, but } ) ( 9... Bg7 { falls into White's hands after } 10. Bxd6 Qxd6 11. e5 Qe7 12. d6 { . } ) 10. Qc2 { White's best strategy is to return to normal play. He can then claim that the bishop on e7 is misplaced. That is only partly true, because we just lose one tempo to put it back to f8 after ...O-O and ...Re8. Besides, we have already managed to play ...b5, which is a move that White usually wants to prevent. } 10... O-O 11. Be2 Re8 12. O-O Bf8 { We have made our standard moves so far. Now White has to defend against the threat of ...b4 followed by ...Nxe4. } 13. a3 Bg4 ( { If we can exchange our light-squared bishop on f3, we usually do so - so why not? There is also nothing wrong with } 13... Nbd7 { . } ) 14. h3 Bxf3 15. Bxf3 Nbd7 { I prefer Black, who has an ideal Benoni position. } *

