[White "Ch 3: Benoni with 6.Nf3 g6 7.Bf4 a6 8.e4"]
[Black "9. Be2 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 ( 6. e4 g6 7. Nf3 a6 8. Bf4 b5 { is another way to reach the starting position of this chapter. } ) 6... g6 7. Bf4 a6 8. e4 { White allows ...b5 but goes for quick play in the centre. With the bishop on f4, White usually chooses a set-up with h3 and e3 (after he has prevented ...b5 with a4 - as in the next chapter), but we need to be prepared for the rare 8. e4 too. } 8... b5 { Of course, we take the opportunity to expand on the queenside, also avoiding an unpleasant check with Qa4+. } 9. Be2 { This prepares both castling and also the e5-advance. Black must play precisely because he is behind in development. } 9... b4 ( { We go for the e4-pawn. There is no time to finish our development, since after } 9... Bg7 10. e5 { is already possible. } ) 10. Na4 Nxe4 { This is the point. It's risky to take on e4, but at least we get rid of the e5 push once and for all. } 11. O-O Bg7 12. Bd3 f5 { Black is fine. } *

