1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 ( 6. e4 g6 7. Nf3 a6 8. Bf4 b5 { is another way to reach the starting position of this chapter. } ) 6... g6 7. Bf4 a6 8. e4 { White allows ...b5 but goes for quick play in the centre. With the bishop on f4, White usually chooses a set-up with h3 and e3 (after he has prevented ...b5 with a4 - as in the next chapter), but we need to be prepared for the rare 8. e4 too. } 8... b5 { Of course, we take the opportunity to expand on the queenside, also avoiding an unpleasant check with Qa4+. } 9. Be2 { This prepares both castling and also the e5-advance. Black must play precisely because he is behind in development. } 9... b4 ( { We go for the e4-pawn. There is no time to finish our development, since after } 9... Bg7 10. e5 { is already possible. } ) 10. Na4 Nxe4 { This is the point. It's risky to take on e4, but at least we get rid of the e5 push once and for all. } 11. a3 Bg7 { Focusing on development. } 12. axb4 cxb4 13. Qc2 { Attacking the e4-knight and threatening Nb6. } 13... Nf6 { The only good move. } 14. Nb6 { This was White’s idea, but it turns out we don’t have to be afraid. } 14... Qxb6 15. Qxc8+ Ke7 { The king is only temporarily staying in the centre. } 16. Qh3 Re8 { Black prepares to evacuate his king from the centre. } 17. O-O Kf8 { Mission accomplished! } 18. Bd1 Nbd7 { Finally Black has finished developing. } 19. Ba4 Re4 { White has compensation for the pawn, but Black is also doing well because of his extra pawn and active pieces. } *

