1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 ( 6. e4 g6 7. Nf3 a6 8. Bf4 b5 { is another way to reach the starting position of this chapter. } ) 6... g6 7. Bf4 a6 8. e4 { White allows ...b5 but goes for quick play in the centre. With the bishop on f4, White usually chooses a set-up with h3 and e3 (after he has prevented ...b5 with a4 - as in the next chapter), but we need to be prepared for the rare 8. e4 too. } 8... b5 { Of course, we take the opportunity to expand on the queenside, also avoiding an unpleasant check with Qa4+. } 9. e5 { This is not the right moment for this pawn push, since Black can develop the bishop to d6, thus blocking the d5-pawn. } 9... dxe5 10. Nxe5 Bd6 { An important resources. The weakening of our kingside is not so relevant because White has no good way to make use of it. } 11. Be2 O-O 12. O-O Re8 ( { The immediate } 12... Qc7 { is also good, though it should be noted that Black doesn’t win a piece on account of } 13. Bg3 Bxe5 14. d6 ) 13. Nc6 Qc7 { After the exchange of the dark-squared bishops, the d5-pawn will become a weakness. } *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Modern Benoni"]
