[White "Ch 3: Benoni with 6.Nf3 g6 7.Bf4 a6 8.e4"]
[Black "9. Bd3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 ( 6. e4 g6 7. Nf3 a6 8. Bf4 b5 { is another way to reach the starting position of this chapter. } ) 6... g6 7. Bf4 a6 8. e4 { White allows ...b5 but goes for quick play in the centre. With the bishop on f4, White usually chooses a set-up with h3 and e3 (after he has prevented ...b5 with a4 - as in the next chapter), but we need to be prepared for the rare 8. e4 too. } 8... b5 { Of course, we take the opportunity to expand on the queenside, also avoiding an unpleasant check with Qa4+. } 9. Bd3 { White defends the e4-pawn. His idea is to go for quick development followed by e5, or just to consolidate his position afterwards with h3, a3 and Re1. } 9... c4 ( { I recommend this novelty. Black has several other playable choices like } 9... Bg7 { , } ) ( 9... Bg4 { or even } ) ( 9... Nh5 { . Instead, with } ) ( 9... c4 { we gain some space on the queenside and clarify the position of White’s light-squared bishop. } ) ( 9... Bg7 10. h3 O-O 11. O-O Qe7 { would transpose back to a line in chapter 2. } ) 10. Be2 { White intends to undermine the b5-c4 pawn chain later on with a4. } 10... Bg7 11. O-O O-O { Already Black is threatening ...b4, which was not possible a move earlier because of the reply Qa4+. } 12. Nd2 { This move both prevents ...Bg4 and defends the e4-pawn. } 12... Re8 { We are preparing to develop the queenside with ...Nbd7, because now after White replies Bxd6 our rook is not hanging. Besides, it's always good to put further pressure on the e4-pawn. } 13. Re1 b4 { Now this move is possible. } 14. Na4 c3 { Weakening White’s queenside, since this pawn would have been lost anyway on the next move. } 15. bxc3 Nxe4 { Although we didn't finish our development, White's pieces are hanging. } 16. cxb4 Bd7 { White is already in trouble. } *

