1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 ( 6. e4 g6 7. Nf3 a6 8. Bf4 b5 { is another way to reach the starting position of this chapter. } ) 6... g6 7. Bf4 a6 8. e4 { White allows ...b5 but goes for quick play in the centre. With the bishop on f4, White usually chooses a set-up with h3 and e3 (after he has prevented ...b5 with a4 - as in the next chapter), but we need to be prepared for the rare 8. e4 too. } 8... b5 { Of course, we take the opportunity to expand on the queenside, also avoiding an unpleasant check with Qa4+. } 9. Bd3 { White defends the e4-pawn. His idea is to go for quick development followed by e5, or just to consolidate his position afterwards with h3, a3 and Re1. } 9... c4 ( { I recommend this novelty. Black has several other playable choices like } 9... Bg7 { , } ) ( 9... Bg4 { or even } ) ( 9... Nh5 { . Instead, with } ) ( 9... c4 { we gain some space on the queenside and clarify the position of White’s light-squared bishop. } ) ( 9... Bg7 10. h3 O-O 11. O-O Qe7 { would transpose back to a line in chapter 2. } ) 10. Bc2 { Usually White wants to retreat the bishop to c2 because from there it defends the e4-pawn. } 10... Bg4 { This is a good moment to swap the bishop. } 11. h3 { This just helps us to swap the bishop. } 11... Bxf3 12. Qxf3 Bg7 13. O-O O-O { With a normal Benoni position. } *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Modern Benoni"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch 4: Benoni with 6.Nf3 g6 7.Bf4 a6 8.a4"]
[Black "8. Nd2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. Bf4 a6 ( { Black prevents the early check with Qa4+. This is a more solid and less forcing line. The alternative } 7... Bg7 { which is covered in the next chapter, leads to very double-edged play because Black often sacrifices a pawn for quick development. } ) 8. Nd2 { White moves the knight to d2 after developing the dark-squared bishop. Thus White prevents us from playing ...Bg4, but allows ...b5. } 8... b5 { When allowed we should go for this, of course. } 9. a4 Nh5 ( { It is good to start by driving the f4-bishop away from its active position. However, } 9... b4 10. Nce4 Nh5 { would most likely transpose back to this line anyway. } ) 10. Be3 b4 11. Nce4 f5 ( { The point is to drive White’s e4-knight away from the centre. } 11... Bf5 { is also interesting. } ) 12. g4 { This is the move White was counting on. } 12... Nf6 ( { Taking the pawn with } 12... fxg4 { would have been wrong because of } 13. h3 { opening up the kingside, with a strong initiative for White. } ) 13. Ng5 { White plays for the initiative. He sacrifices a pawn and has the idea of playing Ne6. } 13... Nxg4 { We can spend a tempo on capturing this pawn. } 14. Bf4 Be7 { This forces White to play Ne6 while keeping the d6-pawn defended. } 15. Ne6 Bxe6 16. dxe6 Nc6 { Black has good play. ...Nd4 is the main idea. For example } 17. Bg2 ( { Or } 17. Nc4 Nd4 { with a nice position for Black. } ) 17... Nd4 { when White loses if he takes the exchange: } 18. Bxa8 Qxa8 19. O-O g5 20. Bg3 h5 { followed by h4 is one sample continuation. } *

