1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. Bf4 a6 ( { Black prevents the early check with Qa4+. This is a more solid and less forcing line. The alternative } 7... Bg7 { which is covered in the next chapter, leads to very double-edged play because Black often sacrifices a pawn for quick development. } ) 8. Nd2 { White moves the knight to d2 after developing the dark-squared bishop. Thus White prevents us from playing ...Bg4, but allows ...b5. } 8... b5 { When allowed we should go for this, of course. } 9. a4 Nh5 ( { It is good to start by driving the f4-bishop away from its active position. However, } 9... b4 10. Nce4 Nh5 { would most likely transpose back to this line anyway. } ) 10. Be3 b4 11. Nce4 f5 ( { The point is to drive White’s e4-knight away from the centre. } 11... Bf5 { is also interesting. } ) 12. g4 { This is the move White was counting on. } 12... Nf6 ( { Taking the pawn with } 12... fxg4 { would have been wrong because of } 13. h3 { opening up the kingside, with a strong initiative for White. } ) 13. gxf5 Nxe4 { It is important to exchange on e4, as White's knights were ready to jump to good squares. Ng5 and Nc4 were the concrete threats. } 14. Nxe4 Bxf5 { Of course we don't want to spoil our pawn structure. } 15. Ng3 Qf6 { I still prefer to keep our structure intact. } 16. Nxf5 Qxf5 { Black is fine. Once White's knights have been exchanged his position looks artificial. Our plan is simple: ...Nd7 and ...Bg7 are next. } *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Modern Benoni"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch 4: Benoni with 6.Nf3 g6 7.Bf4 a6 8.a4"]
[Black "8. a4 Bg7 9. e3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. Bf4 a6 ( { Black prevents the early check with Qa4+. This is a more solid and less forcing line. The alternative } 7... Bg7 { which is covered in the next chapter, leads to very double-edged play because Black often sacrifices a pawn for quick development. } ) 8. a4 { White prevents ...b5 and later on they can play a5 in order to make use of the b6-square. The variation 8. e4 b5 was covered in the previous chapter. } 8... Bg7 9. e3 { This is a mistake, one that can easily be made by a careless player. } 9... Bg4 { I cannot stress enough the importance of this move! Once the opportunity arises we should exchange our light-squared bishop on f3. } 10. Be2 Bxf3 ( { We can swap the bishop right away. However, } 10... O-O { is also good. } ) 11. Bxf3 Qe7 ( { In order to be able to play ...Nbd7 faster. However, again } 11... O-O { is just as strong. } ) 12. Qb3 { White tries to put some pressure on the b7-pawn. } 12... O-O 13. O-O Nbd7 { I’m giving this line just to show that we can sacrifice the b7-pawn if necessary. } 14. Qxb7 Rfb8 15. Qc6 Ne8 { Almost trapping the queen. } 16. a5 { Until now we’ve been following the game 1-0 (33) Gajewski,G (2634)-Rupprecht,A (2401) Germany 2013. } 16... Ra7 { This move allows us to move the b8-rook. } 17. Rab1 Ne5 18. Bxe5 Bxe5 { The pawn minus is not really felt. We have nice pressure on the b-file. } *

