[Black "8. a4 Bg7 9. h3 with 10. e4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. Bf4 a6 ( { Black prevents the early check with Qa4+. This is a more solid and less forcing line. The alternative } 7... Bg7 { which is covered in the next chapter, leads to very double-edged play because Black often sacrifices a pawn for quick development. } ) 8. a4 { White prevents ...b5 and later on they can play a5 in order to make use of the b6-square. The variation 8. e4 b5 was covered in the previous chapter. } 8... Bg7 9. h3 { Both preventing ...Bg4 and creating a refuge for the bishop on h2. } 9... O-O 10. e4 { This hasn't been played often but could be interesting nevertheless. } 10... Re8 { is a target now. } ( { Of course the pawn on } 10... Nxe4 { would lead to the same thing. } ) 11. Bd3 { White is one move away from castling, but... } 11... Nxe4 { Just in time! } 12. Bxe4 Bf5 { We regain the piece with a good position. } 13. O-O Bxe4 14. Re1 Bxc3 { This way we keep the e4-bishop active and gain a tempo. } 15. bxc3 Nd7 { Followed by ...Qf6 in order to cover the dark squares. White has enough compensation for the sacrificed pawn, but not more than that. } { Note that } 16. Bxd6 { can be followed by } 16... Qf6 { and then ...Qxc3. } *

