1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. Bf4 a6 ( { Black prevents the early check with Qa4+. This is a more solid and less forcing line. The alternative } 7... Bg7 { which is covered in the next chapter, leads to very double-edged play because Black often sacrifices a pawn for quick development. } ) 8. a4 { White prevents ...b5 and later on they can play a5 in order to make use of the b6-square. The variation 8. e4 b5 was covered in the previous chapter. } 8... Bg7 9. h3 { Both preventing ...Bg4 and creating a refuge for the bishop on h2. } 9... O-O 10. e4 { This hasn't been played often but could be interesting nevertheless. } 10... Re8 { is a target now. } ( { Of course the pawn on } 10... Nxe4 { would lead to the same thing. } ) 11. Nd2 { This is stronger than moving the f1-bishop, as it keeps the option to develop this bishop to e2. } 11... Nxe4 ( { Again we go for this idea. } 11... Nbd7 12. Be2 Ne5 13. O-O Nfd7 14. Bg3 g5 { is more comfortable for White. } ) 12. Ncxe4 f5 { This is forced in order to get back the piece. } 13. Be2 fxe4 14. Nc4 { White is targeting the d6-pawn. } 14... Nd7 { There was no time to defend the d6-pawn. } 15. Nxd6 Rf8 16. Be3 { Stopping any ...e3 ideas Black might have. } 16... Bxb2 17. O-O { A strong exchange sacrifice. } 17... Bxa1 { We can afford to grab this exchange. } 18. Qxa1 Qf6 { It's good to exchange the queens, as otherwise our king would be very unsafe. } 19. Nxe4 Qxa1 20. Rxa1 b6 { With chances for both sides. White has to play actively in order to prove compensation for the exchange. } *

