1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. Bf4 a6 ( { Black prevents the early check with Qa4+. This is a more solid and less forcing line. The alternative } 7... Bg7 { which is covered in the next chapter, leads to very double-edged play because Black often sacrifices a pawn for quick development. } ) 8. a4 { White prevents ...b5 and later on they can play a5 in order to make use of the b6-square. The variation 8. e4 b5 was covered in the previous chapter. } 8... Bg7 9. h3 { Both preventing ...Bg4 and creating a refuge for the bishop on h2. } 9... O-O 10. e3 { This is the point. On e4 the pawn would have been a target. By playing e3, White can first finish their development and only then prepare the advance of the e-pawn. } 10... Ne8 { In this position Black has tried many different plans. With 10... Ne8 we defend the d6-pawn and prepare ...Nd7. Also in some lines, because the d6-pawn is protected, we can forego having to play ...Qe7. } ( { If Black plays } 10... b6 { immediately then White can reply } 11. Nd2 Ne8 12. Nc4 { with pressure on d6. } ) 11. Be2 b6 { Black prevents a5 and prepares ...Nd7-e5. After the knights are exchanged on e5 the c5-pawn will be defended by the b6-pawn, which favours us. } ( 11... Nd7 { is possible as well, but White can then reply } 12. a5 { thus transposing to the lines with 11. a5. } ) 12. O-O ( { For the rare continuation } 12. e4 { see the model game Nyback - Papaioannou. } ) 12... Nd7 13. Qb3 { A typical move in this line. However in this case White has no threats because we have already played ...b6. } 13... Rb8 { Further securing the b6-pawn. ...Ne5 is our next intended move. } 14. Bg5 { White tries to disrupt our pieces. } 14... f6 { This is possible and good, as we want to push the kingside pawns anyway. } 15. Bf4 g5 16. Bh2 f5 { Further advancing on the kingside, all according to Black's plan. } 17. Qc2 Qe7 { Black is doing fine. ...Ne5 or ...g4 could be his next moves. } *

