1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. Bf4 a6 ( { Black prevents the early check with Qa4+. This is a more solid and less forcing line. The alternative } 7... Bg7 { which is covered in the next chapter, leads to very double-edged play because Black often sacrifices a pawn for quick development. } ) 8. a4 { White prevents ...b5 and later on they can play a5 in order to make use of the b6-square. The variation 8. e4 b5 was covered in the previous chapter. } 8... Bg7 9. h3 { Both preventing ...Bg4 and creating a refuge for the bishop on h2. } 9... O-O 10. e3 { This is the point. On e4 the pawn would have been a target. By playing e3, White can first finish their development and only then prepare the advance of the e-pawn. } 10... Ne8 { In this position Black has tried many different plans. With 10... Ne8 we defend the d6-pawn and prepare ...Nd7. Also in some lines, because the d6-pawn is protected, we can forego having to play ...Qe7. } ( { If Black plays } 10... b6 { immediately then White can reply } 11. Nd2 Ne8 12. Nc4 { with pressure on d6. } ) 11. Be2 b6 { Black prevents a5 and prepares ...Nd7-e5. After the knights are exchanged on e5 the c5-pawn will be defended by the b6-pawn, which favours us. } ( 11... Nd7 { is possible as well, but White can then reply } 12. a5 { thus transposing to the lines with 11. a5. } ) 12. O-O ( { For the rare continuation } 12. e4 { see the model game Nyback - Papaioannou. } ) 12... Nd7 13. e4 { White is now ready for this advance. } 13... Ne5 { This is what we prepared with the previous moves. } 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 { I prefer to exchange the bishop as well, as otherwise it will get shut in on g7. } 15. Bxe5 dxe5 16. Qd2 Nd6 { The knight is established on its ideal square. } 17. Qe3 { With the idea of playing a5. } 17... a5 { This way we fix the pawns on the queenside. White can still try to infiltrate via b5 and c6, but we have own counterplay with ...f5. The knight on d6 is excellently placed, so White should try to exchange it as soon as possible. } 18. Nb5 Qe7 ( { Preparing ...Bd7. } 18... Ba6 19. Nxd6 Qxd6 20. Bxa6 Rxa6 { is also enough for equality. } ) 19. Nxd6 Qxd6 20. Bb5 Ra7 { The plan is to get the rook to e7 and prepare ...f5. } 21. Qb3 ( { After } 21. Bc6 Bd7 { we exchange bishops so that we can defend the b6-pawn. It's hard for White to make any progress. } ) 21... Bd7 { The position is about equal. The d5- pawn is strong but White doesn't have a way to break through. } *

