[White "Ch 5: Benoni with 6.Nf3 g6 7.Bf4 Bg7"]
[Black "7. Bf4 & 8. e4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. Bf4 { White wants to put pressure on the d6-pawn early on. He may continue with either e3 or e4, depending on the setup he chooses. } 7... Bg7 { We continue the development as soon as possible, not being afraid of the check on a4. } 8. e4 O-O 9. Nd2 { An ambitious concept. White has developed his dark-squared bishop actively and also avoids ...Bg4. } ( 9. Be2 Bg4 { transposes to the variation 7. e4 Bg7 8. Be2 Bg4 9. Bf4 O-O. } ) 9... a6 { This seems like a good moment to include the moves ...a6 and a4. } 10. Be2 { Usually White replies to ...a6 with a4. In this case White ignores our threat but prevents ...Nh5. } 10... b5 11. O-O Ne8 { A nice rejoinder. This move prepares both ...Nd7 and ...f5. } 12. Qc2 f5 { Black has nice counterplay. } *

