1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. Bf4 { White wants to put pressure on the d6-pawn early on. He may continue with either e3 or e4, depending on the setup he chooses. } 7... Bg7 { We continue the development as soon as possible, not being afraid of the check on a4. } 8. e4 O-O 9. Nd2 { An ambitious concept. White has developed his dark-squared bishop actively and also avoids ...Bg4. } ( 9. Be2 Bg4 { transposes to the variation 7. e4 Bg7 8. Be2 Bg4 9. Bf4 O-O. } ) 9... a6 { This seems like a good moment to include the moves ...a6 and a4. } 10. a4 Nh5 { The start of an interesting maneuver. } 11. Be3 Bd4 { This is the point of our previous move. We exchange dark-squared bishops in order to gain access to the f4-square. } 12. Bxd4 cxd4 13. Ne2 Nd7 { Black gets good compensation for the pawn. There was no time to defend the d4-pawn because White had Nc4. } 14. Nxd4 Qf6 { White is lagging in development while Black can continue with ...Re8 next. } *

