1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. Bf4 { White wants to put pressure on the d6-pawn early on. He may continue with either e3 or e4, depending on the setup he chooses. } 7... Bg7 { We continue the development as soon as possible, not being afraid of the check on a4. } 8. Nd2 Nh5 ( { We can take advantage of White’s move order by attacking the bishop. } 8... O-O { is also an easy solution and after } 9. e4 { it should transpose to 8. e4 O-O 9. Nd2. } ) 9. Qa4+ { White was counting on this check. } 9... Kf8 ( { White's point is that } 9... Bd7 { is answered by } 10. Qe4+ { when the d6-pawn is no longer defended and can be captured next move. This is why we're forced to move our king. } ) 10. h4 { Making room for the bishop to come to h2. } 10... Nxf4 { This is a good move, but it may lead to a draw by repetition. } 11. Qxf4 Be5 { With ...Kg7 or ...h5 to follow. } 12. Qh6+ Bg7 13. Qf4 Be5 { And a draw by repetition. } *

