1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. Bf4 { White wants to put pressure on the d6-pawn early on. He may continue with either e3 or e4, depending on the setup he chooses. } 7... Bg7 { We continue the development as soon as possible, not being afraid of the check on a4. } 8. Nd2 Nh5 ( { We can take advantage of White’s move order by attacking the bishop. } 8... O-O { is also an easy solution and after } 9. e4 { it should transpose to 8. e4 O-O 9. Nd2. } ) 9. Qa4+ { White was counting on this check. } 9... Kf8 ( { White's point is that } 9... Bd7 { is answered by } 10. Qe4+ { when the d6-pawn is no longer defended and can be captured next move. This is why we're forced to move our king. } ) 10. h4 { Making room for the bishop to come to h2. } 10... Qe7 ( { If you do not want to repeat moves after } 10... Nxf4 { , you can keep the game going by playing } ) ( 10... Qe7 { Now we want to take on f4 and follow up with ...Nd7, which is possible now that the d6-pawn is defended. } ) 11. Bh2 Nd7 { The idea is to play ...Be5, exchange the bishops, ease the pressure on the d6-pawn and make room for the king to come to g7. } 12. e3 Be5 { Black has a good position because there is no more pressure on the d6-pawn. As indicated previously, we can exchange the bishops and bring the king to g7. } *

