1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. Bf4 { White wants to put pressure on the d6-pawn early on. He may continue with either e3 or e4, depending on the setup he chooses. } 7... Bg7 { We continue the development as soon as possible, not being afraid of the check on a4. } 8. Qa4+ { This is the real test for Black in this variation. White combines the threat to the pawn on d6 with this early check in order to disrupt the coordination of the black pieces. } 8... Bd7 { The only good reply. Otherwise either we lose the right to castle, or the d6-pawn falls. } 9. Qb3 b5 ( { The sharpest reply. By sacrificing a pawn, Black fights for the initiative due to his development advantage. } 9... Qc7 { has been played more often but it's more passive. } ) 10. Nxb5 { This is too slow, and White will lag in development. } 10... Bxb5 { This exchange allows us to play ...Nbd7. } 11. Qxb5+ Nbd7 12. Bxd6 { Forced, as otherwise ...Rb8 is strong. } 12... Ne4 { We need to remove the bishop from d6 in order to be able to castle. } 13. Bf4 O-O 14. e3 a6 { Black wins on the spot because White cannot defend against both ...Bxb2 and the check on a5 - for example, } 15. Qa4 Bxb2 16. Qxe4 Nf6 *

