[Round "?"]
[White "Ch 5: Benoni with 6.Nf3 g6 7.Bf4 Bg7"]
[Black "7. Bf4 & 8. Qa4+ #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. Bf4 { White wants to put pressure on the d6-pawn early on. He may continue with either e3 or e4, depending on the setup he chooses. } 7... Bg7 { We continue the development as soon as possible, not being afraid of the check on a4. } 8. Qa4+ { This is the real test for Black in this variation. White combines the threat to the pawn on d6 with this early check in order to disrupt the coordination of the black pieces. } 8... Bd7 { The only good reply. Otherwise either we lose the right to castle, or the d6-pawn falls. } 9. Qb3 b5 ( { The sharpest reply. By sacrificing a pawn, Black fights for the initiative due to his development advantage. } 9... Qc7 { has been played more often but it's more passive. } ) 10. Nxb5 { This is too slow, and White will lag in development. } 10... Bxb5 { This exchange allows us to play ...Nbd7. } 11. Qxb5+ Nbd7 12. Bxd6 { Forced, as otherwise ...Rb8 is strong. } 12... Ne4 { We need to remove the bishop from d6 in order to be able to castle. } 13. Bf4 O-O 14. g3 { This is the best way for White to develop. } 14... Qb6 { A good way to keep the initiative. After the forced exchange of queens the pawn on b2 will be hanging, and we can also push our b- and c-pawns quickly. } 15. Qxb6 axb6 16. Bc1 { The only way to defend b2. } 16... c4 { The idea is ...Ndc5 or even ... c3. } 17. e3 b5 { This renews the threat of ...Ndc5. } 18. Nd4 Ndc5 19. f3 { A draw was agreed here in ½-½ (19) Szczepanski,Z  (2476)-Dimov,D (2432) ICCF 2017. } 19... Nd6 20. a3 Bxd4 { In order to play ...Nb3. } 21. exd4 Nb3 22. Rb1 Nf5 { The white central pawns will fall and the endgame is about equal. } *

