1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. Bf4 { White wants to put pressure on the d6-pawn early on. He may continue with either e3 or e4, depending on the setup he chooses. } 7... Bg7 { We continue the development as soon as possible, not being afraid of the check on a4. } 8. Qa4+ { This is the real test for Black in this variation. White combines the threat to the pawn on d6 with this early check in order to disrupt the coordination of the black pieces. } 8... Bd7 { The only good reply. Otherwise either we lose the right to castle, or the d6-pawn falls. } 9. Qb3 b5 ( { The sharpest reply. By sacrificing a pawn, Black fights for the initiative due to his development advantage. } 9... Qc7 { has been played more often but it's more passive. } ) 10. Nxb5 { This is too slow, and White will lag in development. } 10... Bxb5 { This exchange allows us to play ...Nbd7. } 11. Qxb5+ Nbd7 12. Bxd6 { Forced, as otherwise ...Rb8 is strong. } 12... Ne4 { We need to remove the bishop from d6 in order to be able to castle. } 13. Be5 { It makes sense for White to exchange the black bishop. } 13... O-O { We castle and defend the bishop. } 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. Qa4 Rb8 { There is no time to defend the knight. We need to keep our momentum going. } 16. Qxe4 { White cannot defend b2 in a convenient way, so he has to take the piece. } 16... Qa5+ { This is actually the point. Not only does the queen join the attack, but the white king is stuck in the centre. } 17. Nd2 Rxb2 18. Rd1 { The only move. } 18... Nf6 ( { This has been played in correspondence games. However, } 18... Rxa2 { or } ) ( 18... Rfb8 { are good as well. } ) 19. Qc4 Rfb8 { The threat is ...Rxd2. } 20. e4 R8b4 21. Qc3 Rxd2 { The only way. Now a forced sequence follows. } 22. Qxd2 Nxe4 { A nice concept: if the queen moves, we'll have a decisive discovered check. } 23. a3 Nxd2 24. axb4 cxb4 { With a perpetual to follow after } 25. Rxd2 Qa1+ 26. Rd1 Qc3+ 27. Rd2 Qa1+ { ½-½ (27) Vertíz Gutiérrez,P (2310)-Bulgarini Torres,M (2281) ICCF 2017 } *

