[Black "7. Bf4 & 8. Qa4+ #13"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. Bf4 { White wants to put pressure on the d6-pawn early on. He may continue with either e3 or e4, depending on the setup he chooses. } 7... Bg7 { We continue the development as soon as possible, not being afraid of the check on a4. } 8. Qa4+ { This is the real test for Black in this variation. White combines the threat to the pawn on d6 with this early check in order to disrupt the coordination of the black pieces. } 8... Bd7 { The only good reply. Otherwise either we lose the right to castle, or the d6-pawn falls. } 9. Qb3 b5 ( { The sharpest reply. By sacrificing a pawn, Black fights for the initiative due to his development advantage. } 9... Qc7 { has been played more often but it's more passive. } ) 10. Bxd6 { White takes an important pawn. } 10... Qb6 ( { The best reply. We bring the queen into play with tempo, and after the bishop moves we're ready to castle. } 10... c4 { is not convincing because of } 11. Qa3 Qb6 12. e4 { with an edge for White. } ) 11. Be5 { Fighting for control over the long diagonal. All the other retreats are just inferior. } 11... O-O { The king is safe and we're ready to start our counterplay. } 12. e3 { White needs to develop his pieces. } 12... c4 { This is the right push. First we drive the queen back and then play ...b4. Thus we control the important square c4. } 13. Qd1 b4 { Not only gaining space on the queenside, but also driving back the white knight. } 14. Ne2 { In order to relocate the knight to f4 or d4. } 14... Rc8 ( { This is the popular choice, and also it's easy to remember because after 14.Nb1 we continue the same way. } 14... Bb5 { was played in 1-0 (48) Aronian,L (2805)-Gashimov,V (2761) Wijk aan Zee 2012, and although Black lost, there were several ways to improve his play. } ) 15. Nf4 { Other moves are less challenging. } 15... c3 { This pawn is strong on c3 and spoils the coordination of White’s pieces. } 16. Be2 { This hasn't been played, but deserves attention. } 16... Qa5 { With the idea to play ...Ba4. } 17. Qd4 Ba4 { This works nevertheless. The lines are very concrete. } 18. b3 Nbd7 { Black takes over the initiative, for example } 19. bxa4 Nxe5 20. Nxe5 Nd7 { It's all about the pin on the long diagonal. } 21. Nfd3 Nxe5 22. Nxe5 b3 { with a winning position. } *

