1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. Bf4 { White wants to put pressure on the d6-pawn early on. He may continue with either e3 or e4, depending on the setup he chooses. } 7... Bg7 { We continue the development as soon as possible, not being afraid of the check on a4. } 8. Qa4+ { This is the real test for Black in this variation. White combines the threat to the pawn on d6 with this early check in order to disrupt the coordination of the black pieces. } 8... Bd7 { The only good reply. Otherwise either we lose the right to castle, or the d6-pawn falls. } 9. Qb3 b5 ( { The sharpest reply. By sacrificing a pawn, Black fights for the initiative due to his development advantage. } 9... Qc7 { has been played more often but it's more passive. } ) 10. Bxd6 { White takes an important pawn. } 10... Qb6 ( { The best reply. We bring the queen into play with tempo, and after the bishop moves we're ready to castle. } 10... c4 { is not convincing because of } 11. Qa3 Qb6 12. e4 { with an edge for White. } ) 11. Be5 { Fighting for control over the long diagonal. All the other retreats are just inferior. } 11... O-O { The king is safe and we're ready to start our counterplay. } 12. e3 { White needs to develop his pieces. } 12... c4 { This is the right push. First we drive the queen back and then play ...b4. Thus we control the important square c4. } 13. Qd1 b4 { Not only gaining space on the queenside, but also driving back the white knight. } 14. Nb1 { White has several ideas: he can simply complete the development with Be2 and O-O, play Nbd2 in order to attack c4, or go for a3 to undermine the black pawns. } 14... Rc8 { We continue in the same way as after 14. Ne2. The rook is actively placed on c8, and the bishop may go to either f5 or b5. } 15. a3 { This hasn't been played very often. } 15... Bf5 ( { I suggest this interesting move. The idea is to prepare ...Nbd7. In practical games } 15... c3 { has been played, which is tempting. However White is a bit better after } 16. bxc3 b3 17. Bd4 { . } ) 16. axb4 { This is White’s idea. } 16... Nbd7 { This move is important because it comes with tempo. } 17. Bc3 { White has to keep their bishop. } 17... Bxb1 { It looks strange to exchange our bishop for the undeveloped knight, but we have a clear idea of following up with ...Ne4 is next, putting pressure on c3. } 18. Rxb1 Ne4 { The idea is simply to take ...Nxc3. } 19. Rc1 Nxc3 20. bxc3 a5 { in order to further open up the game. } 21. bxa5 Rxa5 { Our active pieces compensate for the double pawn deficit. ...Ra2 and ...Qb2 are our ideas, and White’s c3-pawn will be hanging. White needs 2 moves to bring his king to safety, which gives us time to develop the initiative. Black is doing fine. } *

