[Black "7. Bf4 & 8. Qa4+ #22"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. Bf4 { White wants to put pressure on the d6-pawn early on. He may continue with either e3 or e4, depending on the setup he chooses. } 7... Bg7 { We continue the development as soon as possible, not being afraid of the check on a4. } 8. Qa4+ { This is the real test for Black in this variation. White combines the threat to the pawn on d6 with this early check in order to disrupt the coordination of the black pieces. } 8... Bd7 { The only good reply. Otherwise either we lose the right to castle, or the d6-pawn falls. } 9. Qb3 b5 ( { The sharpest reply. By sacrificing a pawn, Black fights for the initiative due to his development advantage. } 9... Qc7 { has been played more often but it's more passive. } ) 10. Bxd6 { White takes an important pawn. } 10... Qb6 ( { The best reply. We bring the queen into play with tempo, and after the bishop moves we're ready to castle. } 10... c4 { is not convincing because of } 11. Qa3 Qb6 12. e4 { with an edge for White. } ) 11. Be5 { Fighting for control over the long diagonal. All the other retreats are just inferior. } 11... O-O { The king is safe and we're ready to start our counterplay. } 12. e3 { White needs to develop his pieces. } 12... c4 { This is the right push. First we drive the queen back and then play ...b4. Thus we control the important square c4. } 13. Qd1 b4 { Not only gaining space on the queenside, but also driving back the white knight. } 14. Nb1 { White has several ideas: he can simply complete the development with Be2 and O-O, play Nbd2 in order to attack c4, or go for a3 to undermine the black pawns. } 14... Rc8 { We continue in the same way as after 14. Ne2. The rook is actively placed on c8, and the bishop may go to either f5 or b5. } 15. Nbd2 { White immediately deploys the knight to a more active position. } 15... Bb5 ( { I prefer this to the immediate } 15... c3 { Now the ...c3 advance further gains in strength. } ) 16. a4 bxa3 { Opening the position and gaining time to take the d5-pawn. } 17. Rxa3 Bf8 ( 17... Nbd7 { is also possible, but the bishop move is slightly more precise. } ) 18. Bd4 Qb7 19. Bxf6 { This is just bad for White. } 19... Bxa3 20. bxa3 c3 { Is very good for Black. White's king is stuck in the centre and the c3-pawn is dangerous. A sample line continues } 21. Ne4 c2 22. Qc1 Bxf1 23. Rxf1 Qxd5 24. Nc3 Qd3 25. Qd2 Qa6 { and White is in trouble. } *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Modern Benoni"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch 6: Benoni with 6.Nf3, 7.Nd2"]
[Black "8. Nc4 O-O 9. Bg5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. Nd2 { This is quite a strong plan. White avoids the exchange of the light-squared bishop with ...Bg4 and prepares e4. The knight will defend the e4-pawn, and at the right moment wants to jump to the ideal square c4. } 7... Bg7 8. Nc4 { It makes sense to bring the knight here and put pressure on the d6-pawn. However, White has delayed his development, and the e4-square is not so well defended. } 8... O-O 9. Bg5 { White's setup is ambitious. He has put his knight on the strong c4-square and is also pinning our knight with his bishop. Should he have time to castle, he would have an advantage. However, we can fight his plans by exchanging the c4-knight. } 9... Nbd7 ( { This natural move is a novelty. Black has usually preferred } 9... h6 { or } ) ( 9... Qe7 { here, but why refrain from ...Nbd7 if White cannot take on d6? } ) 10. Nxd6 { This is dubious as White is lagging badly in development. } 10... Qb6 { This is the move we have been counting on: a  double attack on the d6-knight and the b2-pawn. } 11. Nc4 Qb4 { Attacking the knight on c4 while preparing ...Ne4 or ...Nxd5. } 12. Qb3 Nxd5 13. Qxb4 Nxb4 { Black's position is preferable. } *

