[White "Ch 6: Benoni with 6.Nf3, 7.Nd2"]
[Black "8. Nc4 O-O 9. Bf4 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. Nd2 { This is quite a strong plan. White avoids the exchange of the light-squared bishop with ...Bg4 and prepares e4. The knight will defend the e4-pawn, and at the right moment wants to jump to the ideal square c4. } 7... Bg7 8. Nc4 { It makes sense to bring the knight here and put pressure on the d6-pawn. However, White has delayed his development, and the e4-square is not so well defended. } 8... O-O 9. Bf4 Nbd7 ( { There is nothing wrong with defending the pawn with } 9... Ne8 { as seen for example in our model game Moiseenko - Lupulescu. However, I think that is not necessary. I prefer to sacrifice a pawn and fight for the initiative. } ) 10. Nxd6 Nh5 { We need to remove the f4-bishop from its active position. } 11. Be3 b5 ( { An interesting novelty. The idea is to open up the game. } 11... Qb6 { is more conservative. } ) 12. Ndxb5 Rb8 { Black has good compensation. The b2-pawn is hanging and ...Qa5 is an immediate threat. } 13. Rc1 Re8 ( 13... f5 { deserves attention as well. } ) 14. g3 Ne5 { Black has the initiative. We can continue with ...Nc4 or ...Qa5. White is still lagging in development, and White’s king doesn’t feel comfortable in the centre. The b2-pawn may also become a target if the b5-knight moves. } *

