1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. Nd2 { This is quite a strong plan. White avoids the exchange of the light-squared bishop with ...Bg4 and prepares e4. The knight will defend the e4-pawn, and at the right moment wants to jump to the ideal square c4. } 7... Bg7 8. Nc4 { It makes sense to bring the knight here and put pressure on the d6-pawn. However, White has delayed his development, and the e4-square is not so well defended. } 8... O-O 9. Bf4 Nbd7 ( { There is nothing wrong with defending the pawn with } 9... Ne8 { as seen for example in our model game Moiseenko - Lupulescu. However, I think that is not necessary. I prefer to sacrifice a pawn and fight for the initiative. } ) 10. Nxd6 Nh5 { We need to remove the f4-bishop from its active position. } 11. Be3 b5 ( { An interesting novelty. The idea is to open up the game. } 11... Qb6 { is more conservative. } ) 12. g3 b4 { The idea is to dislocate the c3-knight. } 13. Na4 Nb6 { Now we gain access to the b2-pawn. } 14. Nxc8 Nxa4 15. Qxa4 Bxb2 16. Rd1 Bc3+ ( { This check is useful. If } 16... Rxc8 { White can play } 17. Bh3 Bc3+ 18. Kf1 { when the e3-bishop is strong because it attacks c5. } ) 17. Bd2 Bxd2+ 18. Rxd2 Nf6 { This is slightly more precise than taking on c8 right away, as the knight on c8 cannot escape anyway and we threaten to jump ...Ne4. } 19. Bg2 Rxc8 { Now is a good moment to take the knight, as  White doesn't have Bh3 with tempo. } 20. O-O a5 { And the pawns are rolling with ...c4-c3 coming next. Of course White will push as well, so it's going to be an exciting race. } *

