1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. Nd2 { This is quite a strong plan. White avoids the exchange of the light-squared bishop with ...Bg4 and prepares e4. The knight will defend the e4-pawn, and at the right moment wants to jump to the ideal square c4. } 7... Bg7 8. e4 O-O 9. Bd3 { This hasn't been played often. In my view the bishop is probably better placed on e2, but White has the idea to play a quick Nc4 putting pressure on d6. } 9... Nbd7 { There are also other moves, yet there is nothing wrong with this natural move. } 10. Nc4 Ne8 { This move has a specific purpose: it defends the d6-pawn and prepares ...Ne5. } 11. O-O Ne5 { This way we're going to swap a pair of knights. It is of course better to exchange the knight on c4 instead of the bishop on d3. The c4-knight is more active, controlling the important square e5 and putting pressure on d6. Besides that, White has invested several tempi to bring the knight to c4 in the first place. } 12. Bf4 Nxc4 13. Bxc4 f5 { Since we have retreated the knight to e8 it makes sense to push our f-pawn. } 14. Qd2 fxe4 { It's always good to destroy White's centre. } 15. Nxe4 Bf5 { The bishop is actively placed on f5. } 16. Rae1 Qd7 { With a complicated fight ahead. For example: } 17. Ng5 b5 18. Be2 Nc7 19. Bf3 Rae8 { . } *

