1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. Nd2 { This is quite a strong plan. White avoids the exchange of the light-squared bishop with ...Bg4 and prepares e4. The knight will defend the e4-pawn, and at the right moment wants to jump to the ideal square c4. } 7... Bg7 8. e4 O-O 9. Be2 Na6 { I recommend this move to bring the knight to c7, rook to e8 and then ...b6 and ...Ba6. The knight on c7 will help prepare ...b5, but it's not so good against White’s advance e5. However, White loses some time with his knight maneuver so we can afford this. } ( { We can also start with } 9... Re8 { and I think this should lead to the same thing. } ) 10. Nc4 { This is too early. } 10... b5 { This move was asking to be played. } 11. Nxb5 Nxe4 { With good play for Black. We’ve traded the b-pawn for a central pawn which is to our benefit. Furthermore we can play ...Nc7 and exchange White’s active knight on b5. } *

