repertoire for Chessable. The idea is simple: White is preparing b4, in order to open up the position on the queenside in a favourable way. } 14... Bxc4 ( { We exchange right away in order to play ...a6 and prepare ...b5. } 14... Qd7 { is also interesting, but it isn't clear to me that the queen is needed on d7 in all the lines. Sometimes ...Nd7 is a more useful move. } ) 15. Bxc4 a6 { The first step in preparing ...b5. Afterwards we can continue with either ...Nd7 or ...Qd7. } 16. b4 { White carries out their main plan as well. } 16... Nd7 { A typical move. We're ready to take back on c5 with the knight. } 17. Bd2 { White develops the bishop and defends his c3-knight. } 17... Qf6 { Not an easy move to find. The queen is on its way to d4, from where she will create various threats. } 18. Kh1 { A useful prophylactic move. } 18... b5 { A well-timed push. Black is getting counterplay. } 19. Bd3 cxb4 { We can open up the queenside because of the d3-bishop's exposed position, as we'll get in ...Ne5 or ...Nc5 with tempo. } ( { White is ready to meet } 19... c4 { with } 20. Bc2 { but the bishop is more exposed on d3. } ) 20. Rxb4 bxa4 { We continue to open up the position } 21. Nxa4 Reb8 { With good counterplay for Black. We can follow up with ...Rxb4 and ... Nb5. We have active piece play, and in the long run we can push the a-pawn. } *

