repertoire for Chessable. The idea is simple: White is preparing b4, in order to open up the position on the queenside in a favourable way. } 14... Bxc4 ( { We exchange right away in order to play ...a6 and prepare ...b5. } 14... Qd7 { is also interesting, but it isn't clear to me that the queen is needed on d7 in all the lines. Sometimes ...Nd7 is a more useful move. } ) 15. Bxc4 a6 { The first step in preparing ...b5. Afterwards we can continue with either ...Nd7 or ...Qd7. } 16. b4 { White carries out their main plan as well. } 16... Nd7 { A typical move. We're ready to take back on c5 with the knight. } 17. Bd2 { White develops the bishop and defends his c3-knight. } 17... Qf6 { Not an easy move to find. The queen is on its way to d4, from where she will create various threats. } 18. Kh1 { A useful prophylactic move. } 18... b5 { A well-timed push. Black is getting counterplay. } 19. axb5 { The most natural reply. } 19... Qd4 20. Be2 { It's best to retreat the bishop. } 20... cxb4 { Now we can see the effects of the queen's intrusion. It took White some time to regroup his pieces, and we’ve managed to break up the position on the queenside. } 21. Na4 Nxb5 ( 21... axb5 { is also strong, but I prefer } ) ( 21... Nxb5 { because it either brings our knight into play or exchanges it. } ) 22. Rxb4 Qa7 { The queen is a long range piece, and here she moves from one side of the board to the other with ease. } 23. Bxb5 axb5 24. Nc3 { White will take the b5-pawn. However, I think we have enough compensation because of our active pieces. } 24... Qb6 { Ideally White wants to take on b5 with the knight, so we're preparing against that. } 25. Nxb5 Ra1 { This is the point behind our previous move. We manage to invade White's position with our rook. } 26. Qe2 Ra2 { The pawn minus is not really felt. Depending on what White does we can consider ...Qc5 with the idea ...Qxd5 which works because of the pin on the e-file, or just ...Rb8 to bring our rook into play. Black has good compensation. } *

