on. } 15. Kh1 { A useful move. White doesn't want to play Qd2 yet, as after the exchange on c4 they want to play Qd3 directly and thus save a tempo. } 15... Rab8 { We're preparing ...Bxc4 followed by ...a6 and ...b5. } 16. b3 { Another  typical idea. White wants to retake on c4 with the pawn, thus preventing once and for all our idea to push …b5. However, now the c3-knight is not defended, and we can use this to get counterplay on the kingside. } 16... Nh5 17. Qd2 Bxc3 { This is the trick: the bishop on e2 is unprotected. } 18. Qxc3 Nxd5 19. Qd2 Nb4 { White gets compensation for the pawn but nothing more. There is not enough time to take advantage of the dark squares on the kingside because we're planning to play ...d5. } *

