1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. h3 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Bd3 { This is one of the best setups for White against the Benoni. White doesn't allow us to play ...Bg4 and exchange our light-squared  bishop. Given time White can castle, play Re1, Bf4, a4 and achieve a very harmonious position. } 9... b5 { Objectively this is the best move. The temporary pawn sacrifice is justified because White has wasted time by playing h3. } ( 9... Re8 { is a line suggested by John Doknjas in The Modern Benoni, which I considered and analyzed as well. However, objectively this is not so strong. I might add it as an alternative line in a future update. } ) 10. Bxb5 { This leads to forced lines, and the resulting positions are drawish. } 10... Nxe4 { This is the point of our previous move. } 11. Nxe4 Qa5+ 12. Nfd2 Qxb5 13. Nxd6 Qa6 { This is the best square for our queen. We attack the knight on d6 and after White plays either knight to c4, the queen won't be under attack. } 14. N2c4 Nd7 { We need to bring this knight into play immediately, in order to challenge White’s knights in the centre. } 15. O-O { White is happy to castle, of course. } 15... Ne5 { This is the point of the previous move. I prefer ...Ne5 to ...Nb6 because the knight is more actively placed on e5. } 16. Nxe5 { This doesn't achieve anything. } 16... Qxd6 { Otherwise White can annoy us further with Ne4. } 17. Nc6 Bb7 { Exchanges will follow and we'll regain the sacrificed pawn. } 18. Qf3 Bxc6 19. dxc6 Rac8 20. Rb1 Qxc6 { This was just a draw in ½-½ (20) Peralta,F  (2569)-Mareco,S (2649) Santiago de Compostela 2018. } *

