1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. h3 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Bd3 { This is one of the best setups for White against the Benoni. White doesn't allow us to play ...Bg4 and exchange our light-squared  bishop. Given time White can castle, play Re1, Bf4, a4 and achieve a very harmonious position. } 9... b5 { Objectively this is the best move. The temporary pawn sacrifice is justified because White has wasted time by playing h3. } ( 9... Re8 { is a line suggested by John Doknjas in The Modern Benoni, which I considered and analyzed as well. However, objectively this is not so strong. I might add it as an alternative line in a future update. } ) 10. Bxb5 { This leads to forced lines, and the resulting positions are drawish. } 10... Nxe4 { This is the point of our previous move. } 11. Nxe4 Qa5+ 12. Nfd2 Qxb5 13. Nxd6 Qa6 { This is the best square for our queen. We attack the knight on d6 and after White plays either knight to c4, the queen won't be under attack. } 14. N2c4 Nd7 { We need to bring this knight into play immediately, in order to challenge White’s knights in the centre. } 15. O-O { White is happy to castle, of course. } 15... Ne5 { This is the point of the previous move. I prefer ...Ne5 to ...Nb6 because the knight is more actively placed on e5. } 16. Nxc8 { This is White's main attempt to gain an advantage. } 16... Raxc8 17. Nxe5 Bxe5 18. Qf3 Qf6 ( { This is a fresh move, first played in the correspondence game ½-½ (35) Reed, A (2254)-Egan, M (2261) ICCF 2020. The point is that we're going to exchange the queens, resulting in an equal ending. Another good continuation is } 18... Rfe8 19. Rd1 Bd4 { . I think Black should equalize there as well, but there is more room for error. } ) 19. Qxf6 Bxf6 { ...Rfd8 is coming next. } 20. Bf4 Rfd8 21. d6 g5 { This transposes to the next variation, 20. d6 Rfd8. } *

