1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. h3 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Bd3 { This is one of the best setups for White against the Benoni. White doesn't allow us to play ...Bg4 and exchange our light-squared  bishop. Given time White can castle, play Re1, Bf4, a4 and achieve a very harmonious position. } 9... b5 { Objectively this is the best move. The temporary pawn sacrifice is justified because White has wasted time by playing h3. } ( 9... Re8 { is a line suggested by John Doknjas in The Modern Benoni, which I considered and analyzed as well. However, objectively this is not so strong. I might add it as an alternative line in a future update. } ) 10. Bxb5 { This leads to forced lines, and the resulting positions are drawish. } 10... Nxe4 { This is the point of our previous move. } 11. Nxe4 Qa5+ 12. Nfd2 Qxb5 13. Nxd6 Qa6 { This is the best square for our queen. We attack the knight on d6 and after White plays either knight to c4, the queen won't be under attack. } 14. N2c4 Nd7 { We need to bring this knight into play immediately, in order to challenge White’s knights in the centre. } 15. O-O { White is happy to castle, of course. } 15... Ne5 { This is the point of the previous move. I prefer ...Ne5 to ...Nb6 because the knight is more actively placed on e5. } 16. Nxc8 { This is White's main attempt to gain an advantage. } 16... Raxc8 17. Nxe5 Bxe5 18. Qf3 Qf6 ( { This is a fresh move, first played in the correspondence game ½-½ (35) Reed, A (2254)-Egan, M (2261) ICCF 2020. The point is that we're going to exchange the queens, resulting in an equal ending. Another good continuation is } 18... Rfe8 19. Rd1 Bd4 { . I think Black should equalize there as well, but there is more room for error. } ) 19. Qxf6 Bxf6 { ...Rfd8 is coming next. } 20. d6 Rfd8 { We need to keep an eye on this pawn. } 21. Bf4 { White has to give up the b2-pawn in order to defend the d6-pawn and complete their development. } 21... g5 { It is good to include this move in order to have the resource ...f5 later on. Also, it prevents White from trying to make use of our back rank weakness in some lines by playing Bh6. } 22. Bg3 Bxb2 23. Rab1 Bd4 ( { I like to keep this bishop centralized. The other option } 23... Bf6 { is also good, with the idea to push the c-pawn. } ) 24. Rb7 Rb8 { This is important. It parries White's threat of d7. White's d-pawn is dangerous, but we can keep it under control if we are careful. } 25. Rxa7 ( { Or } 25. Re7 Kg7 { In order to prepare ...Rb2. The resulting ending is equal. } ) 25... f5 { A strong move, shutting in White's bishop on g3. Rf1-e1-e7 is generally not so dangerous because our bishop controls the g7-square (White already has one rook on the seventh rank in basically all variations). Also, the c-pawn gives Black enough counterplay, but as soon as Black plays ...c4 the bishop on d4 won’t be protected anymore. Here White has no way to prevent ...f4, and then the d6-pawn falls. } *

