1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. h3 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Bd3 { This is one of the best setups for White against the Benoni. White doesn't allow us to play ...Bg4 and exchange our light-squared  bishop. Given time White can castle, play Re1, Bf4, a4 and achieve a very harmonious position. } 9... b5 { Objectively this is the best move. The temporary pawn sacrifice is justified because White has wasted time by playing h3. } ( 9... Re8 { is a line suggested by John Doknjas in The Modern Benoni, which I considered and analyzed as well. However, objectively this is not so strong. I might add it as an alternative line in a future update. } ) 10. Bxb5 { This leads to forced lines, and the resulting positions are drawish. } 10... Nxe4 { This is the point of our previous move. } 11. Nxe4 Qa5+ 12. Nfd2 Qxb5 13. Nxd6 Qa6 { This is the best square for our queen. We attack the knight on d6 and after White plays either knight to c4, the queen won't be under attack. } 14. N2c4 Nd7 { We need to bring this knight into play immediately, in order to challenge White’s knights in the centre. } 15. O-O { White is happy to castle, of course. } 15... Ne5 { This is the point of the previous move. I prefer ...Ne5 to ...Nb6 because the knight is more actively placed on e5. } 16. Nxc8 { This is White's main attempt to gain an advantage. } 16... Raxc8 17. Nxe5 Bxe5 18. Re1 { This has been played most often, and it makes sense to activate the rook. } 18... Rfe8 { A natural reply, defending the bishop and activating the rook. } 19. Bg5 Bd4 { This is Black's preferred solution. The centralized bishop is very strong and parries the direct threat of d6. } 20. Rc1 { This is also a logical reply. } 20... Qd6 21. Qa4 Re5 { Black is going after the d5-pawn without giving up the e-file. } 22. Rxe5 Qxe5 23. Qd7 Rb8 { The best place for the rook. It is on an open file and is not hanging. } 24. Bh6 { Until here we have followed the game 0-1 (42) Meier,G  (2664)-Gashimov,V (2740) Novi Sad 2009. } 24... Bxf2+ { Black has several solutions, but this is the most forcing one. } 25. Kh1 Bg3 { Both back  ranks are weak. The position will probably peter out to a draw after some exchanges. } 26. Qxa7 Qxd5 { We need to take some material back. } 27. Qxc5 Qxc5 28. Rxc5 f6 { With enough compensation. The white king is stuck on the last rank, while the h6-bishop could get trapped after ...g5. A sample line continues } 29. b3 Rd8 { (activating the rook) } 30. Rc1 g5 { (cutting White’s bishop off) } 31. Rf1 Rd4 { preventing h4 with the additional idea of ...Be5 and ...Rh4 to trap the white bishop. } *

