1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. h3 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Bd3 { This is one of the best setups for White against the Benoni. White doesn't allow us to play ...Bg4 and exchange our light-squared  bishop. Given time White can castle, play Re1, Bf4, a4 and achieve a very harmonious position. } 9... b5 { Objectively this is the best move. The temporary pawn sacrifice is justified because White has wasted time by playing h3. } ( 9... Re8 { is a line suggested by John Doknjas in The Modern Benoni, which I considered and analyzed as well. However, objectively this is not so strong. I might add it as an alternative line in a future update. } ) 10. Nxb5 { This is the more ambitious move; although the exchange of Black’s b-pawn for White’s e-pawn favours Black, White will try to make the best of his piece activity. } 10... Re8 ( { Only like this. Now we're threatening both ...Nxe4 and ...Nxd5. The immediate } 10... Nxe4 { is considerably worse for Black after } 11. Bxe4 Re8 12. Ng5 { . } ) 11. Nd2 { White defends the e4-pawn and wants to bring the knight to c4. } 11... Nxd5 { This time we take the important d5-pawn, gaining access to the c6-square for our knight. The position becomes concrete as White will try to quickly  attack the d6-pawn. } 12. Nc4 Re6 { Defending the d6-pawn, although the rook may be exposed here. } 13. Be2 { This is played the most often. White is renewing the threat to our knight on d5. } 13... Nc7 ( { I prefer to put the knight on c7 instead of } 13... Nb6 { . } ) 14. Ncxd6 Ba6 ( { I would like to add that } 14... Nc6 { is also good. } ) { This is fine for Black. The idea is to go ...Nc6-d4 with a strong grip in the centre. As soon as we get our knight to d4, White’s pair of knights become unstable. A sample line is } 15. Bg5 Qd7 { It is more cautious not to take the bishop. } 16. a4 Nc6 { Just to complete development. } 17. Nb7 Qxd1+ 18. Rxd1 Nxb5 19. Nxc5 Nbd4 20. Nxe6 Nxe6 21. Bxa6 Nb4 { The only way not to lose a piece. } 22. Be3 Nxa6 { With a balanced endgame. } *

