1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. h3 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Bd3 { This is one of the best setups for White against the Benoni. White doesn't allow us to play ...Bg4 and exchange our light-squared  bishop. Given time White can castle, play Re1, Bf4, a4 and achieve a very harmonious position. } 9... b5 { Objectively this is the best move. The temporary pawn sacrifice is justified because White has wasted time by playing h3. } ( 9... Re8 { is a line suggested by John Doknjas in The Modern Benoni, which I considered and analyzed as well. However, objectively this is not so strong. I might add it as an alternative line in a future update. } ) 10. Nxb5 { This is the more ambitious move; although the exchange of Black’s b-pawn for White’s e-pawn favours Black, White will try to make the best of his piece activity. } 10... Re8 ( { Only like this. Now we're threatening both ...Nxe4 and ...Nxd5. The immediate } 10... Nxe4 { is considerably worse for Black after } 11. Bxe4 Re8 12. Ng5 { . } ) 11. O-O { This is the main move. White gives up the e4-pawn but will try to make use of their piece activity to get an advantage. } 11... Nxe4 { We take back the pawn. } 12. Qa4 { White attacks the e4-knight while activating her majesty. } 12... a6 { There is no time to retreat the knight because then White would get the initiative by putting pressure on the d6-pawn. Of course we cannot immediately take the knight on b5 due to the pin on the a-file, but we can further prepare this capture with ...Bd7 or even ...Nd7. } 13. Bxe4 Bd7 { the only way. The knight is pinned and we can take it on the next move. } 14. Re1 { White brings the rook into play and avoids the fork after ...Bxb5. } 14... Qb6 { There is no rush to take the knight. } 15. Bf4 Bxb5 16. Qb3 c4 { The only move, as we need to prevent White from playing a4. } 17. Qa3 Nd7 { This gives up the d6-pawn, but we get good compensation for it. } 18. Bxd6 Rac8 { With good compensation. A sample line is } 19. Bc2 Rxe1+ 20. Rxe1 Bxb2 21. Qxb2 Qxd6 22. a4 c3 23. Qb3 Bc4 24. Qxc3 Qxd5 { with equality. } *

