1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. h3 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Bd3 { This is one of the best setups for White against the Benoni. White doesn't allow us to play ...Bg4 and exchange our light-squared  bishop. Given time White can castle, play Re1, Bf4, a4 and achieve a very harmonious position. } 9... b5 { Objectively this is the best move. The temporary pawn sacrifice is justified because White has wasted time by playing h3. } ( 9... Re8 { is a line suggested by John Doknjas in The Modern Benoni, which I considered and analyzed as well. However, objectively this is not so strong. I might add it as an alternative line in a future update. } ) 10. Nxb5 { This is the more ambitious move; although the exchange of Black’s b-pawn for White’s e-pawn favours Black, White will try to make the best of his piece activity. } 10... Re8 ( { Only like this. Now we're threatening both ...Nxe4 and ...Nxd5. The immediate } 10... Nxe4 { is considerably worse for Black after } 11. Bxe4 Re8 12. Ng5 { . } ) 11. O-O { This is the main move. White gives up the e4-pawn but will try to make use of their piece activity to get an advantage. } 11... Nxe4 { We take back the pawn. } 12. Bxe4 { White gets rid of the knight on e4 and tries to play for a small advantage. } 12... Rxe4 13. Nc3 Re8 { I think it becomes easier for Black to develop their pieces after the exchange on e4. } 14. Re1 Rxe1+ 15. Qxe1 Nd7 16. Bf4 Nf6 { We’ve managed to finish developing, so our position is fine. The internet game ½-½ (45) Giri, A (2764)-Fier, A (2562) Chess.com INT 2020 continued } 17. Qd2 Bb7 18. Re1 Qd7 19. Ng5 Re8 20. Nge4 Nxe4 21. Nxe4 f5 22. Nxd6 Rxe1+ 23. Qxe1 Bxd5 { with an equal endgame. } *

