1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. h3 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Bd3 { This is one of the best setups for White against the Benoni. White doesn't allow us to play ...Bg4 and exchange our light-squared  bishop. Given time White can castle, play Re1, Bf4, a4 and achieve a very harmonious position. } 9... b5 { Objectively this is the best move. The temporary pawn sacrifice is justified because White has wasted time by playing h3. } ( 9... Re8 { is a line suggested by John Doknjas in The Modern Benoni, which I considered and analyzed as well. However, objectively this is not so strong. I might add it as an alternative line in a future update. } ) 10. Nxb5 { This is the more ambitious move; although the exchange of Black’s b-pawn for White’s e-pawn favours Black, White will try to make the best of his piece activity. } 10... Re8 ( { Only like this. Now we're threatening both ...Nxe4 and ...Nxd5. The immediate } 10... Nxe4 { is considerably worse for Black after } 11. Bxe4 Re8 12. Ng5 { . } ) 11. O-O { This is the main move. White gives up the e4-pawn but will try to make use of their piece activity to get an advantage. } 11... Nxe4 { We take back the pawn. } 12. Re1 a6 ( { As usual, we force the knight away from its active square. Retreating the knight with } 12... Nf6 { would be more passive. } ) 13. Nc3 { This is an interesting line. White sacrifices a pawn for the sake of development. I’ve tried this move myself with White many years ago. } 13... Nxc3 14. bxc3 Bxc3 { I think it's best that we accept the pawn  sacrifice. Although we lag a bit in development we'll be able to coordinate our pieces just in time. } 15. Rxe8+ Qxe8 16. Rb1 Bg7 { I prefer to move the bishop back. It is true that we’ve lost two moves by taking the c3-pawn, but I think it was worth the pawn. We can give the pawn back later on and reach an equal position. } 17. Bf4 Qd8 { The queen is well-placed on d8. } 18. Qe2 Bf8 { In this case it is essential to defend the d6-pawn before going ...Nd7, as we would gain nothing from giving back the pawn here. Our next move is ...Nd7 and step by step we'll manage to complete our development. Meanwhile, White has no way to take advantage of their lead in development. } *

