1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. h3 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Bd3 { This is one of the best setups for White against the Benoni. White doesn't allow us to play ...Bg4 and exchange our light-squared  bishop. Given time White can castle, play Re1, Bf4, a4 and achieve a very harmonious position. } 9... b5 { Objectively this is the best move. The temporary pawn sacrifice is justified because White has wasted time by playing h3. } ( 9... Re8 { is a line suggested by John Doknjas in The Modern Benoni, which I considered and analyzed as well. However, objectively this is not so strong. I might add it as an alternative line in a future update. } ) 10. Nxb5 { This is the more ambitious move; although the exchange of Black’s b-pawn for White’s e-pawn favours Black, White will try to make the best of his piece activity. } 10... Re8 ( { Only like this. Now we're threatening both ...Nxe4 and ...Nxd5. The immediate } 10... Nxe4 { is considerably worse for Black after } 11. Bxe4 Re8 12. Ng5 { . } ) 11. O-O { This is the main move. White gives up the e4-pawn but will try to make use of their piece activity to get an advantage. } 11... Nxe4 { We take back the pawn. } 12. Re1 a6 ( { As usual, we force the knight away from its active square. Retreating the knight with } 12... Nf6 { would be more passive. } ) 13. Qa4 Nd7 { This is the most precise. We develop the knight and intend to exchange the knight on e4 for the one on b5. } 14. Rxe4 Rxe4 15. Qxe4 Nf6 { A good in-between move. } 16. Qh4 axb5 17. Bxb5 Qb6 18. a4 Nxd5 { We can finally take back the pawn. } 19. Bh6 Ba6 { After we exchange the b5-bishop we'll be able to attack White's pawns on the queenside. White has no serious attack on the kingside as we can always defend with ...Nf6. } *

