1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 ( 6. Nf3 g6 7. h3 Bg7 8. e4 O-O { is another way to reach the mainline of this chapter. } ) 6... g6 7. h3 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Be3 { This is a relatively new plan. White wants to develop the light-squared bishop to d3 next, considering that an immediate ...b5 is advantageous to him. That's because the e-file is now covered, and White can play Bxb5 directly, without spending time on Bd3. } 9... b5 { However, this is still the most direct approach. We don't allow White to get his desired setup (with Bd3 and O-O, or Nd2 and Be2). This move leads to unclear positions, somehow different from the typical Benoni ones. } 10. Bxb5 { This doesn't pose any problems for Black. } 10... Nxe4 { The point. } 11. Nxe4 Qa5+ { This check gets the piece back. } 12. Nc3 Bxc3+ 13. bxc3 Qxb5 { White's king is stuck in the centre, so he will have to agree to exchange queens, resulting in an equal endgame. } *

