1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 ( 6. Nf3 g6 7. h3 Bg7 8. e4 O-O { is another way to reach the mainline of this chapter. } ) 6... g6 7. h3 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Be3 { This is a relatively new plan. White wants to develop the light-squared bishop to d3 next, considering that an immediate ...b5 is advantageous to him. That's because the e-file is now covered, and White can play Bxb5 directly, without spending time on Bd3. } 9... b5 { However, this is still the most direct approach. We don't allow White to get his desired setup (with Bd3 and O-O, or Nd2 and Be2). This move leads to unclear positions, somehow different from the typical Benoni ones. } 10. e5 { This is White's idea. By giving up the e-pawn he closes the diagonal of our dark-squared bishop and clears the path for the d-pawn. White will win back a pawn on the next move. } 10... dxe5 { We have to take the pawn; there is not much of a choice. } 11. Bxc5 b4 { This pawn sacrifice disrupts White's coordination. It lures White's bishop away from the important g1-a7 diagonal. } 12. Bxf8 Bxf8 { This gives Black a strong initiative as White is lagging in development. } *

