1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 ( 6. Nf3 g6 7. h3 Bg7 8. e4 O-O { is another way to reach the mainline of this chapter. } ) 6... g6 7. h3 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Be3 { This is a relatively new plan. White wants to develop the light-squared bishop to d3 next, considering that an immediate ...b5 is advantageous to him. That's because the e-file is now covered, and White can play Bxb5 directly, without spending time on Bd3. } 9... b5 { However, this is still the most direct approach. We don't allow White to get his desired setup (with Bd3 and O-O, or Nd2 and Be2). This move leads to unclear positions, somehow different from the typical Benoni ones. } 10. e5 { This is White's idea. By giving up the e-pawn he closes the diagonal of our dark-squared bishop and clears the path for the d-pawn. White will win back a pawn on the next move. } 10... dxe5 { We have to take the pawn; there is not much of a choice. } 11. Bxb5 e4 ( { An important move. } 11... Nbd7 { has been played in earlier games, but it gives White easy play and an advantage. We need to open up the diagonal of the g7-bishop right away. } ) 12. Nh2 ( 12. Ng5 { would be a mistake, as after } 12... h6 { we win a piece: after the exchange on e4 we have ...Qa5+ and the b5-bishop drops. } ) 12... Nxd5 { We can grab the d5-pawn because the bishop on b5 is hanging after ...Qa5+. } 13. Nxd5 Qa5+ 14. Qd2 Qxb5 15. Nc7 { White takes his chance and grabs the exchange. } 15... Qc6 16. Nxa8 Ba6 { White’s king is stuck in the centre and also the knight on h2 is out of play. After we collect the a8-knight, we can further develop our initiative. } *

