1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 ( 6. Nf3 g6 7. h3 Bg7 8. e4 O-O { is another way to reach the mainline of this chapter. } ) 6... g6 7. h3 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Be3 { This is a relatively new plan. White wants to develop the light-squared bishop to d3 next, considering that an immediate ...b5 is advantageous to him. That's because the e-file is now covered, and White can play Bxb5 directly, without spending time on Bd3. } 9... b5 { However, this is still the most direct approach. We don't allow White to get his desired setup (with Bd3 and O-O, or Nd2 and Be2). This move leads to unclear positions, somehow different from the typical Benoni ones. } 10. e5 { This is White's idea. By giving up the e-pawn he closes the diagonal of our dark-squared bishop and clears the path for the d-pawn. White will win back a pawn on the next move. } 10... dxe5 { We have to take the pawn; there is not much of a choice. } 11. Bxb5 e4 ( { An important move. } 11... Nbd7 { has been played in earlier games, but it gives White easy play and an advantage. We need to open up the diagonal of the g7-bishop right away. } ) 12. Nd2 { This drops the d5-pawn. } 12... Nxd5 { We get rid of the dangerous d-pawn. } 13. Nxd5 Qxd5 14. O-O Nc6 { White has compensation for the pawn, but we're also doing fine after getting rid of the d5-pawn. We want to play ...Nd4 as the knight will be very strong on d4, so White probably has to give up either bishop for the knight. } *

