1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 ( 6. Nf3 g6 7. h3 Bg7 8. e4 O-O { is another way to reach the mainline of this chapter. } ) 6... g6 7. h3 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Be3 { This is a relatively new plan. White wants to develop the light-squared bishop to d3 next, considering that an immediate ...b5 is advantageous to him. That's because the e-file is now covered, and White can play Bxb5 directly, without spending time on Bd3. } 9... b5 { However, this is still the most direct approach. We don't allow White to get his desired setup (with Bd3 and O-O, or Nd2 and Be2). This move leads to unclear positions, somehow different from the typical Benoni ones. } 10. e5 { This is White's idea. By giving up the e-pawn he closes the diagonal of our dark-squared bishop and clears the path for the d-pawn. White will win back a pawn on the next move. } 10... dxe5 { We have to take the pawn; there is not much of a choice. } 11. Bxb5 e4 ( { An important move. } 11... Nbd7 { has been played in earlier games, but it gives White easy play and an advantage. We need to open up the diagonal of the g7-bishop right away. } ) 12. Ne5 { The only real test. } 12... Nh5 { We need to challenge the e5-knight and see where it goes. } 13. Nc4 { This is more ambitious. White keeps more pieces on the board and is supporting the d5-pawn. } 13... Bd7 { This unlikely move is best. The exchange of the light-squared bishops favours Black. We also have the  immediate threat of ...Bxc3+ followed by ...Bxb5. } 14. O-O Bxc3 { This is forced, as otherwise the c5-pawn is just hanging. } 15. Bxd7 Bd4 { An important move. After the d7-bishop moves, we'll grab the d5-pawn. } 16. Ba4 Qxd5 { We’ve managed to neutralize White’s dangerous d-pawn. However, we haven’t yet managed to develop the knight on b8, so White keeps good compensation. } 17. Na5 Qe5 { Unpinning the queen and preparing ...Nf4 or ...Qc7. The b8-knight has to guard the c6-square, so we cannot move it yet. } 18. Bb3 Qd6 { In order the develop the knight to a good square next, either to c6 or d7. We can move our queen back into a pin on the d-file because, due to his last move, White has no b2-b4 anymore. } 19. Nc4 Qd8 { This is the best square for the queen for now. The whole queen journey was worth it because we have grabbed the dangerous d-pawn. } 20. Qc2 Nf6 { Defending e4. In this position it is more important to pay attention to your opponent's plans than to continue with you own. } 21. Nd2 Nc6 { Finally we give up the extra pawn in exchange for completing our development. } 22. Nxe4 Nxe4 23. Qxe4 Rc8 { Black has active pieces and thus the position is about equal. White will not keep the pair of bishops as the dark-squared bishops will soon be exchanged. } *

