1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 ( 6. Nf3 g6 7. h3 Bg7 8. e4 O-O { is another way to reach the mainline of this chapter. } ) 6... g6 7. h3 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Be3 { This is a relatively new plan. White wants to develop the light-squared bishop to d3 next, considering that an immediate ...b5 is advantageous to him. That's because the e-file is now covered, and White can play Bxb5 directly, without spending time on Bd3. } 9... b5 { However, this is still the most direct approach. We don't allow White to get his desired setup (with Bd3 and O-O, or Nd2 and Be2). This move leads to unclear positions, somehow different from the typical Benoni ones. } 10. e5 { This is White's idea. By giving up the e-pawn he closes the diagonal of our dark-squared bishop and clears the path for the d-pawn. White will win back a pawn on the next move. } 10... dxe5 { We have to take the pawn; there is not much of a choice. } 11. Bxb5 e4 ( { An important move. } 11... Nbd7 { has been played in earlier games, but it gives White easy play and an advantage. We need to open up the diagonal of the g7-bishop right away. } ) 12. Ne5 { The only real test. } 12... Nh5 { We need to challenge the e5-knight and see where it goes. } 13. Nc4 { This is more ambitious. White keeps more pieces on the board and is supporting the d5-pawn. } 13... Bd7 { This unlikely move is best. The exchange of the light-squared bishops favours Black. We also have the  immediate threat of ...Bxc3+ followed by ...Bxb5. } 14. a4 { White postpones the exchange of bishops for now, because if we take on b5 he wants to take back with the a-pawn which is undesirable for us. } 14... a6 { We exchange the bishops on our own terms. } 15. Bxd7 Nxd7 { The inclusion of a4 ...a6 is not so important. Now we can turn our attention to the kingside. } 16. O-O f5 17. d6 Qe8 { Intending ...f4 with an unclear position. } *

