1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 ( 6. Nf3 g6 7. h3 Bg7 8. e4 O-O { is another way to reach the mainline of this chapter. } ) 6... g6 7. h3 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Bg5 { White wants to play 10. Bd3 and avoid the forced lines with ...b5. In case of ...h6 he intends to retreat the bishop to e3, and after Qd2 to gain a tempo by attacking the h6-pawn. } 9... Re8 10. Bd3 c4 { This is Black's preferred solution in this position. } 11. Bc2 b5 { We’ve got our queenside play going and have a nice square for the knight on c5. On the other hand, we’ve given up the d4-square that White can use for his knight, and also for now it's not easy to further advance the queenside  pawns. } 12. O-O ( { This is more flexible than the standard move } 12. a3 { White had to castle anyway, while it is not clear that ...b4 is the best move for Black right now. } ) 12... a6 ( { I like this move. The immediate } 12... b4 { allows White's knight to jump to b5. } ) 13. Qd2 Nbd7 { The knight is heading towards c5. } 14. Rfe1 b4 { It's time to take advantage of the fact that White didn't play a3. } 15. Ne2 Qb6 { With the idea to go for a quick ...b3 push once the e2-knight moves. } 16. Ng3 b3 { Executing our main idea. } 17. axb3 cxb3 18. Be3 Nc5 { Bringing the d7-knight into play. } 19. Bb1 Nfd7 { This is important, as with the bishop on b1 White intends to play e5, since the d5-pawn is defended by the white queen. } 20. Ra5 Rb8 { With the idea to play ...Qb4. The b3-pawn is quite a thorn in White’s position. } *

