1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 ( 6. Nf3 g6 7. h3 Bg7 8. e4 O-O { is another way to reach the mainline of this chapter. } ) 6... g6 7. h3 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Bg5 { White wants to play 10. Bd3 and avoid the forced lines with ...b5. In case of ...h6 he intends to retreat the bishop to e3, and after Qd2 to gain a tempo by attacking the h6-pawn. } 9... Re8 10. Bd3 c4 { This is Black's preferred solution in this position. } 11. Bc2 b5 { We’ve got our queenside play going and have a nice square for the knight on c5. On the other hand, we’ve given up the d4-square that White can use for his knight, and also for now it's not easy to further advance the queenside  pawns. } 12. a3 { The most common move in this position. White prevents ...b4, which will be difficult to achieve later on as well. We'll have to complete our development and then prepare it with ...a5. Of course, White players don't want to calculate the consequences of the ...b4 push every move. } 12... Nbd7 { The knight is heading to c5. } 13. O-O Nc5 ( 13... Qb6 { is also possible and likely transposes later on. } ) 14. Nxb5 Ba6 { The bishop has good perspectives on a6. If the knight retreats we'll have ideas of ...Nd3 at the right moment. } 15. Nc3 h6 { Now if White doesn't take on f6, we’ll win the e4-pawn. } 16. Bxf6 Qxf6 { We’ve sacrificed a pawn, but in return we’ve forced White to give up his strong dark-squared bishop and we can put pressure on the open b-file. Also the knight on c5 has a lot of potential – at the right moment it can jump to the well- protected d3-square. } 17. Rb1 Rab8 { All of Black’s pieces are active. } 18. Re1 Rb7 { Keeping the rooks flexible. Black can double the rooks on either the e- or b-file. } 19. Qc1 Nd3 { A direct approach. It is also possible to shuffle the pieces around a bit more. } 20. Bxd3 cxd3 21. Qd2 Rc8 { This was first seen in the correspondence game ½-½ (31) Kiselev,V (2348) -Nefedov,S (2543) ICCF 2015. Black has easy play and good compensation for the pawn. All the black pieces are active, and the d3-pawn is strong. } *

