1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 ( 6. Nf3 g6 7. h3 Bg7 8. e4 O-O { is another way to reach the mainline of this chapter. } ) 6... g6 7. h3 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Bg5 { White wants to play 10. Bd3 and avoid the forced lines with ...b5. In case of ...h6 he intends to retreat the bishop to e3, and after Qd2 to gain a tempo by attacking the h6-pawn. } 9... Re8 10. Bd3 c4 { This is Black's preferred solution in this position. } 11. Bc2 b5 { We’ve got our queenside play going and have a nice square for the knight on c5. On the other hand, we’ve given up the d4-square that White can use for his knight, and also for now it's not easy to further advance the queenside  pawns. } 12. a3 { The most common move in this position. White prevents ...b4, which will be difficult to achieve later on as well. We'll have to complete our development and then prepare it with ...a5. Of course, White players don't want to calculate the consequences of the ...b4 push every move. } 12... Nbd7 { The knight is heading to c5. } 13. O-O Nc5 ( 13... Qb6 { is also possible and likely transposes later on. } ) 14. Re1 Qb6 { We defend the b5-pawn and prepare the advance ...a5. } 15. Qd2 ( { This move is played the most often here, although it is less critical than } 15. Be3 { . } ) 15... Nfd7 16. Bh6 ( { Black prevents e5. It is important that we can meet } 16. Nd4 { with } 16... Nd3 ) 16... Bh8 ( { This doesn't really change much, as our bishop is just as good on h8 as on g7. } 16... Ne5 { is also a good move. } ) 17. Be3 a5 { We continue with our play on the queenside. } 18. Ng5 { White’s idea behind this move is to continue with f4. } 18... h6 { It's better to drive the knight away immediately. } 19. Nf3 Ba6 { If White takes the h6-pawn the c5-knight is not pinned anymore and we can continue ...b4 with strong counterplay. } 20. Bxh6 b4 { Starting our queenside counterplay. } 21. axb4 axb4 22. Na4 { It's useful for White to exchange the knights. } 22... Nxa4 23. Bxa4 c3 { We’ve finally managed to achieve this important push. } 24. bxc3 Bxc3 { With good counterplay and compensation for the pawn. A sample line is } 25. Qc2 Bb5 26. Bxb5 Qxb5 27. Rxa8 Rxa8 { . } *

