1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 ( 6. Nf3 g6 7. h3 Bg7 8. e4 O-O { is another way to reach the mainline of this chapter. } ) 6... g6 7. h3 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Bg5 { White wants to play 10. Bd3 and avoid the forced lines with ...b5. In case of ...h6 he intends to retreat the bishop to e3, and after Qd2 to gain a tempo by attacking the h6-pawn. } 9... Re8 10. Bd3 c4 { This is Black's preferred solution in this position. } 11. Bc2 b5 { We’ve got our queenside play going and have a nice square for the knight on c5. On the other hand, we’ve given up the d4-square that White can use for his knight, and also for now it's not easy to further advance the queenside  pawns. } 12. a3 { The most common move in this position. White prevents ...b4, which will be difficult to achieve later on as well. We'll have to complete our development and then prepare it with ...a5. Of course, White players don't want to calculate the consequences of the ...b4 push every move. } 12... Nbd7 { The knight is heading to c5. } 13. O-O Nc5 ( 13... Qb6 { is also possible and likely transposes later on. } ) 14. Re1 Qb6 { We defend the b5-pawn and prepare the advance ...a5. } 15. Be3 { The bishop is better placed on e3 in this position. White wants to continue with either Bd4 or the immediate e5. } 15... a5 { We expand on the queenside. It’s good that we were able to move the pawn to a5 in one move. } 16. e5 { White sacrifices the e-pawn for the initiative. } 16... dxe5 17. Nd2 { White is trying to make use of the pin on the g1-a7 diagonal. } 17... Bf8 { We need to keep the c5-knight defended. } 18. a4 b4 { There was no way for us to keep the c4-pawn. } 19. Nxc4 Qa6 { Other queen retreats are possible as well. } 20. Nb5 Bd7 21. Bxc5 ( { Going after the b5-knight. Of course White cannot answer } 21. Nc7 { because of } 21... Qxc4 { . } ) 21... Bxc5 22. Qe2 Rac8 { Followed by ...e4 with good play. At the right moment we can consider taking on b5 as well. } *

