1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 ( 6. Nf3 g6 7. h3 Bg7 8. e4 O-O { is another way to reach the mainline of this chapter. } ) 6... g6 7. h3 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Bg5 { White wants to play 10. Bd3 and avoid the forced lines with ...b5. In case of ...h6 he intends to retreat the bishop to e3, and after Qd2 to gain a tempo by attacking the h6-pawn. } 9... Re8 10. Bd3 h6 { Let's see where the g5-bishop is going. We can go ...g5 later on and get some play on the kingside. Of course this involves some risks but it may be fun to play! } 11. Bh4 { This keeps the pin, but I think it is stronger to keep the bishop on the c1-h6 diagonal. } 11... c4 { We can expand on the queenside. } 12. Bc2 b5 { This provides us with a good version of the 10...c4 line. } *

