1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 ( 6. Nf3 g6 7. h3 Bg7 8. e4 O-O { is another way to reach the mainline of this chapter. } ) 6... g6 7. h3 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Bg5 { White wants to play 10. Bd3 and avoid the forced lines with ...b5. In case of ...h6 he intends to retreat the bishop to e3, and after Qd2 to gain a tempo by attacking the h6-pawn. } 9... Re8 10. Bd3 h6 { Let's see where the g5-bishop is going. We can go ...g5 later on and get some play on the kingside. Of course this involves some risks but it may be fun to play! } 11. Be3 { The only good move, as here the bishop covers the e-file. } 11... Nbd7 { It's better to skip the inclusion of ...a6 and a4 for now, because we want to keep open the option to play ...b5 directly. } 12. a4 { This is a subtle solution. It has never been played according to my database. } 12... g5 { We continue our expansion on the kingside. } 13. Qd2 { White delays castling and wants to put pressure on Black’s kingside with h4. } 13... a6 { I don't think we can do without this move. } 14. O-O Rb8 { We can play ...b5 next. White cannot take on b5 twice because the e4-pawn is hanging. } *

