1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 ( 6. Nf3 g6 7. h3 Bg7 8. e4 O-O { is another way to reach the mainline of this chapter. } ) 6... g6 7. h3 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Bg5 { White wants to play 10. Bd3 and avoid the forced lines with ...b5. In case of ...h6 he intends to retreat the bishop to e3, and after Qd2 to gain a tempo by attacking the h6-pawn. } 9... Re8 10. Bd3 h6 { Let's see where the g5-bishop is going. We can go ...g5 later on and get some play on the kingside. Of course this involves some risks but it may be fun to play! } 11. Be3 { The only good move, as here the bishop covers the e-file. } 11... Nbd7 { It's better to skip the inclusion of ...a6 and a4 for now, because we want to keep open the option to play ...b5 directly. } 12. O-O { This has been played in most of the games that reach this position. } 12... a6 ( { It seems to me that sooner or later we have to include ...a6 and a4. The immediate } 12... g5 { is also possible, however. } ) 13. a4 g5 { We make use of our extra h6 move to expand on the kingside. This idea is double edged, because it weakens the kingside but at the same time grabs some space over there. It also prevents Bf4 and prepares ...g4 at the right moment. Finally, I want to mention that in these positions it is essential to keep our light-squared bishop alive, as it may be the only piece that can control the f5- square. } 14. Re1 g4 { This is a good moment to start our counterplay on the kingside by gaining access to the g4-square. } 15. hxg4 Nxg4 16. Bf4 { ½-½ (54) Van Wely,L (2610)-Ivanisevic,I (2598) Germany 2019. } 16... Nde5 { This natural move is good. The black king isn't weak, and we have some play on the kingside. ...Ng6 and ...Qf6 are some ideas, for instance. If necessary we can also turn our attention to the queenside with ...Bd7 and ...Rb8. } *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Modern Benoni"]
[Site "?"]
