1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. g3 { Thus Black players who don’t want to play the Catalan when White plays 3. g3 often go for this specific variation in the Benoni. } 7... Bg7 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O { White's plan is to bring the bishop to f4 before or after playing Nd2. h3 is a useful move as it takes away the g4-square for Black. White will play a4 as a response to a6. Usually White doesn't go for e2-e4 quickly, instead preparing it with moves like Re1. } 9... Re8 { This is the starting position of the fianchetto variation. The rook is well placed on e8, and White already has to take into account the move ...Ne4, since it is often quite useful for Black to exchange a pair of knights. Also, after White's Nd2-c4 we need to be ready to play Nd7-e5 or Nd7-b6 in order to challenge White's knight. Therefore Black's b8-knight has to go to d7. It is too slow to instead develop it with ...Na6-c7.It is always a question when to include the moves ...a6 and a4. For the time being, I prefer to be flexible and not include them yet. On the one hand, having White’s pawn on a4 is good for us if we swap the knights on e4 since we can then have a stable square on b4 for our rook. However, in other lines, having the pawn on a4 gives White the additional option of playing a5 with a grip on the queenside. } 10. Nd2 { This is the old approach. White is redirecting the knight towards c4, and at the same time keeps the e4-square under control, thus preventing us from playing ...Ne4. } 10... Nbd7 ( { This is the most flexible move. Other moves are possible too, for example } 10... a6 { or } ) ( 10... b6 { could transpose later on. } ) 11. a4 { A useful move for White, preventing ...b5 and gaining some space on the queenside. } 11... b6 { An interesting move order as we keep open the option of playing ...Ba6. However, most likely we will return to the  plan with ...a6. } 12. Nc4 Ne5 { We defend the d6-pawn and propose an exchange of knights. } 13. Nxe5 Rxe5 14. Bf4 Re8 { This is the best square for the rook. } 15. Nb5 { This is not dangerous, as we can answer } 15... Ne4 { Followed by } 16. -- a6 { back the b5-knight. } *

