1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. g3 { Thus Black players who don’t want to play the Catalan when White plays 3. g3 often go for this specific variation in the Benoni. } 7... Bg7 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O { White's plan is to bring the bishop to f4 before or after playing Nd2. h3 is a useful move as it takes away the g4-square for Black. White will play a4 as a response to a6. Usually White doesn't go for e2-e4 quickly, instead preparing it with moves like Re1. } 9... Re8 { This is the starting position of the fianchetto variation. The rook is well placed on e8, and White already has to take into account the move ...Ne4, since it is often quite useful for Black to exchange a pair of knights. Also, after White's Nd2-c4 we need to be ready to play Nd7-e5 or Nd7-b6 in order to challenge White's knight. Therefore Black's b8-knight has to go to d7. It is too slow to instead develop it with ...Na6-c7.It is always a question when to include the moves ...a6 and a4. For the time being, I prefer to be flexible and not include them yet. On the one hand, having White’s pawn on a4 is good for us if we swap the knights on e4 since we can then have a stable square on b4 for our rook. However, in other lines, having the pawn on a4 gives White the additional option of playing a5 with a grip on the queenside. } 10. Nd2 { This is the old approach. White is redirecting the knight towards c4, and at the same time keeps the e4-square under control, thus preventing us from playing ...Ne4. } 10... Nbd7 ( { This is the most flexible move. Other moves are possible too, for example } 10... a6 { or } ) ( 10... b6 { could transpose later on. } ) 11. a4 { A useful move for White, preventing ...b5 and gaining some space on the queenside. } 11... b6 { An interesting move order as we keep open the option of playing ...Ba6. However, most likely we will return to the  plan with ...a6. } 12. h3 { This is the main move. White prevents a potential ...Ng4. } 12... a6 { This position can be reached via various different move orders - for example, if Black plays a faster ...a6 and ...b6. The point of the move ...b6 is that we prevent White from continuing with a5. We are preparing ...Rb8 and then ...b5. In case of Nc4 we can respond ...Ne5.Time is important in this position. If we manage to play ...b5 we get a very good position. That's why White will try to push his central pawns and get his knight to c4. } 13. Nc4 Ne5 14. Na3 { This is a typical maneuver to open up the c1-bishop, lure our knight to e5 and prepare to kick it with f4 to gain a tempo. } 14... Nh5 { With the idea ...f5. White can push f4 or g4 and win a piece for 2 pawns, but Black will get a strong attack in return, so we would be happy to see that! } 15. g4 Nxg4 { A typical sacrifice. The white king will be in danger a long time from now on. } 16. hxg4 Bxg4 { We’ve  sacrificed a piece for 2 pawns, but we’ve received a lot in return: White's king is weak, there is the direct threat of ...Bxc3 followed by ...Bxe2, and ...b5 is an idea as well. At the same time White is struggling to coordinate their pieces. } 17. Nc4 { White brings the knight into play. } 17... Bxc3 { With the idea to take on e2 next. } 18. f3 { The only move. By attacking 2 pieces, White is sure to get one back. } 18... Ng3 { The knight joins the fight! What an unusual position! The correspondence game ½-½ (39) Biedermann, T (2413)-Morrow, W (2296) ICCF 2012 continued with } 19. Rf2 Nxe2+ 20. Rxe2 Bd4+ 21. Kf1 Qf6 { , and Black had a long-term initiative. } *

