1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. g3 { Thus Black players who don’t want to play the Catalan when White plays 3. g3 often go for this specific variation in the Benoni. } 7... Bg7 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O { White's plan is to bring the bishop to f4 before or after playing Nd2. h3 is a useful move as it takes away the g4-square for Black. White will play a4 as a response to a6. Usually White doesn't go for e2-e4 quickly, instead preparing it with moves like Re1. } 9... Re8 { This is the starting position of the fianchetto variation. The rook is well placed on e8, and White already has to take into account the move ...Ne4, since it is often quite useful for Black to exchange a pair of knights. Also, after White's Nd2-c4 we need to be ready to play Nd7-e5 or Nd7-b6 in order to challenge White's knight. Therefore Black's b8-knight has to go to d7. It is too slow to instead develop it with ...Na6-c7.It is always a question when to include the moves ...a6 and a4. For the time being, I prefer to be flexible and not include them yet. On the one hand, having White’s pawn on a4 is good for us if we swap the knights on e4 since we can then have a stable square on b4 for our rook. However, in other lines, having the pawn on a4 gives White the additional option of playing a5 with a grip on the queenside. } 10. Nd2 { This is the old approach. White is redirecting the knight towards c4, and at the same time keeps the e4-square under control, thus preventing us from playing ...Ne4. } 10... Nbd7 ( { This is the most flexible move. Other moves are possible too, for example } 10... a6 { or } ) ( 10... b6 { could transpose later on. } ) 11. a4 { A useful move for White, preventing ...b5 and gaining some space on the queenside. } 11... b6 { An interesting move order as we keep open the option of playing ...Ba6. However, most likely we will return to the  plan with ...a6. } 12. h3 { This is the main move. White prevents a potential ...Ng4. } 12... a6 { This position can be reached via various different move orders - for example, if Black plays a faster ...a6 and ...b6. The point of the move ...b6 is that we prevent White from continuing with a5. We are preparing ...Rb8 and then ...b5. In case of Nc4 we can respond ...Ne5.Time is important in this position. If we manage to play ...b5 we get a very good position. That's why White will try to push his central pawns and get his knight to c4. } 13. e4 Rb8 { Preparing ...b5. } 14. Nc4 Ne5 { Again this typical way of defending the d6-pawn while offering a knight trade. } 15. Na3 c4 { White’s threat is to play 16.f4 to drive away our knight from the centre. That's why we have to act quickly and with 15... c4 we prepare the knight jump to d3. } 16. f4 { The logical follow-up. } 16... Nd3 { Establishing our knight on the strong d3-square, if only just for one move. } 17. Nxc4 Nxc1 18. e5 { White must play energetically. The knight on c1 has nowhere to go and can be captured later anyway. } 18... dxe5 { We must take on e5 because otherwise the d6-pawn is hanging. } 19. Nxe5 Nh5 { Black must also act quickly. The position is very concrete, but with accurate play Black is fine. } 20. Nc6 Qd6 { The only move. } 21. Rxc1 Nxg3 { Now the white king will be weakened for a long time. } 22. Rf2 Bf5 { We shouldn't waste time trying to save the b8-rook. Besides, the knight on c6 is a strong piece which we are glad to be rid of. } 23. Nxb8 Rxb8 { Black has good compensation for the exchange because of his strong dark-squared bishop and White's weak kingside pawns. Also, we’ve managed to get rid of the c6-knight which was very strong. } *

