1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. g3 { Thus Black players who don’t want to play the Catalan when White plays 3. g3 often go for this specific variation in the Benoni. } 7... Bg7 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O { White's plan is to bring the bishop to f4 before or after playing Nd2. h3 is a useful move as it takes away the g4-square for Black. White will play a4 as a response to a6. Usually White doesn't go for e2-e4 quickly, instead preparing it with moves like Re1. } 9... Re8 { This is the starting position of the fianchetto variation. The rook is well placed on e8, and White already has to take into account the move ...Ne4, since it is often quite useful for Black to exchange a pair of knights. Also, after White's Nd2-c4 we need to be ready to play Nd7-e5 or Nd7-b6 in order to challenge White's knight. Therefore Black's b8-knight has to go to d7. It is too slow to instead develop it with ...Na6-c7.It is always a question when to include the moves ...a6 and a4. For the time being, I prefer to be flexible and not include them yet. On the one hand, having White’s pawn on a4 is good for us if we swap the knights on e4 since we can then have a stable square on b4 for our rook. However, in other lines, having the pawn on a4 gives White the additional option of playing a5 with a grip on the queenside. } 10. Nd2 { This is the old approach. White is redirecting the knight towards c4, and at the same time keeps the e4-square under control, thus preventing us from playing ...Ne4. } 10... Nbd7 ( { This is the most flexible move. Other moves are possible too, for example } 10... a6 { or } ) ( 10... b6 { could transpose later on. } ) 11. a4 { A useful move for White, preventing ...b5 and gaining some space on the queenside. } 11... b6 { An interesting move order as we keep open the option of playing ...Ba6. However, most likely we will return to the  plan with ...a6. } 12. h3 { This is the main move. White prevents a potential ...Ng4. } 12... a6 { This position can be reached via various different move orders - for example, if Black plays a faster ...a6 and ...b6. The point of the move ...b6 is that we prevent White from continuing with a5. We are preparing ...Rb8 and then ...b5. In case of Nc4 we can respond ...Ne5.Time is important in this position. If we manage to play ...b5 we get a very good position. That's why White will try to push his central pawns and get his knight to c4. } 13. f4 { This is White's latest solution, preventing ...Ne5. Thus White is ready to play Nc4. Also the e4 push cannot be stopped. } 13... c4 { I like this pawn sacrifice played by Navara. We get the c-file for our queen (...Qc7 is our next move), and also the d7-knight gets a nice square on c5. Afterwards we can prepare the ...b5 push by playing ...Rb8. } 14. Nxc4 { White probably has to take the pawn. } 14... Qc7 15. Nd2 { There is no better square for the knight. } 15... Nc5 { The next step is to prepare ...b5. } 16. e4 Rb8 ( { Preparing ...b5. I prefer this to } 16... Bd7 { as the rook is removed from the a-file and we can get ...b5 in more quickly. Black is fine in the ensuing complications, but the positions are wild. The game 0-1 (50) Warmerdam,M (2480)-Navara,D (2734) Patras 2019 continued } ) ( 16... Bd7 { and Black won in the end. However, I think White can improve over Warmerdam’s } 17. Kh2 { with } ( 17. g4 ) ) 17. g4 { This is more ambitious, White is preparing e5 and doesn’t want his g3-pawn to be hanging after that. } 17... b5 { While we could have further prepared this advance, now seems to be the right moment to go for it! } 18. e5 { White gives the pawn back and tries to get the initiative. } 18... dxe5 19. fxe5 Rxe5 ( { This slightly limits White's options, however there is not much of difference between this move and } 19... Qxe5 { . } ) 20. Nf3 Re8 { The only move. } 21. Nd4 b4 { We need to keep up the pressure. } 22. Bf4 Qd7 { The queen is quite safe on d7. The position is very unclear and both sides have their trumps. } 23. Bxb8 bxc3 { Followed by ...Nxd5 gives Black good compensation for the exchange. } *

