1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. g3 { Thus Black players who don’t want to play the Catalan when White plays 3. g3 often go for this specific variation in the Benoni. } 7... Bg7 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O { White's plan is to bring the bishop to f4 before or after playing Nd2. h3 is a useful move as it takes away the g4-square for Black. White will play a4 as a response to a6. Usually White doesn't go for e2-e4 quickly, instead preparing it with moves like Re1. } 9... Re8 { This is the starting position of the fianchetto variation. The rook is well placed on e8, and White already has to take into account the move ...Ne4, since it is often quite useful for Black to exchange a pair of knights. Also, after White's Nd2-c4 we need to be ready to play Nd7-e5 or Nd7-b6 in order to challenge White's knight. Therefore Black's b8-knight has to go to d7. It is too slow to instead develop it with ...Na6-c7.It is always a question when to include the moves ...a6 and a4. For the time being, I prefer to be flexible and not include them yet. On the one hand, having White’s pawn on a4 is good for us if we swap the knights on e4 since we can then have a stable square on b4 for our rook. However, in other lines, having the pawn on a4 gives White the additional option of playing a5 with a grip on the queenside. } 10. Re1 { This move is flexible. White is preparing to play e4 in the future. } 10... Nbd7 { Of course Black has other options as well. However after some research I came to like this move. We continue our development and we are intending ...Ne4 on the next move if White doesn't stop it. Although the move sequence ...a6 a4 is part of our plans, we’ve delayed it for now because in some lines White can push the pawn to a5, which is to his advantage. } 11. e4 Ng4 { Now we can make use of the fact that White didn't play h3 before going e4. Our g4-knight will get to e5, and from there it can jump to either c4 or d3. } 12. Bg5 f6 { This just temporarily blocks the long diagonal, and it also further secures the e5-square. At the right moment we'll be able to push ...f5 and open up the g7-bishop again. } 13. Bf4 Nde5 { Making use of our outpost on e5. } 14. h3 Nxf3+ 15. Qxf3 Ne5 { After exchanging one pair of knights we can continue ...Bd7 and launch our play on the queenside. Of course, we also have ...f5 in mind in order to open up the g7-bishop. } 16. Qe2 Bd7 17. a4 a6 { I want to make note of the fact that Black is the one who can break open the position with either ...b5 or ...f5. The correspondence game ½-½ (30) Solar, J (2253) -Zeltsan, J ICCF 2018 continued } 18. a5 b5 19. axb6 Qxb6 20. Ra3 f5 21. Rea1 a5 { with a good position for Black. } *

