1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. g3 { Thus Black players who don’t want to play the Catalan when White plays 3. g3 often go for this specific variation in the Benoni. } 7... Bg7 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O { White's plan is to bring the bishop to f4 before or after playing Nd2. h3 is a useful move as it takes away the g4-square for Black. White will play a4 as a response to a6. Usually White doesn't go for e2-e4 quickly, instead preparing it with moves like Re1. } 9... Re8 { This is the starting position of the fianchetto variation. The rook is well placed on e8, and White already has to take into account the move ...Ne4, since it is often quite useful for Black to exchange a pair of knights. Also, after White's Nd2-c4 we need to be ready to play Nd7-e5 or Nd7-b6 in order to challenge White's knight. Therefore Black's b8-knight has to go to d7. It is too slow to instead develop it with ...Na6-c7.It is always a question when to include the moves ...a6 and a4. For the time being, I prefer to be flexible and not include them yet. On the one hand, having White’s pawn on a4 is good for us if we swap the knights on e4 since we can then have a stable square on b4 for our rook. However, in other lines, having the pawn on a4 gives White the additional option of playing a5 with a grip on the queenside. } 10. Re1 { This move is flexible. White is preparing to play e4 in the future. } 10... Nbd7 { Of course Black has other options as well. However after some research I came to like this move. We continue our development and we are intending ...Ne4 on the next move if White doesn't stop it. Although the move sequence ...a6 a4 is part of our plans, we’ve delayed it for now because in some lines White can push the pawn to a5, which is to his advantage. } 11. a4 Ne4 { Now this works just fine. Additionally we have the b4-square for our rook after the exchange on e4. } 12. Nxe4 Rxe4 13. Qc2 { So far this was ½-½ (42) Sadzikowski,D (2534)-Donchenko,A (2604) Caleta 2019. } 13... Rb4 { It's a pity if Black doesn’t bring the rook to b4. } 14. Ra2 b5 { A typical way of opening the b-file. } 15. axb5 Rxb5 16. Nd2 a5 { Black has active play on the queenside. } *

