1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. g3 { Thus Black players who don’t want to play the Catalan when White plays 3. g3 often go for this specific variation in the Benoni. } 7... Bg7 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O { White's plan is to bring the bishop to f4 before or after playing Nd2. h3 is a useful move as it takes away the g4-square for Black. White will play a4 as a response to a6. Usually White doesn't go for e2-e4 quickly, instead preparing it with moves like Re1. } 9... Re8 { This is the starting position of the fianchetto variation. The rook is well placed on e8, and White already has to take into account the move ...Ne4, since it is often quite useful for Black to exchange a pair of knights. Also, after White's Nd2-c4 we need to be ready to play Nd7-e5 or Nd7-b6 in order to challenge White's knight. Therefore Black's b8-knight has to go to d7. It is too slow to instead develop it with ...Na6-c7.It is always a question when to include the moves ...a6 and a4. For the time being, I prefer to be flexible and not include them yet. On the one hand, having White’s pawn on a4 is good for us if we swap the knights on e4 since we can then have a stable square on b4 for our rook. However, in other lines, having the pawn on a4 gives White the additional option of playing a5 with a grip on the queenside. } 10. a4 { This prevents a potential ...b5, but it does nothing against ...Ne4. } 10... Ne4 ( { This is justified, as after the exchange on e4 we can use the b4-square for the rook. } 10... b6 11. Nd2 Nbd7 { would transpose to the line 10. Nd2 Nbd7 11. a4 b6. } ) 11. Nxe4 Rxe4 12. Nd2 Rb4 { This is the point. The rook is actively placed on b4 and cannot be attacked by a pawn as White has already played a4. If White attacks the rook with Bd2 we can just sacrifice the exchange. Our idea is to play ...a5 to secure the rook against an exchange sacrifice. } 13. Ra2 { White plans to improve his position with b3 and Nc4. } 13... a5 { A strong move. The idea is to gain space on the queenside and prepare ...b5. } 14. b3 b5 ( { We continue our counterplay on the queenside. } 14... Nd7 { should lead to the same position. } ) 15. axb5 Nd7 { This is an important move, as otherwise we will not be in time to parry 16. Nc4 followed by Bf4 with strong pressure on the d6-pawn. } 16. Qc2 Nb6 { A useful move. We keep open the option  of playing ...a4 even before taking on b5. } 17. Nc4 Rxb5 18. Nb2 Rb8 { A good way to put even more pressure on the b-file. } 19. Bd2 Bf5 { It is good to force White to play e4. } 20. e4 Bd7 { This position was reached in some correspondence games. Black's pieces are active. We can improve the position even further by ...h5 or ...Qc7 or get ready to push ...a4. } 21. Bxa5 { Of course the pawn cannot be taken. } 21... Rxa5 22. Rxa5 Bxb2 23. Qxb2 Nc4 { Winning a piece. } *

