gain space on the queenside and prepare ...b5. } 14. b3 b5 ( { We continue our counterplay on the queenside. } 14... Nd7 { should lead to the same position. } ) 15. axb5 Nd7 { This is an important move, as otherwise we will not be in time to parry 16. Nc4 followed by Bf4 with strong pressure on the d6-pawn. } 16. Ne4 Qe7 17. Qc2 Rxb5 { Regaining the pawn. } 18. Bg5 Nf6 { White cannot make use of this pin. } 19. Qd3 Rb7 { Preventing tricks with Nxc5 followed by d6. } 20. Qe3 h6 21. Bxf6 { After this move, Black's superiority on the queenside is undisputed. } 21... Bxf6 22. Qf4 Be5 23. Qxh6 Rxb3 { White's strategy is not working out. } 24. Nxc5 { This was 0-1 (39) Grischuk,A (2792)-Caruana,F (2791) Stavanger 2014. } 24... Rb2 { Black is slightly better due to the strong dark-squared bishop and the passed a-pawn. The combination of these two factors more than compensate for the pawn minus. } *

