1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. g3 { Thus Black players who don’t want to play the Catalan when White plays 3. g3 often go for this specific variation in the Benoni. } 7... Bg7 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O { White's plan is to bring the bishop to f4 before or after playing Nd2. h3 is a useful move as it takes away the g4-square for Black. White will play a4 as a response to a6. Usually White doesn't go for e2-e4 quickly, instead preparing it with moves like Re1. } 9... Re8 { This is the starting position of the fianchetto variation. The rook is well placed on e8, and White already has to take into account the move ...Ne4, since it is often quite useful for Black to exchange a pair of knights. Also, after White's Nd2-c4 we need to be ready to play Nd7-e5 or Nd7-b6 in order to challenge White's knight. Therefore Black's b8-knight has to go to d7. It is too slow to instead develop it with ...Na6-c7.It is always a question when to include the moves ...a6 and a4. For the time being, I prefer to be flexible and not include them yet. On the one hand, having White’s pawn on a4 is good for us if we swap the knights on e4 since we can then have a stable square on b4 for our rook. However, in other lines, having the pawn on a4 gives White the additional option of playing a5 with a grip on the queenside. } 10. h3 { Again a useful move, but this doesn't prevent ...Ne4. } 10... Ne4 11. Nxe4 Rxe4 { The knights exchange favours Black because it opens up our dark-squared bishop and gives us more space to develop our pieces. } 12. Nd2 Re8 13. a4 Nd7 14. Ra2 { White is preparing to play b3 and only then Nc4. } ( { We are ready to meet } 14. Nc4 { with } 14... Ne5 { . } ) 14... Qe7 15. Re1 { This is a typical strategy for White in this line. White makes small useful moves before pushing the pawns forward. } 15... b6 { We'll bring the bishop to a6 where it has a good position. } 16. Nc4 Ne5 17. b3 Bd7 { Black is doing fine because we’ve  managed to exchange a pair of knights and now all our pieces have good positions. We keep open options to play either ...f5 or ...b5. } *

