at this closes in our g7-bishop, but White's attack on the g5-pawn is parried. The bishop on g7 is not permanently closed in, we can open it up at the right moment with ...f5. The knight on g4 is well-placed, and the other knight can come to either e5 and from there to g6 or f7, or via f8 to g6. White may have to prepare b4 and play on the queenside. } 15. Qc2 Nde5 { An obvious and strong move. From here the knight can head to f7, and meanwhile we are preparing to develop the light-squared bishop to d7. } 16. b4 b6 { This is generally a good reply against b4, as we need to be able to take back on c5 with the b-pawn. } 17. bxc5 bxc5 18. Rab1 Nf7 { We're defending the g5 pawn in order to continue ...f5 to activate our dark-squared bishop. White controls the b-file but there is not much for him to do there yet. The position is balanced. } *

