at this closes in our g7-bishop, but White's attack on the g5-pawn is parried. The bishop on g7 is not permanently closed in, we can open it up at the right moment with ...f5. The knight on g4 is well-placed, and the other knight can come to either e5 and from there to g6 or f7, or via f8 to g6. White may have to prepare b4 and play on the queenside. } 15. a4 b6 { This is a useful prophylactic move, as sooner or later White will play b4. } 16. Qc2 a6 { This move has two ideas. If White doesn't play b4 we can prepare the push ...b5 after ...Rb8. Secondly, we gain the possibility of playing ...Ra7 in order to transfer the rook to the kingside. } 17. Rab1 Nde5 18. b4 Nc4 { Why not take advantage of this square? } 19. Bc1 Qe7 { Securing the position of the knight on c4, as now White cannot move the c3-knight without leaving the e2-pawn hanging. } 20. bxc5 bxc5 21. Re1 { White prepares to play Nd1 after which we would have to move the c4-knight, and then White can continue Ne3. } 21... Nce5 { With the idea to exchange on f3 since White cannot take back with the pawn. } *

