1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. Bg5 { White intends to get an ideal setup with a grip after e4 and Nd2, when the pin on the h4-d8 diagonal will be annoying. } 7... h6 { I'd rather see where this bishop is going. } 8. Bh4 g5 9. Bg3 Nh5 { We should chase the bishop immediately. White's position will lose its flexibility once the bishop is gone. } 10. e3 { This is played the most often. } 10... Nxg3 ( { It's good to take the bishop at once. If } 10... Bg7 { White has the option to play } 11. Bb5+ { . } ) 11. hxg3 Bg7 12. Bd3 Nd7 { I think it's better to delay castling for now, and see what White is doing. We have some useful moves like ...Qe7, ...Ne5, ...a6 in any case. } 13. Qc2 Qe7 14. Bf5 O-O { Now we can castle, as White can no longer gain a tempo by playing Bh7+ and Bf5. } 15. O-O Ne5 16. Nd2 a6 { We can start by preparing ...b5. } 17. a4 b6 { With a good position. The f5-square is weak, but there is no way for White to get a knight there. } *

