1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f3 { . } 7... Bg7 8. Bg5 h6 { It makes sense to include this in order to remove the bishop from its active position. } 9. Be3 a6 { Sooner or later we have to go for this move. } 10. a4 O-O ( 10... Nbd7 { would be imprecise because it allows White to set up with } 11. Nh3 { followed by Nf2. } ) 11. Qd2 Re8 12. Be2 ( { The h6-pawn is taboo. If } 12. Bxh6 { there is } 12... Nxe4 ) 12... h5 ( { Again, this is a useful move. It's important not to play } 12... Nbd7 { because White can then play } 13. Nh3 { and solve the problem with their development. } ) 13. Bh6 Bh8 { We can keep the bishops on the board. Black’s position looks fine, while White still has to find a way to get his g1-knight out. We can make useful moves like ...Qe7 or ...Nh7, in order to keep the diagonal of the c8-bishop open and not to allow White to play Nh3. Only if White goes Bd3 or Bd1 should we play ...Nbd7 followed by ...Ne5. } *

