1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f3 { . } 7... Bg7 8. Bg5 h6 { It makes sense to include this in order to remove the bishop from its active position. } 9. Be3 a6 { Sooner or later we have to go for this move. } 10. a4 O-O ( 10... Nbd7 { would be imprecise because it allows White to set up with } 11. Nh3 { followed by Nf2. } ) 11. Qd2 Re8 12. Nge2 { This is the move  preferred by most white players. } ( { The h6-pawn is taboo. If } 12. Bxh6 { there is } 12... Nxe4 ) 12... Nbd7 { Now we can play this move, since there is no more Nh3 anyway. } 13. Nd1 { Making room for the other knight to come to c3. Here the inclusion of ... a6 and a4 doesn't benefit us because we cannot play ...b5. However, thankfully we have many other ideas. } 13... Ne5 { A good square for the knight. } 14. Nec3 Nh5 { Clearing the path for ...f5 or even ...g5. } 15. Bxh6 Qh4+ { The first step in proving the compensation is by activating the queen. } 16. Nf2 Bxh6 { We lure White’s queen to h6, where she is misplaced because she lacks other pieces to help in the attack. } 17. Qxh6 Bd7 { The compensation is enduring, so we simply connect the rooks and prepare ...b5. } 18. a5 Rab8 { With good compensation for the pawn. A nice trick to remember is } 19. Be2 Nf4 20. Qxh4 Nxg2+ { followed by ...Nxh4. } *

