1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Bg5 Bg7 8. f4 { this overly aggressive setup hasn't been played very often, and for good reasons. With the move 8. f4 White weakens the dark squares in his position. } 8... O-O { For now we just develop our pieces. } 9. Nf3 Re8 10. Be2 { This is the most solid as it avoids the pin down the e-file. } ( { We are already threatening } 10. -- Nxe4 { and White has to be precise in order not to get a lost position. } ) 10... Qb6 { With the double threat of ...Nxe4 and ...Qxb2. } 11. Qc2 { This allows Black some nice tactics. } 11... Nxe4 ( { The start of a forced tactical sequence. We're breaking up White's centre. The more quiet } 11... c4 { is also good. } ) 12. Nxe4 Bf5 13. Nfd2 Rxe4 { This is the point. ...Qb4+ will come next, and we'll get back some material. } 14. Nxe4 Qb4+ 15. Qd2 Qxe4 { We may exchange the queens in the future, but for now it's important to keep our pawn structure intact. } 16. O-O Nd7 { With plenty of compensation. In return for the exchange we have one pawn, good central control and pressure on the long diagonal. } *

