1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Bg5 Bg7 8. f4 { this overly aggressive setup hasn't been played very often, and for good reasons. With the move 8. f4 White weakens the dark squares in his position. } 8... O-O { For now we just develop our pieces. } 9. Nf3 Re8 10. Be2 { This is the most solid as it avoids the pin down the e-file. } ( { We are already threatening } 10. -- Nxe4 { and White has to be precise in order not to get a lost position. } ) 10... Qb6 { With the double threat of ...Nxe4 and ...Qxb2. } 11. Nd2 { Again the most precise, sacrificing the b2-pawn and preparing Nc4. } 11... Qxb2 12. Qc1 Qxc1+ 13. Rxc1 Nbd7 { I prefer Black here, although White has some compensation for the pawn. } 14. Nb5 Rxe4 { This exchange sacrifice begs to be played! } 15. Nxe4 Nxe4 { With a very pleasant position for Black. We've got 2 pawns for the exchange, good control in the centre and pressure on the long diagonal. The queenside pawns will be very strong once we drive away the b5-knight. } *

