1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Bg5 Bg7 8. Nf3 { White wants to get an improved version of the Nf3-d2 variation by developing the dark-squared bishop first. We have to use the fact that White saved on the move h3 and try to exchange our light-squared bishop. } 8... a6 ( { First we have to secure the a4-e8 diagonal, preparing both ...b5 and ...Bg4. A hasty } 8... O-O { would allow White to play } 9. Nd2 { and get a firm hold on the position. } ) 9. a4 Bg4 10. Be2 Bxf3 { It's better to exchange this bishop for the knight before White has time to play Nd2. } 11. Bxf3 Nbd7 { I'd rather develop the knight first and castle afterwards. It's probably a matter of taste, however I want to avoid any e5-breaks just in case. } 12. O-O O-O { We have a typical Benoni position in which we’ve managed to exchange our light-squared bishop. Thus we have enough space for our pieces and good control over the e5-square. } 13. Qd2 c4 ( { We should take advantage of the fact that this move is possible. The knight now gets a nice square on c5. The game 1-0 (89) Berkes, F (2649)-Castellanos Rodriguez, R (2465) Linares 2014 continued } 13... Re8 14. Rfe1 { , and here } 14... c4 { , with a balanced position. } ) 14. Be2 Nc5 15. Qf4 Re8 16. Bxc4 Nh5 { With nice play, as White cannot hold on to the e4-pawn. } *

