1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Bg5 Bg7 8. Nf3 { White wants to get an improved version of the Nf3-d2 variation by developing the dark-squared bishop first. We have to use the fact that White saved on the move h3 and try to exchange our light-squared bishop. } 8... a6 ( { First we have to secure the a4-e8 diagonal, preparing both ...b5 and ...Bg4. A hasty } 8... O-O { would allow White to play } 9. Nd2 { and get a firm hold on the position. } ) 9. a4 Bg4 10. Be2 Bxf3 { It's better to exchange this bishop for the knight before White has time to play Nd2. } 11. Bxf3 Nbd7 { I'd rather develop the knight first and castle afterwards. It's probably a matter of taste, however I want to avoid any e5-breaks just in case. } 12. O-O O-O { We have a typical Benoni position in which we’ve managed to exchange our light-squared bishop. Thus we have enough space for our pieces and good control over the e5-square. } 13. Be2 { This parries the ...c4 move. } 13... Re8 14. f3 Rc8 { Activating the rook and preparing ...c4. It is better to put the rook here than on b8 because in any case we cannot push ...b5 without sacrificing a pawn. } 15. Qb3 Qa5 { Threatening to continue with ...c4 or ...Ne5. } 16. Qxb7 c4 { Trapping the queen. } *

