1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Bd3 Bg7 8. Nge2 { First of all, the point of White’s setup is that it doesn't allow us to exchange the c8-bishop for White’s knight. Also, it’s not possible anymore for us to play a quick ...b5. White wants to bring the knight to g3 from where it will defend the e4-pawn, then play h3 and f4 and establish control over the centre. } 8... O-O 9. O-O a6 ( { I see no difference between this move and } 9... Nbd7 { . These moves probably just transpose. } ) 10. a4 Nbd7 11. Ng3 Rb8 { The first step in preparing ...b5. } 12. f4 h5 { Although this weakens our king's position, it makes sense to target the knight on g3. Besides, White cannot reply Bg5 anymore because of the f4-pawn. } 13. e5 dxe5 14. f5 { This is a typical breakthrough that we have to be aware of. } 14... h4 15. Nge4 c4 { We open up the diagonal g1-a7 and speed up our counterplay. } 16. Bc2 b5 { White has compensation for the pawn, but we have started our counterplay on the queenside as well. } *

