1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Bd3 Bg7 8. Nge2 { First of all, the point of White’s setup is that it doesn't allow us to exchange the c8-bishop for White’s knight. Also, it’s not possible anymore for us to play a quick ...b5. White wants to bring the knight to g3 from where it will defend the e4-pawn, then play h3 and f4 and establish control over the centre. } 8... O-O 9. O-O a6 ( { I see no difference between this move and } 9... Nbd7 { . These moves probably just transpose. } ) 10. a4 Nbd7 11. Ng3 Rb8 { The first step in preparing ...b5. } 12. f4 h5 { Although this weakens our king's position, it makes sense to target the knight on g3. Besides, White cannot reply Bg5 anymore because of the f4-pawn. } 13. Qe2 h4 14. Nh1 c4 { An interesting pawn sacrifice. We free up the c5-square for the knight and we'll attack the e4-pawn. } 15. Bxc4 Nc5 { The logical follow-up. } 16. Nf2 Re8 { ...Nfxe4 is a threat. } 17. e5 Bf5 { Black is doing fine in this very unclear position. } *

