[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Bd3 Bg7 8. Nge2 { First of all, the point of White’s setup is that it doesn't allow us to exchange the c8-bishop for White’s knight. Also, it’s not possible anymore for us to play a quick ...b5. White wants to bring the knight to g3 from where it will defend the e4-pawn, then play h3 and f4 and establish control over the centre. } 8... O-O 9. O-O a6 ( { I see no difference between this move and } 9... Nbd7 { . These moves probably just transpose. } ) 10. a4 Nbd7 11. Ng3 Rb8 { The first step in preparing ...b5. } 12. h3 Ne8 { We bring the knight to c7 in order to prepare ...b5. } 13. Be2 { I will only mention this move because it was tried in some correspondence games. The bishop may be better off on e2 because our ...c4 push will no longer come with tempo. Now White wants to continue Bf4 and Qd2 rather than f4. } 13... Nc7 { We continue with our plan. } 14. Bf4 Qe7 15. Qd2 b5 16. axb5 Nxb5 ( { This is important, because after } 16... axb5 { White has the unpleasant } 17. Ra7 { . } ) 17. Nxb5 axb5 18. Ra7 b4 { Once the b-pawn is no longer hanging we can continue with ...Rb7. } 19. Rfa1 Rb7 { We have to exchange a pair of rooks in order to stave off White's pressure. } 20. Rxb7 Bxb7 21. Ra7 Rb8 { White doesn't have any breaks and we’ve managed to exchange a pair of knights, so the position is balanced. The correspondence game ½-½ (32) Shapiro, V (2356)-Volodarsky, Y (2375) ICCF 2019 continued } 22. Bg5 Nf6 23. Qc2 h6 24. Be3 Nd7 25. b3 Nb6 { with an equal position. This game ended in a draw a few moves later. } *

