1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Bd3 Bg7 8. Nge2 { First of all, the point of White’s setup is that it doesn't allow us to exchange the c8-bishop for White’s knight. Also, it’s not possible anymore for us to play a quick ...b5. White wants to bring the knight to g3 from where it will defend the e4-pawn, then play h3 and f4 and establish control over the centre. } 8... O-O 9. O-O a6 ( { I see no difference between this move and } 9... Nbd7 { . These moves probably just transpose. } ) 10. a4 Nbd7 11. Ng3 Rb8 { The first step in preparing ...b5. } 12. h3 Ne8 { We bring the knight to c7 in order to prepare ...b5. } 13. f4 { White is pushing in the centre. The typical break idea is e5 ...dxe5 and then f5, so as not to give Black the e5-square for a piece. } 13... Nc7 { We continue our standard plan. } 14. e5 { White is acting quickly. } 14... b5 ( { We're starting off our counterplay. It isn't so good to take } 14... dxe5 { because of } 15. f5 ) 15. axb5 axb5 16. Bc2 ( { We can meet } 16. exd6 { with } 16... Ne8 { and then take back the pawn. } ) 16... c4 17. Nce4 ( { There is a hidden threat of Nh5 that I want to avoid. Now we control the d3-square so } 17. Nh5 { doesn't work for White anymore. } ) 17... dxe5 { Finally it's time to take the e5-pawn. } 18. f5 Bb7 { White has compensation, but Black is also quite active and, after all, a pawn up. } *

