1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Bb5+ { This check is not dangerous, but it has been tried now and then. } 7... Bd7 ( { This is probably the simplest answer, but } 7... Nbd7 { is also good. If White retreats the bishop we'll have options to play ...Bg4 later on to exchange the bishop, or to push ...b5, as it gains in strength due to the position of the d7-bishop. } ) 8. a4 Bg7 9. Nge2 { This looks artificial to me, and I doubt many White players are going to try this way of playing. Of course, the point is to avoid ...Bg4. } 9... Bxb5 { Otherwise the white bishop could have retreated to c4 and left our light-squared bishop misplaced. } 10. axb5 O-O 11. O-O Re8 12. f3 Nbd7 { We can challenge White's grip on the queenside with ...a6. } 13. Be3 a6 { White has stabilized the position in the centre. However he has no pawn breaks, and I think Black has an easy game. } *

