1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Be2 Bg7 8. Be3 { This looks like a strange setup to me. White is developing his pieces while avoiding both ...b5 and ...Bg4. In some games I played on the internet White tried to start a suspicious kingside attack with g4, f3 and h4. We shouldn't worry about that. However, we have to be careful about a more realistic plan with Nf3-d2. } 8... a6 ( { With this move order I'm trying to avoid } 8... O-O 9. Nf3 Bg4 10. Nd2 { which is not a problem for Black either. However, I'd rather exchange our light-squared bishop for a knight. } ) 9. a4 Qe7 { This is a good move to take advantage of the fact that White cannot protect the e4-pawn in a good way. } 10. Qc2 O-O 11. Nf3 Bg4 { Of course, it is good the exchange the light-squared bishop for the knight. } 12. O-O Nbd7 { Black has no problems. We'll exchange our light-squared bishop and put the rooks on e8 and b8 with a typical Benoni position. In the meantime White lacks a clear plan. } *

