1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Nge2 { White will bring the knight to g3 where it defends the e4-pawn. In case Black plays ...h5, White intends to answer Bg5. Besides, he's trying to save time on the move f2-f3; he ideally wants to play f4 in one move. } 7... h5 { Preventing Ng3, so that White doesn't have enough time to develop the pieces to their desired positions. } 8. Bf4 { This is also possible, although the bishop looks a bit strange on f4 in this variation. } 8... Bg7 ( { Of course, } 8... a6 9. a4 { could be included first, but then we lose the option to play an immediate ...b5 with some tricks related to the e4-pawn. } ) 9. f3 { Defending the e4-pawn in order to avoid ...b5. } 9... O-O 10. Qd2 a6 { It makes sense to include this move now. } 11. a4 Nh7 { The f4-bishop didn't prove to be too useful, as it didn’t prevent us from moving the f6-knight. We can follow up with ...f5, with good play. } *

