1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Nge2 { White will bring the knight to g3 where it defends the e4-pawn. In case Black plays ...h5, White intends to answer Bg5. Besides, he's trying to save time on the move f2-f3; he ideally wants to play f4 in one move. } 7... h5 { Preventing Ng3, so that White doesn't have enough time to develop the pieces to their desired positions. } 8. Ng1 { Not many players would go for this, although it makes some sense because we have weakened the g5-square. } 8... Bg7 9. Nf3 O-O 10. Bg5 { White makes use of the strong g5-square. } 10... a6 11. a4 Qe8 { A typical move to remove the queen from the pin and start creating some threats. } 12. Bd3 Bg4 { Black is fine in this unclear position. We're going to play ...Nbd7 and exchange our light-squared bishop for the f3-knight. } *

