1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Nge2 { White will bring the knight to g3 where it defends the e4-pawn. In case Black plays ...h5, White intends to answer Bg5. Besides, he's trying to save time on the move f2-f3; he ideally wants to play f4 in one move. } 7... h5 { Preventing Ng3, so that White doesn't have enough time to develop the pieces to their desired positions. } 8. Bg5 { Of course White takes advantage of the g5-square now that we have weakened it. } 8... Bg7 9. Qd2 { It's natural to develop the queen to d2. However, this does take away White's option to play Nc1-b3-d2. } 9... a6 ( { It makes sense to delay ...O-O for the time being, so that White cannot play Ng3. I tried to make the variations with } 9... O-O 10. Ng3 h4 { work, but I came to the conclusion that White is slightly better after } 11. e5 ) 10. a4 Nbd7 { This was part of our plan anyway. } 11. Nc1 O-O { Of course, we can also play a normal position by castling early on. } 12. f3 Qc7 13. Be2 Rb8 { This transposes to the variation 9. f3 a6 10. a4 Nbd7 11. Nc1 O-O 12. Be2 Qc7 13. Qd2 Rb8. } *

