[White "Ch 11: 4.g3 Symmetrical English"]
[Black "7. Nb3  #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. g3 { White avoids the Benoni and goes for an English Opening setup. They want to develop with Bg2, putting pressure on the long diagonal. } 4... cxd4 { We have to act fast before White has time to comfortably establish their ideal setup. } 5. Nxd4 d5 { with a long-lasting initiative in return for the pawn. } 6. Bg2 ( { I like this natural move. We simply fight for the centre. Of course } 6. cxd5 { is not good because we can take back with the queen } 6... Qxd5 { . } ) 6... e5 { This is a good moment to push the pawns in the centre. This allows us to gain space and we'll be able to develop our pieces to good squares. } 7. Nb3 { Preparing the push f4. } 7... d4 { We keep the centre intact. } 8. O-O Nc6 { Knights should be developed first! } 9. Bg5 a5 { It is an interesting idea to harass the white knight with ...a4. } *

