[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. g3 { White avoids the Benoni and goes for an English Opening setup. They want to develop with Bg2, putting pressure on the long diagonal. } 4... cxd4 { We have to act fast before White has time to comfortably establish their ideal setup. } 5. Nxd4 d5 { with a long-lasting initiative in return for the pawn. } 6. Bg2 ( { I like this natural move. We simply fight for the centre. Of course } 6. cxd5 { is not good because we can take back with the queen } 6... Qxd5 { . } ) 6... e5 { This is a good moment to push the pawns in the centre. This allows us to gain space and we'll be able to develop our pieces to good squares. } 7. Nb3 { Preparing the push f4. } 7... d4 { We keep the centre intact. } 8. O-O Nc6 { Knights should be developed first! } 9. f4 { The point of the variation. White undermines the black centre. } 9... Be7 10. Bxc6+ ( { Apparently ignoring White's threat. The idea is that after } 10. fxe5 { we can jump } 10... Ng4 { . } ) ( { White gives his strong bishop in order to win a pawn. } 10. fxe5 Ng4 { would likely lead to the same thing. } ) 10... bxc6 11. fxe5 Ng4 { A good square for the knight. } 12. Qxd4 O-O { We have good compensation for the two pawns down. The e5-pawn is weak and likely to fall soon. If White trades queens, the pair of bishops and good structure give us compensation, while with the queens on the board the white king is weak. } *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Modern Benoni"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch 11: 4.g3 Symmetrical English"]
[Black "7. Nc2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. g3 { White avoids the Benoni and goes for an English Opening setup. They want to develop with Bg2, putting pressure on the long diagonal. } 4... cxd4 { We have to act fast before White has time to comfortably establish their ideal setup. } 5. Nxd4 d5 { with a long-lasting initiative in return for the pawn. } 6. Bg2 ( { I like this natural move. We simply fight for the centre. Of course } 6. cxd5 { is not good because we can take back with the queen } 6... Qxd5 { . } ) 6... e5 { This is a good moment to push the pawns in the centre. This allows us to gain space and we'll be able to develop our pieces to good squares. } 7. Nc2 { This looks like a strange place to put the knight. } 7... d4 { We keep the centre intact. } 8. f4 { White is eager to break up Black's centre. } 8... Nc6 9. fxe5 Ng4 ( { This is interesting. We want to take the e5-pawn with the g4-knight, in order to keep the pawn on d4 defended. However, it should be mentioned that } 9... Nxe5 { is also good. } ) 10. Bxc6+ { Forced, otherwise Black just retakes ...Ngxe5 and is better. } 10... bxc6 11. Qxd4 { White has to exchange queens because the white king is very weak. } 11... Qxd4 12. Nxd4 Nxe5 { The pair of bishops and superior pawn structure fully compensate for the pawn minus. } *

