1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. g3 { White avoids the Benoni and goes for an English Opening setup. They want to develop with Bg2, putting pressure on the long diagonal. } 4... cxd4 { We have to act fast before White has time to comfortably establish their ideal setup. } 5. Nxd4 d5 { with a long-lasting initiative in return for the pawn. } 6. Bg2 ( { I like this natural move. We simply fight for the centre. Of course } 6. cxd5 { is not good because we can take back with the queen } 6... Qxd5 { . } ) 6... e5 { This is a good moment to push the pawns in the centre. This allows us to gain space and we'll be able to develop our pieces to good squares. } 7. Nc2 { This looks like a strange place to put the knight. } 7... d4 { We keep the centre intact. } 8. f4 { White is eager to break up Black's centre. } 8... Nc6 9. Bxc6+ { This is necessary so that the d4-pawn loses its main defender. } 9... bxc6 10. fxe5 Qa5+ { As White has not castled yet, this is possible as well. } 11. Qd2 Qxe5 12. Qxd4 Qf5 { It's better for Black to keep the queens on the board, given the weak white king. } 13. Qe3+ Be7 14. Nd4 Qc5 { Defending the e7-bishop. } 15. Nd2 O-O { With good compensation. The pawn down is not felt at all. } *

