1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. g3 { White avoids the Benoni and goes for an English Opening setup. They want to develop with Bg2, putting pressure on the long diagonal. } 4... cxd4 { We have to act fast before White has time to comfortably establish their ideal setup. } 5. Nxd4 d5 { with a long-lasting initiative in return for the pawn. } 6. Bg2 ( { I like this natural move. We simply fight for the centre. Of course } 6. cxd5 { is not good because we can take back with the queen } 6... Qxd5 { . } ) 6... e5 { This is a good moment to push the pawns in the centre. This allows us to gain space and we'll be able to develop our pieces to good squares. } 7. Nf3 d4 8. O-O ( { This is White's main move. } 8. e3 Nc6 { would just transpose after } 9. O-O { . } ) ( { A trick to be aware of is that } 8. Nxe5 { is not possible because of } 8... Qa5+ { winning the knight. } ) 8... Nc6 9. b4 { This is not justified. } 9... e4 ( { White's idea is } 9... Bxb4 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. Qa4+ { 9... e4 is the refutation. We are going to take the b4-pawn in a more favourable way. } ) 10. Ng5 Bxb4 { Winning a pawn and developing the bishop -  what more can we ask from one move? } 11. Nxe4 { White gets back the pawn but neglects their development. } 11... Nxe4 12. Bxe4 Bh3 { Our control of the centre and lead in development ensure us a better position. } *

