1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. g3 { White avoids the Benoni and goes for an English Opening setup. They want to develop with Bg2, putting pressure on the long diagonal. } 4... cxd4 { We have to act fast before White has time to comfortably establish their ideal setup. } 5. Nxd4 d5 { with a long-lasting initiative in return for the pawn. } 6. Bg2 ( { I like this natural move. We simply fight for the centre. Of course } 6. cxd5 { is not good because we can take back with the queen } 6... Qxd5 { . } ) 6... e5 { This is a good moment to push the pawns in the centre. This allows us to gain space and we'll be able to develop our pieces to good squares. } 7. Nf3 d4 8. O-O ( { This is White's main move. } 8. e3 Nc6 { would just transpose after } 9. O-O { . } ) ( { A trick to be aware of is that } 8. Nxe5 { is not possible because of } 8... Qa5+ { winning the knight. } ) 8... Nc6 9. b4 { This is not justified. } 9... e4 ( { White's idea is } 9... Bxb4 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. Qa4+ { 9... e4 is the refutation. We are going to take the b4-pawn in a more favourable way. } ) 10. Ng5 Bxb4 { Winning a pawn and developing the bishop -  what more can we ask from one move? } 11. Nd2 O-O { The e4-pawn couldn't be defended anyway. } 12. Ndxe4 h6 { This forces some exchanges in a manner which is advantageous for Black. } 13. Nxf6+ Qxf6 14. a3 { An in-between move to force us to clarify where the bishop goes. } 14... Be7 { We keep the bishop on the a3-f8 diagonal in order to keep control over the c5-square. Black is already preferable. The d4-pawn grants us a nice space advantage. } { The game could continue } 15. Ne4 Qg6 { followed by ...Bf5, highlighting the fact that White's knight is very unstable in the centre. } *

