[Black "7. Nf3 & 9. a3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. g3 { White avoids the Benoni and goes for an English Opening setup. They want to develop with Bg2, putting pressure on the long diagonal. } 4... cxd4 { We have to act fast before White has time to comfortably establish their ideal setup. } 5. Nxd4 d5 { with a long-lasting initiative in return for the pawn. } 6. Bg2 ( { I like this natural move. We simply fight for the centre. Of course } 6. cxd5 { is not good because we can take back with the queen } 6... Qxd5 { . } ) 6... e5 { This is a good moment to push the pawns in the centre. This allows us to gain space and we'll be able to develop our pieces to good squares. } 7. Nf3 d4 8. O-O ( { This is White's main move. } 8. e3 Nc6 { would just transpose after } 9. O-O { . } ) ( { A trick to be aware of is that } 8. Nxe5 { is not possible because of } 8... Qa5+ { winning the knight. } ) 8... Nc6 9. a3 Be6 ( { Attacking the c4-pawn. Of course } 9... a5 { is also good, so if you don't remember the exact details you can go for that instead. } ) 10. b4 { White has to go for this pawn sacrifice. } 10... Bxc4 { Challenge accepted! } 11. Nbd2 { Removing the bishop from the f1-a6 diagonal in order to push b5. } 11... Bd5 { In order to exchange the light-squared bishops later on. } 12. b5 { This way White regains the sacrificed pawn. } 12... Na5 13. Nxe5 Bxg2 { It's a good idea to exchange the bishops so as to decrease White's pressure on the long diagonal. } 14. Kxg2 Qd5+ { We cannot miss the opportunity to centralize the queen! } 15. Ndf3 Bd6 { Developing with tempo and harassing the e5-knight. } 16. Nd3 Nb3 { The knight was offside on the rim, so it's good to exchange it. Afterwards we can either castle or go for a pawn, depending on how White replies. } *

