[Black "7. Nf3 mainline, 11. a3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. g3 { White avoids the Benoni and goes for an English Opening setup. They want to develop with Bg2, putting pressure on the long diagonal. } 4... cxd4 { We have to act fast before White has time to comfortably establish their ideal setup. } 5. Nxd4 d5 { with a long-lasting initiative in return for the pawn. } 6. Bg2 ( { I like this natural move. We simply fight for the centre. Of course } 6. cxd5 { is not good because we can take back with the queen } 6... Qxd5 { . } ) 6... e5 { This is a good moment to push the pawns in the centre. This allows us to gain space and we'll be able to develop our pieces to good squares. } 7. Nf3 d4 8. O-O ( { This is White's main move. } 8. e3 Nc6 { would just transpose after } 9. O-O { . } ) ( { A trick to be aware of is that } 8. Nxe5 { is not possible because of } 8... Qa5+ { winning the knight. } ) 8... Nc6 9. e3 { This is the best. White tries to break up Black's centre. } 9... Be7 10. exd4 exd4 11. a3 Be6 ( { Attacking the c4-pawn and limiting White's options a bit. } 11... a5 { is a perfectly playable alternative, and should lead to positions similar to the ones we analyze. } ) 12. b4 { An interesting pawn sacrifice. } 12... Bxc4 { Forced. } 13. Re1 O-O { We bring our king to safety. } 14. Nbd2 Bd5 { It's important to challenge White's g2-bishop. } 15. Bb2 Re8 { Activating the rook and preparing ...Bf8 in order to exchange some pieces. } 16. b5 { Driving the knight away from its good position. } 16... Nb8 ( { This is just temporary. The knight will come back into play via d7. } 16... Na5 { is good as well. } ) 17. Nxd4 Bxg2 { We exchange pieces to release the tension. } 18. Kxg2 Qd5+ { The queen is activated with tempo. } 19. Qf3 Qxf3+ ( 19... Nbd7 { is also good. } ) 20. N2xf3 Nbd7 { With an equal ending. We can continue with ...Bf8 and exchange one pair of rooks. } *

