[White "Ch 11: 4.g3 Symmetrical English"]
[Black "7. Nf3 mainline, 11. b4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. g3 { White avoids the Benoni and goes for an English Opening setup. They want to develop with Bg2, putting pressure on the long diagonal. } 4... cxd4 { We have to act fast before White has time to comfortably establish their ideal setup. } 5. Nxd4 d5 { with a long-lasting initiative in return for the pawn. } 6. Bg2 ( { I like this natural move. We simply fight for the centre. Of course } 6. cxd5 { is not good because we can take back with the queen } 6... Qxd5 { . } ) 6... e5 { This is a good moment to push the pawns in the centre. This allows us to gain space and we'll be able to develop our pieces to good squares. } 7. Nf3 d4 8. O-O ( { This is White's main move. } 8. e3 Nc6 { would just transpose after } 9. O-O { . } ) ( { A trick to be aware of is that } 8. Nxe5 { is not possible because of } 8... Qa5+ { winning the knight. } ) 8... Nc6 9. e3 { This is the best. White tries to break up Black's centre. } 9... Be7 10. exd4 exd4 11. b4 { This is a concrete line. White gives up their b-pawn for our d-pawn, and the position opens up. } 11... Bxb4 ( { This is more usual than the other capture } 11... Nxb4 { , which however is good as well. It's good to have some knowledge of this line, or at least to remember the first couple of moves, so as not to end up in a worse ending. } ) 12. Nxd4 O-O ( { We cannot keep the king in the centre any longer. If } 12... Nxd4 { then there is } 13. Qa4+ { . } ) 13. Nxc6 { Of course White wants to keep the g2-bishop alive. } 13... bxc6 ( { We should refrain from } 13... Qxd1 { as this would gift White the d-file. } ) 14. Bxc6 { It's too early for White to grab this pawn. } 14... Bh3 { It's hard to refrain from this move! } 15. Qxd8 Rfxd8 { This is more precise as it intends to activate both our rooks. } 16. Bg2 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Rac8 { The c4-pawn is bound to fall. } *

