1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. g3 { White avoids the Benoni and goes for an English Opening setup. They want to develop with Bg2, putting pressure on the long diagonal. } 4... cxd4 { We have to act fast before White has time to comfortably establish their ideal setup. } 5. Nxd4 d5 { with a long-lasting initiative in return for the pawn. } 6. Bg2 ( { I like this natural move. We simply fight for the centre. Of course } 6. cxd5 { is not good because we can take back with the queen } 6... Qxd5 { . } ) 6... e5 { This is a good moment to push the pawns in the centre. This allows us to gain space and we'll be able to develop our pieces to good squares. } 7. Nf3 d4 8. O-O ( { This is White's main move. } 8. e3 Nc6 { would just transpose after } 9. O-O { . } ) ( { A trick to be aware of is that } 8. Nxe5 { is not possible because of } 8... Qa5+ { winning the knight. } ) 8... Nc6 9. e3 { This is the best. White tries to break up Black's centre. } 9... Be7 10. exd4 exd4 11. Bf4 ( 11. Re1 O-O { likely transposes to other 11th moves that we analyze. } ) 11... Be6 { is the most played move, and Black is fine there as well. } 12. Ne5 { This has to be the most critical. } ( { Developing the bishop to a nice position, with the idea to meet } 12. Ne5 { with } 12... Rc8 { . } ) 12... Rc8 { This is the idea behind 11… Be6 – the rook can come to c8, defending the knight on c6. } 13. Nxc6 { This exchange favours us. } 13... bxc6 14. Be5 { White was counting on this move. } 14... c5 { It would be a pity if we didn’t make this move, even if we now have to sacrifice an exchange. } 15. Bb7 Bxc4 16. Re1 ( { A simple calculation shows that } 16. Qa4+ { is parried by } 16... Qd7 { . } ) 16... O-O { Bringing the king to safety. } 17. Bxc8 { Sooner or later White has to take the exchange. } 17... Qxc8 18. Bxd4 { This is a risky way of playing, wanting to grab a pawn. } 18... cxd4 { Challenge accepted! } 19. Rxe7 Qh3 { Our queen is getting closer to the white king. } 20. f3 { Forced. } 20... Nd5 { The knight needs to join the fight. } 21. Re1 Ne3 22. Qd2 Qf5 { With good compensation. White would be wise to give back the exchange sooner rather than later. A few sample continuations are: } 23. Rxe3 ( 23. Na3 Bd5 24. Qf2 Bb7 { The bishop returns in order to prepare ...Ng4 and ...Qd5. For example, } 25. Rac1 Ng4 26. fxg4 { (forced, as otherwise the knight goes to e5) } 26... Qd5 27. Kf1 d3 { followed by ...Qh1+ and ...Qf3+ with perpetual check. } ) 23... dxe3 24. Qxe3 Bxa2 25. Nc3 Be6 26. Rxa7 Qc2 { with ...Rb8 coming the b2-pawn will fall next. } *

