1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. g3 { White avoids the Benoni and goes for an English Opening setup. They want to develop with Bg2, putting pressure on the long diagonal. } 4... cxd4 { We have to act fast before White has time to comfortably establish their ideal setup. } 5. Nxd4 d5 { with a long-lasting initiative in return for the pawn. } 6. Bg2 ( { I like this natural move. We simply fight for the centre. Of course } 6. cxd5 { is not good because we can take back with the queen } 6... Qxd5 { . } ) 6... e5 { This is a good moment to push the pawns in the centre. This allows us to gain space and we'll be able to develop our pieces to good squares. } 7. Nf3 d4 8. O-O ( { This is White's main move. } 8. e3 Nc6 { would just transpose after } 9. O-O { . } ) ( { A trick to be aware of is that } 8. Nxe5 { is not possible because of } 8... Qa5+ { winning the knight. } ) 8... Nc6 9. e3 { This is the best. White tries to break up Black's centre. } 9... Be7 10. exd4 exd4 11. Bf4 ( 11. Re1 O-O { likely transposes to other 11th moves that we analyze. } ) 11... Be6 { is the most played move, and Black is fine there as well. } 12. Ne5 { This has to be the most critical. } ( { Developing the bishop to a nice position, with the idea to meet } 12. Ne5 { with } 12... Rc8 { . } ) 12... Rc8 { This is the idea behind 11… Be6 – the rook can come to c8, defending the knight on c6. } 13. Qa4 { This is not really justified. } 13... Qb6 ( { Defending the knight, although } 13... O-O { is also quite possible. } ) 14. Nd2 O-O { Let's not delay our castling any further. } 15. Nxc6 { Otherwise we can take on e5. } 15... bxc6 16. Nf3 c5 { It feels right to connect the c- and d-pawns. } 17. Rfe1 Rfe8 { Preparing to contest  the e-file. The position is about equal, although I would choose Black here because of the strong passed d-pawn. } *

