1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. Nc3 { White avoids playing 4. d5 and fights for the centre by developing the knight. We have now entered a line of the English Opening. } 4... cxd4 { We usually get rid of the d4-pawn if possible. } 5. Nxd4 d5 ( { We are following a central strategy. Black has other choices here like } 5... Bb4 { or } ) ( 5... Nc6 { . However, I think } ) ( 5... d5 { is sound and simple. } ) 6. Bg5 { White puts some pressure on the black centre. } 6... e5 { I like this active move, as we fully occupy the centre with our pawns. } 7. Ndb5 { This plays into Black's hands. } 7... a6 8. Qa4 { White is going for tricks. } ( { The b5-knight has no good retreat squares, as after } 8. Na3 d4 { Black takes full control while the a3-knight is completely out of play. } ) 8... Bd7 { But now White has no way to get away from the pin. } 9. cxd5 Bc5 { We continue to develop. It will be difficult for White to unpin the knight. } *

