1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. Nc3 { White avoids playing 4. d5 and fights for the centre by developing the knight. We have now entered a line of the English Opening. } 4... cxd4 { We usually get rid of the d4-pawn if possible. } 5. Nxd4 d5 ( { We are following a central strategy. Black has other choices here like } 5... Bb4 { or } ) ( 5... Nc6 { . However, I think } ) ( 5... d5 { is sound and simple. } ) 6. Bg5 { White puts some pressure on the black centre. } 6... e5 { I like this active move, as we fully occupy the centre with our pawns. } 7. Nf3 { A reasonable retreat. } 7... d4 { We continue our advance in the centre. } 8. Bxf6 { White wants to establish the knight to d5, so he has to get rid of the f6-knight anyway. } 8... gxf6 ( { Reinforcing the centre and gaining some tempi compared to } 8... Qxf6 9. Nd5 { . } ) 9. Nd5 Be6 { We immediately challenge the d5-knight. } 10. e4 { The only move. } 10... dxe3 ( { Opening up the position a bit. Of course } 10... Nd7 { is also possible. } ) 11. fxe3 Nd7 { I prefer the knight on d7 rather than on c6 because from d7 it  defends f6, and also after a future ...Bxd5 cxd5 the knight won’t be under attack. } 12. Be2 Qa5+ { Going for an endgame. } 13. Qd2 Qxd2+ 14. Nxd2 O-O-O { With a pleasant ending for Black. We have the pair of bishops and can continue ...f5 next. Also the e3-pawn is weak, and if White were to play e4, he weakens the dark squares. } *

