1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. Nc3 { White avoids playing 4. d5 and fights for the centre by developing the knight. We have now entered a line of the English Opening. } 4... cxd4 { We usually get rid of the d4-pawn if possible. } 5. Nxd4 d5 ( { We are following a central strategy. Black has other choices here like } 5... Bb4 { or } ) ( 5... Nc6 { . However, I think } ) ( 5... d5 { is sound and simple. } ) 6. Bg5 { White puts some pressure on the black centre. } 6... e5 { I like this active move, as we fully occupy the centre with our pawns. } 7. Nf3 { A reasonable retreat. } 7... d4 { We continue our advance in the centre. } 8. Nd5 { White postpones taking on f6 and for the moment wants to take the e5-pawn instead. } 8... Be7 { I think this is the simplest. We solve the pin on the f6-knight and indirectly defend the e5-pawn. } 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 { Here it doesn't make any sense to spoil our pawn structure. } 10. g3 { White tries to play on the light squares. } 10... Nc6 ( { Continuing our development. It is also possible to challenge the d5-knight with } 10... Be6 { but I think the text is more simple. } ) 11. Bg2 O-O 12. O-O g6 { Giving White a choice: either you take the bishop, or let it retreat to g7. In either case Black has good control over the centre and is doing well. } *

