1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. Nc3 { White avoids playing 4. d5 and fights for the centre by developing the knight. We have now entered a line of the English Opening. } 4... cxd4 { We usually get rid of the d4-pawn if possible. } 5. Nxd4 d5 ( { We are following a central strategy. Black has other choices here like } 5... Bb4 { or } ) ( 5... Nc6 { . However, I think } ) ( 5... d5 { is sound and simple. } ) 6. Bg5 { White puts some pressure on the black centre. } 6... e5 { I like this active move, as we fully occupy the centre with our pawns. } 7. Nb3 d4 { It’s natural to advance in the centre. } 8. Bxf6 { Sooner or later White has to make this exchange. } 8... gxf6 ( { This is more ambitious. The other way } 8... Qxf6 { is possible as well, with an equal position, but I prefer not to allow White to gain a tempo on our queen with } 9. Nd5 { . } ) 9. Nd5 Nc6 { c6 is the natural square for the knight, and we can play ...Nb4 next. } 10. e4 { White is supporting the central knight. } 10... dxe3 { It's good to open up the position since we have the pair of bishops. } 11. fxe3 Nb4 { We need to get rid of that central knight. } 12. Qf3 { A sharp move, allowing Black to win the a1-rook. } 12... Nxd5 ( { This is the way to keep play in the position. A quick draw would be reached after } 12... Nc2+ 13. Kf2 Nxa1 14. Nxf6+ Ke7 15. Nd5+ Ke8 { . } ) 13. O-O-O { This is White's other idea after 12. Qf3. } 13... Qc7 { The queen had to leave the d-file anyway. Next we will play ...Be6 to attack the c4-pawn a second time. } 14. Rxd5 Be6 15. Qxf6 { White is forced to enter this sharp line. } 15... Bxd5 { There is no time to save the h8-rook. } 16. Qxh8 a5 { It's more important for us to go for the initiative rather than take the c4-pawn. White is under pressure here. } *

