1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. Nc3 { White avoids playing 4. d5 and fights for the centre by developing the knight. We have now entered a line of the English Opening. } 4... cxd4 { We usually get rid of the d4-pawn if possible. } 5. Nxd4 d5 ( { We are following a central strategy. Black has other choices here like } 5... Bb4 { or } ) ( 5... Nc6 { . However, I think } ) ( 5... d5 { is sound and simple. } ) 6. e3 { This is not really ambitious. White usually prefers to develop the dark-squared bishop outside the pawn chain before playing e3 in order to fight for an advantage. } 6... dxc4 { Clarifying the position in the centre. Afterwards we'll have ...a6 and ...b5 hitting the c4-bishop. } 7. Bxc4 a6 { We keep the option of playing ...b5 in reserve. } 8. O-O Bd6 { The bishop is more actively placed here than on e7. On d7 it also usefully controls the e5-square in case White plays e4. } 9. b3 O-O 10. Bb2 Qe7 ( { We are preparing both ...b5 and ...Nbd7. Note that the immediate } 10... Nbd7 { is wrong because of } 11. Nxe6 ) ( { However, } 10... b5 { is possible. } ) 11. Bd3 { So that ...b5 no longer comes with tempo. } 11... Nbd7 { This knight can jump to e5 or c5 to attack the bishop. With so many pieces on the board, the game has just started and there are chances for both sides. } *

