1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. Nc3 { White avoids playing 4. d5 and fights for the centre by developing the knight. We have now entered a line of the English Opening. } 4... cxd4 { We usually get rid of the d4-pawn if possible. } 5. Nxd4 d5 ( { We are following a central strategy. Black has other choices here like } 5... Bb4 { or } ) ( 5... Nc6 { . However, I think } ) ( 5... d5 { is sound and simple. } ) 6. cxd5 { This has occurred most commonly. White clarifies the situation in the centre. } 6... Nxd5 { is the right recapture. We don't allow White to give us an isolated pawn. } 7. Ndb5 ( { This is the main alternative to } 7. Bd2 { . } ) 7... a6 ( 7... Nc6 { is also good, but the text move is more direct. } ) 8. Nxd5 { is imprecise, as after } 8... axb5 { we'll get counterplay on the a-file. } 9. Nc3 Bd7 { I prefer to keep the queens on the board in order to fight for an advantage. However, exchanging the queens would also lead to a pleasant ending for Black. } 10. e3 Qa5 { With a nice initiative. It feels like White has wasted some tempi in the opening. } *

