1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. Nc3 { White avoids playing 4. d5 and fights for the centre by developing the knight. We have now entered a line of the English Opening. } 4... cxd4 { We usually get rid of the d4-pawn if possible. } 5. Nxd4 d5 ( { We are following a central strategy. Black has other choices here like } 5... Bb4 { or } ) ( 5... Nc6 { . However, I think } ) ( 5... d5 { is sound and simple. } ) 6. cxd5 { This has occurred most commonly. White clarifies the situation in the centre. } 6... Nxd5 { is the right recapture. We don't allow White to give us an isolated pawn. } 7. Ndb5 ( { This is the main alternative to } 7. Bd2 { . } ) 7... a6 ( 7... Nc6 { is also good, but the text move is more direct. } ) 8. e4 { This is White’s point after 7. Ndb5. } 8... Nb4 { A good square for the knight. White will have to retreat the b5-knight to a3, and it will take some time before White will manage to exchange the b4-knight. } 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 { Our knight is well placed on b4, and it's there to stay. Having equalised on move 9 is generally a good achievement with the black pieces. There are plenty of pieces left on the board: eventually, the stronger player should prevail. Let’s follow a sample continuation. } 10. Na3 { The only retreat. } 10... Bc5 { The bishop is actively placed on the a7-g1 diagonal. } 11. Bf4 b5 { A useful move. It prepares ...Bb7 while preventing Na4 and Nc4. } 12. Rc1 Nd7 { Defending the c5-bishop just in case. } 13. Nc2 { Finally White brings the a3-knight back into play. } 13... Bb7 { Simply developing. } 14. Nxb4 Bxb4 15. f3 Ke7 { A good square for the king. Afterwards we can bring the rooks into play. } 16. Kf2 Rac8 { With an equal ending. } *

