1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. Nc3 { White avoids playing 4. d5 and fights for the centre by developing the knight. We have now entered a line of the English Opening. } 4... cxd4 { We usually get rid of the d4-pawn if possible. } 5. Nxd4 d5 ( { We are following a central strategy. Black has other choices here like } 5... Bb4 { or } ) ( 5... Nc6 { . However, I think } ) ( 5... d5 { is sound and simple. } ) 6. cxd5 { This has occurred most commonly. White clarifies the situation in the centre. } 6... Nxd5 { is the right recapture. We don't allow White to give us an isolated pawn. } 7. Bd2 { Obviously White doesn't want to spoil the structure after ...Nxc3 either. } 7... Be7 ( { We simply finish our development. Other moves like } 7... Bc5 { , } ) ( 7... Bb4 { or } ) ( 7... Nf6 { are good as well. } ) 8. e3 { This seems too passive to me. Of course White is very solid here too, though. } 8... O-O { This is a good moment to castle before deciding what to do later on. } 9. Be2 e5 { Again, we go for this push in the centre if it's possible. } 10. Nxd5 { Exchanges lead to an equal game. } 10... Qxd5 11. Bf3 e4 ( { Why not, since it's possible. } 11... Qd6 { is also good enough. } ) 12. Be2 Nc6 { Black has no problems. We can consider whether to play actively by ...Qg5 or to go for simplifications with ...Nxd4. } *

