1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. Nc3 { White avoids playing 4. d5 and fights for the centre by developing the knight. We have now entered a line of the English Opening. } 4... cxd4 { We usually get rid of the d4-pawn if possible. } 5. Nxd4 d5 ( { We are following a central strategy. Black has other choices here like } 5... Bb4 { or } ) ( 5... Nc6 { . However, I think } ) ( 5... d5 { is sound and simple. } ) 6. cxd5 { This has occurred most commonly. White clarifies the situation in the centre. } 6... Nxd5 { is the right recapture. We don't allow White to give us an isolated pawn. } 7. Bd2 { Obviously White doesn't want to spoil the structure after ...Nxc3 either. } 7... Be7 ( { We simply finish our development. Other moves like } 7... Bc5 { , } ) ( 7... Bb4 { or } ) ( 7... Nf6 { are good as well. } ) 8. g3 { This has rarely been played. White’s idea is to continue in the spirit of the English Opening by putting pressure on the long diagonal. } 8... e5 { This central push is possible and we should go for it. We drive White's knight from the centre and next we'll be able to develop our bishop to e6. } 9. Ndb5 Nxc3 { It is simpler to exchange the knights right now, although it is also possible to wait a bit longer. } 10. Bxc3 { An ambitious move that fails tactically because the b5-knight is stranded. } 10... Qb6 { The double threat of ...Qxb5 and ...Qc6 is hard to parry. } *

