1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. Nc3 { White avoids playing 4. d5 and fights for the centre by developing the knight. We have now entered a line of the English Opening. } 4... cxd4 { We usually get rid of the d4-pawn if possible. } 5. Nxd4 d5 ( { We are following a central strategy. Black has other choices here like } 5... Bb4 { or } ) ( 5... Nc6 { . However, I think } ) ( 5... d5 { is sound and simple. } ) 6. cxd5 { This has occurred most commonly. White clarifies the situation in the centre. } 6... Nxd5 { is the right recapture. We don't allow White to give us an isolated pawn. } 7. Bd2 { Obviously White doesn't want to spoil the structure after ...Nxc3 either. } 7... Be7 ( { We simply finish our development. Other moves like } 7... Bc5 { , } ) ( 7... Bb4 { or } ) ( 7... Nf6 { are good as well. } ) 8. e4 { White removes our knight from its central square. } 8... Nxc3 ( { This is simple and good. Previously } 8... Nb4 { has also been tried. } ) 9. Bxc3 O-O { White's bishop on c3 doesn't really attack our king because it lacks other pieces to support it. Moreover, after ...Bf6 and ...Qb6 with the threat of ...Rd8 we may force the exchange of the dark-squared bishops. } 10. Bc4 Bf6 { We counter White's c3-bishop. } 11. O-O Qb6 { White already has to find a way to parry ...Rd8 with an unpleasant pin. } 12. Re1 { Threatening e5. } 12... Nd7 { Of course we cannot allow White to play e5. } 13. Rc1 Rd8 { The rook feels good on d8. } 14. Bf1 Ne5 { If we move this knight somewhere else, White could have played e5. Now we threaten ...Ng6 or ...Nc6 with material gain. } 15. Qb3 Bd7 { We’ve finished our development and established a good position. There is no worry about doubling the b-pawns because we would get further activity down the a-file. } *

