[Black "6. cxd5 #11"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. Nc3 { White avoids playing 4. d5 and fights for the centre by developing the knight. We have now entered a line of the English Opening. } 4... cxd4 { We usually get rid of the d4-pawn if possible. } 5. Nxd4 d5 ( { We are following a central strategy. Black has other choices here like } 5... Bb4 { or } ) ( 5... Nc6 { . However, I think } ) ( 5... d5 { is sound and simple. } ) 6. cxd5 { This has occurred most commonly. White clarifies the situation in the centre. } 6... Nxd5 { is the right recapture. We don't allow White to give us an isolated pawn. } 7. Bd2 { Obviously White doesn't want to spoil the structure after ...Nxc3 either. } 7... Be7 ( { We simply finish our development. Other moves like } 7... Bc5 { , } ) ( 7... Bb4 { or } ) ( 7... Nf6 { are good as well. } ) 8. e4 { White removes our knight from its central square. } 8... Nxc3 ( { This is simple and good. Previously } 8... Nb4 { has also been tried. } ) 9. Bxc3 O-O { White's bishop on c3 doesn't really attack our king because it lacks other pieces to support it. Moreover, after ...Bf6 and ...Qb6 with the threat of ...Rd8 we may force the exchange of the dark-squared bishops. } 10. Be2 { The bishop is less exposed here than on c4. } 10... Qb6 ( { This has been Black’s choice in all the games played so far. I see no difference between this and } 10... Bf6 { . } ) 11. Qb3 { White goes for the endgame. } 11... Qxb3 ( { It's a matter of taste whether to allow White to double our b-pawns or not. Actually I think they are good for Black. Here it is not necessary though to allow it. Other moves like } 11... Rd8 { , which has been played by Wesley So, or } ) ( 11... Na6 { are also good for Black. } ) 12. Nxb3 Bd7 { Followed by ...Rc8 with a comfortable ending for Black. } *

