1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. Nc3 { White avoids playing 4. d5 and fights for the centre by developing the knight. We have now entered a line of the English Opening. } 4... cxd4 { We usually get rid of the d4-pawn if possible. } 5. Nxd4 d5 ( { We are following a central strategy. Black has other choices here like } 5... Bb4 { or } ) ( 5... Nc6 { . However, I think } ) ( 5... d5 { is sound and simple. } ) 6. cxd5 { This has occurred most commonly. White clarifies the situation in the centre. } 6... Nxd5 { is the right recapture. We don't allow White to give us an isolated pawn. } 7. Bd2 { Obviously White doesn't want to spoil the structure after ...Nxc3 either. } 7... Be7 ( { We simply finish our development. Other moves like } 7... Bc5 { , } ) ( 7... Bb4 { or } ) ( 7... Nf6 { are good as well. } ) 8. e4 { White removes our knight from its central square. } 8... Nxc3 ( { This is simple and good. Previously } 8... Nb4 { has also been tried. } ) 9. Bxc3 O-O { White's bishop on c3 doesn't really attack our king because it lacks other pieces to support it. Moreover, after ...Bf6 and ...Qb6 with the threat of ...Rd8 we may force the exchange of the dark-squared bishops. } 10. Be2 { The bishop is less exposed here than on c4. } 10... Qb6 ( { This has been Black’s choice in all the games played so far. I see no difference between this and } 10... Bf6 { . } ) 11. Qb3 { White goes for the endgame. } 11... Na6 { This is a good move as well. } 12. Qxb6 { White decides to double our pawns. } 12... axb6 13. f3 Nc5 { The knight enters play. } 14. b3 Bd7 { Due to the doubled pawns we’ve got some pressure down the a-file. } 15. e5 Rfc8 { All our pieces enter the game! } 16. Bb2 b5 17. Kf2 ( { Just to gain more space on the queenside. The pawn is taboo: if } 17. Nxb5 { then } 17... Bxb5 18. Bxb5 Nxb3 { wins. } ) 17... b4 { With a good ending for Black. We can consider doubling rooks on the a-file. } *

