1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. Nc3 { White avoids playing 4. d5 and fights for the centre by developing the knight. We have now entered a line of the English Opening. } 4... cxd4 { We usually get rid of the d4-pawn if possible. } 5. Nxd4 d5 ( { We are following a central strategy. Black has other choices here like } 5... Bb4 { or } ) ( 5... Nc6 { . However, I think } ) ( 5... d5 { is sound and simple. } ) 6. cxd5 { This has occurred most commonly. White clarifies the situation in the centre. } 6... Nxd5 { is the right recapture. We don't allow White to give us an isolated pawn. } 7. Bd2 { Obviously White doesn't want to spoil the structure after ...Nxc3 either. } 7... Be7 ( { We simply finish our development. Other moves like } 7... Bc5 { , } ) ( 7... Bb4 { or } ) ( 7... Nf6 { are good as well. } ) 8. e4 { White removes our knight from its central square. } 8... Nxc3 ( { This is simple and good. Previously } 8... Nb4 { has also been tried. } ) 9. Bxc3 O-O { White's bishop on c3 doesn't really attack our king because it lacks other pieces to support it. Moreover, after ...Bf6 and ...Qb6 with the threat of ...Rd8 we may force the exchange of the dark-squared bishops. } 10. Be2 { The bishop is less exposed here than on c4. } 10... Qb6 ( { This has been Black’s choice in all the games played so far. I see no difference between this and } 10... Bf6 { . } ) 11. O-O Rd8 ( { Pinning the knight. } 11... Bf6 { is also good. } ) 12. Qb3 { White has to go for this queen move. } 12... Na6 { A more ambitious idea. Exchanging the queens is enough for equality. } 13. Qxb6 axb6 14. Bxa6 { White simplifies in order to make a draw. } 14... Rxa6 ( { A good decision. } 14... bxa6 { allows } 15. Nc6 { when we have to give up the bishop pair. } ) 15. a3 Bd7 16. Rfd1 Raa8 { With an equal position that Black even managed to win in the end, in 0-1 (59) Duda,J (2743)-So,W (2770) Chess.com INT 2020. The bishop pair fully compensates for the doubled pawns. } *

