1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 { White delays c4 for now and first wants to fianchetto the bishop to g2 and castle. } 3... c5 ( { The typical break in the spirit of the Benoni. Of course, Black has other good alternatives like } 3... d5 { transposing to the Catalan, or } ) ( 3... b5 { which is another way to exploit the fact that White has delayed playing c4. } ) 4. Bg2 cxd4 { Of course, we want to take this pawn. } 5. O-O d5 { We establish a foothold in the centre. } 6. Bf4 { White prevents ...e5 before taking on d4. } 6... Nbd7 ( { This is more ambitious than } 6... Nc6 { . After } ) ( 6... Nbd7 { The knight seems artificially developed on d7, but now White can no longer take } 7. Nxd4 { because of } 7... e5 { . } ) 7. Qxd4 Bc5 { Of course, we cannot miss making this move with tempo. } 8. Qa4 { The queen is both more active and more exposed on a4 compared to d1. } 8... O-O 9. c4 Nb6 { Not the only move, but it is a tempting one. } 10. Qb5 Be7 { The bishop is less exposed here than if we tried to keep it on c5. } 11. cxd5 Nfxd5 { With an active position for Black. White has wasted too many tempi moving the queen around. } *

