1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 { White delays c4 for now and first wants to fianchetto the bishop to g2 and castle. } 3... c5 ( { The typical break in the spirit of the Benoni. Of course, Black has other good alternatives like } 3... d5 { transposing to the Catalan, or } ) ( 3... b5 { which is another way to exploit the fact that White has delayed playing c4. } ) 4. Bg2 cxd4 { Of course, we want to take this pawn. } 5. O-O d5 { We establish a foothold in the centre. } 6. Bf4 { White prevents ...e5 before taking on d4. } 6... Nbd7 ( { This is more ambitious than } 6... Nc6 { . After } ) ( 6... Nbd7 { The knight seems artificially developed on d7, but now White can no longer take } 7. Nxd4 { because of } 7... e5 { . } ) 7. Qxd4 Bc5 { Of course, we cannot miss making this move with tempo. } 8. Qd1 O-O 9. c4 { White has to act fast and fight for the centre. } 9... dxc4 { White will manage to regain this pawn, but meanwhile we can finish our development and equalize. } 10. Bd6 Bxd6 11. Qxd6 Nb6 { This is the most straightforward, but other moves are possible as well. } 12. Qxd8 Rxd8 13. Ne5 Nfd5 { Covering up the long diagonal. } 14. Rc1 Bd7 { With an equal ending. White will take back the c4-pawn while we activate our pieces. A sample line is } 15. Na3 Rac8 16. Naxc4 Nxc4 17. Nxc4 Kf8 { with an equal position. } *

