1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 { White delays c4 for now and first wants to fianchetto the bishop to g2 and castle. } 3... c5 ( { The typical break in the spirit of the Benoni. Of course, Black has other good alternatives like } 3... d5 { transposing to the Catalan, or } ) ( 3... b5 { which is another way to exploit the fact that White has delayed playing c4. } ) 4. Bg2 cxd4 { Of course, we want to take this pawn. } 5. Nxd4 { Sooner or later White has to take the pawn back. } 5... d5 { We get a foothold in the centre. } 6. O-O e5 { We use this opportunity to drive the knight away, while creating new possibilities for our light-squared  bishop. } 7. Nb3 { A natural retreat. } 7... Be6 { The bishop belongs here in order to defend the centre. } 8. e4 Nc6 ( { We continue our development. } 8... dxe4 { is also good. } ) 9. exd5 Bxd5 { The bishop exchange favours Black. } 10. Qe2 { White avoids the trade of queens. } 10... Bxg2 11. Rd1 { A strong in-between move that deprives us of the ...Qd5+ resource. } 11... Qc8 { A good square for the queen. We can contemplate ...Qg4 in the future. } 12. Kxg2 Be7 { Developing yet another piece. Of course, once we finish development, Black's position will be comfortable. } 13. Bg5 Qg4 { A well-timed queen exchange. Our king will stay in the centre, thus assuring a good ending for us. } 14. Qxg4 Nxg4 15. Bxe7 Kxe7 { The king in the centre is good news for Black. } 16. Nc3 Rhd8 ( { It's better to bring the rook into play first. If } 16... Nf6 { White can put pressure on the e5-pawn with } 17. Re1 { with the idea 18. Na5. } ) 17. Nd5+ Kf8 18. h3 Nh6 { I prefer the knight on h6 so as not to spoil our pawn structure. Our next priority is to bring the knight into play via f5 or g8-e7. } *

