1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 { White delays c4 for now and first wants to fianchetto the bishop to g2 and castle. } 3... c5 ( { The typical break in the spirit of the Benoni. Of course, Black has other good alternatives like } 3... d5 { transposing to the Catalan, or } ) ( 3... b5 { which is another way to exploit the fact that White has delayed playing c4. } ) 4. Bg2 cxd4 { Of course, we want to take this pawn. } 5. Nxd4 { Sooner or later White has to take the pawn back. } 5... d5 { We get a foothold in the centre. } 6. O-O e5 { We use this opportunity to drive the knight away, while creating new possibilities for our light-squared  bishop. } 7. Nb3 { A natural retreat. } 7... Be6 { The bishop belongs here in order to defend the centre. } 8. c4 { A typical way for White to challenge our centre. } 8... Nc6 { The knight belongs on c6 in most variations. } 9. cxd5 Nxd5 ( { Actually in a game I once took on d5 with the bishop: } 9... Bxd5 10. Bg5 Bxg2 11. Kxg2 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 Ne4 13. Be3 Rd8 14. Rc1 Be7 15. Na3 O-O 16. Nc4 Rd5 17. f3 Nd6 18. Nxd6 Bxd6 19. Kf2 Rd8 20. Bc5 Kf8 21. Bxd6+ R8xd6 { with an equal endgame and a draw later on in ½-½ (32) Istratescu, A (2656)-Parligras, M (2574) Abu Dhabi 2014. However, it makes more sense to bring the knight in the centre. } ) 10. N1d2 { Since the c3-square is controlled by Black, this is a logical way to bring the knight to e4. } 10... Be7 { Preparing to castle and preventing a knight jump to g5. } 11. Ne4 b6 { We cannot allow a white knight to land on c5. The long diagonal is slightly weakened, but we'll manage to cover it. } 12. Nc3 { Increasing the pressure on the long diagonal. } 12... Ndb4 { This is the way to defend. The knights may look loose on b4, but there is no good way for White to take advantage of this. } 13. a3 Qxd1 14. Rxd1 Bxb3 { This is the point: the knight on b3 was hanging. } 15. axb4 Rc8 { The only move, but it's enough. } 16. Bh3 { An interesting try recommended by Christof Sielecki in his Chessable course 'Keep it Simple: 1. d4'. The position is very concrete and Black has to be precise in order to equalize. } 16... Bxd1 { The rook trade favours us because we simplify the position and our king will have access to the central squares. } 17. Bxc8 Bb3 { The best place for the bishop, as we need to keep the d5-square under control. } 18. Bb7 Kd7 { Forced, but also logical. We defend the knight and bring the king into play. } 19. b5 { White has to act quickly } 19... Na5 { again the only move, but it's easy to find as we need to keep the a7-pawn shielded. } 20. Bd5 Bxd5 { We have to exchange the bishops- as White was threatening Rxa5. } 21. Nxd5 Ra8 { The ending is approximately equal. We defend the a7-pawn and prepare ...Nb3 or ...Bd8. Our centralized king ensures us good play. } ( 21... Bd6 { is also possible, and in the correspondence game ½-½ (27) Gardner, A (2255)-Thurlow, K (2260) ICCF 2020 this continuation ended in a draw after } 22. b4 Ke6 23. bxa5 Kxd5 24. axb6 axb6 25. Ra7 Rc8 26. Be3 Kc4 27. Bxb6 { . } ) *

