1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 { White delays c4 for now and first wants to fianchetto the bishop to g2 and castle. } 3... c5 ( { The typical break in the spirit of the Benoni. Of course, Black has other good alternatives like } 3... d5 { transposing to the Catalan, or } ) ( 3... b5 { which is another way to exploit the fact that White has delayed playing c4. } ) 4. Bg2 cxd4 { Of course, we want to take this pawn. } 5. Nxd4 { Sooner or later White has to take the pawn back. } 5... d5 { We get a foothold in the centre. } 6. O-O e5 { We use this opportunity to drive the knight away, while creating new possibilities for our light-squared  bishop. } 7. Nb3 { A natural retreat. } 7... Be6 { The bishop belongs here in order to defend the centre. } 8. c4 { A typical way for White to challenge our centre. } 8... Nc6 { The knight belongs on c6 in most variations. } 9. cxd5 Nxd5 ( { Actually in a game I once took on d5 with the bishop: } 9... Bxd5 10. Bg5 Bxg2 11. Kxg2 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 Ne4 13. Be3 Rd8 14. Rc1 Be7 15. Na3 O-O 16. Nc4 Rd5 17. f3 Nd6 18. Nxd6 Bxd6 19. Kf2 Rd8 20. Bc5 Kf8 21. Bxd6+ R8xd6 { with an equal endgame and a draw later on in ½-½ (32) Istratescu, A (2656)-Parligras, M (2574) Abu Dhabi 2014. However, it makes more sense to bring the knight in the centre. } ) 10. N1d2 { Since the c3-square is controlled by Black, this is a logical way to bring the knight to e4. } 10... Be7 { Preparing to castle and preventing a knight jump to g5. } 11. Ne4 b6 { We cannot allow a white knight to land on c5. The long diagonal is slightly weakened, but we'll manage to cover it. } 12. Nc3 { Increasing the pressure on the long diagonal. } 12... Ndb4 { This is the way to defend. The knights may look loose on b4, but there is no good way for White to take advantage of this. } 13. a3 Qxd1 14. Rxd1 Bxb3 { This is the point: the knight on b3 was hanging. } 15. axb4 Rc8 { The only move, but it's enough. } 16. Bxc6+ Rxc6 17. Rd3 Bxb4 { The smoke has cleared and Black has a nice position. } 18. Rxa7 O-O { The ending is just equal. } *

