[Black "Mainline 7. Nb3 Be6 8. Nc3 #11"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 { White delays c4 for now and first wants to fianchetto the bishop to g2 and castle. } 3... c5 ( { The typical break in the spirit of the Benoni. Of course, Black has other good alternatives like } 3... d5 { transposing to the Catalan, or } ) ( 3... b5 { which is another way to exploit the fact that White has delayed playing c4. } ) 4. Bg2 cxd4 { Of course, we want to take this pawn. } 5. Nxd4 { Sooner or later White has to take the pawn back. } 5... d5 { We get a foothold in the centre. } 6. O-O e5 { We use this opportunity to drive the knight away, while creating new possibilities for our light-squared  bishop. } 7. Nb3 { A natural retreat. } 7... Be6 { The bishop belongs here in order to defend the centre. } 8. Nc3 { The most common move in this position. } 8... Be7 9. f4 { The most played move in this position. } 9... exf4 10. gxf4 g6 { We have to prevent White from playing f5. } 11. Kh1 { The most flexible continuation, prophylactically moving the king off of the open g1-a7 diagonal. } 11... Nc6 { It makes sense to develop this knight first before castling. Thus we get control over the d4-square. } 12. Be3 { With the idea to play Nd4 and after an exchange on d4, recapture with the bishop. } 12... O-O ( { Time to bring the king to safety! I was tempted to recommend the interesting } 12... Qc8 { , but I think it's not so natural and it's difficult to remember. } ) 13. Nd4 Qd7 { Connecting the rooks and preparing ...Bh3. } 14. f5 { This temporary pawn sacrifice deserves attention as it weakens our kingside. } 14... gxf5 { We accept the offer. } 15. Bg1 Kh8 { Black is trying to make use of the g-file. Doing so, we have to act quickly and avoid a pin on the a1-h8 diagonal. } 16. Qd3 Ne5 17. Qh3 Rg8 { Black takes over the initiative. The idea is to double the rooks on the g-file with ...Rg4/...Rg6 and ...Rag8. } 18. Rxf5 { can be met with } 18... Neg4 *

