[White "Ch 14: 2.Bg5/3.Bg5: Trompowsky & Torre Attack"]
[Black "Trompowsky 5. c3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 { The Trompowsky Attack. White intends to exchange the bishop for the knight and then take advantage of their superior pawn structure, or just to develop normally and claim that the pin on the f6-knight is annoying for Black. } 2... e6 { Of course, there are many good replies at this juncture. I chose 2... e6 because I have experience with it, and also because it fits our repertoire's move order which can transpose from the 2.Nf3 e6 3.Bg5 lines. } ( { The idea behind } 2... e6 { is to not allow White to double our pawns, while we are preparing ...h6. } ) ( 2... c5 { , } ) ( 2... d5 { or } ) ( 2... Ne4 { are all options which can be recommended as well. } ) 3. e4 { White takes the centre, and is ready to part with his dark-squared bishop. } 3... h6 { We force White to give up the bishop. Exchanging pieces is good for us because we lack some space. } 4. Bxf6 Qxf6 5. c3 { This little move is the start of a long-term plan. White intends to go Bd3, Ne2 and then play f4, and that's why he needs to defend the d4-pawn first. } 5... d5 { I have analysed this position previously for over the board games, and I came to the conclusion that Black needs to fight for the centre straight away. } 6. Bd3 c5 ( { We continue fighting for the centre. Another option is to take } 6... dxe4 { followed by ...Nd7 and break in the centre later on. } ) 7. Nf3 cxd4 { Clearing up the situation in the centre. } 8. cxd4 dxe4 9. Bxe4 Bd6 { The bishop is actively placed on d6. } 10. Nc3 O-O 11. O-O Nd7 12. Qe2 ( { An interesting idea. The knight is heading to f6, where it defends Black’s king and also controls the important d5-square. Another point is that we are ready to meet } 12. d5 { with } 12... e5 { . } ) 12... Qe7 { Making space for the knight to come to f6. } 13. Rfe1 Nf6 { By driving the white bishop away we'll be able to develop with ...Bd7 next. } 14. Bc2 Rd8 15. Rad1 { White brings his last pieces into play. } ( { This is useful, and a fine point is that we can meet } 15. d5 { with } 15... Qf8 { . } ) 15... a6 { With the idea to continue ...b5. } 16. Ne5 Bd7 { Black is doing well, but the position remains sharp. } *

