[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch 14: 2.Bg5/3.Bg5: Trompowsky & Torre Attack"]
[Black "Torre 5. c3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bg5 { The Torre Attack. According to Wikipedia the opening is named after the Mexican grandmaster Carlos Torre Repetto, who beat former World Champion Emanuel Lasker with it. It has ideas that are similar ideas to those in the London System. White is developing the pieces harmoniously: pawns to e3 and c3, knight to d2, bishop to d3, castle short and then try to push e4. The setup is very solid, but because of the pin on the f6-knight we have to be careful about possible ideas of an early e3-e4 or even d4-d5 after ...c5. } 3... h6 ( { I prefer to include this move as soon as possible in order to see how White is intending to setup. The immediate } 3... c5 { gives White more options, including } 4. d5 ) 4. Bh4 c5 ( { We're fighting for control over the centre. In previous over the board games I have usually preferred } 4... d6 { here, with ideas to capture White’s dark-squared bishop. However, White can play h3 at some point and keep the bishop, while we may have to play ...d5 later anyway. The line I am giving instead of 4... d6 is easier to play for Black. } ) 5. c3 { Very solid. White wants to recapture on d4 with the c-pawn, while keeping the knight on b1 ready to go to c3. } 5... Nc6 6. Nbd2 cxd4 { Now we take on d4 as White doesn't have the possibility of developing his knight to c3 anymore. } 7. cxd4 Qb6 { With a double attack. } *

