1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bg5 { The Torre Attack. According to Wikipedia the opening is named after the Mexican grandmaster Carlos Torre Repetto, who beat former World Champion Emanuel Lasker with it. It has ideas that are similar ideas to those in the London System. White is developing the pieces harmoniously: pawns to e3 and c3, knight to d2, bishop to d3, castle short and then try to push e4. The setup is very solid, but because of the pin on the f6-knight we have to be careful about possible ideas of an early e3-e4 or even d4-d5 after ...c5. } 3... h6 ( { I prefer to include this move as soon as possible in order to see how White is intending to setup. The immediate } 3... c5 { gives White more options, including } 4. d5 ) 4. Bh4 c5 ( { We're fighting for control over the centre. In previous over the board games I have usually preferred } 4... d6 { here, with ideas to capture White’s dark-squared bishop. However, White can play h3 at some point and keep the bishop, while we may have to play ...d5 later anyway. The line I am giving instead of 4... d6 is easier to play for Black. } ) 5. e3 cxd4 { I see no reason why we shouldn't exchange these pawns. } 6. exd4 b6 { Here I propose an easy to play setup: ...Be7, ...Bb7,  ...O-O and then ...Nh5 in order to exchange White’s dark-squared bishop. } ( { As an alternative } 6... Qb6 { is risky but interesting. } ) 7. c4 { In this case it is useful that we have included the moves ...h6 and Bh4. } 7... Be7 ( 7... Bb7 { first should lead to the same thing. It is good to develop our bishops, after which we can consider ideas with ...Bxf3 and ...Nc6. } ) 8. Nc3 Bb7 9. Be2 { Preventing our …Bxf3 motif. } 9... O-O 10. O-O d5 ( { It's time to fight in the centre! } 10... Nc6 { is also good. } ) 11. Rc1 dxc4 { Now White gets an isolated pawn. Most likely the position will peter out to a draw after White eventually pushes d5. } 12. Bxc4 Nc6 { The knight is more active here than on d7. } 13. a3 Rc8 ( { The immediate } 13... Nh5 { is also good, but I prefer to bring the rook into play first. } ) 14. Ba2 Nh5 { Now we are ready to exchange the bishop. This is a typical maneuver when playing against an isolated pawn. } 15. Bg3 Nxg3 16. hxg3 Bf6 { Regrouping the pieces. Anyway, there was no way for us to prevent White from playing d5. } 17. d5 exd5 18. Bxd5 Rc7 { With an equal position where the f6-bishop is strong. } *

