1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bg5 { The Torre Attack. According to Wikipedia the opening is named after the Mexican grandmaster Carlos Torre Repetto, who beat former World Champion Emanuel Lasker with it. It has ideas that are similar ideas to those in the London System. White is developing the pieces harmoniously: pawns to e3 and c3, knight to d2, bishop to d3, castle short and then try to push e4. The setup is very solid, but because of the pin on the f6-knight we have to be careful about possible ideas of an early e3-e4 or even d4-d5 after ...c5. } 3... h6 ( { I prefer to include this move as soon as possible in order to see how White is intending to setup. The immediate } 3... c5 { gives White more options, including } 4. d5 ) 4. Bh4 c5 ( { We're fighting for control over the centre. In previous over the board games I have usually preferred } 4... d6 { here, with ideas to capture White’s dark-squared bishop. However, White can play h3 at some point and keep the bishop, while we may have to play ...d5 later anyway. The line I am giving instead of 4... d6 is easier to play for Black. } ) 5. e3 cxd4 { I see no reason why we shouldn't exchange these pawns. } 6. exd4 b6 { Here I propose an easy to play setup: ...Be7, ...Bb7,  ...O-O and then ...Nh5 in order to exchange White’s dark-squared bishop. } ( { As an alternative } 6... Qb6 { is risky but interesting. } ) 7. c4 { In this case it is useful that we have included the moves ...h6 and Bh4. } 7... Be7 ( 7... Bb7 { first should lead to the same thing. It is good to develop our bishops, after which we can consider ideas with ...Bxf3 and ...Nc6. } ) 8. Nc3 Bb7 9. Be2 { Preventing our …Bxf3 motif. } 9... O-O 10. O-O d5 ( { It's time to fight in the centre! } 10... Nc6 { is also good. } ) 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. cxd5 exd5 { It’s true that the b7-bishop is not so active now. However, all our other pieces will get good positions and Black has good control over the key e5-square. } 13. Ne5 { White grabs the opportunity to put the knight in the centre, and wants to support it with f4. } 13... Bxe5 { We immediately get rid of the knight. } 14. dxe5 d4 { This is the point. The passive bishop comes alive! } 15. Nb5 Qg5 { The move Black was counting on. } 16. Bf3 Bxf3 17. Qxf3 Nd7 { The end of a forced sequence of moves. } 18. Nxd4 Nxe5 19. Qe4 Ng6 { The smoke has cleared. The position has become symmetrical and equal. } *

