1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bg5 { The Torre Attack. According to Wikipedia the opening is named after the Mexican grandmaster Carlos Torre Repetto, who beat former World Champion Emanuel Lasker with it. It has ideas that are similar ideas to those in the London System. White is developing the pieces harmoniously: pawns to e3 and c3, knight to d2, bishop to d3, castle short and then try to push e4. The setup is very solid, but because of the pin on the f6-knight we have to be careful about possible ideas of an early e3-e4 or even d4-d5 after ...c5. } 3... h6 ( { I prefer to include this move as soon as possible in order to see how White is intending to setup. The immediate } 3... c5 { gives White more options, including } 4. d5 ) 4. Bh4 c5 ( { We're fighting for control over the centre. In previous over the board games I have usually preferred } 4... d6 { here, with ideas to capture White’s dark-squared bishop. However, White can play h3 at some point and keep the bishop, while we may have to play ...d5 later anyway. The line I am giving instead of 4... d6 is easier to play for Black. } ) 5. e3 cxd4 { I see no reason why we shouldn't exchange these pawns. } 6. exd4 b6 { Here I propose an easy to play setup: ...Be7, ...Bb7,  ...O-O and then ...Nh5 in order to exchange White’s dark-squared bishop. } ( { As an alternative } 6... Qb6 { is risky but interesting. } ) 7. Bd3 Be7 { This is more flexible, as we keep open the possibility of developing the c8-bishop to either b7 or a6. } 8. Nbd2 Ba6 { We can also consider the exchange of light-squared bishops. } 9. Nc4 Qc7 { Insisting on the bishop exchange! } 10. Bg3 d6 11. Nfd2 O-O { We have two possible plans. The first is ...Nc6 and ...Na5, the second ...Qb7 and ...d5. } 12. O-O Nc6 13. c3 Na5 { Intending to exchange some pieces. } 14. Qe2 Nxc4 15. Nxc4 Rac8 { Forcing even more exchanges. } 16. Ne3 Bxd3 17. Qxd3 Nh5 ( { And finally we can exchange White’s bishop as well. } 17... Qb7 { with ...b5 next is also possible. } ) *

