[Black "3. Bg5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 { This line has successfully been tried by the Georgian GM Baadur Jobava lately. I don't think it's really dangerous for Black, but we should be prepared to meet it. By playing an early Nc3 White skips the option to move his pawn to c4, and instead is looking for play in the centre and on the kingside. } 2... d5 { The most principled reply. We need to prevent e4. } 3. Bg5 { White is fighting for the centre by keeping the option open to take our f6-knight. } 3... c5 ( { We immediately challenge White's centre. Of course, there are other good moves as well, and here I'd mention } 3... h6 { followed by 4... c5. However, the extra h6 may not make a big difference. } ) 4. Bxf6 { This exchange is debatable as it reinforces our centre, and White will have to keep the position closed so as not to open up our pair of bishops. } 4... gxf6 5. e4 { This opens up the position, hoping to get a quick initiative. } 5... dxe4 { By taking this pawn we delete White's centre. } 6. dxc5 f5 { First we should defend the e4-pawn, even though we lose the right to castle after the exchange of queens. } 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. O-O-O+ Bd7 { The best way to parry the check. } 9. g4 { White is opening up the position while we still haven’t coordinated our pieces. } 9... Bg7 { By exchanging off White’s c3-knight, we reduce White's pressure. } 10. gxf5 Bxc3 { Completely ruining White's structure as well. } 11. bxc3 Kc7 { Now we have this nice square for the king. } 12. Ne2 Bxf5 13. Nd4 Bg6 { Only to g6, as we need to cover up the g-file. } 14. h4 { White intends to dislodge our bishop. } 14... Bh5 ( { We give up the e4-pawn, but activate our bishop. } 14... h5 { is possible as well, although a bit more passive. } ) 15. Re1 Nd7 16. Rxe4 e5 { This is the point. We remove White’s knight from its central position. } 17. Nb5+ Kc6 { Black has managed to coordinate their pieces and the endgame looks promising. } *

