1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 { This line has successfully been tried by the Georgian GM Baadur Jobava lately. I don't think it's really dangerous for Black, but we should be prepared to meet it. By playing an early Nc3 White skips the option to move his pawn to c4, and instead is looking for play in the centre and on the kingside. } 2... d5 { The most principled reply. We need to prevent e4. } 3. Bg5 { White is fighting for the centre by keeping the option open to take our f6-knight. } 3... c5 ( { We immediately challenge White's centre. Of course, there are other good moves as well, and here I'd mention } 3... h6 { followed by 4... c5. However, the extra h6 may not make a big difference. } ) 4. Bxf6 { This exchange is debatable as it reinforces our centre, and White will have to keep the position closed so as not to open up our pair of bishops. } 4... gxf6 5. e3 cxd4 ( { Let's go for this exchange, as it somehow limits White's options. } 5... Nc6 { is also possible, but then Black has to consider the extra possibility of } 6. dxc5 { . } ) 6. Qxd4 e6 { Defending the d5-pawn. } 7. Nf3 Nc6 { The central pawns and the dark-squared bishop give Black a good game. } *

