1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 { This line has successfully been tried by the Georgian GM Baadur Jobava lately. I don't think it's really dangerous for Black, but we should be prepared to meet it. By playing an early Nc3 White skips the option to move his pawn to c4, and instead is looking for play in the centre and on the kingside. } 2... d5 { The most principled reply. We need to prevent e4. } 3. Bg5 { White is fighting for the centre by keeping the option open to take our f6-knight. } 3... c5 ( { We immediately challenge White's centre. Of course, there are other good moves as well, and here I'd mention } 3... h6 { followed by 4... c5. However, the extra h6 may not make a big difference. } ) 4. Bxf6 { This exchange is debatable as it reinforces our centre, and White will have to keep the position closed so as not to open up our pair of bishops. } 4... gxf6 5. e3 cxd4 ( { Let's go for this exchange, as it somehow limits White's options. } 5... Nc6 { is also possible, but then Black has to consider the extra possibility of } 6. dxc5 { . } ) 6. exd4 Nc6 { The most natural reply. } 7. Qh5 { This is White's idea. } 7... e6 ( { Again a natural reply. My idea is to make the lines easy to remember. Taking the pawn with } 7... Nxd4 { is dubious, but } ) ( 7... Be6 { is an interesting alternative that comes into consideration. } ) 8. O-O-O Bd7 { The only square left for the bishop. Now we can continue ...Rc8 or even try to go for ...O-O-O later on. } 9. Nge2 { A typical maneuver. } 9... f5 { I like this plan. We intend to bring the queen to f6 and then castle long since the f7-pawn is defended. } 10. Nf4 Qf6 { Followed by long castling gives Black good play. } *

