1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 { This line has successfully been tried by the Georgian GM Baadur Jobava lately. I don't think it's really dangerous for Black, but we should be prepared to meet it. By playing an early Nc3 White skips the option to move his pawn to c4, and instead is looking for play in the centre and on the kingside. } 2... d5 { The most principled reply. We need to prevent e4. } 3. Bg5 { White is fighting for the centre by keeping the option open to take our f6-knight. } 3... c5 ( { We immediately challenge White's centre. Of course, there are other good moves as well, and here I'd mention } 3... h6 { followed by 4... c5. However, the extra h6 may not make a big difference. } ) 4. Bxf6 { This exchange is debatable as it reinforces our centre, and White will have to keep the position closed so as not to open up our pair of bishops. } 4... gxf6 5. e3 cxd4 ( { Let's go for this exchange, as it somehow limits White's options. } 5... Nc6 { is also possible, but then Black has to consider the extra possibility of } 6. dxc5 { . } ) 6. exd4 Nc6 { The most natural reply. } 7. Qh5 { This is White's idea. } 7... e6 ( { Again a natural reply. My idea is to make the lines easy to remember. Taking the pawn with } 7... Nxd4 { is dubious, but } ) ( 7... Be6 { is an interesting alternative that comes into consideration. } ) 8. O-O-O Bd7 { The only square left for the bishop. Now we can continue ...Rc8 or even try to go for ...O-O-O later on. } 9. Kb1 { This has been played in some correspondence games. } 9... f5 { I analyzed this position for some time and finally came up with this nice plan, which is similar to how we play inother lines. I wasn't happy with the long forcing lines that have been played in correspondence games. } 10. Bb5 Qf6 11. Nf3 O-O-O { Black's position is safe with the king away from the centre. } 12. Bxc6 Bxc6 { Only like this, so as not to weaken our king’s position. } 13. Ne5 Be8 { The only way to defend the f7-pawn, but it's good enough. } 14. Ne2 Bd6 { White’s knights have good squares, but we can also improve our position with ...Kb8 and ...Rc8. } *

