1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 { This line has successfully been tried by the Georgian GM Baadur Jobava lately. I don't think it's really dangerous for Black, but we should be prepared to meet it. By playing an early Nc3 White skips the option to move his pawn to c4, and instead is looking for play in the centre and on the kingside. } 2... d5 { The most principled reply. We need to prevent e4. } 3. Bg5 { White is fighting for the centre by keeping the option open to take our f6-knight. } 3... c5 ( { We immediately challenge White's centre. Of course, there are other good moves as well, and here I'd mention } 3... h6 { followed by 4... c5. However, the extra h6 may not make a big difference. } ) 4. e4 { A sharp move that has been tried sometimes. } 4... Nxe4 { It's important to exchange the knights as ...Qa5+ can them come with check when White plays 6. dxc5. } 5. Nxe4 dxe4 6. d5 { White turns the opening into a gambit, albeit a slightly dubious one. } 6... g6 { We need to complete our development and the bishop will have good perspectives on the long diagonal. } 7. Qd2 { White is preparing to castle long and also to exchange the bishops with Bh6. } 7... Bg7 8. O-O-O Qb6 { The queen comes into play with tempo. } 9. c3 Nd7 { Followed by ...Nf6. Black's position is already preferable. } *

