1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 { This line has successfully been tried by the Georgian GM Baadur Jobava lately. I don't think it's really dangerous for Black, but we should be prepared to meet it. By playing an early Nc3 White skips the option to move his pawn to c4, and instead is looking for play in the centre and on the kingside. } 2... d5 { The most principled reply. We need to prevent e4. } 3. Bg5 { White is fighting for the centre by keeping the option open to take our f6-knight. } 3... c5 ( { We immediately challenge White's centre. Of course, there are other good moves as well, and here I'd mention } 3... h6 { followed by 4... c5. However, the extra h6 may not make a big difference. } ) 4. e4 { A sharp move that has been tried sometimes. } 4... Nxe4 { It's important to exchange the knights as ...Qa5+ can them come with check when White plays 6. dxc5. } 5. Nxe4 dxe4 6. dxc5 { The more objective approach. } 6... Qa5+ ( { I think it's better to take the c5-pawn, although probably } 6... Qxd1+ { is also good enough. } ) 7. Qd2 Qxd2+ { Now we swap the queens, as White's pieces will be in a worse place compared to after 6... Qxd1+. } 8. Bxd2 e5 { With a good endgame for Black. Our development is about the same, but our position is slightly preferable because we have more central pawns. } *

