1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 { This line has successfully been tried by the Georgian GM Baadur Jobava lately. I don't think it's really dangerous for Black, but we should be prepared to meet it. By playing an early Nc3 White skips the option to move his pawn to c4, and instead is looking for play in the centre and on the kingside. } 2... d5 { The most principled reply. We need to prevent e4. } 3. Bg5 { White is fighting for the centre by keeping the option open to take our f6-knight. } 3... c5 ( { We immediately challenge White's centre. Of course, there are other good moves as well, and here I'd mention } 3... h6 { followed by 4... c5. However, the extra h6 may not make a big difference. } ) 4. e4 { A sharp move that has been tried sometimes. } 4... Nxe4 { It's important to exchange the knights as ...Qa5+ can them come with check when White plays 6. dxc5. } 5. Nxe4 dxe4 6. dxc5 { The more objective approach. } 6... Qa5+ ( { I think it's better to take the c5-pawn, although probably } 6... Qxd1+ { is also good enough. } ) 7. c3 Qxc5 8. Qa4+ { White was counting on this check. } 8... Nc6 { We develop the knight first! } 9. Be3 Qa5 { I think it's better to just forget about the e4-pawn and continue with our development. In case we try to keep the pawn White gets good compensation. } 10. Qxe4 Bf5 ( { Developing with tempo. } 10... g6 { is also possible. } ) 11. Qc4 e5 { A good move, taking control over the d4-square just in case. } 12. Nf3 Be6 ( { This forces White to take a decision regarding the queen. Of course } 12... Be7 { is also good. } ) 13. Qb5 Qxb5 { The endgame is good for Black. } 14. Bxb5 f6 { We have a good grip over the centre, and we can continue with ...Kf7, ...Be7 and so on. } *

