1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 { This line has successfully been tried by the Georgian GM Baadur Jobava lately. I don't think it's really dangerous for Black, but we should be prepared to meet it. By playing an early Nc3 White skips the option to move his pawn to c4, and instead is looking for play in the centre and on the kingside. } 2... d5 { The most principled reply. We need to prevent e4. } 3. Bg5 { White is fighting for the centre by keeping the option open to take our f6-knight. } 3... c5 ( { We immediately challenge White's centre. Of course, there are other good moves as well, and here I'd mention } 3... h6 { followed by 4... c5. However, the extra h6 may not make a big difference. } ) 4. Nf3 { Not really an ambitious continuation. } 4... Nc6 ( { We continue with natural development. } 4... Ne4 { is a good move as well, but that would significantly change the character of the position. } ) 5. e3 cxd4 { This is a good moment to clear up the situation in the centre. } 6. exd4 Bg4 ( { On almost every move Black has interesting alternatives. Here } 6... h6 { deserves attention. However, I wanted to stick to natural moves that are easy to remember. } ) 7. h3 Bxf3 { There is no need to try to keep this bishop longer. } 8. Qxf3 e6 ( { Black's position looks good since we have managed to get rid of our light-squared bishop. White's knight on c3 is a bit misplaced. } 8... Nxd4 { is possible as well, but it’s a bit more risky. } ) *

