1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 { This line has successfully been tried by the Georgian GM Baadur Jobava lately. I don't think it's really dangerous for Black, but we should be prepared to meet it. By playing an early Nc3 White skips the option to move his pawn to c4, and instead is looking for play in the centre and on the kingside. } 2... d5 { The most principled reply. We need to prevent e4. } 3. Bg5 { White is fighting for the centre by keeping the option open to take our f6-knight. } 3... c5 ( { We immediately challenge White's centre. Of course, there are other good moves as well, and here I'd mention } 3... h6 { followed by 4... c5. However, the extra h6 may not make a big difference. } ) 4. e3 cxd4 { We can keep the tension in the centre a bit longer, but probably it’s easier to immediately clarify the pawn structure in the centre. } 5. exd4 Nc6 6. Bb5 { White delays developing the knight as he wants to avoid the pin. } 6... Bg4 { It's too tempting not to develop the bishop with tempo. } 7. f3 Bf5 ( { This is more provocative than } 7... Bd7 { but it can be reached from the lines with Nge2 first as well. } ) 8. g4 Bd7 { White's g4 is a weakness rather than a strength. } *

