1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 { This line has successfully been tried by the Georgian GM Baadur Jobava lately. I don't think it's really dangerous for Black, but we should be prepared to meet it. By playing an early Nc3 White skips the option to move his pawn to c4, and instead is looking for play in the centre and on the kingside. } 2... d5 { The most principled reply. We need to prevent e4. } 3. Bf4 { The main move. White develops their queenside pieces and can consider creating a threat with Nb5. } 3... c5 4. e3 { Now White is ready to play Nb5. } ( { We fight for the centre as } 4. Nb5 { is not yet possible due to } 4... Qa5+ { . } ) 4... cxd4 { Clarifying the pawn structure – we would like to avoid a future dxc5. } 5. exd4 a6 { We need to parry the threat of Nb5. } 6. Nf3 Nc6 { Our knight belongs on c6. Afterwards we can develop the light-squared bishop. } 7. Be2 { White just continues developing. } 7... Bg4 { We make sure we're going to exchange this bishop. } 8. O-O e6 9. Ne5 Bxe2 { Following our plan of exchanging the light-squared bishop. } 10. Nxe2 Bd6 { Black's position is strategically sound. } 11. c3 Bxe5 ( { This is more direct. Of course there is nothing wrong with } 11... O-O { either. } ) 12. dxe5 { White tries to keep the bishop alive. } 12... Nh5 { We exchange the dark-squared bishop and then the e5-pawn may become a target. } *

