1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 { This line has successfully been tried by the Georgian GM Baadur Jobava lately. I don't think it's really dangerous for Black, but we should be prepared to meet it. By playing an early Nc3 White skips the option to move his pawn to c4, and instead is looking for play in the centre and on the kingside. } 2... d5 { The most principled reply. We need to prevent e4. } 3. Bf4 { The main move. White develops their queenside pieces and can consider creating a threat with Nb5. } 3... c5 4. e3 { Now White is ready to play Nb5. } ( { We fight for the centre as } 4. Nb5 { is not yet possible due to } 4... Qa5+ { . } ) 4... cxd4 { Clarifying the pawn structure – we would like to avoid a future dxc5. } 5. exd4 a6 { We need to parry the threat of Nb5. } 6. Nf3 Nc6 { Our knight belongs on c6. Afterwards we can develop the light-squared bishop. } 7. Ne5 { This way White avoids ...Bg4. } 7... Bd7 { Our idea is to be able to take back on c6 with the bishop, and thus not spoil our pawn structure. } 8. g3 { This has been tried in a few blitz games. Of course the g2-bishop bites on granite. } 8... e6 9. Bg2 Nxe5 { A good moment to exchange White’s active knight. } 10. dxe5 Ng8 { I know, we are moving backwards, but there is no way for White to take advantage of this. Once we develop, our pieces will have good positions. } 11. Ne2 Bc5 { A good square for the bishop. Next is ...Ne7. } 12. O-O Ne7 { Followed by ...O-O, ...Qb6 or ... Bb5 with a good position for Black. } *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Modern Benoni"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch 16: 2.Bf4/3.Bf4: London System"]
[Black "2. Bf4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 { White is eager to establish the London System setup as soon as possible. } 2... d5 { This is good since White has showed his intentions so early by immediately moving the bishop. } 3. e3 e6 ( { This way we just transpose to our setup against 2. Nf3 and 3. Bf4. } 3... c5 { is also fine, but in that case we need to consider the lines with } 4. dxc5 { as well. Now after 3... e6, if at any point White plays Nf3 a direct transposition to the lines after 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 should occur. Of course, White has some independent tries as well. } ) 4. c4 { This move has been played from time to time, although this is not in the spirit of the London System. } 4... c5 { We can break in the centre as the early Bf4 doesn't help White much. } 5. Nc3 cxd4 6. exd4 Bb4 7. Nf3 O-O { Again, the f4-bishop is a bit misplaced in this position. } 8. Bd3 dxc4 { This comes with tempo, so why not? } 9. Bxc4 b6 10. O-O Bb7 { Followed by ...Nc6 with a nice position for Black. We have entered a Nimzo-Indian in which White's bishop would be better off on g5. } *

