1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 { White is eager to establish the London System setup as soon as possible. } 2... d5 { This is good since White has showed his intentions so early by immediately moving the bishop. } 3. e3 e6 ( { This way we just transpose to our setup against 2. Nf3 and 3. Bf4. } 3... c5 { is also fine, but in that case we need to consider the lines with } 4. dxc5 { as well. Now after 3... e6, if at any point White plays Nf3 a direct transposition to the lines after 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 should occur. Of course, White has some independent tries as well. } ) 4. Nd2 c5 { Fighting for the centre. } 5. c3 Nc6 { Our knight is well placed on c6. } 6. Bg3 { This is a useful waiting move. White is trying to be tricky. } 6... Be7 { Since ...Nh5 is not available for now, we can just complete our development instead. } 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Ngf3 { Sooner or later White had to play this move. } 8... Nh5 { We go for the dark-squared bishop at the first opportunity. } 9. Ne5 g6 { Defending the knight and keeping the status quo on the kingside. } 10. Ndf3 a5 { This may seem strange at first, but the idea is to gain some space on the queenside. } 11. a4 Kg7 ( { Simply defending the g6-pawn and preparing ...f6. The immediate } 11... f6 { would allow } 12. Nxg6 hxg6 13. Nh4 { with a dangerous attack. } ) 12. Qc2 c4 { We drive White’s bishop back. } ( { In order to meet } 12... f6 { with } 13. Bxg6 ) 13. Be2 f6 { And now we take out the centrally posted knight. } 14. Nxc6 bxc6 15. b3 { In order to get rid of Black’s strong c4-pawn. } 15... cxb3 16. Qxb3 Nxg3 17. hxg3 Bd6 { Followed by ...Rb8 or ...e5 with a nice position for Black. } *

