1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 { White is eager to establish the London System setup as soon as possible. } 2... d5 { This is good since White has showed his intentions so early by immediately moving the bishop. } 3. e3 e6 ( { This way we just transpose to our setup against 2. Nf3 and 3. Bf4. } 3... c5 { is also fine, but in that case we need to consider the lines with } 4. dxc5 { as well. Now after 3... e6, if at any point White plays Nf3 a direct transposition to the lines after 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 should occur. Of course, White has some independent tries as well. } ) 4. Nd2 c5 { Fighting for the centre. } 5. c3 Nc6 { Our knight is well placed on c6. } 6. Bd3 Bd6 7. Bxd6 Qxd6 { This exchange favours Black because we are ready to continue with ...e5. } 8. f4 { White goes for a Stonewall setup after having exchanged dark-squared bishops. } 8... cxd4 9. cxd4 ( { Forcing White to take back with the c-pawn as } 9. exd4 { leaves f4 hanging. } ) 9... Bd7 10. a3 Ne7 { Black’s plan is easy: just improve your pieces! } 11. Ngf3 Nf5 12. Qe2 Qb6 { Making room for the knight to come to d6. } 13. Ne5 { Preventing Black from playing ...Ng4. } 13... Rc8 14. O-O Nd6 { With a playable position for both sides. } *

