1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 { The starting position of the London System, one of the most solid setups for White. It has quickly gained in popularity in blitz and rapid games, as it is suited for those time controls. White develops his pieces harmoniously. } 3... c5 ( { There is no much difference between this move and } 3... d5 { I decided to start with 3... c5 because it's a logical consequence of 2... e6. Another main line is } ) ( 3... d5 4. e3 { and now } 4... Bd6 { This has been very popular recently, and it justifies the early ...e6. However I find it a bit dull, and Black is only fighting for equality. I think that as Benoni players we want to get more interesting positions, even against the London. } ) 4. e3 d5 ( { We take control over the centre. Here too Black has multiple good alternatives, like } 4... Qb6 { or } ) ( 4... cxd4 5. exd4 b6 { . } ) 5. c3 ( { This is played more often than } 5. Nbd2 { , but in all likelihood it just transposes to the same position. } ) 5... Nc6 6. Bd3 Nh5 { We can go for the f4-bishop immediately. } ( { This is another move order, incidentally aimed against our setup. } 6... cxd4 { is not so good now because White answers } 7. cxd4 { and follows up with Nc3. However in a different way 6. Bd3 is less flexible, as White loses the option to develop the bishop directly to b5. } ) 7. Be5 { White tries to create some weaknesses on our kingside. } 7... f6 8. Ng5 { Looks fancy but it doesn't actually work. } 8... fxe5 { The start of a forced sequence. } 9. Qxh5+ g6 { The only way to parry the check. } 10. Bxg6+ { Otherwise ...e4 follows. } 10... hxg6 11. Qxg6+ Kd7 12. Nf7 Qh4 { Black has a big advantage. The king is quite safe now and the bishops will dominate the game. } *

