[Black "3. Bf4 mainline with 6. Bb5 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 { The starting position of the London System, one of the most solid setups for White. It has quickly gained in popularity in blitz and rapid games, as it is suited for those time controls. White develops his pieces harmoniously. } 3... c5 ( { There is no much difference between this move and } 3... d5 { I decided to start with 3... c5 because it's a logical consequence of 2... e6. Another main line is } ) ( 3... d5 4. e3 { and now } 4... Bd6 { This has been very popular recently, and it justifies the early ...e6. However I find it a bit dull, and Black is only fighting for equality. I think that as Benoni players we want to get more interesting positions, even against the London. } ) 4. e3 d5 ( { We take control over the centre. Here too Black has multiple good alternatives, like } 4... Qb6 { or } ) ( 4... cxd4 5. exd4 b6 { . } ) 5. Nbd2 Nc6 6. Bb5 { This has been played every now and then. } 6... Qb6 ( { Forcing events a bit. Black also has other reasonable moves at his disposal like } 6... Bd6 { or } ) ( 6... Bd7 { . I will give the latter as an alternative variation. } ) 7. c4 { The logical follow up to Bb5. } 7... cxd4 { Sooner or later we’ll have to play this move. } 8. Nxd4 Be7 { Intending to castle as soon as possible. } 9. b4 { Not an easy to find move. White is trying to open up the position on the queenside. } 9... Bxb4 { We need to grab this pawn. } 10. O-O O-O 11. Rb1 Nxd4 { So that we are able to move the bishop without losing material. } 12. exd4 Bxd2 13. c5 { This is a big blunder. } 13... Qxb5 14. Rxb5 Bxf4 { With three pieces and a pawn for the queen, Black is just winning. } *

