1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 { The starting position of the London System, one of the most solid setups for White. It has quickly gained in popularity in blitz and rapid games, as it is suited for those time controls. White develops his pieces harmoniously. } 3... c5 ( { There is no much difference between this move and } 3... d5 { I decided to start with 3... c5 because it's a logical consequence of 2... e6. Another main line is } ) ( 3... d5 4. e3 { and now } 4... Bd6 { This has been very popular recently, and it justifies the early ...e6. However I find it a bit dull, and Black is only fighting for equality. I think that as Benoni players we want to get more interesting positions, even against the London. } ) 4. e3 d5 ( { We take control over the centre. Here too Black has multiple good alternatives, like } 4... Qb6 { or } ) ( 4... cxd4 5. exd4 b6 { . } ) 5. Nbd2 Nc6 6. Bb5 { This has been played every now and then. } 6... Qb6 ( { Forcing events a bit. Black also has other reasonable moves at his disposal like } 6... Bd6 { or } ) ( 6... Bd7 { . I will give the latter as an alternative variation. } ) 7. c4 { The logical follow up to Bb5. } 7... cxd4 { Sooner or later we’ll have to play this move. } 8. exd4 Bd7 ( { It's time to address the pin. } 8... dxc4 { is a good option as well. } ) 9. Bxc6 Bxc6 10. c5 { This was White's idea. } 10... Qxb2 { More or less forced. Otherwise White would just get a nice space advantage. } 11. O-O Be7 { It is important to castle quickly, as otherwise White may play Rb1 and Ne5 followed by Nxc6 and we won't be able to finish our development. } 12. Re1 O-O 13. Rb1 Qa3 { White has compensation for the pawn but not more than that. } *

