1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 { The starting position of the London System, one of the most solid setups for White. It has quickly gained in popularity in blitz and rapid games, as it is suited for those time controls. White develops his pieces harmoniously. } 3... c5 ( { There is no much difference between this move and } 3... d5 { I decided to start with 3... c5 because it's a logical consequence of 2... e6. Another main line is } ) ( 3... d5 4. e3 { and now } 4... Bd6 { This has been very popular recently, and it justifies the early ...e6. However I find it a bit dull, and Black is only fighting for equality. I think that as Benoni players we want to get more interesting positions, even against the London. } ) 4. e3 d5 ( { We take control over the centre. Here too Black has multiple good alternatives, like } 4... Qb6 { or } ) ( 4... cxd4 5. exd4 b6 { . } ) 5. Nbd2 Nc6 6. Bb5 { This has been played every now and then. } 6... Qb6 ( { Forcing events a bit. Black also has other reasonable moves at his disposal like } 6... Bd6 { or } ) ( 6... Bd7 { . I will give the latter as an alternative variation. } ) 7. c4 { The logical follow up to Bb5. } 7... cxd4 { Sooner or later we’ll have to play this move. } 8. exd4 Bd7 ( { It's time to address the pin. } 8... dxc4 { is a good option as well. } ) 9. O-O dxc4 { Now is the right time to take on c4. } 10. a4 a6 { Forcing some exchanges. } 11. Nxc4 Qd8 12. Bxc6 Bxc6 13. Nfe5 Rc8 { So as not to spoil our pawn structure. } 14. Nxc6 Rxc6 15. Ne5 Rc7 { Thankfully, White has no good knight move to take advantage of our rook's position. } 16. a5 Bd6 { Just in time! } 17. Qa4+ Ke7 { Black is fine although we’ve lost the right to castle. ...Nd5 is next, and we can even play ...Re8 and ...Kf8 to bring the king to safety. } *

