1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 { The starting position of the London System, one of the most solid setups for White. It has quickly gained in popularity in blitz and rapid games, as it is suited for those time controls. White develops his pieces harmoniously. } 3... c5 ( { There is no much difference between this move and } 3... d5 { I decided to start with 3... c5 because it's a logical consequence of 2... e6. Another main line is } ) ( 3... d5 4. e3 { and now } 4... Bd6 { This has been very popular recently, and it justifies the early ...e6. However I find it a bit dull, and Black is only fighting for equality. I think that as Benoni players we want to get more interesting positions, even against the London. } ) 4. e3 d5 ( { We take control over the centre. Here too Black has multiple good alternatives, like } 4... Qb6 { or } ) ( 4... cxd4 5. exd4 b6 { . } ) 5. Nbd2 Nc6 6. Bb5 { This has been played every now and then. } 6... Bd7 { Simply addressing the pin that White has just introduced. } 7. O-O Be7 { I'd rather not delay our development any longer. } 8. dxc5 { White breaks open the centre while still leading in development. } 8... Bxc5 9. Bd3 { White wants to go for c4 next. } 9... Nh5 { This is a good moment to get the f4 bishop, but we'll have to be careful with castling now because of Bxh7+ ideas. } 10. c4 Nxf4 { Mission accomplished! } 11. exf4 Nb4 ( { It is important not to blunder with } 11... O-O { , which fails in view of } 12. cxd5 exd5 13. Bxh7+ Kxh7 14. Qc2+ { and Qxc5. } ) 12. Be2 dxc4 { We make room for the knight to come to d5. } 13. Nxc4 O-O { Our dark-squared bishop will prove useful later on. } *

