[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 { The starting position of the London System, one of the most solid setups for White. It has quickly gained in popularity in blitz and rapid games, as it is suited for those time controls. White develops his pieces harmoniously. } 3... c5 ( { There is no much difference between this move and } 3... d5 { I decided to start with 3... c5 because it's a logical consequence of 2... e6. Another main line is } ) ( 3... d5 4. e3 { and now } 4... Bd6 { This has been very popular recently, and it justifies the early ...e6. However I find it a bit dull, and Black is only fighting for equality. I think that as Benoni players we want to get more interesting positions, even against the London. } ) 4. e3 d5 ( { We take control over the centre. Here too Black has multiple good alternatives, like } 4... Qb6 { or } ) ( 4... cxd4 5. exd4 b6 { . } ) 5. Nbd2 Nc6 6. c3 cxd4 ( { We remove the tension in the centre and prepare our next move, ...Nh5. } 6... Nh5 { straightaway is interesting as well. } ) 7. cxd4 { This is possible and very solid, of course. However I don't think Black should have problems because White’s queenside knight is already developed to d2, which means it won’t be developed to the superior square c3. } 7... Qb6 { Attacking the b2-pawn and also planning ...Nh5 in order to take the dark-squared bishop. } 8. Rb1 { This cautious move has been preferred by the London experts Artemiev and Kamsky. } 8... Nh5 { It’s time to hunt down the bishop. } 9. Bg5 { Trying to create some weaknesses on our kingside. } 9... h6 { The chase continues. } 10. Bh4 g5 11. Bg3 g4 { A strong move, dislodging the white knight from f3. } 12. Ne5 Nxg3 { We get rid of the bishop. } 13. hxg3 Nxe5 14. dxe5 h5 { The e5-pawn is quite weak. } 15. Qa4+ Bd7 16. Qd4 Bg7 { This was seen in ½-½ (30) Artemiev,V (2701)-Adhiban,B (2661) Sharjah 2018. The game ended in a draw, but Black could have gotten an edge if he had continued with a quick ...f6. } *

