1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 { The starting position of the London System, one of the most solid setups for White. It has quickly gained in popularity in blitz and rapid games, as it is suited for those time controls. White develops his pieces harmoniously. } 3... c5 ( { There is no much difference between this move and } 3... d5 { I decided to start with 3... c5 because it's a logical consequence of 2... e6. Another main line is } ) ( 3... d5 4. e3 { and now } 4... Bd6 { This has been very popular recently, and it justifies the early ...e6. However I find it a bit dull, and Black is only fighting for equality. I think that as Benoni players we want to get more interesting positions, even against the London. } ) 4. e3 d5 ( { We take control over the centre. Here too Black has multiple good alternatives, like } 4... Qb6 { or } ) ( 4... cxd4 5. exd4 b6 { . } ) 5. Nbd2 Nc6 6. c3 cxd4 ( { We remove the tension in the centre and prepare our next move, ...Nh5. } 6... Nh5 { straightaway is interesting as well. } ) 7. cxd4 { This is possible and very solid, of course. However I don't think Black should have problems because White’s queenside knight is already developed to d2, which means it won’t be developed to the superior square c3. } 7... Qb6 { Attacking the b2-pawn and also planning ...Nh5 in order to take the dark-squared bishop. } 8. Rb1 { This cautious move has been preferred by the London experts Artemiev and Kamsky. } 8... Nh5 { It’s time to hunt down the bishop. } 9. Bg5 { Trying to create some weaknesses on our kingside. } 9... h6 { The chase continues. } 10. Bh4 g5 11. Ne5 ( { This is preferable to Artemiev’s } 11. Bg3 { . } ) 11... Nxe5 { We start exchanging some pieces. } 12. Qxh5 gxh4 13. Qxe5 Rg8 { Most likely the black king will stay in the centre. However, it is not difficult for us to activate all of our pieces. } 14. g3 Bd7 { There is no need to take on g3 as this would merely open up the h-file for White's rook. } 15. Bd3 Bb5 { An advantageous exchange. } 16. Bxb5+ Qxb5 17. Rc1 Rd8 { With an unbalanced position, both kings being stuck in the centre. Black is doing fine. } *

