1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 { The starting position of the London System, one of the most solid setups for White. It has quickly gained in popularity in blitz and rapid games, as it is suited for those time controls. White develops his pieces harmoniously. } 3... c5 ( { There is no much difference between this move and } 3... d5 { I decided to start with 3... c5 because it's a logical consequence of 2... e6. Another main line is } ) ( 3... d5 4. e3 { and now } 4... Bd6 { This has been very popular recently, and it justifies the early ...e6. However I find it a bit dull, and Black is only fighting for equality. I think that as Benoni players we want to get more interesting positions, even against the London. } ) 4. e3 d5 ( { We take control over the centre. Here too Black has multiple good alternatives, like } 4... Qb6 { or } ) ( 4... cxd4 5. exd4 b6 { . } ) 5. Nbd2 Nc6 6. c3 cxd4 ( { We remove the tension in the centre and prepare our next move, ...Nh5. } 6... Nh5 { straightaway is interesting as well. } ) 7. cxd4 { This is possible and very solid, of course. However I don't think Black should have problems because White’s queenside knight is already developed to d2, which means it won’t be developed to the superior square c3. } 7... Qb6 { Attacking the b2-pawn and also planning ...Nh5 in order to take the dark-squared bishop. } 8. Bd3 { White bets everything on development. } 8... Qxb2 { Challenge accepted – we grab the pawn. } 9. O-O Qa3 { Followed by standard  development. Black should be fine playing ...Be7, ...O-O etc. } 10. Qe2 Be7 11. Bc7 { White cuts off our queen's escape route and is now threatening Nb1. } 11... Bd8 { We make room for the queen to retreat to e7 so that she doesn’t get trapped. } 12. Bxd8 Nxd8 { White has enough compensation for the pawn but nothing more. } *

