1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 { The starting position of the London System, one of the most solid setups for White. It has quickly gained in popularity in blitz and rapid games, as it is suited for those time controls. White develops his pieces harmoniously. } 3... c5 ( { There is no much difference between this move and } 3... d5 { I decided to start with 3... c5 because it's a logical consequence of 2... e6. Another main line is } ) ( 3... d5 4. e3 { and now } 4... Bd6 { This has been very popular recently, and it justifies the early ...e6. However I find it a bit dull, and Black is only fighting for equality. I think that as Benoni players we want to get more interesting positions, even against the London. } ) 4. e3 d5 ( { We take control over the centre. Here too Black has multiple good alternatives, like } 4... Qb6 { or } ) ( 4... cxd4 5. exd4 b6 { . } ) 5. Nbd2 Nc6 6. c3 cxd4 ( { We remove the tension in the centre and prepare our next move, ...Nh5. } 6... Nh5 { straightaway is interesting as well. } ) 7. cxd4 { This is possible and very solid, of course. However I don't think Black should have problems because White’s queenside knight is already developed to d2, which means it won’t be developed to the superior square c3. } 7... Qb6 { Attacking the b2-pawn and also planning ...Nh5 in order to take the dark-squared bishop. } 8. Bd3 { White bets everything on development. } 8... Qxb2 { Challenge accepted – we grab the pawn. } 9. a4 { Trying to make our queen uncomfortable. } 9... Qc3 { Here our queen is one step away from escaping to a5. Moreover, White doesn't have the resource 10. Qe2 because the a1-rook would remain hanging. } 10. Bb5 Bd7 { I think we should address this pin immediately. } 11. O-O Be7 { We're one step away from bringing our king to safety. } 12. Qe2 Qa5 ( { This keeps the game going. If we play } 12... O-O { immediately, White can force a draw } 13. a5 { followed by a move repetition with Rf1-c1-b1, chasing our queen. } ) 13. Ne5 O-O { Finally bringing the king to safety. } 14. Nxd7 Nxd7 15. Nb3 Qd8 { White has enough compensation for the pawn, but we're doing fine as well. } *

