[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 { The starting position of the London System, one of the most solid setups for White. It has quickly gained in popularity in blitz and rapid games, as it is suited for those time controls. White develops his pieces harmoniously. } 3... c5 ( { There is no much difference between this move and } 3... d5 { I decided to start with 3... c5 because it's a logical consequence of 2... e6. Another main line is } ) ( 3... d5 4. e3 { and now } 4... Bd6 { This has been very popular recently, and it justifies the early ...e6. However I find it a bit dull, and Black is only fighting for equality. I think that as Benoni players we want to get more interesting positions, even against the London. } ) 4. e3 d5 ( { We take control over the centre. Here too Black has multiple good alternatives, like } 4... Qb6 { or } ) ( 4... cxd4 5. exd4 b6 { . } ) 5. Nbd2 Nc6 6. c3 cxd4 ( { We remove the tension in the centre and prepare our next move, ...Nh5. } 6... Nh5 { straightaway is interesting as well. } ) 7. exd4 Nh5 { would be quite strong. } 8. Bg5 f6 { We don’t mind making this move – it’s quite useful to us. } 9. Be3 Bd6 { The extra move ...f6 has cut off our knight's retreat, but now we can prepare ...e5 faster. } 10. g3 O-O { Now that our king is safe we have a variety of ideas: ...g6 followed by ...Ng7-f5, or ...e5, or even ...f5. } 11. Bd3 Qe8 { First safeguarding the h5-knight. } 12. Nh4 g6 { I like this maneuver to relocate the knight via g7 to f5. } 13. O-O Ng7 { With an unclear position where Black is doing well. We can complete our development with ...Bd7 and ...Ne7 and then prepare the next steps. } *

