[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 { The starting position of the London System, one of the most solid setups for White. It has quickly gained in popularity in blitz and rapid games, as it is suited for those time controls. White develops his pieces harmoniously. } 3... c5 ( { There is no much difference between this move and } 3... d5 { I decided to start with 3... c5 because it's a logical consequence of 2... e6. Another main line is } ) ( 3... d5 4. e3 { and now } 4... Bd6 { This has been very popular recently, and it justifies the early ...e6. However I find it a bit dull, and Black is only fighting for equality. I think that as Benoni players we want to get more interesting positions, even against the London. } ) 4. e3 d5 ( { We take control over the centre. Here too Black has multiple good alternatives, like } 4... Qb6 { or } ) ( 4... cxd4 5. exd4 b6 { . } ) 5. Nbd2 Nc6 6. c3 cxd4 ( { We remove the tension in the centre and prepare our next move, ...Nh5. } 6... Nh5 { straightaway is interesting as well. } ) 7. exd4 Nh5 { would be quite strong. } 8. Bg3 { Now the position resembles a reversed Slav Defence. } 8... Nxg3 { We may as well exchange the bishop. } 9. hxg3 g6 { I like this plan to put the pawns on the light squares after we’ve exchanged White’s dark-squared bishop. } 10. Bb5 Bg7 { The bishop protects the king very well. } 11. Ne5 ( { This is just greedy. Instead after } 11. O-O O-O { we'd have a normal position with plenty of play ahead. } ) 11... O-O { The pawn sacrifice is an obvious decision. White will be in trouble after he takes the pawn. } 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. Bxc6 Rb8 { We develop an initiative with natural moves. } 14. Nb3 Qd6 15. Ba4 Ba6 { It is difficult for White to defend this position as his pieces are awkwardly placed and his king is stuck in the centre. } *

