1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 { The starting position of the London System, one of the most solid setups for White. It has quickly gained in popularity in blitz and rapid games, as it is suited for those time controls. White develops his pieces harmoniously. } 3... c5 ( { There is no much difference between this move and } 3... d5 { I decided to start with 3... c5 because it's a logical consequence of 2... e6. Another main line is } ) ( 3... d5 4. e3 { and now } 4... Bd6 { This has been very popular recently, and it justifies the early ...e6. However I find it a bit dull, and Black is only fighting for equality. I think that as Benoni players we want to get more interesting positions, even against the London. } ) 4. e3 d5 ( { We take control over the centre. Here too Black has multiple good alternatives, like } 4... Qb6 { or } ) ( 4... cxd4 5. exd4 b6 { . } ) 5. Nbd2 Nc6 6. c3 cxd4 ( { We remove the tension in the centre and prepare our next move, ...Nh5. } 6... Nh5 { straightaway is interesting as well. } ) 7. exd4 Nh5 { would be quite strong. } 8. Be3 Bd6 { We take control over the important b8-h2 diagonal, and now a struggle for control over the e5-square begins. } 9. g3 Nf6 { Our knight did its job on h5 and now it comes back into play via f6. I want to avoid White's Ne5, and also I'm not a big fan of the ...f5 ideas. } 10. Bd3 O-O 11. O-O h6 { This can be useful in the long run. } 12. Re1 Re8 { Followed by developing our queenside pieces with ...Bd7 and ...Rc8. Afterwards we can consider ...e5 or just try to push the pawns on the queenside. It is important that we’ve managed to drive the white bishop away from the h2-b8 diagonal. } *

