1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 { The starting position of the London System, one of the most solid setups for White. It has quickly gained in popularity in blitz and rapid games, as it is suited for those time controls. White develops his pieces harmoniously. } 3... c5 ( { There is no much difference between this move and } 3... d5 { I decided to start with 3... c5 because it's a logical consequence of 2... e6. Another main line is } ) ( 3... d5 4. e3 { and now } 4... Bd6 { This has been very popular recently, and it justifies the early ...e6. However I find it a bit dull, and Black is only fighting for equality. I think that as Benoni players we want to get more interesting positions, even against the London. } ) 4. e3 d5 ( { We take control over the centre. Here too Black has multiple good alternatives, like } 4... Qb6 { or } ) ( 4... cxd4 5. exd4 b6 { . } ) 5. Nbd2 Nc6 6. c3 cxd4 ( { We remove the tension in the centre and prepare our next move, ...Nh5. } 6... Nh5 { straightaway is interesting as well. } ) 7. exd4 Nh5 { would be quite strong. } 8. Be3 Bd6 { We take control over the important b8-h2 diagonal, and now a struggle for control over the e5-square begins. } 9. Bd3 { This is also quite a popular option. } 9... Nf4 { It's a good idea to force the exchange our knight for White’s dark-squared bishop. } 10. Bxf4 Bxf4 11. O-O O-O 12. Re1 g6 { It makes strategic sense to put our pawns on light squares once we’ve managed to exchange White's dark-squared bishop. The position is playable for both sides. } *

