1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 { The starting position of the London System, one of the most solid setups for White. It has quickly gained in popularity in blitz and rapid games, as it is suited for those time controls. White develops his pieces harmoniously. } 3... c5 ( { There is no much difference between this move and } 3... d5 { I decided to start with 3... c5 because it's a logical consequence of 2... e6. Another main line is } ) ( 3... d5 4. e3 { and now } 4... Bd6 { This has been very popular recently, and it justifies the early ...e6. However I find it a bit dull, and Black is only fighting for equality. I think that as Benoni players we want to get more interesting positions, even against the London. } ) 4. e3 d5 ( { We take control over the centre. Here too Black has multiple good alternatives, like } 4... Qb6 { or } ) ( 4... cxd4 5. exd4 b6 { . } ) 5. Nbd2 Nc6 6. c3 cxd4 ( { We remove the tension in the centre and prepare our next move, ...Nh5. } 6... Nh5 { straightaway is interesting as well. } ) 7. exd4 Nh5 { would be quite strong. } 8. Be3 Bd6 { We take control over the important b8-h2 diagonal, and now a struggle for control over the e5-square begins. } 9. Ne5 { This is deemed the most ambitious continuation for White. By relocating the knight, White has ideas to continue with f4 or even g4. } 9... Nf6 ( { An important moment. In most games that reached this position Black has played } 9... g6 { , which for a long time has been considered the most precise. Back in 2017 when I had an interest in this variation I saw the game Lupulescu- Tabatabaei, Rasht 2017 and thought that Black went wrong with } ) ( 9... Nf6 { . However, when I was preparing the material for this course I changed my mind. The reason I don't like } ) ( 9... g6 { is the forcing line } 10. g4 Ng7 { (the most ambitious) } 11. h4 Nxe5 12. dxe5 Bxe5 13. h5 O-O { and here either } 14. Qf3 { or } ( 14. f4 { when White has a dangerous initiative for the pawn. Benoni players like to have the initiative themselves, and this position is not in that spirit. } ) ) 10. f4 { Very logical. White supports the knight in the centre, hoping for a long-term edge. } 10... Qb6 { This is a big improvement over the above-mentioned game Lupulescu- Tabatabaei, Rasht 2017. This move actually introduces a double attack: both ...Qxb2 and ... Bxe5 are in the air (it seems better to go ...Bxe5 than ...Nxe5) as the e3-bishop is unprotected. } 11. Qb3 { The only way to stop both threats. } 11... Ng8 ( { A nice rejoinder. We want to go ...Nge7/...Nh6 followed by ...f6 in order to kick the e5-knight away from the centre. Exchanging the queens with } 11... Qxb3 { would give White a more comfortable ending. } ) 12. g3 Nge7 { We continue with our plan. } 13. Bf2 f6 { Black is doing fine. } *

