1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 { The starting position of the London System, one of the most solid setups for White. It has quickly gained in popularity in blitz and rapid games, as it is suited for those time controls. White develops his pieces harmoniously. } 3... c5 ( { There is no much difference between this move and } 3... d5 { I decided to start with 3... c5 because it's a logical consequence of 2... e6. Another main line is } ) ( 3... d5 4. e3 { and now } 4... Bd6 { This has been very popular recently, and it justifies the early ...e6. However I find it a bit dull, and Black is only fighting for equality. I think that as Benoni players we want to get more interesting positions, even against the London. } ) 4. e3 d5 ( { We take control over the centre. Here too Black has multiple good alternatives, like } 4... Qb6 { or } ) ( 4... cxd4 5. exd4 b6 { . } ) 5. Nbd2 Nc6 6. c3 cxd4 ( { We remove the tension in the centre and prepare our next move, ...Nh5. } 6... Nh5 { straightaway is interesting as well. } ) 7. exd4 Nh5 { would be quite strong. } 8. Be3 Bd6 { We take control over the important b8-h2 diagonal, and now a struggle for control over the e5-square begins. } 9. Ne5 { This is deemed the most ambitious continuation for White. By relocating the knight, White has ideas to continue with f4 or even g4. } 9... Nf6 ( { An important moment. In most games that reached this position Black has played } 9... g6 { , which for a long time has been considered the most precise. Back in 2017 when I had an interest in this variation I saw the game Lupulescu- Tabatabaei, Rasht 2017 and thought that Black went wrong with } ) ( 9... Nf6 { . However, when I was preparing the material for this course I changed my mind. The reason I don't like } ) ( 9... g6 { is the forcing line } 10. g4 Ng7 { (the most ambitious) } 11. h4 Nxe5 12. dxe5 Bxe5 13. h5 O-O { and here either } 14. Qf3 { or } ( 14. f4 { when White has a dangerous initiative for the pawn. Benoni players like to have the initiative themselves, and this position is not in that spirit. } ) ) 10. Ndf3 { White reinforces the e5-knight with his pieces. } 10... Qc7 ( { I prefer this to } 10... Nd7 { as in that case White can take } 11. Nxd7 { Black is OK there as well, but I want to see what White is doing with the e5-knight. This has been played by Nakamura in a few blitz games. } ) 11. Nd3 { White wants to keep pieces on the board and just play the position. } 11... O-O { This move is useful anyway. } 12. g3 Ng4 ( { Beginning active play in the centre. } 12... b6 { followed by ...Ba6 is a good alternative. } ) 13. Bc1 e5 { Not the only good move, but the most direct option. } 14. dxe5 Ngxe5 { Taking with the other knight leads to the same thing. } 15. Ndxe5 Nxe5 16. Nxe5 Bxe5 { Black has an advantage in development. The isolated d5-pawn is not a big problem because we have options to push it or even to sacrifice it for the initiative. } 17. Bg2 Qc4 { So as not to allow White to castle. } 18. Bxd5 { The pawn grab is tactically refuted: } 18... Bxc3+ 19. bxc3 Qxc3+ 20. Bd2 { Otherwise the a1-rook is hanging, but now the bishop on d5 remains unprotected. } 20... Re8+ 21. Kf1 Qd3+ { Followed by ...Qxd5 with a pawn up and a winning attack. } *

