tiative themselves, and this position is not in that spirit. } ) ) 10. Ndf3 { White reinforces the e5-knight with his pieces. } 10... Qc7 ( { I prefer this to } 10... Nd7 { as in that case White can take } 11. Nxd7 { Black is OK there as well, but I want to see what White is doing with the e5-knight. This has been played by Nakamura in a few blitz games. } ) 11. Nd3 { White wants to keep pieces on the board and just play the position. } 11... O-O { This move is useful anyway. } 12. g3 Ng4 ( { Beginning active play in the centre. } 12... b6 { followed by ...Ba6 is a good alternative. } ) 13. Bc1 e5 { Not the only good move, but the most direct option. } 14. dxe5 Ngxe5 { Taking with the other knight leads to the same thing. } 15. Ndxe5 Nxe5 16. Nxe5 Bxe5 { Black has an advantage in development. The isolated d5-pawn is not a big problem because we have options to push it or even to sacrifice it for the initiative. } 17. Bg2 Qc4 { So as not to allow White to castle. } 18. Be3 Bg4 { This comes with tempo. } 19. f3 Be6 { Black has active play for the isolated pawn. We can prepare to play ...d4 at the right moment. } *

