1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 { The starting position of the London System, one of the most solid setups for White. It has quickly gained in popularity in blitz and rapid games, as it is suited for those time controls. White develops his pieces harmoniously. } 3... c5 ( { There is no much difference between this move and } 3... d5 { I decided to start with 3... c5 because it's a logical consequence of 2... e6. Another main line is } ) ( 3... d5 4. e3 { and now } 4... Bd6 { This has been very popular recently, and it justifies the early ...e6. However I find it a bit dull, and Black is only fighting for equality. I think that as Benoni players we want to get more interesting positions, even against the London. } ) 4. e3 d5 ( { We take control over the centre. Here too Black has multiple good alternatives, like } 4... Qb6 { or } ) ( 4... cxd4 5. exd4 b6 { . } ) 5. Nbd2 Nc6 6. c3 cxd4 ( { We remove the tension in the centre and prepare our next move, ...Nh5. } 6... Nh5 { straightaway is interesting as well. } ) 7. exd4 Nh5 { would be quite strong. } 8. Be3 Bd6 { We take control over the important b8-h2 diagonal, and now a struggle for control over the e5-square begins. } 9. Ne5 { This is deemed the most ambitious continuation for White. By relocating the knight, White has ideas to continue with f4 or even g4. } 9... Nf6 ( { An important moment. In most games that reached this position Black has played } 9... g6 { , which for a long time has been considered the most precise. Back in 2017 when I had an interest in this variation I saw the game Lupulescu- Tabatabaei, Rasht 2017 and thought that Black went wrong with } ) ( 9... Nf6 { . However, when I was preparing the material for this course I changed my mind. The reason I don't like } ) ( 9... g6 { is the forcing line } 10. g4 Ng7 { (the most ambitious) } 11. h4 Nxe5 12. dxe5 Bxe5 13. h5 O-O { and here either } 14. Qf3 { or } ( 14. f4 { when White has a dangerous initiative for the pawn. Benoni players like to have the initiative themselves, and this position is not in that spirit. } ) ) 10. Ndf3 { White reinforces the e5-knight with his pieces. } 10... Qc7 ( { I prefer this to } 10... Nd7 { as in that case White can take } 11. Nxd7 { Black is OK there as well, but I want to see what White is doing with the e5-knight. This has been played by Nakamura in a few blitz games. } ) 11. Bf4 { White tries to maintain the centrally posted e5-knight. } 11... Ne4 { Now we can centralize our knight as well, so why not do so? We also prepare to evict White’s knight with ...f6. } 12. Nxc6 { Otherwise ...f6 would be unpleasant. } 12... Bxf4 13. Nce5 O-O { This is the safer choice. We avoid any checks on the a4-e8 diagonal. } 14. g3 Bxe5 { The simplest. there is no need to play 14… f6. } 15. Nxe5 b6 { Forces White’s bishop to remain on the f1-a6 diagonal, as otherwise we can play ...Ba6 and prevent White from castling. Next we can prepare ...f6 and ...e5 with a good game. } *

