1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. e3 { White avoids the Benoni, and just wants to get a normal game by developing their pieces. } 4... d5 ( { We reach a symmetrical position. I was considering also to suggest } 4... cxd4 5. exd4 { and then } 5... d5 { , entering the Panov Attack. However, the resulting positions seem a bit passive to me. Instead, the text move is very natural. We are just fighting for the centre. } ) 5. Nc3 { White is not yet defining the pawn structure. } 5... a6 ( { This is a useful move. Our plan is to take ...dxc4 and follow up with ...b5. We also avoid an unpleasant check on b5. } 5... dxc4 6. Bxc4 a6 { is interesting as well, when the game enters a Queen's Gambit Accepted where White played has played a quick Nc3 which should  favour Black. } ) 6. a3 { White goes for symmetry. } 6... dxc4 { We continue with our plan. } 7. Bxc4 b5 8. Bd3 Nbd7 9. O-O ( { We develop the knight first so that we can meet } 9. dxc5 { with } 9... Nxc5 { . } ) 9... Bb7 10. Qe2 Bd6 ( { With a good position for Black. The bishop is more active on d6, but } 10... Be7 { is also fine. } ) *

