1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. e3 { White avoids the Benoni, and just wants to get a normal game by developing their pieces. } 4... d5 ( { We reach a symmetrical position. I was considering also to suggest } 4... cxd4 5. exd4 { and then } 5... d5 { , entering the Panov Attack. However, the resulting positions seem a bit passive to me. Instead, the text move is very natural. We are just fighting for the centre. } ) 5. Nc3 { White is not yet defining the pawn structure. } 5... a6 ( { This is a useful move. Our plan is to take ...dxc4 and follow up with ...b5. We also avoid an unpleasant check on b5. } 5... dxc4 6. Bxc4 a6 { is interesting as well, when the game enters a Queen's Gambit Accepted where White played has played a quick Nc3 which should  favour Black. } ) 6. a3 { White goes for symmetry. } 6... dxc4 { We continue with our plan. } 7. Bxc4 b5 8. Be2 { A solid move, but hardly fighting for an advantage. } 8... Bb7 9. O-O Nbd7 { Black gets a good position with natural moves. } 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. b4 Be7 { The bishop is well placed here because it prevents White from playing a4. } 12. Bb2 O-O { With an equal and uneventful position. } *

