1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. e3 { White avoids the Benoni, and just wants to get a normal game by developing their pieces. } 4... d5 ( { We reach a symmetrical position. I was considering also to suggest } 4... cxd4 5. exd4 { and then } 5... d5 { , entering the Panov Attack. However, the resulting positions seem a bit passive to me. Instead, the text move is very natural. We are just fighting for the centre. } ) 5. Nc3 { White is not yet defining the pawn structure. } 5... a6 ( { This is a useful move. Our plan is to take ...dxc4 and follow up with ...b5. We also avoid an unpleasant check on b5. } 5... dxc4 6. Bxc4 a6 { is interesting as well, when the game enters a Queen's Gambit Accepted where White played has played a quick Nc3 which should  favour Black. } ) 6. a3 { White goes for symmetry. } 6... dxc4 { We continue with our plan. } 7. Bxc4 b5 8. Ba2 { It makes sense for White to put the bishop here since he has played a3. } 8... Bb7 9. O-O Nbd7 { It's more flexible to develop the queenside first. } 10. d5 { This push doesn't really work. } 10... exd5 11. Nxd5 Bd6 ( 11... c4 { is also good, but I want to finish our development as soon as possible. } ) 12. e4 O-O 13. Bg5 { White was counting on this pin. } 13... h6 { We want to have the option of ...g5 in reserve. } 14. Bh4 Re8 { A useful move. } 15. Re1 g5 { Finally we are ready for this important move that allows us to unpin the knight. I have checked and the sacrifices on g5 don't work. } 16. Bg3 Bxg3 17. hxg3 Nxe4 { It's not easy for White to justify the pawn minus. } *

