1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. e3 { White avoids the Benoni, and just wants to get a normal game by developing their pieces. } 4... d5 ( { We reach a symmetrical position. I was considering also to suggest } 4... cxd4 5. exd4 { and then } 5... d5 { , entering the Panov Attack. However, the resulting positions seem a bit passive to me. Instead, the text move is very natural. We are just fighting for the centre. } ) 5. Nc3 { White is not yet defining the pawn structure. } 5... a6 ( { This is a useful move. Our plan is to take ...dxc4 and follow up with ...b5. We also avoid an unpleasant check on b5. } 5... dxc4 6. Bxc4 a6 { is interesting as well, when the game enters a Queen's Gambit Accepted where White played has played a quick Nc3 which should  favour Black. } ) 6. a3 { White goes for symmetry. } 6... dxc4 { We continue with our plan. } 7. Bxc4 b5 8. Ba2 { It makes sense for White to put the bishop here since he has played a3. } 8... Bb7 9. O-O Nbd7 { It's more flexible to develop the queenside first. } 10. e4 { An attempt to do something quickly by opening up the centre. This has not been played very often. } 10... cxd4 11. Nxd4 Bc5 ( { Going for a quick castling. } 11... Ne5 { also deserves attention. } ) 12. Be3 O-O 13. f3 { White has managed to lock down our light-squared bishop. } 13... Ne5 { A good square for the knight. } 14. Kh1 Qe7 { Followed by bringing the rooks to the d- and c-files, with a good position for Black. } *

