1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. e3 { White avoids the Benoni, and just wants to get a normal game by developing their pieces. } 4... d5 ( { We reach a symmetrical position. I was considering also to suggest } 4... cxd4 5. exd4 { and then } 5... d5 { , entering the Panov Attack. However, the resulting positions seem a bit passive to me. Instead, the text move is very natural. We are just fighting for the centre. } ) 5. Nc3 { White is not yet defining the pawn structure. } 5... a6 ( { This is a useful move. Our plan is to take ...dxc4 and follow up with ...b5. We also avoid an unpleasant check on b5. } 5... dxc4 6. Bxc4 a6 { is interesting as well, when the game enters a Queen's Gambit Accepted where White played has played a quick Nc3 which should  favour Black. } ) 6. cxd5 exd5 { We’ve managed to avoid the check on b5 at the expense of a tempo. } 7. g3 { An ambitious move. White wants to fianchetto his bishop and put pressure on the d5-pawn. } 7... Nc6 { The knight is well-placed here. } 8. Bg2 c4 { We gain more space on the queenside. This works because we are ready to support the c4-pawn with ...b5. } 9. Ne5 Bb4 { We avoid b3 and keep open the option of taking on c3 at the right moment. } 10. O-O O-O { Transposing to 9. O-O Bb4 10. Ne5 O-O. } *

