1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. e3 { White avoids the Benoni, and just wants to get a normal game by developing their pieces. } 4... d5 ( { We reach a symmetrical position. I was considering also to suggest } 4... cxd4 5. exd4 { and then } 5... d5 { , entering the Panov Attack. However, the resulting positions seem a bit passive to me. Instead, the text move is very natural. We are just fighting for the centre. } ) 5. Nc3 { White is not yet defining the pawn structure. } 5... a6 ( { This is a useful move. Our plan is to take ...dxc4 and follow up with ...b5. We also avoid an unpleasant check on b5. } 5... dxc4 6. Bxc4 a6 { is interesting as well, when the game enters a Queen's Gambit Accepted where White played has played a quick Nc3 which should  favour Black. } ) 6. cxd5 exd5 { We’ve managed to avoid the check on b5 at the expense of a tempo. } 7. g3 { An ambitious move. White wants to fianchetto his bishop and put pressure on the d5-pawn. } 7... Nc6 { The knight is well-placed here. } 8. Bg2 c4 { We gain more space on the queenside. This works because we are ready to support the c4-pawn with ...b5. } 9. O-O Bb4 { The right place for the bishop. We avoid the possibility of White playing b3, and keep the option to take on c3 at the right moment. } 10. Ne5 O-O 11. Bd2 Re8 { Forcing the exchange of the central e5-knight. } 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. b3 { The is White’s typical way of fighting against the black pawn chain. } 13... Bxc3 ( { This is the most direct – we want to follow up with ...Ne4. } 13... a5 { is also good. } ) 14. Bxc3 Ne4 15. Rc1 a5 { A nice way to bring the bishop into play. } 16. bxc4 Ba6 { We want to take back on c4 with the bishop. } 17. f3 Nxc3 18. Rxc3 Bxc4 19. Rf2 h5 { Black keeps a slight initiative. } ( { This was played in 0-1 (38) Carlsen, M (2862)-Dubov, D (2702) chess24.com INT 2020. Now instead of Dubov’s } 19... Qg5 { , I think it is better to play the immediate } ) *

