1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. e3 { White avoids the Benoni, and just wants to get a normal game by developing their pieces. } 4... d5 ( { We reach a symmetrical position. I was considering also to suggest } 4... cxd4 5. exd4 { and then } 5... d5 { , entering the Panov Attack. However, the resulting positions seem a bit passive to me. Instead, the text move is very natural. We are just fighting for the centre. } ) 5. Nc3 { White is not yet defining the pawn structure. } 5... a6 ( { This is a useful move. Our plan is to take ...dxc4 and follow up with ...b5. We also avoid an unpleasant check on b5. } 5... dxc4 6. Bxc4 a6 { is interesting as well, when the game enters a Queen's Gambit Accepted where White played has played a quick Nc3 which should  favour Black. } ) 6. cxd5 exd5 { We’ve managed to avoid the check on b5 at the expense of a tempo. } 7. Be2 cxd4 ( { By going for the exchange right now we get an improved version in case White replies exd4. That being said, in most of the games that reached this position Black played } 7... Nc6 { first. } ) 8. exd4 h6 { The idea is to avoid the pin with Bg5 and to play the more active Bd6. } 9. O-O Bd6 { We're just in time to castle and avoid a check on e1. } 10. Ne5 O-O 11. f4 { It's interesting to support the knight on e5 like this, but Black has his own play. } 11... Nc6 12. Be3 Ne7 { We can push ...b5 and ...Bb7 and fight for the e4-square. } *

