1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. e3 { White avoids the Benoni, and just wants to get a normal game by developing their pieces. } 4... d5 ( { We reach a symmetrical position. I was considering also to suggest } 4... cxd4 5. exd4 { and then } 5... d5 { , entering the Panov Attack. However, the resulting positions seem a bit passive to me. Instead, the text move is very natural. We are just fighting for the centre. } ) 5. Nc3 { White is not yet defining the pawn structure. } 5... a6 ( { This is a useful move. Our plan is to take ...dxc4 and follow up with ...b5. We also avoid an unpleasant check on b5. } 5... dxc4 6. Bxc4 a6 { is interesting as well, when the game enters a Queen's Gambit Accepted where White played has played a quick Nc3 which should  favour Black. } ) 6. cxd5 exd5 { We’ve managed to avoid the check on b5 at the expense of a tempo. } 7. Be2 cxd4 ( { By going for the exchange right now we get an improved version in case White replies exd4. That being said, in most of the games that reached this position Black played } 7... Nc6 { first. } ) 8. Nxd4 { White decides to play against the isolani. } 8... Nc6 ( { This looks good now. I prefer this to } 8... Bd6 { because in that case White could play } 9. b3 { and fianchetto the bishop to b2. After 8... Nc6 this would run into ...Bb4, ...Ne4 and ...Qa5. } ) 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. e4 { An early attempt to break in the centre. } 10... Bd6 { The best way to handle the opening of the centre is to castle quickly. } 11. exd5 cxd5 12. Bf3 O-O { White cannot really afford to take the d5-pawn. } 13. O-O Be6 { Defending the d5-pawn. } 14. Be3 Qb8 { With some kind of double attack, although we cannot really take the b2-pawn because of Bd4. } 15. g3 Be5 { The best place for the bishop. } 16. Na4 Re8 { We can go for ...Qb5 next. The position is playable for both sides. } *

