1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. e3 { White avoids the Benoni, and just wants to get a normal game by developing their pieces. } 4... d5 ( { We reach a symmetrical position. I was considering also to suggest } 4... cxd4 5. exd4 { and then } 5... d5 { , entering the Panov Attack. However, the resulting positions seem a bit passive to me. Instead, the text move is very natural. We are just fighting for the centre. } ) 5. a3 { White improves the position a little bit. } 5... dxc4 { I think this is a good solution. We'll go for some Queen's Gambit Accepted positions in which White has played an early a3. } 6. Bxc4 a6 7. dxc5 { Doesn't achieve anything. } ( { Preparing to gain a tempo with ...b5. It's funny that now in some games White has continued } 7. a4 { in order to prevent ...b5. Well, with an extra tempo Black shouldn't have any problems after for example } 7... Nc6 { . } ) 7... Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 Bxc5 { The ending is about equal, but of course there is plenty of play ahead. } *

