1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. e3 { White avoids the Benoni, and just wants to get a normal game by developing their pieces. } 4... d5 ( { We reach a symmetrical position. I was considering also to suggest } 4... cxd4 5. exd4 { and then } 5... d5 { , entering the Panov Attack. However, the resulting positions seem a bit passive to me. Instead, the text move is very natural. We are just fighting for the centre. } ) 5. a3 { White improves the position a little bit. } 5... dxc4 { I think this is a good solution. We'll go for some Queen's Gambit Accepted positions in which White has played an early a3. } 6. Bxc4 a6 7. O-O ( { Preparing to gain a tempo with ...b5. It's funny that now in some games White has continued } 7. a4 { in order to prevent ...b5. Well, with an extra tempo Black shouldn't have any problems after for example } 7... Nc6 { . } ) 7... b5 ( { I see no reason to delay this move. } 7... Nbd7 { could be interesting, but then after } 8. a4 { the knight is slightly misplaced. } ) 8. Be2 { White is preparing a4. } 8... Nbd7 { To avoid the queens exchange. } 9. a4 b4 { Only like this. } 10. Nbd2 { White is trying to establish a hold on the light squares. } 10... Bb7 11. b3 Be7 { We continue with normal development. } 12. Bb2 O-O 13. Nc4 cxd4 { Not the only move, but a solid choice. } 14. Bxd4 Nd5 { This was the point of our previous move. } 15. Rc1 Rc8 { With an equal game. Black has various ideas, which include ...Bf6, ...Nc5 and ...Rc7. } *

