1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. e3 { White avoids the Benoni, and just wants to get a normal game by developing their pieces. } 4... d5 ( { We reach a symmetrical position. I was considering also to suggest } 4... cxd4 5. exd4 { and then } 5... d5 { , entering the Panov Attack. However, the resulting positions seem a bit passive to me. Instead, the text move is very natural. We are just fighting for the centre. } ) 5. a3 { White improves the position a little bit. } 5... dxc4 { I think this is a good solution. We'll go for some Queen's Gambit Accepted positions in which White has played an early a3. } 6. Bxc4 a6 7. O-O ( { Preparing to gain a tempo with ...b5. It's funny that now in some games White has continued } 7. a4 { in order to prevent ...b5. Well, with an extra tempo Black shouldn't have any problems after for example } 7... Nc6 { . } ) 7... b5 ( { I see no reason to delay this move. } 7... Nbd7 { could be interesting, but then after } 8. a4 { the knight is slightly misplaced. } ) 8. Bd3 { The most active square for the bishop in the plan with a4. } 8... Bb7 { Now it's not possible for White to exchange the queens. We should delay ...Nbd7 because after a future a4 ...b4 the knight is better placed on c6. } 9. a4 { Even though it loses a tempo, this is still the most dangerous plan for White. } 9... b4 10. Nbd2 Be7 { As I mentioned before, the b8-knight may be better off on c6. } 11. Nc4 O-O 12. a5 Nc6 { The knight is better here than on d7 as it attacks both the a5- and d4-pawns. } 13. Qe2 Qc7 { And then we can bring a rook to d8 with a good position. } *

