1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. e3 { White avoids the Benoni, and just wants to get a normal game by developing their pieces. } 4... d5 ( { We reach a symmetrical position. I was considering also to suggest } 4... cxd4 5. exd4 { and then } 5... d5 { , entering the Panov Attack. However, the resulting positions seem a bit passive to me. Instead, the text move is very natural. We are just fighting for the centre. } ) 5. cxd5 exd5 { In return for the isolated pawn we get good control in the centre. } 6. Bb5+ { This is White’s most testing move. } 6... Nc6 { I've analysed this position for a long time, and looked for the best alternatives for Black. Every reply has its pros and cons, but developing the knight to c6 looks like the most natural move to me. } 7. Qc2 { An early attempt to put pressure on the c-file. However, it's not really justified. } 7... Qb6 { From b6 the black queen protects everything. } 8. Nc3 Bd6 { With a lot of play ahead. I think the inclusion of Qc2 and ...Qb6 slightly favours Black. } *

