1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. e3 { White avoids the Benoni, and just wants to get a normal game by developing their pieces. } 4... d5 ( { We reach a symmetrical position. I was considering also to suggest } 4... cxd4 5. exd4 { and then } 5... d5 { , entering the Panov Attack. However, the resulting positions seem a bit passive to me. Instead, the text move is very natural. We are just fighting for the centre. } ) 5. cxd5 exd5 { In return for the isolated pawn we get good control in the centre. } 6. Bb5+ { This is White’s most testing move. } 6... Nc6 { I've analysed this position for a long time, and looked for the best alternatives for Black. Every reply has its pros and cons, but developing the knight to c6 looks like the most natural move to me. } 7. Nc3 cxd4 { We continue in the same way as in the main line 7. O-O. } 8. exd4 Bd6 ( { This is even more ambitious than } 8... Be7 { which would most likely transpose to the lines with 7. O-O. Here we are in time to castle, as White doesn't get Re1+ with check. } ) 9. Bg5 { An early pin, even before castling. } 9... O-O { We're not afraid of the pin. } 10. Bxf6 { Gives up the bishop too easily. } 10... Qxf6 11. Nxd5 Re8+ { White keeps the pawn, but he's under a lot of pressure. } *

