1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. e3 { White avoids the Benoni, and just wants to get a normal game by developing their pieces. } 4... d5 ( { We reach a symmetrical position. I was considering also to suggest } 4... cxd4 5. exd4 { and then } 5... d5 { , entering the Panov Attack. However, the resulting positions seem a bit passive to me. Instead, the text move is very natural. We are just fighting for the centre. } ) 5. cxd5 exd5 { In return for the isolated pawn we get good control in the centre. } 6. Bb5+ { This is White’s most testing move. } 6... Nc6 { I've analysed this position for a long time, and looked for the best alternatives for Black. Every reply has its pros and cons, but developing the knight to c6 looks like the most natural move to me. } 7. Nc3 cxd4 { We continue in the same way as in the main line 7. O-O. } 8. exd4 Bd6 ( { This is even more ambitious than } 8... Be7 { which would most likely transpose to the lines with 7. O-O. Here we are in time to castle, as White doesn't get Re1+ with check. } ) 9. O-O O-O { We're just in time to avoid Re1 with check. } 10. Bg5 Bg4 { Of course, we also go for the pin. } 11. Be2 { This is a good decision by White. } 11... Re8 { It seems to me that Black shouldn't have any problems. However, it's good to be precise, as the position can be tricky. } 12. h3 { White may consider to take on d5 next as the h2-pawn is not hanging. } 12... Bxf3 { By exchanging the knight we can increase the pressure on the d4-pawn. } 13. Bxf3 h6 { This is the idea. We need to get rid of the pin. } 14. Bh4 g5 { We weaken the king a bit, but get rid of the pin. } 15. Bg3 Bxg3 { It's good to exchange the bishop as we release some tension from the position. } 16. fxg3 Qd6 { We need to bring our rooks into play. It’s important to note that White cannot make good use of the open f-file. } *

