1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. e3 { White avoids the Benoni, and just wants to get a normal game by developing their pieces. } 4... d5 ( { We reach a symmetrical position. I was considering also to suggest } 4... cxd4 5. exd4 { and then } 5... d5 { , entering the Panov Attack. However, the resulting positions seem a bit passive to me. Instead, the text move is very natural. We are just fighting for the centre. } ) 5. cxd5 exd5 { In return for the isolated pawn we get good control in the centre. } 6. Bb5+ { This is White’s most testing move. } 6... Nc6 { I've analysed this position for a long time, and looked for the best alternatives for Black. Every reply has its pros and cons, but developing the knight to c6 looks like the most natural move to me. } 7. O-O { This is best, and also the most flexible. } 7... cxd4 ( { I prefer to clarify the pawn structure early on. } 7... Bd6 { is an alternative, however. } ) 8. Nxd4 { This is more ambitious. White gives us an isolated pawn. } 8... Bd7 ( { We address the pin. } 8... Qc7 { deserves attention as well. } ) 9. b3 { White keeps the option open of developing the knight to d2. } 9... Bd6 { The bishop is best placed on d6. } 10. Bb2 O-O 11. Nd2 { With the knight on d2 White has better control over the d4-square, but it's not attacking d5 anymore. } 11... Re8 { The isolated pawn gives us a good position with so many pieces on the board. A typical plan is to bring the other rook to c8, play ...Qe7 and then try to create some threats on the kingside. } 12. Rc1 Rc8 13. N2f3 Qe7 { We may consider a knight jump to e4 on the next moves. } 14. Qe2 { This position was reached in ½-½ (59) So,W (2822)-Radjabov,T (2710) Shamkir 2017. } 14... Ne4 ( { I recommend this move instead of Radjabov’s } 14... Bb8 { The knight is doing great on e4. We have a middlegame position with chances for both sides. } ) *

