1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. e3 { White avoids the Benoni, and just wants to get a normal game by developing their pieces. } 4... d5 ( { We reach a symmetrical position. I was considering also to suggest } 4... cxd4 5. exd4 { and then } 5... d5 { , entering the Panov Attack. However, the resulting positions seem a bit passive to me. Instead, the text move is very natural. We are just fighting for the centre. } ) 5. cxd5 exd5 { In return for the isolated pawn we get good control in the centre. } 6. Bb5+ { This is White’s most testing move. } 6... Nc6 { I've analysed this position for a long time, and looked for the best alternatives for Black. Every reply has its pros and cons, but developing the knight to c6 looks like the most natural move to me. } 7. O-O { This is best, and also the most flexible. } 7... cxd4 ( { I prefer to clarify the pawn structure early on. } 7... Bd6 { is an alternative, however. } ) 8. Nxd4 { This is more ambitious. White gives us an isolated pawn. } 8... Bd7 ( { We address the pin. } 8... Qc7 { deserves attention as well. } ) 9. Nc3 { The knight is actively placed on c3 and attacks the d5-pawn. } 9... Bd6 { Our bishop is strongly positioned on d6. } 10. e4 { An immediate break in the centre! It works because we haven't castled yet. } 10... Nxe4 ( { Beginning a sequence of forced moves. } 10... dxe4 { is just as strong. } ) 11. Nxd5 O-O { Bringing the king to safety just in time. } *

