1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. e3 { White avoids the Benoni, and just wants to get a normal game by developing their pieces. } 4... d5 ( { We reach a symmetrical position. I was considering also to suggest } 4... cxd4 5. exd4 { and then } 5... d5 { , entering the Panov Attack. However, the resulting positions seem a bit passive to me. Instead, the text move is very natural. We are just fighting for the centre. } ) 5. cxd5 exd5 { In return for the isolated pawn we get good control in the centre. } 6. Bb5+ { This is White’s most testing move. } 6... Nc6 { I've analysed this position for a long time, and looked for the best alternatives for Black. Every reply has its pros and cons, but developing the knight to c6 looks like the most natural move to me. } 7. O-O { This is best, and also the most flexible. } 7... cxd4 ( { I prefer to clarify the pawn structure early on. } 7... Bd6 { is an alternative, however. } ) 8. Nxd4 { This is more ambitious. White gives us an isolated pawn. } 8... Bd7 ( { We address the pin. } 8... Qc7 { deserves attention as well. } ) 9. Nc3 { The knight is actively placed on c3 and attacks the d5-pawn. } 9... Bd6 { Our bishop is strongly positioned on d6. } 10. e4 { An immediate break in the centre! It works because we haven't castled yet. } 10... Nxe4 ( { Beginning a sequence of forced moves. } 10... dxe4 { is just as strong. } ) 11. Nxc6 Bxc6 { Only like this. } 12. Qxd5 { Yes, this is possible! } 12... O-O { The point. Once we have castled our position looks good. } 13. Bxc6 Nxc3 { A necessary in-between move. } 14. Qf3 bxc6 15. Qxc3 Qc7 { It's time to take stock of what has happened. We have a slightly worse pawn structure on the queenside, but we do have a lead in development. } 16. g3 Be5 { It's a good idea to centralize this bishop. } 17. Qc2 Bd4 { A multi-purpose bishop! } 18. Bd2 c5 { We secure the bishop on its nice square. } 19. Bc3 Qb6 { We need to avoid the pin on the c-file. } 20. Rfe1 { A correspondence game ended in a draw in this position. } 20... Rad8 { Followed by ...Rfe8 or ...h5 with an equal game. } *

