1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. e3 { White avoids the Benoni, and just wants to get a normal game by developing their pieces. } 4... d5 ( { We reach a symmetrical position. I was considering also to suggest } 4... cxd4 5. exd4 { and then } 5... d5 { , entering the Panov Attack. However, the resulting positions seem a bit passive to me. Instead, the text move is very natural. We are just fighting for the centre. } ) 5. cxd5 exd5 { In return for the isolated pawn we get good control in the centre. } 6. Bb5+ { This is White’s most testing move. } 6... Nc6 { I've analysed this position for a long time, and looked for the best alternatives for Black. Every reply has its pros and cons, but developing the knight to c6 looks like the most natural move to me. } 7. O-O { This is best, and also the most flexible. } 7... cxd4 ( { I prefer to clarify the pawn structure early on. } 7... Bd6 { is an alternative, however. } ) 8. Nxd4 { This is more ambitious. White gives us an isolated pawn. } 8... Bd7 ( { We address the pin. } 8... Qc7 { deserves attention as well. } ) 9. Nc3 { The knight is actively placed on c3 and attacks the d5-pawn. } 9... Bd6 { Our bishop is strongly positioned on d6. } 10. Nf3 { Aiming at the d5-pawn. } 10... Bg4 { A good moment to activate the bishop while at the same time defending the d5-pawn. } 11. h3 Bh5 { Keeping the pressure on the f3-knight. } 12. Be2 { White has to take care of the pin sooner or later. } 12... O-O 13. b3 { White completes their development and later on hopes to take advantage of the isolated pawn. } 13... a6 { I have some experience with this position. My conclusion was that this little move is very useful. } 14. Bb2 Re8 { The rook belongs on e8. } 15. Rc1 Bc7 { Obviously preparing ...Qd6. } 16. Ba3 { No ...Qd6 please! } 16... Bg6 { Since White has neutralized the pin on the f3-knight, our  bishop is more active on g6. } 17. Bd3 Ne4 { With the idea to take on c3 and play ...Be4. Black had a good position in the correspondence game 