1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. e3 { White avoids the Benoni, and just wants to get a normal game by developing their pieces. } 4... d5 ( { We reach a symmetrical position. I was considering also to suggest } 4... cxd4 5. exd4 { and then } 5... d5 { , entering the Panov Attack. However, the resulting positions seem a bit passive to me. Instead, the text move is very natural. We are just fighting for the centre. } ) 5. cxd5 exd5 { In return for the isolated pawn we get good control in the centre. } 6. Bb5+ { This is White’s most testing move. } 6... Nc6 { I've analysed this position for a long time, and looked for the best alternatives for Black. Every reply has its pros and cons, but developing the knight to c6 looks like the most natural move to me. } 7. O-O { This is best, and also the most flexible. } 7... cxd4 ( { I prefer to clarify the pawn structure early on. } 7... Bd6 { is an alternative, however. } ) 8. Nxd4 { This is more ambitious. White gives us an isolated pawn. } 8... Bd7 ( { We address the pin. } 8... Qc7 { deserves attention as well. } ) 9. Nc3 { The knight is actively placed on c3 and attacks the d5-pawn. } 9... Bd6 { Our bishop is strongly positioned on d6. } 10. Nf3 { Aiming at the d5-pawn. } 10... Bg4 { A good moment to activate the bishop while at the same time defending the d5-pawn. } 11. h3 Bh5 { Keeping the pressure on the f3-knight. } 12. Be2 { White has to take care of the pin sooner or later. } 12... O-O 13. b3 { White completes their development and later on hopes to take advantage of the isolated pawn. } 13... Qa5 { This is an original move played by Grischuk. The idea is to continue ...Rad8 while keeping the queen actively positioned. } 14. Bb2 Rad8 15. Nd4 { Understandably, White wants to exchange some pieces. } 15... Nxd4 16. Qxd4 Bc5 { Followed by ...d4 with an equal position. } *

