[Black "4. Bd3 c5 5. O-O #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 { The Colle System. White is building up the position slowly, and is going for a setup with Bd3, b3 and Bb2. This system is popular in blitz and rapid even among top players. Although it's not so ambitious, White develops all the pieces to good squares and gets a playable position. } 3... d5 ( { As much as I prefer to avoid symmetry, this seems more natural to me than } 3... c5 { . } ) 4. Bd3 c5 ( { We can fight for the centre straight away. A good alternative is } 4... Bd6 { , but that is too symmetrical for me! } ) 5. O-O c4 { We can take advantage of this move order by expanding on the queenside. } 6. Be2 b5 { Continuing our expansion. } 7. b3 Bb7 8. a4 ( { Defending the a8-rook so that we can meet } 8. a4 { with } 8... a6 { . } ) 8... a6 9. c3 { A typical maneuver. White plans to exchange his dark-squared bishop via a3. } 9... Nbd7 ( { Where to develop the knight is a matter of taste in this position. } 9... Nc6 { is fine as well. } ) 10. Nbd2 Be7 { It's time to finish our  development! } 11. Ba3 O-O 12. Qc1 Bxa3 { Sooner or later we have to make this exchange anyway. } 13. Rxa3 Qc7 { With an equal position. We have some space advantage on the queenside, but White has managed to exchange their bad dark-squared bishop. } *

