1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 { The Colle System. White is building up the position slowly, and is going for a setup with Bd3, b3 and Bb2. This system is popular in blitz and rapid even among top players. Although it's not so ambitious, White develops all the pieces to good squares and gets a playable position. } 3... d5 ( { As much as I prefer to avoid symmetry, this seems more natural to me than } 3... c5 { . } ) 4. Bd3 c5 ( { We can fight for the centre straight away. A good alternative is } 4... Bd6 { , but that is too symmetrical for me! } ) 5. O-O c4 { We can take advantage of this move order by expanding on the queenside. } 6. Be2 b5 { Continuing our expansion. } 7. b3 Bb7 8. Nc3 { No risk, no gain. I would say that this move is rather dubious, but White has been successful with it in practical play. } ( { Defending the a8-rook so that we can meet } 8. a4 { with } 8... a6 { . } ) 8... b4 ( { This move is begging to be played! The more cautious } 8... a6 { is also possible. } ) 9. Na4 c3 { We get a nice grip on the queenside, but White will try to open up the position at all costs. } 10. a3 { It is useful for White to include this move. } 10... a5 { We need to keep the pawn chain intact. } 11. Ne5 { Until here it we’ve been following 1-0 (52) Artemiev,V (2716)-Dominguez Perez,L (2758) chess24.com INT 2020. } 11... Qc7 ( { This is my improvement over Dominguez’s } 11... Nbd7 { Playing the queen to c7 allows us to parry the check on b5 with ...Nc6. } ) 12. Bb5+ Nc6 ( { The knight is much better here than on d7. In case of } 12... Nbd7 { the f6-knight would have been overloaded after } 13. e4 { . } ) 13. e4 Nxe4 { Now this move is available to us. } 14. Qg4 h5 { Driving the queen away from her active square. We can follow up with ...Bd6. Black is clearly better. } *

