[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 { The Colle System. White is building up the position slowly, and is going for a setup with Bd3, b3 and Bb2. This system is popular in blitz and rapid even among top players. Although it's not so ambitious, White develops all the pieces to good squares and gets a playable position. } 3... d5 ( { As much as I prefer to avoid symmetry, this seems more natural to me than } 3... c5 { . } ) 4. Bd3 c5 ( { We can fight for the centre straight away. A good alternative is } 4... Bd6 { , but that is too symmetrical for me! } ) 5. b3 { Preventing ...c4 and getting ready to fianchetto the bishop. } 5... b6 ( { We need to solve the problem of our light-squared bishop. } 5... Nc6 { followed by ...b6 and ... Bb7 should lead to the same thing. } ) 6. Bb2 Bb7 7. O-O Nc6 { This is the setup I recommend: ...Nc6, ...Be7 and ...O-O. Afterwards we can act depending on what White does. } 8. c4 { White opens up the centre as well. } 8... cxd4 { In order to avoid the aforementioned hanging pawns. } 9. exd4 { The only way for White to fight for an advantage. } 9... Be7 { Preparing to castle. It's not a good idea to open the position with the king still in the centre. } 10. Nc3 { Allowing mass simplifications. } 10... dxc4 ( { This leads to equality. Alternatively we can play } 10... O-O { or } ) ( 10... Nb4 { if we want to keep the game going. } ) 11. Bxc4 { The only move, as otherwise the d4-pawn falls. } 11... O-O { This isolated pawn position is not good for White in the long run, because the bishop on b2 is misplaced. } 12. d5 { Leading to further simplifications. } 12... Na5 ( { Trying to create some imbalance. } 12... exd5 { is an easy path to equality. For example, } 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. Qxd5 Na5 15. Qxd8 Rfxd8 16. Be2 Rac8 { eventually led to a draw in ½-½ (42) Franco Ocampos, Z (2490)-Karpov, A (2780) Córdoba 1995. } ) 13. dxe6 Nxc4 { The pair of bishops and the better structure will give us enough compensation for the pawn. } 14. exf7+ Rxf7 15. bxc4 Qxd1 { The easiest. This way we'll be able to spoil White's pawn structure even more. } 16. Raxd1 Bxf3 17. gxf3 Rc8 { With a pleasant ending for Black. } *

