1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 { The Colle System. White is building up the position slowly, and is going for a setup with Bd3, b3 and Bb2. This system is popular in blitz and rapid even among top players. Although it's not so ambitious, White develops all the pieces to good squares and gets a playable position. } 3... d5 ( { As much as I prefer to avoid symmetry, this seems more natural to me than } 3... c5 { . } ) 4. Bd3 c5 ( { We can fight for the centre straight away. A good alternative is } 4... Bd6 { , but that is too symmetrical for me! } ) 5. b3 { Preventing ...c4 and getting ready to fianchetto the bishop. } 5... b6 ( { We need to solve the problem of our light-squared bishop. } 5... Nc6 { followed by ...b6 and ... Bb7 should lead to the same thing. } ) 6. Bb2 Bb7 7. O-O Nc6 { This is the setup I recommend: ...Nc6, ...Be7 and ...O-O. Afterwards we can act depending on what White does. } 8. c4 { White opens up the centre as well. } 8... cxd4 { In order to avoid the aforementioned hanging pawns. } 9. exd4 { The only way for White to fight for an advantage. } 9... Be7 { Preparing to castle. It's not a good idea to open the position with the king still in the centre. } 10. Nbd2 Nb4 ( { This seems interesting. We want to force White to play a3. There is nothing wrong with } 10... O-O { either. } ) 11. Bb1 O-O 12. a3 { White cannot do without this move. } 12... Nc6 13. Bd3 { White's plan is to play Qe2, Rc1 and then prepare the advance c5. The a3-pawn could be useful for this purpose. } 13... Rc8 14. Qe2 Bd6 { With the idea to maneuver the knight to e7 and g6. White's rook is not yet on c1, so he cannot play c5. } 15. Rac1 Ne7 16. Ne5 { White takes the opportunity to place the knight in the centre. } 16... Ng6 17. f4 a5 { Preventing b4. Then we can play ...Qe7 and attack the a3-pawn. Both sides have their chances in this position. } *

