1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 { The Colle System. White is building up the position slowly, and is going for a setup with Bd3, b3 and Bb2. This system is popular in blitz and rapid even among top players. Although it's not so ambitious, White develops all the pieces to good squares and gets a playable position. } 3... d5 ( { As much as I prefer to avoid symmetry, this seems more natural to me than } 3... c5 { . } ) 4. Bd3 c5 ( { We can fight for the centre straight away. A good alternative is } 4... Bd6 { , but that is too symmetrical for me! } ) 5. b3 { Preventing ...c4 and getting ready to fianchetto the bishop. } 5... b6 ( { We need to solve the problem of our light-squared bishop. } 5... Nc6 { followed by ...b6 and ... Bb7 should lead to the same thing. } ) 6. Bb2 Bb7 7. O-O Nc6 { This is the setup I recommend: ...Nc6, ...Be7 and ...O-O. Afterwards we can act depending on what White does. } 8. Nbd2 Be7 ( { I prefer the bishop on e7, although } 8... Bd6 { is also good. } ) 9. dxc5 bxc5 { Since we have already played ...Be7, it's better to retake with the pawn this time. } 10. Qe2 O-O { White has to take into account ideas like ...Nb4 or ...a5. } *

