1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. Nxd5 { This move is rather popular at a club level. } 5... Nxd5 { I think it's good for Black to exchange one pair of knights so that we won't have space problems. } 6. Qxd5 { The queen is not well suited to occupy the d5-square. } 6... d6 { Followed by ...Nc6 and ...Be6, driving away the white queen. } ( 6... Nc6 { amounts to the same thing. } ) 7. Nf3 Nc6 { We need to make sure White can’t take the b7-pawn before playing ...Be6. } 8. Bd2 { White tries to bring the bishop to c3 to put pressure on the long diagonal. } ( { In case of } 8. e4 Be6 9. Qd3 Be7 { followed by ...Bf6 White has problems on the dark squares. } ) 8... Be6 ( { This comes with tempo, so why not play it? However, } 8... Be7 { with the idea to castle is also good. } ) 9. Qd3 d5 ( { After this central break the position is equal, but Black has a slight initiative. There is also nothing wrong with } 9... Be7 { followed by castling. } ) *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Modern Benoni"]
