1. d4 Nf6 2. g4 { White plays an early gambit. It seems this move has many names, among them being the Bronstein Gambit and the Humphrey Bogart Gambit. GM Simon Williams who has also played 2. g4 called it the Kilkenny Gambit. Whatever its name, this doesn't seem like a sound gambit, but rather an attempt to confuse the opponent as soon as move 2. } 2... Nxg4 { I guess we have to accept the challenge. } 3. e4 d5 { I like this move because we immediately get a foothold in the centre. } 4. e5 c5 { This is easy to play for Black. White’s pawn sacrifice seems unjustified. } *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Modern Benoni"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch 19: Other Early Deviations"]
[Black "2. g4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. g4 { White plays an early gambit. It seems this move has many names, among them being the Bronstein Gambit and the Humphrey Bogart Gambit. GM Simon Williams who has also played 2. g4 called it the Kilkenny Gambit. Whatever its name, this doesn't seem like a sound gambit, but rather an attempt to confuse the opponent as soon as move 2. } 2... Nxg4 { I guess we have to accept the challenge. } 3. e4 d5 { I like this move because we immediately get a foothold in the centre. } 4. Be2 { This is White's idea. } 4... Qd7 { Let me suggest this move. According to my database it's a novelty. The point is that in case of e5 Black can play ...b6 and ...Ba6 in order to exchange the light-squared bishop, analogous to some lines in the French Defense. } 5. e5 h5 { Preparing the knight retreat to h6. } 6. h3 Nh6 7. Bxh5 c5 { White has regained the pawn, but their position is falling apart. Black has a lead in development and White's kingside is very weak. Black's h6-knight will have a wonderful square on f5. } *

