1. d4 Nf6 2. g4 { White plays an early gambit. It seems this move has many names, among them being the Bronstein Gambit and the Humphrey Bogart Gambit. GM Simon Williams who has also played 2. g4 called it the Kilkenny Gambit. Whatever its name, this doesn't seem like a sound gambit, but rather an attempt to confuse the opponent as soon as move 2. } 2... Nxg4 { I guess we have to accept the challenge. } 3. e4 d5 { I like this move because we immediately get a foothold in the centre. } 4. Be2 { This is White's idea. } 4... Qd7 { Let me suggest this move. According to my database it's a novelty. The point is that in case of e5 Black can play ...b6 and ...Ba6 in order to exchange the light-squared bishop, analogous to some lines in the French Defense. } 5. exd5 Qxd5 { The h1-rook is hanging, so White cannot take our knight. } 6. Nf3 g6 { After we fianchetto the bishop, our king will be safe. } 7. Nc3 Qf5 { A nice square for the queen. } 8. h3 Nf6 9. Ne5 { Trying to trap the queen. } 9... Ne4 { This move saves the day. } 10. f4 Nxc3 11. bxc3 Bg7 { White's compensation is not enough. } *

