1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 a6 ( { Gashimov plays a very early ...a6. Usually } 6... g6 { is preferred because the move ...g6 is part of the plan anyway, while Black might want to do without or delay ...a6. } ) 7. a4 g6 8. Bf4 { This game was played in the last round of the European Team Championship in Porto Carras. I didn't have much time to prepare and so I chose this variation which allows White to develop his pieces nicely. Vugar knew the Benoni positions very well, and although he was a bit worse at some moment, he managed to win this game convincingly. } 8... Bg7 9. h3 O-O 10. e3 Ne8 11. Be2 Nd7 ( { In the course I recommend } 11... b6 { in order to prepare ...Ne5 - see here. I think White is slightly better in the line played in the game. } ) 12. O-O Qe7 13. a5 Rb8 14. Nd2 Ne5 15. Na4 { A thematic maneuver, but not the most precise. } ( 15. Qb3 Nc7 16. Bg3 f5 17. Na4 { And in order to prevent Nxc5 Black has to play ...Kh8, which he skipped in the game. } 17... Bd7 18. Nxc5 dxc5 19. d6+ ) 15... Bd7 16. Nb6 { During the game I was quite happy to get a knight to b6, but things are not so easy. Black has access to the b5-square. } ( 16. Qb3 Nc7 17. Bg3 Bb5 18. Rfe1 ) 16... Bb5 17. Re1 f5 18. Qb3 Nc7 19. Ndc4 Nf7 ( 19... Rbd8 ) 20. Rad1 ( 20. Rab1 ) 20... Qf6 21. Bg3 Rbd8 22. Na4 ( 22. Qa3 g5 ) ( 22. f4 Rfe8 23. Bd3 ) 22... Na8 23. Nc3 Bxc4 24. Bxc4 Rb8 25. Na4 { I wanted to prevent ...b5, but now the a5-pawn becomes a target. } ( 25. Bf1 ) ( 25. Qc2 Ne5 26. Ne2 ) ( 25. f4 ) 25... Ne5 26. Bf1 { I should have prepared the defence of my a5-pawn instead. } ( 26. Ra1 Qd8 27. Nc3 b5 28. axb6 Rxb6 29. Qa2 Nxc4 30. Qxc4 Rxb2 ) ( 26. Qa2 b5 27. axb6 Nxb6 28. Bf1 Nxa4 29. Qxa4 Rxb2 30. Rb1 Rxb1 31. Rxb1 ) 26... Qd8 27. Nb6 ( { This was a good moment to start to fight for the initiative by sacrificing the a5-pawn: } 27. f4 Nd7 28. e4 Qxa5 29. e5 b5 30. Nc3 Nab6 31. Qc2 ) 27... Nxb6 28. axb6 ( 28. Qxb6 Qxb6 29. axb6 Rbc8 { Here I was worried I could lose the b6-pawn in the long run. } ) 28... Qe7 29. Bxe5 { Here comes the decisive mistake, at least from a psychological point of view. After this exchange Black gets an attack on my king and I don't have any counterplay. My dark-squared bishop is strong and I could have traded it for the knight at any moment. } ( 29. Qa3 Rbc8 30. Rc1 Nd7 31. b4 ) 29... Qxe5 30. Rb1 { A passive move which allows ...f4. } ( 30. Re2 { was called for. Apparently White can hold, but Black will push for a long time. } 30... f4 31. exf4 Qxf4 32. g3 ) 30... f4 { Of course Black opens up the position. } 31. Qc4 Qg5 ( 31... fxe3 32. Rxe3 Qf5 { would have won faster. } ) 32. exf4 Rxf4 { Black is completely winning, and Vugar realized his advantage with ease. } 33. Re4 Bd4 34. Rxf4 Qxf4 35. Qe2 Rf8 36. Kh1 Bxf2 37. Qe6+ Kg7 38. Be2 Rf6 39. Qg4 Qe5 40. Bf3 h5 41. Qc8 Rf7 42. Qe6 Qg3 43. Rf1 Bd4 44. Qe1 Qxe1 45. Rxe1 Bxb2 46. Re8 a5 47. Be2 a4 48. Ra8 a3 49. g4 hxg4 50. hxg4 Kh6 51. Bb5 Rf4 *

