1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. Bf4 Bg7 8. h3 O-O 9. e3 Qe7 ( { In the course I recommend } 9... Na6 { because it is more clear-cut - see the lines with 8. h3 and 9. e3 in chapter 5. However, } ) ( 9... Qe7 { , played in this game, is also interesting. In this game we're going to see Black's attacking resources in the Benoni. Although objectively speaking White was a bit better after the opening, Black's victory in this game seems very straightforward. } ) 10. Be2 Nbd7 11. Bh2 h6 { Black wants to play the position slowly. He keeps the option to push ...g5 at some point. I think White is slightly better because he has a nice setup, but Black can go for an attack on White’s king which should not  be underestimated. } 12. O-O Ne8 { Preparing ...f5, and also the knight can go to c7 afterwards. } 13. a4 f5 14. a5 { White gains some space on the queenside, but I'm not sure that this is necessary. Usually White goes for this only after Black plays ...a6. } ( 14. Nd2 { is a useful move, although White doesn't want to continue Nc4 yet in view of ...Ne5. } 14... Nc7 15. Qb3 b6 16. Nb5 Nxb5 17. axb5 ) 14... Nc7 15. Ra3 { An interesting plan to activate the rook. However, it's not clear that the rook will have targets. } ( 15. Re1 { followed by Nd2 was more natural. } 15... Rb8 16. Nd2 ) ( 15. Nd2 ) 15... g5 16. Nd2 Ne5 17. Kh1 ( 17. f4 gxf4 18. exf4 Nd3 19. Bg3 Nxb2 20. Qc2 ) ( { Perhaps it made more sense for White to continue his rook maneuver with } 17. Rb3 ) 17... g4 18. Rb3 ( 18. f4 { I think this move asks to be played. White has to do something on the kingside, otherwise Black is just pushing there. } 18... gxf3 19. Nxf3 Bd7 20. e4 Nxf3 21. Bxf3 Bb5 22. Re1 f4 ) 18... Na6 19. Na2 { Marin is preventing ...Nb4, but his own knight will be out of play on a2. } ( 19. f4 gxf3 20. Nxf3 Nb4 ) 19... h5 20. f4 Nf7 21. Nc4 ( { White had to open up the centre: } 21. e4 fxe4 22. hxg4 hxg4 23. Bxg4 e3 24. Nc4 Bxg4 25. Qxg4 Nh6 26. Qe6+ Qxe6 27. dxe6 Rae8 28. Rxe3 { . } ) 21... Rb8 22. hxg4 hxg4 23. Bg3 Bd7 { Now Black has easy play and the white king becomes a target. } 24. Qb1 Nc7 25. Qd3 Bf6 { Rapport prepares to take control over the h-file. } 26. Be1 ( 26. Kg1 Kg7 27. Nc3 Rh8 28. Bd1 Rh6 ) 26... Kg7 27. Kg1 Rh8 28. Nc3 Rh6 { Very logical. Black doubles the rooks on the h-file, thus increasing the pressure on the white king. } 29. Nd1 { White brings the knight to f2 in order to defend the king, but this doesn't help. } ( 29. Bd1 ) 29... Rbh8 30. Nf2 Nb5 31. Bd1 ( 31. g3 Qe8 ) 31... Kg8 32. Na3 a6 33. Nc4 Bh4 34. Nb6 Bg3 35. e4 Rh1+ { A nice finish. Forced mate follows: } 36. Nxh1 Rxh1+ 37. Kxh1 Qh4+ 38. Kg1 Qh2# *

