1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 d6 5. Nc3 exd5 6. cxd5 g6 7. Bf4 a6 8. a4 Bg7 9. h3 O-O 10. e3 Ne8 11. Be2 b6 12. e4 ( { This move is very rare. White usually castles first and only then prepares the push in the centre. That's why in the course I have only mentioned the move order } 12. O-O { - see here. } ) 12... Nd7 { Black continues with the plan to bring the knight to e5. } 13. Qd2 Ne5 14. Nxe5 dxe5 { This comes with tempo. } ( { It's not clear whether Black wants to trade the bishops with } 14... Bxe5 { since White may get an attack. } 15. Bxe5 dxe5 16. h4 Nd6 17. h5 Bd7 18. Qe3 g5 ) 15. Be3 ( 15. Bg5 f6 16. Bh4 { This way White could try to forestall ...f5 for some time, but then he wouldn't be able to push h4. } 16... Nd6 17. f3 Bd7 { . } ) 15... f5 16. f3 Nd6 17. h4 { White's plan is to push the h-pawn and start an attack. This is interesting, but let's not forget that White has already lost a tempo with h3. } 17... Bd7 ( { Opening the position would be double-edged: } 17... fxe4 18. Nxe4 Bf5 19. Bg5 Qc7 { . } ) 18. h5 f4 { Black tries to block the position in order to keep the king safe. } 19. Bf2 g5 { The blocking strategy continues. } 20. a5 { Just in time. Otherwise Black can play ...Qc7 and defend the c5-pawn. } 20... bxa5 21. Bxc5 { A natural move, White takes the pawn back, but he had a better option. } ( { It was much stronger to bring the knight into play first: } 21. Na4 g4 22. h6 Bf6 23. Nxc5 g3 24. Bg1 a4 25. Rc1 { . } ) 21... Qc7 22. Bf2 Rfb8 23. Na4 { Nyback goes for the right plan, but it feels like he has lost some tempi. } 23... g4 24. Rc1 Qd8 25. Bh4 Qe8 26. Nc5 Rb4 ( 26... Rc8 { It was more precise to keep an eye on the c5-knight. } 27. Nxd7 Qxd7 28. Rc6 Rxc6 29. dxc6 Qxc6 { . } ) 27. h6 Bxh6 { This loses an important tempo and opens up the h-file. } ( 27... Bf8 { was essential: } 28. Nxd7 Qxd7 29. Bf6 Rd4 30. Bd3 Rc8 { with a very sharp position. } ) 28. Bf6 Bg7 29. Bxg7 Kxg7 30. Nxd7 ( 30. g3 { would crown White's attack. The position opens up and Black is defenseless. } ) 30... Qxd7 31. Rc6 Nf7 ( 31... Rab8 ) 32. Qc3 Rab8 { Black has managed to stop the attack and started some counterplay on the b-file. The position is complicated. Probably both players were in time trouble as well. } 33. Rc7 ( 33. Rh4 { it was better to play this immediately. } ) 33... Qd6 34. Rh4 ( 34. Rc6 Rb3 35. Qxa5 Qb4+ 36. Qxb4 R3xb4 37. Rh5 Rxb2 38. fxg4 ) 34... Rxb2 35. Rxg4+ Kf8 36. Qxa5 { A decisive mistake in a sharp position. White loses the option to play Rc8+, which is a crucial resource in some variations. } ( 36. Bd1 { would keep White in the game. } ) 36... h5 { Very precise. Black drives the white rook off the g-file. } 37. Rh4 ( 37. Rc6 Rb1+ 38. Kd2 R8b2+ 39. Kd3 Rb3+ 40. Kd2 Ra3 ) 37... Qg6 { The black queen joins the attack, deciding the game. } 38. Qc5+ Kg8 39. Rc8+ Rxc8 40. Qxc8+ Kg7 *

