1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. Nd2 Bg7 { I chose this game to show how you can use the Benoni to play for a win against a higher rated opponent. In this game Lupulescu was worse at some point, but there were resources in the position, as he was mounting an attack on the king. One blunder was enough for White to find himself in a lost position. } 8. Nc4 O-O 9. Bf4 { A tricky line. It's White's dream to establish a knight on c4 and a bishop on f4, but here he is lagging behind in development. } 9... Ne8 { At that time it was considered that Black had to play this move. It's not a bad move, but it isn't actually  necessary to go backwards with the knight. } ( 9... Nbd7 { is what I recommend in the course - see here. If White takes the d6-pawn we get good compensation. } ) 10. e3 { Of course, White is not yet ready to play e4. } 10... b6 { A good way to activate the light-squared bishop and exchange it for the c4-knight. } 11. h3 { Alexander is making all the useful moves first. } 11... Ba6 12. a4 Qc7 { This was not necessary. } ( 12... Nd7 { deserved attention, but it's not an easy decision to sacrifice the d6-pawn. } 13. Nxd6 Bxf1 14. Kxf1 Nxd6 15. Bxd6 Re8 16. Bg3 c4 { With good compensation for the pawn. ...Nc5 and ...Rc8 are coming next. } ) ( 12... Bxc4 { This would be the more practical decision. Black can play ...Nd7 next without having to first play ...Qc7. } 13. Bxc4 Nd7 14. O-O Ne5 15. Be2 f5 { With a normal Benoni position. } ) 13. Qd2 ( 13. Nb5 { White had this extra option. After the exchange on b5 the a7-pawn may become a target. } 13... Bxb5 14. axb5 Nd7 15. Be2 Ne5 16. Nd2 { White keeps some tension in the position. } 16... f5 17. O-O Qe7 18. Ra4 { with some pressure on the a7-pawn. } ) 13... Bxc4 14. Bxc4 a6 15. O-O Nd7 16. Rfc1 ( 16. Rfe1 { The idea is to prepare e4. } 16... f5 17. e4 Ne5 18. Bf1 Qf7 19. Ra3 { The rook may be useful on the third rank once the knight moves. } ) 16... Ne5 17. Be2 Qe7 18. Rab1 g5 { Although White's attack on the queenside is more justified, Black's attack on the kingside is more dangerous! } 19. Bh2 f5 20. b4 Nf6 { The knight finally joins the game. } 21. bxc5 bxc5 22. Rb6 g4 { Constantin doesn't waste time on defending the a6-pawn. } 23. hxg4 fxg4 24. Rcb1 Nfd7 25. Rxa6 ( 25. Rb7 ) 25... Qf6 26. Bf4 Rxa6 27. Bxa6 c4 28. a5 { White has maneuvered well until now, and he has won the  a6-pawn. However, here Alexander fails to notice Black's threats. } ( 28. Rb4 { With the idea to take on c4, and most importantly on b4 the rook is not hanging anymore. } 28... Qg6 29. Ne2 { The knight will cover the king. } 29... Qd3 { Black is still in the game despite being a pawn down. } ) 28... Qg6 { Game over. It's not possible to parry the threat of ...Nf3+ because the rook on b1 is hanging. } 29. Rb7 { White tries to save the rook, but loses a bishop. } ( 29. Bg3 Nf3+ 30. gxf3 Bxc3 ) 29... Rxf4 30. Ne2 ( 30. exf4 Nf3+ { leads to checkmate or wins the queen: } 31. gxf3 gxf3+ 32. Kf1 Qg2+ 33. Ke1 Qg1# ) 30... Rf8 { Black emerges a piece up, and now it's an easy win. } 31. Rc7 Nc5 32. Bc8 c3 33. Qa2 c2 34. a6 Nf3+ 35. Kf1 Nh2+ 36. Kg1 Nf3+ 37. Kf1 Qd3 38. Rxg7+ Kxg7 39. Qb2+ Kh6 *

