1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 d6 5. Nc3 exd5 6. cxd5 g6 7. g3 Bg7 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O Re8 { In this game you can see how Gashimov skillfully maneuvers his pieces, activating them and not allowing White any counterplay. Rodshtein is an expert in the fianchetto variation for White, but he lost this game without making any obvious mistakes. } 10. Bf4 a6 ( { In the course I recommend the interesting } 10... h6 { with the idea to dislodge the bishop from f4 - see the variations with 10. Bf4. } ) 11. a4 b6 { The idea of this move is to prevent White from playing a5, and also to bring the a8 rook into play via a7 to e7. True, it's a slow plan but it can be achieved. } 12. Re1 { A useful move, Maxim is getting ready to play e4. } 12... Nh5 { It makes sense to chase away the bishop from f4. } 13. Bg5 Qc7 14. e4 Nd7 15. Rc1 { White’s idea is to prepare b2-b4 at some point. However, energetic play was called for: } ( 15. g4 Nhf6 16. e5 { White could go for drastic measures to break open the position, but are they really required? Usually White wants to improve the position slowly and get a positional grip. } 16... dxe5 17. d6 Qb8 18. Bxf6 Bxf6 19. g5 Bg7 20. Nd2 Ra7 21. Nde4 ) 15... h6 16. Bd2 Qb8 { Not only does Black remove the queen from the pin on the c-file, but he also prepares ...Ra7 and ...Re7. } 17. Bf1 { From f1 the bishop prevents ...b5. } 17... Ra7 18. b3 Nf8 { The knight makes room for the rook to come to e7. } 19. h3 Rae7 20. Qc2 g5 { Very logical. The f8-knight will get a great position on g6. } 21. Kg2 Ng6 22. Bd3 Nf6 { Both players have developed their pieces harmoniously and now the game has come to a standstill. However, it seems that while White is lacking a plan, Black can focus on preparing the ...b5 push. } 23. Rh1 Qb7 24. Rce1 Bd7 { This is it. There is no way to stop ...b5 anymore. } 25. Bc1 ( 25. Nd1 b5 26. Bc3 { It was probably better to redeploy the pieces like this. At the very least White remains in the game. } ) 25... b5 { Here it comes! } 26. axb5 axb5 27. Bb2 c4 { The pawns continue pushing! This is a nice pawn sacrifice that spoils the coordination of White's pieces. } 28. bxc4 bxc4 29. Bxc4 Bxh3+ { This is the point! } 30. Kg1 ( { It was necessary to accept the sacrifice: } 30. Rxh3 g4 31. Bb5 gxh3+ 32. Kxh3 Rc8 33. Bc6 Qb4 ) 30... Rc8 { Now the pin on the c-file is decisive. } 31. Ba2 { It's difficult to find a defence for White. } 31... Nxe4 { Game over. } 32. Rxh3 Nxc3 33. Rxe7 Nxe7 34. Bxc3 Rxc3 35. Qe4 g4 36. Qxg4 Qa6 *

