1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 { This is a popular move order for White. She avoids the Queen's Indian Defence (with ...b6) and is expecting a Catalan setup. } 3... c5 { No Catalan for you - it's going to be a Benoni. } 4. d5 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O a6 ( { In the course I recommend } 9... Re8 { because it is more flexible - see chapter 8. However, at the time I played this game, the setup with ...a6 and ...Nbd7 was fashionable, and even nowadays it's still considered a good approach. } ) 10. a4 Nbd7 11. Bf4 ( { A popular move. The other main line starts with } 11. Nd2 { . } ) 11... Qc7 ( { I've always preferred to put the queen on c7. Thus I think it's easier to get some play on the queenside, but the downside is that the queen will become exposed after White plays Rc1 and b4. } 11... Qe7 { is the alternative. } ) 12. Rc1 { Very logical. White’s plan is to push b4. } 12... Re8 ( { Of course, the rook belongs on e8, but there are alternatives like } 12... Nh5 { in order to drive the bishop away, or } ) ( 12... Qb8 { to get the queen out of the pin on the c-file. } ) 13. b4 { Nino continues with her plan. Usually in the Benoni White strives to push in the centre, but there are cases like the current one where queenside play is possible. This is no less dangerous, and can pose Black big problems. } 13... Nh5 { In the game I decided to drive away the dark-squared bishop from its active position. This is a typical maneuver, although my knight will be misplaced at the edge of the board. } ( 13... b6 { Obviously it would be good to be able to take back on c5 with the b-pawn. I rejected this because of 14. a5. } 14. a5 { This was the move that had me worried. } 14... bxa5 { is a direct approach. } 15. bxc5 Nxc5 16. Na4 { White is putting pressure on the c-file. } 16... Nfe4 17. Nd4 { The knight is heading towards c6. } 17... Qb7 18. Nxc5 dxc5 19. Nc6 { White has some initiative. Of course during the game it was difficult to assess such a line, and I preferred to steer clear of it. } ) 14. Bd2 ( 14. Be3 { would be an unfortunate retreat: } 14... Rxe3 { This exchange sacrifice begs to be played, although Black can do without it - } ( 14... Qd8 { Nhf6=∞ } ) ) 14... Qd8 { This is possible now, as the d6-pawn is not attacked anymore. } 15. Ne1 { Nino redeploys her knight to c2 or d3. She thought the b4-pawn cannot be taken because of Ne4 with a double attack. This was too optimistic, and she should have defended the b4-pawn instead. } ( 15. Qb3 { guards the pawn. } 15... Rb8 { is probably what I would have played. The idea is to push ...b5. } 16. b5 { White prevents the counterplay with ...b5, but now there is no more pressure on the c5-pawn } 16... axb5 17. Nxb5 Ndf6 { This knight is heading to e4. The position is unclear, and the game has just started. } ) 15... cxb4 { Of course I took the opportunity to grab the pawn. The position now becomes sharp, as the play opens up and White is about to regain the pawn. } 16. Ne4 { This is what White was counting on. } 16... Ndf6 { Not a bad move, but also not the best. I decided to return the pawn and activate my pieces. However, the exchange sacrifice on e4 is an obvious alternative. } ( 16... Rxe4 { looking back at the game I wonder why I didn't go for this. For the exchange I'll be able to secure the strong pawn on b4 and also gain access to the c5-square for my knight. } 17. Bxe4 a5 { I think this is simplest. In any case, it's good to keep the b4-pawn defended. } 18. Be3 Nhf6 { Sooner or later I have to bring this knight back into play. } 19. Bf3 Nb6 { Followed by ...Bd7 with a very promising position for Black. The strong b4-pawn and the active pieces give me an easy game. } ) 17. Nxf6+ Nxf6 { It's good that I’ve managed to bring the h5-knight back into play, and now it can head towards e4. } 18. Bxb4 Bg4 { I made sure to develop all my pieces, and this comes with tempo. } ( 18... Ne4 { was worth considering. The knight gets a strong position and it's not easy to drive it away. } 19. a5 b6 { Black opens up the queenside with a preferable position. } ) 19. Nf3 { White brings her knight back into play. } ( 19. Bf3 { White could have tried to swap the bishops. } 19... Bh3 { There are other good options as well. This move accepts a bishop trade, but on a more favourable square. } 20. Ng2 Ne4 21. a5 b6 { with a promising position for Black. } ) 19... Ne4 20. a5 { White is renewing the threat of Nd4. } ( { Of course this is a desirable move. I'm also preventing } 20. Nd4 { for now because of the retort } 20... Qb6 { . } ) 20... Rc8 { The fight for the c-file starts, and with this move all of my pieces are activated. } ( 20... Qd7 21. Nd4 { would allow White to come back into the game. } ) 21. Qb3 { Not the best place for the queen because it doesn't prevent ...Qd7-b5. } ( 21. Qd3 Nc5 22. Bxc5 Rxc5 23. Rxc5 dxc5 24. Qc4 Bf5 25. Nh4 Bd7 26. Qxc5 Bf8 ) ( 21. h3 Bd7 ) ( 21. Rxc8 Qxc8 22. Qb3 Bd7 { Black's position is preferable, but nothing concrete is happening yet. } ) 21... Qd7 22. Rxc8 ( 22. Rc4 { It’s not possible to fight for the c-file: } 22... Qb5 23. Rfc1 Rxc4 24. Qxc4 Rc8 25. Qxc8+ Bxc8 26. Rxc8+ Bf8 ) 22... Rxc8 23. Qd3 Bf5 { it was tempting to threaten a discovered attack with the knight. } ( 23... Nc3 { was also a good move. } 24. e4 Bxf3 25. Bxf3 Be5 { Once the d6-pawn is defended I can infiltrate with my queen into White's camp. } ) 24. Nh4 ( 24. Ne5 { would have been strong. Alas, it's not an easy move to find. } 24... Nxf2 25. Nxd7 Nxd3 26. exd3 Bxd7 27. Bxd6 Bd4+ 28. Kh1 Bc3 { with a promising endgame for Black. } ) 24... Nxf2 { Nino must have missed this. Now her position is lost. } 25. Qa3 Nh3+ 26. Kh1 Bg4 27. Bxd6 Rc3 28. Qb4 Bxe2 29. Re1 ( 29. Bxh3 Qxh3 30. Re1 Rf3 31. Qc5 Rf1+ 32. Rxf1 Qxf1+ 33. Qg1 Bf3+ 34. Nxf3 Qxf3+ 35. Qg2 Qd1+ 36. Qg1 Qxd5+ ) 29... Nf2+ 30. Kg1 Nd3 *

