1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f4 Bg7 8. e5 { This move is not so popular nowadays. White forces the black king to stay in the centre, but otherwise Black is doing fine. } ( 8. Bb5+ { is the critical main line. } ) 8... Nfd7 9. Ne4 dxe5 10. Nd6+ Ke7 11. Nxc8+ Qxc8 12. Nf3 Rd8 13. fxe5 Nxe5 14. Bg5+ Kf8 15. Bxd8 Qxd8 { In the course I analysed until arriving at this position, concluding that Black is standing very well because the white king is stuck in the centre - see variation. } 16. Be2 { White is preparing to castle. } 16... Nxf3+ 17. Bxf3 Bxb2 { Grabbing an important pawn, because Black is now ready to push the b- and c-pawns down the board. } 18. Rb1 { This was not necessary. It was much more important to castle and bring the king to safety, although even then Black is better. } ( 18. O-O Qd6 { It's important to block the d5-pawn. } 19. Rb1 Bd4+ 20. Kh1 b6 21. Qa4 Nd7 { Black can slowly improve his position and later on push the pawns. } ) 18... Bc3+ ( 18... Qa5+ { was even stronger, in order to activate the queen and bring the bishop to an ideal square: d4. This would win a tempo compared to the game. } 19. Kf2 Bd4+ 20. Kg3 Qc7+ 21. Kh3 Nd7 { White is in trouble. } ) 19. Kf1 Qa5 { Indirectly defending the b7-pawn in view of ...Qa6+. } 20. g3 { White makes room for the king to come to g2, so that he can bring the h1-rook into play. } 20... Bd4 { The best square for the bishop. From d4 it is protected and looks at both flanks. } ( 20... Nd7 21. a4 Ne5 22. Rxb7 Qa6+ 23. Rb5 Re8 ) 21. Kg2 ( 21. a4 { It was possible to save the a-pawn this way. } 21... Nd7 22. Rxb7 Qa6+ 23. Rb5 Ne5 24. Kg2 Kg7 25. Re1 Rd8 { Black's position looks a bit better because of the active pieces. } ) 21... Qxa2+ 22. Kh3 Nd7 23. Rxb7 Ne5 24. Rf1 ( 24. Qe2 { Forcing the queen trade, or else the white queen becomes more active. } 24... Qxe2 25. Bxe2 Rd8 26. Rxa7 Rxd5 27. Rb1 { Black's position looks good, but there is no way to make progress. } ) 24... Qa6 25. Qb1 { Grandelius was probably still hoping to play for a win. } ( 25. d6 { was a good opportunity to activate the bishop. } 25... Qxd6 26. Rxf7+ Kxf7 27. Bxa8+ Kg7 ) 25... Qd6 26. Bg2 Kg8 27. Be4 { White's last two moves show that it's not easy to find a plan in this position. } 27... a5 28. Rb6 { I suspect around here both players were in time trouble, as several inaccuracies occur. } ( 28. Qb6 { The queen trade was called for, in order to create counterplay with the d-pawn. } 28... Qxb6 29. Rxb6 a4 30. Rfb1 Kg7 { The d-pawn keeps White in the game, although Black's position is preferable. } ) 28... Qf8 ( 28... Qd7+ 29. Kg2 Ra7 { would have been strong. Black can push the a-pawn down the board. } ) 29. Qc1 ( 29. d6 { White had another chance to open up the bishop and create counterplay. } 29... Rd8 30. Bd5 ) 29... a4 ( 29... Qd8 30. Qb1 Nc4 { would have been more precise. } ) 30. d6 Qc8+ 31. Kg2 a3 { Now the a-pawn decides the game. } 32. Bxa8 Qxa8+ 33. Kh3 a2 34. Rb2 Qc8+ 35. Kg2 Qc6+ 36. Kh3 Qxd6 { Black is winning. White will have to give a rook for the a-pawn. } 37. Qc2 ( 37. Rxa2 Qe6+ ) 37... Qe6+ 38. Kg2 Qc6+ 39. Kh3 Qc8+ 40. Kg2 Qa8+ 41. Kh3 a1=Q 42. Rxa1 Qxa1 43. Rb1 Qa6 44. Qe4 Qe6+ 45. Kg2 h5 46. Re1 Kg7 47. Re2 Qg4 48. Re1 Qxe4+ 49. Rxe4 Kf6 50. Re2 Ke6 { A nice fighting game. Black had a great position after the opening, and he managed to win against a higher rated player. } *

