1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. Nd2 Bg7 8. e4 O-O 9. Be2 Na6 10. O-O Nc7 11. a4 Re8 12. Re1 b6 13. f4 ( { This move is not in the spirit of this variation. White usually wants to improve his position little by little without weakening it. In the course I mentioned } 13. h3 { and } ) ( 13. Bf1 { , which are stronger alternatives. } ) 13... Ba6 ( { Actually against 13. f4 I recommend } 13... Rb8 { because it is more flexible - see variation. However, } ) ( 13... Ba6 { is also good. } ) 14. Bf3 { Very ambitious. Shankland wants to keep pieces on the board in order to keep  d5 defended and be able to push e5. However, this allows the black bishop to come to d3, and afterwards White starts to experience problems. } ( 14. Bc4 { was called for, so as not to allow the black bishop to d3. Obviously trading on c4 only helps White. } 14... Qd7 15. h3 Rad8 16. Ba2 ) ( { White can also try } 14. Bxa6 { with the idea to bring the knight to c4, but this allows the black knight to come to b4. } 14... Nxa6 15. Nc4 Nb4 { White cannot push e5 because the d5-pawn is hanging, so we've reached a stand-off. } ) 14... Bd3 { The bishop becomes very active here, and it will soon be supported by the c-pawn. } 15. Nf1 c4 { It is important that the bishop is cemented in its strong position. } 16. Ng3 h5 ( 16... Nd7 { is stronger and the move I recommend. The knight is on its way to c5. However the move played is also good, and quite natural. Black keeps the threat of ...h4 in reserve. } ) 17. Bd2 Rb8 { The ...b5 push is always on the agenda. } 18. Nh1 { White redeploys the knight to f2 in order to attack the bishop on d3. } 18... Nd7 { Black’s knight is heading towards c5 from where it will defend the d3-bishop. } 19. Nf2 Nc5 { Black is just in time to defend the bishop. } 20. Rc1 ( 20. Be3 N7a6 { with the idea to bring the knight to b4. White is lost. } ) 20... b5 { A well-timed push. Gao is opening up the game on the queenside. } 21. Be3 ( 21. axb5 Nxb5 { In spite of having a nice pawn centre, White's position is lost. Black's pieces will infiltrate on the d4-square with decisive effect. } ) 21... b4 { The pawn marches forward. } 22. Bxc5 bxc3 { The simplest. This wins a piece and the game. } ( 22... dxc5 { was also winning: } 23. Ne2 { The knight has no better squares. } 23... Bxb2 24. Nxd3 cxd3 25. Qxd3 Bxc1 26. Rxc1 b3 { The b-pawn is strong and decides the game. } 27. e5 Ne6 { A nice detail. The knight joins the fight as well. This is a nice variation, but not called for as the game continuation is easier. } ) 23. bxc3 dxc5 24. Nxd3 cxd3 25. Qxd3 { White has two central pawns for the piece, but Black will be able to create threats quickly, before the pawns start rolling. } 25... Rb2 { The rook enters the second rank, and already ...Qh4 is a threat. } 26. g3 ( 26. e5 Qh4 27. Qe3 Bh6 ) 26... c4 { A nice move that opens up the g1-a7 diagonal. } 27. Qd1 ( 27. Qxc4 Nxd5 { This is the point. Next, ...Qb6+ followed by ...Qf2+ is very strong. } 28. Qxd5 Qb6+ 29. Kh1 Qf2 ) 27... Nb5 { Gao finishes the game in style. The same idea of ...Qb6+ and ...Qf2 applies here. } 28. Re3 ( 28. axb5 Qb6+ 29. Kh1 Qf2 30. Be2 Rxe4 ) 28... Qb6 29. Qe1 Bxc3 { White's position is falling apart, so Shankland resigned. Gao took his chances by playing the Benoni against a player with 150 rating points more than him, and he was rewarded with a beautiful win. } { A possible finish is } 30. Rxc3 Nxc3 31. Qxc3 Rb3 *

