1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nc3 g6 { This is an important game from a historical point of view. The World Championship match between Fischer and Spassky in Reykjavik 1972 had gathered a huge attention worldwide. At this point in the match  Spassky was leading 2-0, so Fischer had to fight back, even if he was playing with the black pieces. The game proved to be the turning point of the match, and the Benoni was an inspired opening choice. } 7. Nd2 Nbd7 ( { in the course I recommend } 7... Bg7 { followed by ...O-O and then ...Na6. However, Fischer's choice is also sound. } ) 8. e4 Bg7 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O Re8 11. Qc2 { A useful move in these kind of positions, but I'm not sure if it should be White's first priority. However back in 1972 this was the latest trend. } ( { Nowadays } 11. a4 { is by far the most popular move for White. } ) 11... Nh5 { An interesting, double-edged idea. Black hopes to get good piece play for the doubled pawns. } ( 11... Ne5 { is preferred nowadays. For example, the game ½-½ (30) Aronian,L (2786)-Caruana,F (2794) Moscow 2016 continued } 12. b3 Bg4 13. Bxg4 Nfxg4 14. Bb2 a6 15. h3 Nf6 16. f4 Ned7 { with a complex position. } ) 12. Bxh5 gxh5 13. Nc4 ( 13. b3 { makes sense to me, in order to put the bishop to b2 and then continue with Nd1-e3. } 13... b5 14. Bb2 b4 15. Nd1 Ba6 16. Re1 Ne5 17. Ne3 { looks preferable for White. } ) ( 13. a4 Ne5 14. Nd1 { was recommended afterwards. White has ideas to play Ra3 and bring the rook to the kingside. } ) 13... Ne5 14. Ne3 { Understandably Spassky avoids the exchange. The knight on e3 prevents Black's ... f5. } 14... Qh4 ( 14... Ng4 { It was also interesting to play this move immediately. } ) 15. Bd2 ( 15. f3 { White had to try this in order to avoid ...Ng4. He may have been reluctant to weaken his kingside, but it seems that nothing dangerous happens. } 15... f5 16. exf5 Nf7 17. Bd2 Be5 18. g3 Qh3 19. Rae1 ) 15... Ng4 { Black forces the trade of knights and straightens out his pawn structure. } 16. Nxg4 hxg4 17. Bf4 Qf6 18. g3 { Spassky wants to keep the bishop on its active position but weakens his pawn structure on the kingside. } ( 18. Bg3 { had to be played: } 18... Qg6 ) 18... Bd7 19. a4 b6 20. Rfe1 a6 { Fischer is slowly preparing ...b5, while White is lacking counterplay. } 21. Re2 b5 22. Rae1 Qg6 { It's important to prevent White from playing e5. } 23. b3 Re7 24. Qd3 Rb8 25. axb5 axb5 { Now Black is threatening ...b4 followed by ...Bb5. } 26. b4 { A good decision, but now Black will get a passed pawn. } 26... c4 27. Qd2 Rbe8 28. Re3 h5 { This is the point. Black can slowly improve his position, while White can only sit and wait. } 29. R3e2 ( 29. Kf1 ) 29... Kh7 ( 29... Bxc3 { would have been strong. Instead Fischer first repeated the moves and then went for this resource. } ) 30. Re3 Kg8 31. R3e2 ( 31. Kf1 ) 31... Bxc3 { It's time to force the events! } 32. Qxc3 Rxe4 33. Rxe4 Rxe4 34. Rxe4 Qxe4 { The opposite-coloured bishops favour Black because of the weak white king. } 35. Bh6 Qg6 36. Bc1 Qb1 37. Kf1 Bf5 38. Ke2 Qe4+ 39. Qe3 Qc2+ 40. Qd2 Qb3 41. Qd4 ( 41. Ke1 Qb1 42. Qc3 Bg6 ) 41... Bd3+ *

