1. d4 e6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 exd5 4. cxd5 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 ( { This is a wrong move order. } 5... d6 { has to be played first, and only then ...g6. } ) 6. Nf3 { White goes for a known setup, and yet the opportunity was there... } ( 6. d6 { Pay close attention! This move order is rarely seen, as Black almost always plays ...d6 first. It's not easy for White to decide to go for this because it involves a pawn sacrifice. However the pawn push would have been very strong with a correct follow-up. Here are a few sample continuations: } 6... Qb6 7. Nf3 Bxd6 8. e4 O-O 9. Be2 Re8 10. O-O { ± } ) 6... Bg7 7. e4 d6 8. h3 O-O 9. Bd3 a6 { Black goes for a slightly worse but playable position. He certainly took some risks, but his effort was rewarded in the end. Also, this was a rapid game, and in a rapid or blitz game it's not easy to be precise, so mistakes on both sides are expected. } ( 9... b5 { is a sound move which I recommend in the course - see chapter 7. } ) 10. a4 Nbd7 11. O-O Nh5 12. Bg5 Bf6 13. Be3 Bg7 ( 13... Re8 14. Qd2 Ne5 15. Be2 Nxf3+ 16. Bxf3 Ng7 17. a5 ) 14. Bg5 ( 14. Be2 ) ( 14. Qd2 Ne5 15. Be2 f5 ) 14... Qc7 15. Nd2 ( 15. Be2 { with the idea Nd2 was interesting. } ) 15... Re8 16. Re1 Rb8 17. Be2 h6 ( 17... Nhf6 18. Bh4 ) 18. Be3 Nhf6 19. Bf4 { It's desirable to put the bishop on the h2-b8 diagonal, but here it was better to prepare f4 instead. } ( 19. Bf1 g5 20. f4 gxf4 21. Bxf4 Ne5 22. Nc4 ) 19... Ne5 20. Bh2 g5 { Seasoned Benoni players play such a move instantly. f4 is prevented, and the knight is secured on e5. } 21. Bf1 Bd7 22. a5 g4 23. hxg4 { Not the best move, but a fully understandable decision. White doesn't want to weaken his king. } ( 23. Ra3 gxh3 24. gxh3 b5 25. axb6 Qxb6 ) ( 23. Bxe5 Rxe5 24. Nc4 Ree8 25. Re3 h5 ) 23... Nfxg4 24. Bg3 h5 { That's the spirit! Black is pushing! } 25. Nc4 Nxc4 26. Bxc4 b5 { A nice Benoni position. Black is opening a second front. } 27. axb6 Rxb6 28. Qd2 Bc8 { This leaves the e8-rook undefended. } ( 28... Qd8 29. Rxa6 Rxa6 30. Bxa6 Bd4 ) 29. Qg5 ( 29. e5 { And yet this move is possible, although e5 is the best defended square in Black’s position. This move works because of the pin on the e-file. That's why Black should have played ...Qd8 before. Of course such possibilities are easy to miss, especially in a rapid game. } 29... dxe5 30. Rad1 Rg6 31. d6 Qd7 32. Qd3 ) 29... Rxb2 30. Rac1 Ne5 31. Bf1 Bg4 ( 31... Qd8 ) 32. Nd1 Rb6 33. Ne3 a5 ( 33... Qe7 { It would have made sense to trade the queens and then try to push the a-pawn. } ) 34. Nf5 ( 34. f3 { It's easy to miss this tactical trick in a rapid game. } 34... Bxf3 35. Nf5 f6 36. Qxg7+ Qxg7 37. Nxg7 Kxg7 38. Bxe5 fxe5 39. gxf3 ) 34... Bxf5 35. exf5 Qd8 36. Qxh5 Nd7 37. Bh4 Nf6 38. Bxf6 ( 38. Qg5 a4 39. Rxe8+ Qxe8 40. Qg3 ) 38... Bxf6 39. Red1 ( 39. g4 { White had to seek counterplay by pushing the pawns. } ) 39... Re4 40. Rd3 Rh4 41. Qe2 Rb2 42. Rc2 Rxc2 43. Qxc2 a4 44. Ra3 Qa5 45. Qe2 Kf8 46. Qb5 ( 46. g3 Rb4 { Black's pawns look dangerous, but his king is exposed. } ) 46... Qb4 47. Ra2 ( 47. Qd3 c4 ) 47... Kg7 ( 47... Qb3 ) 48. Qc6 Be5 49. g3 Re4 50. Qd7 Qb3 51. Re2 Rxe2 52. Bxe2 Qb1+ 53. Kg2 a3 54. Bh5 ( 54. f6+ Kxf6 55. Qd8+ Kg6 ) 54... Qe4+ 55. Bf3 Qc4 56. f6+ Bxf6 *

