1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 g6 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. e4 d6 6. Bd3 O-O 7. h3 e6 8. Nf3 exd5 9. cxd5 { Now we're back in one of the main lines of the Benoni. } ( 9. exd5 { is another option for White. In this case the position is symmetrical, but White has more space. } ) 9... b5 { Black goes for the approved solution. I chose this game because I wanted to show how the ...b5 line fares in a rapid game. As it turns out there is a lot of play, and the line is not necessarily drawish. } 10. Nxb5 Nxe4 { Sometimes Black plays this move, but I think it's dubious. } ( 10... Re8 { is essential, and what I recommend in the course - see the 10. Nxb5 lines in chapter 7. } ) 11. Bxe4 Re8 12. O-O { White misses the opportunity missed. Now we're back to the lines similar to those in chapter 7. Understandably White wanted to avoid the complications, especially in a rapid game. } ( { However, } 12. Ng5 { is strong here: } 12... Qa5+ 13. Nc3 Ba6 { This is what Black is counting on. } 14. f3 { This move refutes the line. White is ready to move the king to f2. } ) 12... Rxe4 13. Bg5 { This is tempting, as it comes with tempo. } 13... f6 { This shuts off the bishop, but gains a tempo. } ( 13... Qd7 { is the most precise reply. } 14. Qd3 { A tricky idea. White wants to connect the rooks and get control over the e-file. } 14... Ra4 { With the idea to play ...Ba6, when White doesn't have a4 to support the knight. 14...Rb4 is also possible. } 15. Nc3 Ba6 16. Qc2 Bxf1 17. Nxa4 Bd3 { forces more exchanges: } 18. Qxd3 Qxa4 ) 14. Nc3 { It was better to keep the knight on its active position for a longer time, and then if Black plays ...Rb4 the knight can be defended with Qe2. } ( 14. Be3 Bf8 15. Re1 ) ( 14. Bh4 Na6 15. Bg3 ) 14... Rb4 15. Bh4 ( 15. Bc1 Nd7 ) 15... Nd7 16. Re1 Ne5 { Black utilizes a practical approach: development first! } ( 16... Rxb2 { It was possible to take the pawn, but then Black is lagging in development. } 17. Ne4 Qf8 18. Rb1 Rxb1 19. Qxb1 Rb8 20. Qc2 ) 17. Nxe5 dxe5 18. d6 { A good practical decision. White is going for active play. } ( 18. Bg3 Bf5 ) 18... Rd4 19. Qf3 Rb8 ( 19... Bf5 { would be just wrong. } 20. g4 Be6 21. Rxe5 Rxd6 22. Rae1 ) 20. Rxe5 Bb7 { An important in-between move. } ( 20... Rxh4 21. Qd5+ Kh8 22. Re7 Bf5 23. Rae1 ) 21. Qg3 ( 21. Qe3 Rxh4 22. Rxc5 Qxd6 23. Rd1 { Despite the piece down, White gets good compensation because of the active pieces. The white rooks are ready to enter the 7th rank. } ) 21... Rxh4 22. Re7 ( 22. Rxc5 Rb4 23. Rd1 ) 22... Rd4 23. d7 { This forces a series of exchanges. White gives up the initiative and the d-pawn, but gets back the piece. } 23... Qxe7 24. Qxb8+ Kf7 25. Qxb7 Qxd7 26. Qa6 ( 26. Qxd7+ { It would have been a good decision to trade the queens here. The resulting endgame is about equal. } 26... Rxd7 27. Rc1 f5 28. Rc2 ) 26... f5 { Opening up the bishop. Suddenly Black's pieces become active. } 27. Re1 Bf6 28. Qa5 c4 29. Qc5 Kg7 30. a4 a6 { This takes away the b5-square. } 31. Kf1 { The position is slightly better for Black because of the more active pieces and the c4-pawn. Here White is lacking a clear plan. } ( 31. g3 ) 31... h5 32. Ne2 { This loses because it gives the black rook access to the d1-square. } ( 32. Kg1 { Perhaps it was an idea to just sit and wait. } ) 32... Rd1 { Very strong. Now Black can create mate threats. } 33. Qb4 ( 33. f3 Qxa4 { would leave White a pawn down. } ) 33... Qd3 34. Rxd1 Qxd1+ 35. Qe1 Qxa4 { White's position is lost. His pieces are passive and the b2-pawn is a target. The game ended in a few more  moves. } 36. Nf4 c3 37. Ne6+ Kf7 38. b4 Qxb4 *
